\par TURNS ABOUT TOWN
\par 
\par CHAPTER I
\par 
\par THE HOTEL GUEST
\par 
\par 
\par Some people just go to a hotel (sometimes referred to as "an hotel") and
\par stay awhile and go away again. And think nothing about the matter.
\par 
\par Of course, some may complain more or less at the place about the
\par "service." Or swank round outside about the address, saying carelessly:
\par "Oh! yes: at the Blackstone, you know." Or again, if it's a rather
\par inexpensive place, remark to friends: "Isn't it a funny hole! But the
\par cuisine is excellent. You'd be surprised! That's why I stop there. And
\par then it's much more homey, too, than those garish places."
\par 
\par Now I myself am a fan for hotels.
\par 
\par If I was a rich man I'd do like an aristocratic and restless young man I
\par know, who used to go to one New York hotel about twelve at night (after
\par the evening's entertainment) and leave a call for ten in the morning,
\par when he would get up and drive to another hotel, check in, eat lunch and
\par dinner there, and move on to a third New York hotel that night. A
\par cheerful way he had of adding variety to his life.
\par 
\par He was a highly agreeable youth, this chap. Always "wore" a
\par silver-headed cane. I'm sorry to have to say that he is now in jail.
\par Yep! You see, he had many attractive qualities, but dependability was
\par not a feature of his equipment. However, his is a resilient nature, and,
\par fortunately, he is an epicure by temperament. I was rather distressed,
\par myself, when I heard that he was in jail; and other of his friends that
\par I met also were decidedly disturbed about him. One day one of them got a
\par letter from him (it was in France, you know, that he was then in jail),
\par a bubbling, delightful letter (just like the youth), in which he
\par declared with much gusto that the jail he was in had the best menu of
\par any jail in France.
\par 
\par But about hotels. Oh, yes!
\par 
\par I always like those huge, brown-paper laundry bags they have hanging up,
\par pressed beautifully flat, in the rooms, closets or bathrooms of hotels.
\par You can't roll up your laundry all in one wad and thrust it into one of
\par these bags, because this would tear the bag. The way to do is to put in,
\par for instance, first your collars, then, say, your sox, follow perhaps
\par with your shirts, and so on. In hotels of the very first water, you have
\par observed, a neat little pocket is attached to the outside of the bag,
\par into which you have the fun of pinning your laundry slip, all
\par elaborately made out.
\par 
\par Next thing, of course, is to get your laundry started on its way. And
\par here come up a view of the nice nuances of hotels. You gotta watch your
\par Ps and Qs in these matters or you're likely to get a black-eye at your
\par hotel. All right in a modest sort of place just to holler down the
\par telephone for a boy. Then you say to boy, waving hand toward objects:
\par "Laundry to go down, suit to be pressed, hat to be ironed, shoes to be
\par polished, letters to be mailed," and so forth. Boy gathers up
\par miscellaneous collection of articles and proceeds upon these divers
\par assignments. Presto! Nothing further to detain you.
\par 
\par But suppose you have gone in for a little more class in the matter of
\par your hotel--Statler, or something like that. Then you find much more of
\par a ritual to life. To accomplish your existence requires thought, a clear
\par head--and time. You pay the penalty of the dignity of pomp and
\par circumstance. No large, off-hand, free and easy manner about sending up
\par a boy. The "operator" knows nothing of boys. In the matter of your
\par laundry you may request her to connect you with the "bell captain,"
\par through whose agency (but not otherwise) a boy may be procured. One
\par message. In the matter of your suit you may request to be connected with
\par the "valet service." Message two. And so on.
\par 
\par Then you sit you down and await the procession. Or, if you prefer,
\par contemplate the spectacle of life by looking out at the window.
\par 
\par You fee Buttons. Lapse of time.
\par 
\par Boots (as Dickens calls him) arrives--what probably here is a
\par porter--for shoes. Then you have an excellent opportunity (which may not
\par occur again during the day) for a slight period of philosophical
\par meditation, or to whistle a tune, before the valet appears.
\par 
\par In such places as I am describing it is not etiquette at all (though it
\par may seem to you the simplest way of doing the thing) to call a bellboy
\par to get down your bag. The porter does that--and through the correct
\par channel, that is by way of the freight elevator. And, say, something
\par goes wrong with your ice-water pipe. You are not to outrage hotel
\par decency here. What is necessary for you to procure is a waiter. Waiters
\par attend to your inner wants.
\par 
\par I like best the character of valet when he is English (either so by
\par birth, or this by self-cultivation); wears a skirt coat, immaculately
\par pressed, and a "buttonhole"; advances into the room in the attitude of a
\par bow, and comes to a pause in the pose of one listening with deep and
\par profoundly respectful attention to the haughty utterance of a stage
\par earl. Though, indeed, there is an element of disquiet in your being thus
\par elevated to the Peerage if, as with me, the suit you turn over to this
\par unexceptionable servitor is of Hirt, Snuffler and Muss manufacture, and
\par growing a trifle frail in the seat.
\par 
\par The same thing is true of bath-rooms. I don't, of course, mean that
\par bath-rooms perform the valet act. But that the more aristocratic in
\par hotels you get the more likely you are, so to say, to get into hot water
\par in bath-rooms. Like this:
\par 
\par If you get into a bathtub which is not quite the last word in bathtubs,
\par that is a bathtub which has legs and spigots to turn on the water, you
\par know where you are at all the while. You turn on the hot water in the
\par amount desired. It comes out of the hot water spout. As desired you turn
\par on the cold water. Out of the cold water spout comes it.
\par 
\par But, as you know, the last word in bathtubs is not simple and democratic
\par like that. It is built onto the floor and has a clock-like dial on the
\par wall. Dial marked at different points: "Cold," "Medium," "Hot," "Off."
\par Turn little handle to regulate temperature and flow of water. All out of
\par same pipe. Yes--but--dial untruthful--very. "Off" scalds you; "Medium"
\par freezes you. Bad time trying to take last word in baths.
\par 
\par "Tub or shower?" Maybe you say "shower." And draw one of those
\par police-court cells. Except the door, no opening in the little, square,
\par completely cement room but the small hole in the center of the floor
\par through which the water runs away. But that's not the way to look at it.
\par These little catacomb-like chambers are \'e6sthetic in their ascetic
\par character. You may entertain yourself by fancying that you are St.
\par Jerome, or somebody like that. In here nothing that it will hurt can
\par get wet, and you can have a fine time making the whole room a
\par merry-go-round of splashes. One disturbing thought may occur to you. If
\par the door should stick you might not be found until the hotel got worried
\par about your bill, when perhaps it would be too late.
\par 
\par Still, I think the chummiest bath-rooms are those with a bay-window;
\par very reprehensible those which have no hooks on which to hang your
\par pajamas and razor strop.
\par 
\par Then there are those hotels so far-seeing into the possibilities of evil
\par chance and so solicitous of your equanimity that they provide your pin
\par cushion with one suspender button. I suppose the thought is to impress
\par you with the idea that nothing for your comfort, even down to the
\par smallest detail, is forgotten. Still, though I do not know that such an
\par untoward incident ever happened, it is within the range of human
\par possibility that a man might be shorn of two suspender buttons at once.
\par If, further, the hotel management were co-ordinated with the gentlemen's
\par underwear business a safety pin would be served along with the suspender
\par button--in view of the singular fact that, until your wife has taken a
\par reef in them, all nether garments are much too great in girth for any
\par figure at all approximating normal.
\par 
\par Working, however, as it does, with human material no hotel can get away
\par with perfection. For, as Dr. Johnson observed, "a fallible being will
\par fail somewhere." It was in San Francisco recently that three days were
\par required for me to recover a suit sent in the morning to be pressed by
\par that afternoon. This mischance was occasioned by three circumstances. To
\par wit: goblins (presumably) made away with the ticket attached to it; the
\par hotel tailor fell indisposed with (I hope) leprosy; and his assistant
\par had a slight mental infirmity, in other words he was seven times an
\par idiot.
\par 
\par Reverse English in Los Angeles a few days later. When one night I found
\par neatly hung on the coat frame in my closet a suit of excellent material,
\par of fashionable design, and seemingly of virgin character. I reported the
\par matter to the third assistant manager. One criticism only I have to make
\par of that suit. It was too confoundedly tight.
\par 
\par Then, of course, even at the best places (I almost think particularly in
\par the best places) you are likely any time to find under your door in the
\par morning a telephone message stamped "Rush," directing you to call
\par so-and-so "as soon as possible"--and dated 5:17-1/2 two days earlier.
\par Or, on coming in you are handed by the clerk a memorandum which states
\par that Mr. Cohan telephoned. Such matters, you reflect, are retrogressive.
\par If you are unacquainted with any gentleman of the name of Mr. Cohan, so
\par it may very well be that the guest here who is a friend of Mr. Cohan
\par received notice that _your_ friend Mr. Sloan telephoned. And there you
\par are!
\par 
\par My friend Harry Heartydrop (who, I declare! looks rosier even than
\par before the middle of January, 1920) has adopted a hotel life altogether
\par of late. He explains to me that the advantage of this is the new
\par side-line activity of numerous compassionate bell captains, who, it
\par seems--but that would be telling.
\par 
\par One of the pleasantest things, I think, about hotels is the "night maid
\par service" furnished at fashionable places. When you come in you find your
\par light burning and so do not break your shins, and your bed is "turned
\par down" for you. Very softening to the spirit, this. In a kind of a sort
\par of a hazy way one's thoughts turn back to the maternal solicitude which
\par used to "tuck" one "in."
\par 
\par Good night!
\par 
