\par CHAPTER II
\par 
\par A HUMORIST MISFITS AT A MURDER TRIAL
\par 
\par 
\par Are you in on the great Crime Wave, brother? Almost everybody is, I
\par guess, in one way or another. What's your particular line? Murderer,
\par bandit, burglar, mortally wounded innocent bystander, juror, witness, or
\par victim? The police are in on it, too; every once in awhile one of them
\par gets blackjacked, or something like that.
\par 
\par I had the flu bad enough, when that was the big thing going; but somehow
\par so far I myself have escaped being caught in the Crime Wave. This gives
\par me the great advantage over most people of being a detached spectator of
\par the rollicking game.
\par 
\par I have a friend, though, who was caught up just a few days ago. He has
\par been telling me all about it. Murder case.
\par 
\par This fellow is a sort of author. He had served a time or two as a juror
\par in the Supreme Court of New York County. In that building down by the
\par City Hall. But he says those cases bored him terribly. They were
\par chicken-feed sort of rows, generally concerned with the question of how
\par many dollars and fractions thereof X had occasioned the loss of to Z by
\par reason of his failure to deliver such and such a quantity of (say)
\par beeswax before the drop in the market of 39.7-1/4 cents, as called for
\par by telephone agreement, possibly. The "Court" (a nice, pink and grey old
\par fellow) would go to sleep, with his mouth open, during the drone of the
\par legal argument, and be awakened automatically (apparently by some change
\par in atmospheric conditions) at the moment required for him to begin his
\par charge to the jury. Occasionally, he would come semi-to for an instant
\par before this, and indistinctly utter the words, "Objection sustained."
\par 
\par My friend's chief impression of these proceedings is his recollection of
\par one phenomenon which he observed. Not long after the opening of the
\par presentation of X's side of the case he saw very clearly that Z hadn't a
\par leg to stand on. It was ridiculous that he had the face to come into
\par court with an attempt to question the truth of facts which were as
\par apparent to the naked eye as the Woolworth Building. My friend felt it
\par needless to pay any further attention to the foolish formalities of the
\par argument. If he had not had an uneasy feeling that he might get pinched
\par for this, he would have gone to sleep, like the Judge.
\par 
\par But those were dull days in the jury business.
\par 
\par A little later my friend gets some sort of a ticket instructing him to
\par call and talk things over with a gentleman having the university degree
\par of Commissioner of Jurors. This gentleman asks my friend if he has ever
\par been arrested on a criminal charge, if he is opposed to capital
\par punishment, and if he has any prejudice against Episcopalians. My friend
\par is a man of liberal mind, and replies that he would just as soon hang an
\par Episcopalian as anybody else. "You're on," said the gentleman, reaching
\par for a blotter; and signed him up. My friend didn't know exactly for
\par what. But the gentleman said everything was all right, they might not
\par call on my friend for a long time, and then perhaps it would be a short
\par case.
\par 
\par Sometime back was all this. My friend had almost forgotten about his
\par acquaintance with the Commissioner. Then all of a sudden the gong sounds
\par and the great Crime Wave is on. Detectives dash madly about with
\par shotguns. A jeweller is shot every day after lunch and a subway
\par ticket-seller is robbed directly after every train starts. My friend
\par hurries home early because everybody is fined who is caught on any paved
\par street after dark, and there in his letter-box is the summons from his
\par old friend the Commissioner, who apparently has borne him in mind all
\par this while.
\par 
\par On the document is printed by a printing-press, "Jack Hammond _vs._ The
\par People of the State of New York." And on it is written with a pen my
\par friend's name, before the printed words "Special Juror." It very
\par urgently invites my friend to appear at ten o'clock four days distant at
\par the Criminal Courts Building and there "await further order of the
\par Court."
\par 
\par You get off the subway at Brooklyn Bridge, you know, and go, past the
\par Municipal Building, up Centre Street. A district around behind the
\par "lanes" (as they say of steamship travel) of general traffic, and one
\par infrequently traversed by my friend. He was much interested in the
\par spectacle hereabout. Buildings labelled Public Health on this hand,
\par buildings labelled Public Records on that. Then you come to that prison
\par as gruesome in its name as the Tower of London is romantic in its
\par connotation--the Tombs. The structure itself, a cluster of rather
\par slender wings, rises from behind its dark walls with an element of
\par grace, in contrast to that chill, squat, mouldering pile which begot and
\par bequeathed the historic name. Ugh! though, those barred windows, row
\par upon row, give a fellow such qualms as do the ugly symbols of our
\par mortality. Even though you ain't done nothin', make you feel sorta faint
\par like inside!
\par 
\par There in the south wall is a little door, like a rabbit burrow, with a
\par little group about it, and quite a small bustle going on. Standing in
\par this bit of a doorway, as though she had something to do in the way of
\par belonging there, is a queer, oval body who looks much as though she
\par might be what is called an "apple woman." Marked "Visitors' Entrance,"
\par this door. What is it all the people on this side of the street are
\par pausing to look at over there?
\par 
\par A cab is drawn up. From this lightly steps (or flashes) a dizzy dream.
\par "Floppy" hat, scant skirt awhirl, pink-hued stockings gleaming to the
\par height of the full curve behind the knee, tall satin pump-heels dancing
\par the wearer on her toes--she swirls through the dark doorway. "They all
\par have their wimmin," remarks a blousy-looking loiterer to my friend.
\par 
\par At the north, three stories up, the prison connects with the courts
\par building by that fabled structure the "bridge of sighs."
\par 
\par Lively scene before the main entrance to this edifice on Centre Street.
\par Streams of figures hurrying up the broad front steps--on their way to a
\par busy day at the height of the crime season. Taxis flying up and
\par discharging chattering groups as at a theatre. Open pops a taxi door,
\par out leap three. A couple of very hard-looking young men, of that
\par sawed-off, stocky stature frequently observed in this type of very
\par hard-looking young man. Elegantly dressed, these; between them one of
\par "Oh!-you-beautiful-doll" type. Rapidly they make their way up the steps,
\par as though very well acquainted with the place.
\par 
\par Regular jam inside. My friend learned from an attendant that his
\par particular destination was two flights up. Great crush wedging into the
\par elevator. Elevator man calls out merrily to an acquaintance he observes
\par outside his door: "It's a great life if you don't weaken!"
\par 
\par Threads his way, my friend, around the balcony, so to say, upstairs.
\par Centre of building open from ground floor to roof. Effect: spacious,
\par beautiful, ornamented in the richness of a house of grand opera. Finds
\par the right door. Card on the wall nearby. Several persons (tough-looking
\par youths in caps and soft collars) reading it. It lists previous day's
\par proceedings in this court room. Says: So-and-so; Murder; Indicted (or
\par something like that). Then the names of attorneys for the defense given.
\par Second line: So-and-so; Murder; etc. Third line: So-and-so; Murder.
\par Fourth line: So-and-so; Grand Larceny. Next line: So-an-so; Rape. Next:
\par Murder. And so on. Sure, my friend thinks, I've got to the real shop
\par this time. He has a few moments yet, and so he strolls over to a door at
\par the opposite side of the building. 'Nother card there. Same sort of
\par thing: murder, murder, grand larceny, homicide, murder, murder. (If you
\par don't believe it, go down there and look at those cards.) "Holy cat!"
\par says my friend to himself, "comparatively little of this crime stuff
\par gets into the papers, after all, don't it? I never heard of any of these
\par cases."
\par 
\par Enters court room. Takes a seat. Room soon filled. Now in my friend's
\par experience as a petit juror he had found himself among a rather
\par grotesque company of very small characters, frequently somewhat seedy in
\par outward effect. Here he was much struck by the decidedly first-rate
\par quality in appearance of practically every man in the room. Also,
\par before, he had observed with a good deal of annoyance that a court of
\par law could consume about twenty-nine times the time in accomplishing a
\par very simple matter that would be devoted to a thing of similar
\par consequence in any practical business office. Here in this flourishing
\par mill for dealing with capital crime the clerk of the court (or whatever
\par you call him) began to call the roll of jurors present fifteen minutes
\par before the hour set for opening of court. And so did affairs proceed
\par with well-oiled despatch.
\par 
\par "Oyez-mumble-jumble-jabber-jabber-yah-meow-wow-jumble-jabber-jumble" (or
\par whatever the devil it is), sang out the attendant who cries out that.
\par Everybody at once gets to his feet. In comes his corpulent Honor,
\par swinging along briskly, his gown flowing out behind, and mounts to his
\par wooden-canopied throne. A large, glossy, rather handsome face, neatly
\par cropped dark moustache, eye-glasses swinging from a broad black ribbon.
\par General effect what might be called that of a heavy-weight "club man,"
\par looks as if he might be quite a hearty fellow when out with "the boys."
\par 
\par Door opens at back of room. Sound of marching steps. Then are seen
\par coming along through a zoo-like cage round two sides of the room three
\par figures, burly civilian-clothed one in the middle, uniformed officer
\par fore and aft. They line up this side of a rail fencing the jurors off
\par from an area before the Judge. Burly figure is very well dressed. Stands
\par solidly on his feet, eyes trained directly on the Judge. Holds a dark
\par soft hat in his hands which he clasps behind his back. What from a
\par position somewhat to the rear can be seen of the side of his face
\par reveals a heavy scar, the result evidently of a knife slash across one
\par cheek. The Judge puts his palms together and addresses this person. "You
\par are charged with murder," he begins. He says it rather gently, in a
\par somewhat chiding manner, as though he had said, "Bad fellow, bad
\par fellow." Just then, "For the defendant!" calls out an attendant, and
\par another figure hurries forward.
\par 
\par The defendant's attorneys have not appeared, it seems. Their case is not
\par quite prepared. A postponement is asked. "Why is it not prepared?" asks
\par the Judge. The defendant speaks out. Declares his attorney has not been
\par paid. Judge's reply is that the attorney provided for him is an able
\par man, who will see that all his rights are observed. Grants postponement
\par until the next morning, positively no further. Officer by his side
\par plucks defendant's coat tail, and starts him off back through the cage.
\par As he goes he is heard to say that his attorney will not be there in the
\par morning either.
\par 
\par And as he turns, my friend gets, with a shock, a full-face view of him.
\par He had never expected anybody off the melodramatic stage to _look_ so
\par much like a murderer. Scarey, that face, a countenance almost majestic
\par in its ruthlessness and force: gangster, gunman, typically personified.
\par 
\par Jurors excused until ten-thirty next day. As they move toward the door,
\par two attractively dressed young women arise from the rear. "Who are the
\par ladies?" asks one. "Friends of the defendant," says another.
\par 
\par Next day, game called sharp on the stroke of the clock. Following
\par preliminaries of the day before, attendant spins that little roulette
\par wheel sort of an affair. Looks at slip thus drawn. "John Cole," he
\par cries. Mr. Cole passes round behind jury box, reappears in far corner at
\par left of Judge. "Rigmarole-rigmarole-solemnly swear, rigmarole," chaunts
\par attendant there, thrusting very dilapidated Bible before him. Mr. Cole
\par takes what later will be the witness chair.
\par 
\par Assistant district attorney arises and explains the case to him. The
\par charge is murder in the first degree. The prosecution must rely largely
\par on the testimony of an accomplice.
\par 
\par Defendant sits in whispered consultation with his attorney, his arm
\par almost around him. As prosecutor seats himself, attorney for the defense
\par gets up to put Mr. Cole through his paces. A fat, oily-looking man, with
\par (it is evident) a browbeating manner in reserve.
\par 
\par Has Mr. Cole, or anyone "near and dear" to him, recently met with any
\par "accident" at the hands of robbers? No. He will not, then, have a
\par revengeful feeling toward any person charged with crime? Not at all.
\par Would he give the same weight to the "story" of a "self-confessed thief
\par and murderer" that he would to the testimony of a "man of probity"?
\par Probably not. Now, doubtless, Mr. Cole is a reader of newspapers. He
\par has, of course, seen this "literature" (with a sneer), this "newspaper
\par hysteria" about a "c-r-i-m-e wave" (tongue in cheek). Well, can Mr. Cole
\par go into the jury box and look at this case detached from the
\par "atmosphere" now "being created by the newspapers"? Finally, is Mr. Cole
\par acquainted with anyone connected with the police department?
\par 
\par Mr. Cole, for some reason, strikes out.
\par 
\par Third man accepted. He comes around from behind it to enter the jury
\par box. At the gateway, while defendant stands and faces him, some more
\par rigmarole-mumble-jumble business.
\par 
\par Suddenly my friend is called. His business? asks district attorney. A
\par writer, he replies. Defendant and his attorney exchange strange glances.
\par Undoubtedly there is something low and suspicious about a fellow with
\par such a business. Attorney for the defense comes forward hurriedly. Soon
\par takes my friend in hand. He at once adopts the sarcastic. My friend's
\par work must require unusual "observation." He must be "gifted" with "great
\par powers of de-duct-shun" (said out of one corner of his mouth). Of
\par course, he has too a "fine imagination." By the way, what is the nature
\par of his writing? Has he written any novels?
\par 
\par No, my friend says, he is a humorous writer. "A what?" exclaims the
\par lawyer, his mouth remaining open. Then, "Like Don Mark_ee_?" "Somewhat,"
\par says my friend. Lawyer visibly pales. Withdrawing toward counsel table,
\par looks back at the accused, who vigorously shakes his head.
\par 
\par "Excused by per-emptory challenge," utters lawyer, dropping into his
\par chair.
