\par CHAPTER III
\par 
\par QUEER THING, 'BOUT UNDERTAKERS' SHOPS
\par 
\par 
\par Queer thing, that, about undertakers' shops! I don't remember to have
\par been struck by undertakers' shops in San Francisco. Maybe they have none
\par there--because, as you'll see, it's a queer thing about them.
\par 
\par Now in Indianapolis undertaking is a very fashionable affair. People
\par there, apparently, want "class" in the matter of being finally disposed
\par of. They believe, evidently, with the author of the popular little idyl,
\par "Urn Burial," that "Man is a noble animal, splendid in ashes and pompous
\par in the tomb."
\par 
\par The most aristocratic street in that city is named North Meridian
\par Street. A street, until a short time ago, entirely of stately lawns and
\par patrician homes--mansions. Of late, a little business, shops of the most
\par distinguished character, has been creeping up this street from
\par down-town. Notably, de luxe motor car salesrooms, studios of highly
\par \'e6sthetic photographers, and particularly palatial undertaking
\par establishments. They are, these last, wondrous halls, which surely none
\par could enter but those who (in life) had been rich in treasure. Features
\par of the city are they--"sights."
\par 
\par But here's the riddle:
\par 
\par Strolling about New York, from river to river, uptown and down, one
\par might readily fancy that here only the poor pass out of the world. Or
\par that if the rich and fashionable ever die their bodies are mysteriously
\par spirited away to destinations unknown; or are secretly preserved
\par (presumably by some taxidermal process) in their homes.
\par 
\par Why? Well, where on Fifth Avenue is an undertaker's? True, a man I know
\par declares there is a single one there. I am unable to find it. Where on
\par any fine street of the metropolis? Why, yes; as a rare phenomenon. You
\par do know, of course, that enormous place on upper Broadway. Sign says
\par branches in Paris, London, Berlin, Petrograd.
\par 
\par Viewed through the great windows interior presents somewhat the effect
\par of the Metropolitan Museum of Art. In foreground large harp, equally
\par huge Chinese vase--probably of the Tang Wang period, on great marble
\par pedestal enormous bronze of a mounted Diana repelling with spear attack
\par of ferocious animal resembling tiger. Appropriateness of this sculpture
\par somewhat puzzling. On wall, somewhat further within, immense tapestry.
\par One door labelled "Delivery Entrance." All of this, of course, is
\par magnificence as much as even the most covetous would crave.
\par 
\par But in New York this august undertaking hall is an anachronism. Here,
\par for some reason mysterious, it is in shabby neighborhoods that the
\par "parlors" of undertakers abound. You may find them sprinkled all about
\par the lower East Side. Frequent on Hudson Street, and, say, on Varick.
\par Quaint and curious places, these. Very human in their appeal. Tiny
\par places, most of them.
\par 
\par One such cozy crib I know on Greenwich Avenue. Has a stained glass
\par screen in the window, suggesting a good deal the style of window
\par ornamentation popular with that American institution lately
\par deceased--the saloon. The social spirit rife in small undertaking shops,
\par at least in some of them, is pleasant to observe. Business there not
\par being pressing, and life moving in these inns of death in a leisurely
\par and quiet current, neighborly amenities appear to be much cultivated.
\par 
\par This place of which I speak has, particularly in the evenings, much the
\par air of a club, where choice spirits of the locality foregather to
\par discuss politics, it may be, and the more engrossing forms of sport,
\par such as boxing. And perhaps relish a little game at cards. I often pass
\par this place at night and feel a warmth of spirit at the hum of jovial
\par social contact within.
\par 
\par I like, too, the way the undertakers' shops of the humble and obscure
\par carry on cheek by jowl with the familiar, homely, friendly things of
\par life. This gives Death a neighborly sort of air. On my walks in that
\par quarter I always give a friendly glance to the windows of a "Cremation
\par Ass'n" on Eighth Avenue, on one side of it a delicatessen shop, on the
\par other a "loan office," in the basement below a plumber.
\par 
\par Attractive, too, is it to consider how founders of tidy undertaking
\par houses have become personages and are held in revered esteem. For they
\par are not, it would seem, like unto those who have established just
\par ordinary businesses. This I will show you:
\par 
\par At a corner of Twenty-third Street, over a telegraph office, is an
\par establishment of some caste. Window legend reads:
\par "Undertakers--Cremations--Night and Day--Interments in all Cemeteries."
\par The last phrase reminds me of the way my old friend James Huneker used
\par to date his letters to me from Brooklyn. They began, "Flatbush by the
\par C--emeteries." But that's not the point. It's a pity the alert English
\par writer who recently visited us and discovered a statue of General Grant
\par in Grant Park, overlooking the Blackstone (where nobody had ever seen
\par one before), and that the huge bust of Washington Irving in Bryant Park,
\par behind the New York Public Library, was an effigy of Father George
\par Washington--it's a rotten shame E. V. Lucas missed this corner while
\par here.
\par 
\par Because when you go round this corner you are to look up just above the
\par level of your head. (Though I'm afraid you neglect to do this.) There on
\par a ledge is a grand sight. It's a bust of God. Fact! Anyhow, looks just
\par like pictures of God William Blake used to make. Old gentleman. Noble
\par brow. Patriarchal beard, flowing out in a pattern of rhythmical
\par waves--most realistically mildewed by time and weather.... But, no;
\par inquiry reveals that it's a likeness of the founder of this "old
\par established" undertaking concern.
\par 
\par Then there's that place a short step down Eighth Avenue. It declares on
\par its sign that it is the "original" house bearing the name of the
\par Reverend gentleman who conducts it. When you look through the glass in
\par the door you view just within, displayed on an ornamental easel, a
\par life-size crayon portrait, enlarged from a photograph, of a
\par distinguished-looking person wearing brown Dundreary whiskers and a top
\par hat. One corner of the portrait is gracefully draped in an American
\par flag.
\par 
\par Yes; you'd be surprised how strong undertakers are on patriotism. Hard
\par by here, next door to a dentist advertising "painless extraction," you
\par find a firm of "Funeral Directors" where conspicuous among such
\par ornaments as tall, bronze lamps with big shades, a spittoon, a little
\par model of a casket and an urn, is a large bronze bust of Abraham Lincoln.
\par A plate says: "No Charge for Rooms or Chapels for Funerals." And above
\par stairs is seen a row of somewhat ecclesiastical stained-glass windows.
\par Though we are given to understand by an advertisement that the
\par atmosphere of these chapels is "non-sectarian."
\par 
\par Then over on Third Avenue (where there are lots and lots of undertakers)
\par is a place. Always sitting just within the doorway, very silent, a
\par stout, very solemn individual wearing a large, black derby hat and big,
\par round, green-lens spectacles. Above him on the wall a framed lithograph
\par in colors of George Washington--beside it a thermometer. In the window a
\par rubber-plant. Rubber-plants varying in size from infant to elephant are
\par in the windows of all undertakers. The symbolism of this decoration I
\par know not. Beside the plant an infant's white casket, proclaimed by a
\par poster which leans against it to be composed of "purity metal." In some
\par places the casket, perhaps not of purity metal, is protected by being
\par enclosed in a glass case. The name of the proprietor of this shop, as
\par given on his sign, ends in "skey." Set in the door-frame is the usual
\par "Night Bell." And, as always in undertakers' shops, the card of a
\par "notary public" is displayed. Next door "Family Shoes" are featured.
\par 
\par Only yesterday afternoon I was looking in at the window of an undertaker
\par on Second Avenue, one I had just found. Along the curb before the door
\par a string of rather frayed and wobbly-looking "hacks," with a rusty-black
\par hearse at the head. Horses to these vehicles drowsy in disposition,
\par moth-eaten in effect as to pelt, and in the visibility of their
\par anatomical structure suggesting that they might have been drawn by
\par Albert D\'fcrer in some particularly melancholy mood.
\par 
\par In groups along the edge of the sidewalk, conversing in subdued tones,
\par the Dickensesque drivers of this caravan. Tall and gaunt, some; short
\par and stout, others. Skirt coat on one, "sack" coat on another. Alike in
\par this: frayed and rusty and weather-beaten, all. And hard, very hard of
\par countenance. Each topped by a very tall, and quite cylindrical hat of
\par mussed, shoddy-black, plush texture. Hangovers, so to say, these
\par figures, from New York's hansom-cab days, or the time in London of the
\par "four-wheeler."
\par 
\par No, not altogether. There was something piquant--Villonesque, or
\par jovial--Rabelaisian, about the pickpockets of that tribe. These solemn
\par mummers strike a ghoulish note. But at the same time, out here in the
\par sane and cheerful sunlight, they don't look real. Create an odd
\par impression. Strikes you as about as queer, this bunch, as if a lot of
\par actors from a melodrama should turn up in the street with their makeup
\par on and gravely pretend to belong to real life.
\par 
\par "Perhaps," I thought, "there is a funeral, or something, going on
\par inside, and I should not be gaping in at this window."
\par 
\par Out of doorway pops little, rotund man, oily countenance. "Are you
\par looking for anybody?" he asks.
\par 
\par "Here," I said inwardly, "is where I get moved on." No, I told him, I
\par was just observing his window.
\par 
\par "Ah!" he cried, immensely flattered. He waved his hand back toward a
\par couple of little, marble crosses with hearts carved in relief on the
\par base. "You don't often see that, do you? Do you, now? They're sixty
\par years old. Made out of a single piece!"
\par 
\par But the saddest thing about undertakers' shops is to go by where was one
\par long familiar to you and find it gone. There was a splendid little place
\par which it was a great consolation to me to admire. That building is now
\par given over to an enterprise called "The Goody Shop." Its lofty dignity
\par and deep eloquence are gone! It looks like a department store. It is
\par labelled, with the blare of a brass band, "The Home of Pussy Willow
\par Chocolates."
\par 
