\par CHAPTER IV
\par 
\par THE HAIR CUT THAT WENT TO MY HEAD
\par 
\par 
\par I did not expect anything in particular when I went in. Though, indeed,
\par it is a very famous place. That is, the hotel is--the Brevoort.
\par 
\par The name itself, Brevoort, is very rich in romantic Knickerbocker
\par associations. Probably you know all about that. Or, possibly, you don't
\par know--or have forgotten. Well, you do know how Broadway curves around
\par there at Tenth Street. That ought to recall Hendrick Brevoort to you.
\par His farm was all about this neighborhood. Caused this kink, he did, so
\par it is said.
\par 
\par This valorous descendant of the old burgher defied the commissioners to
\par destroy his homestead, which lay in the proposed path of Broadway. Or to
\par cut down a favorite tree which blocked the intended course of Eleventh
\par Street. Stood at his threshold with a blunderbuss in his trembling old
\par hands (so the story has it), when the workmen arrived to carry out their
\par instructions to demolish the house--and carried his point so
\par effectively that Broadway was deflected from its course, while Eleventh
\par Street between Broadway and Fourth Avenue was never completed. Grace
\par Church, which now stands at about where valiant Henry stood that day,
\par was built by a descendant of his, the architect also of St. Patrick's
\par Cathedral.
\par 
\par I like to think of these matters sometimes when I enter the cool cream
\par beauty of this ancient frame hostelry.
\par 
\par Also of another Henry Brevoort, a descendant of the original proprietor
\par of the farm in New Netherland, who built the substantial old double
\par house at the corner of Ninth Street and Fifth Avenue. Fine iron
\par balconies, pillared door, within a small green enclosure, and a walled
\par garden to one side: all preserved.
\par 
\par Here was held (in 1840) the first masked ball given in New York. An
\par affair of picturesque celebrity, on account of the occasion it furnished
\par a famous beauty of the day, Miss Mathilda Barclay, daughter of Anthony
\par Barclay, the British consul, to elope in fancy dress, domino and mask
\par with a certain young Burgwyne of South Carolina, of whom her parents had
\par unamiable views. She went as Lalla Rookh and he as Feramorz, and in
\par this disguise they slipped away from the ball, at four in the morning,
\par and were married. That, it seems to me, is the way for a man who does
\par not enjoy solemn ceremonies to be happy while getting married.
\par 
\par Across the way, at the corner of Eighth Street, the mellow white hotel
\par maintains the distinguished name, and touches "the Avenue" with a very
\par aromatic French flavor. Famous for its cuisine, largely patronized by
\par the transient French population of the city, a habitual port of call of
\par many painters and writers, the scene of the annual Illustrators' Ball,
\par and so on.
\par 
\par I like within the frequent spectacle of gentlemen of magnificent bulk
\par and huge black beards, in general effect impressively suggesting the
\par probability of their all being Academicians. I like the fact (or the
\par hypothesis) that all the waiters are Looeys and Sharses and Gastongs. I
\par like the little marble-top tables with wire spindle legs. I like the
\par lady patrons (Oh! immensely) who are frequently very chic (and with
\par exquisite ankles). I like the young gentlemen customers, who (many of
\par them) look exactly as though their faces were modelled in wax, and who
\par wear the sort of delicate moustaches that are advertised in _Vanity
\par Fair_.
\par 
\par But even more I like the quaintness of the scene without doors. There
\par along the curb, you recall, stand (in summer beneath the pleasant
\par greenery of drooping trees), awaiting hire, a succession of those
\par delightful, open, low-swung, horse-drawn vehicles, victorias, which were
\par the fashionable thing at the period named by Mrs. Wharton "The Age of
\par Innocence." The romantically leisurely drivers of these unbelievably
\par leisurely craft are perfectly turned out to be, so to say, in the
\par picture. They affect coachmen's coats (piquantly tempered by age) with
\par large silver buttons and, in mild weather, top hats constructed of
\par straw, painted black. In some instances these coachmen are
\par "colored"--which is a very pleasant thing, too, I think.
\par 
\par This hotel, naturally, has figured in a number of pieces of fiction. In
\par Samuel Merwin's novel "The Trufflers" it is the Parisian, where
\par Greenwich Village, when in funds, dines, lunches, breakfasts in the
\par little rooms which you enter from the Avenue, directly under the wide
\par front steps, or from the side street through the bar, and where Upper
\par West Side, when seeking the quaintly foreign dissociated from squalor,
\par goes up the steps into the airy eating rooms with full length hinged
\par windows to dine. And where (in this book) the young lady whose blooming
\par presence in the barber shop in the basement invites you to manicure
\par attentions gives rise to some very dramatic occurrences. The place, this
\par shop, of Marius (as called in the story), "the one barber in New York
\par who does not ask 'Wet or dry.'"
\par 
\par Now I had plumb forgotten about this barber's celebrity in fiction when
\par the other day I entered this shop. And I was struck with embarrassment
\par by the immediate attentions of so very distinguished a figure as that
\par which sprang forward to assist me out of my coat. I thought surely this
\par gentleman must be some kind of an Ambassador, who had perhaps mistaken
\par me for the President. A slimmish man, obviously very French. Amazingly,
\par overwhelmingly polite. Fine, a very fine beard. Long. Swept his chest.
\par Pointed. Auburn. Wavy. Silken. Shot delicately with grey. Beautifully
\par kept. Responded gently to the breeze--waving softly to and fro. A most
\par beautiful beard--oh, my! And a glorious crown of hair! It rose from the
\par line of its parting in a billowing wave, then fell with a luxuriant and
\par graceful sweep to his ear. Only when he had tucked me in the chair could
\par I realize that this must be the head barber. I had never before had the
\par honor of being served by, or even of having seen himself, the proprietor
\par here.
\par 
\par Then I mentioned Mr. Merwin's book. He took from a drawer several copies
\par of _The Saturday Evening Post_, in which periodical the story had
\par appeared serially, proudly to exhibit them to me. So it was we fell to
\par chatting of his place. He had been here some sixteen or eighteen years.
\par Before he had opened his shop this room had been several tiny rooms;
\par Cleveland Moffett had for a time occupied them as a residence, and had
\par here written his first book. My friend gayly produced a copy of an old
\par magazine article by Mr. Moffett in which mention was given the shop.
\par 
\par        *       *       *       *       *
\par 
\par Shaved, I was straightened up to have my hair trimmed. And, being for a
\par moment free to look about. I spied a card on the wall. It said:
\par 
\par       SILK HATS IRONED
\par             25_\'a2_
\par     COUP-DE-FER-AU CHAPEAU
\par 
\par But, my goodness! That was not all. No, indeed!
\par 
\par _This very man who was cutting my hair_ had cut the hair of General
\par Joffre--when he had his hair here in the United States. At "Mr. Frick's
\par house," where they were guests, he had attended the distinguished party
\par on its mission here. He would go in the morning, stay until they had
\par gone forth for the day; return in the afternoon, and spruce them up for
\par their evening out.
\par 
\par And what did they say, these great men of might?
\par 
\par Well, Joffre didn't say much. They were always out late--hurry out
\par again. He shaved some of them "almost in the bath." That fellow, the
\par Blue Devil,--one leg--cane--but back and forth from his bath quick like
\par anybody. He was the most talkative:
\par 
\par "I could not but laugh at what he told me. I asked, 'Do you speak
\par English?' 'No,' he said, 'but I ought to.' 'How is that?' I asked.
\par 'Because,' he said, 'I'm half American.' 'Oh!' I said, 'your father then
\par was American and your mother French?' 'No,' he said. 'Ah!' I say, 'then
\par your mother was American and your father was French.' Do you
\par understand? I say that to him. 'No,' he say; 'no.' 'What then?' I ask.
\par 'Why,' he say, 'I have one leg in France and one leg in America.' I
\par could not but laugh. Do you understand?"
\par 
\par When the visitors had departed Mr. Frick asked my friend for his bill.
\par "Oh, no!" he said; "he would take nothing but the great honor for his
\par little services."
\par 
\par My hair cut was finished. As I paid him (there being in this case, I
\par felt, no such great honor for his little services), he showed me a
\par drawing on the wall of a poodle he had one time owned. It had died. Very
\par sad. He was very fond of dogs. Of bred dogs, that is. He bred them
\par himself. He handed me his card as a professional dog fancier. It read:
\par 
\par                    CHINK A TU KENNELS
\par     CHOW CHOWS, PEKINGESES, POMERANIANS, ALL COLORS
\par               FROM PRICE WINNING STOCK
\par                MINIATURE SPECIMENS
\par         AT STUD. PEKINGESE, WONDERFUL SON OF WENTY
\par              OF HYDEGREE. FEE REASONABLE.
\par     AT STUD. LORD CHOLMONDELEY III SON OF CHAMPION
\par                  LORD CHOLMONDELEY II.
\par                TOY DOGS BOARDED
\par                   MME. HENRI GRECHEN
\par 
\par Yes, that morning he had done "some manicure work" for his dogs. She
\par looked up, the manicurist (milk-white blonde, black velvet gown), and
\par said, "Do you use the clippers?"
\par 
\par He: "Yes, of course. But not powder and polish. Quick, they want. Not
\par hold hands for hour--conversation about best show in town."
\par 
\par He bowed, very low, as I crossed his threshold. I turned and bowed, very
\par low, to him. A man of many parts and a barber illustrious in his
\par profession. It was some time before my head cooled off.
