\par 
\par CHAPTER V
\par 
\par SEEING MR. CHESTERTON
\par 
\par 
\par Somewhat later in this article I am going to present an "interview" (or
\par something like that) with Gilbert E. Chesterton. At least I hope I am
\par going to present it. Yesterday it looked as though I might have to get
\par up my interview without having seen Mr. Chesterton. Though today the
\par situation appears somewhat brighter. "Seeing" Mr. Chesterton (on his
\par visit over here, at any rate) seems to be a complicated matter.
\par 
\par As anything which gives some view of the workings of the Chestertonian
\par machinery ought to be of interest to all who can lay claim to the happy
\par state of mind of being Chestertonites, I'll begin by telling the
\par proceedings so far in this affair. Then as matters progress to supply me
\par with more material (if they do progress) I'll continue.
\par 
\par I one time wrote an article in which I told with what surprising ease I
\par saw Mr. Chesterton several years ago in England. Without acquaintances
\par in England, some sort of a fit of impudence seized me. I wrote Mr.
\par Chesterton a letter, communicating to him the intelligence that I had
\par arrived in London, that it was my belief that he was one of the noblest
\par and most interesting monuments in England; and I asked him if he
\par supposed that he could be "viewed" by me, at some street corner, say, at
\par a time appointed, as he rumbled past in his triumphal car. Mrs.
\par Chesterton replied directly in a note that her husband wished to thank
\par me for my letter and to say that he would be pleased if I cared to come
\par down to spend an afternoon with him at Beaconsfield. Mr. Chesterton, I
\par later recollected, had no means readily at hand of ascertaining whether
\par or not I was an American pickpocket; but from the deference of his
\par manner I was led to suspect that he vaguely supposed I was perhaps the
\par owner of the New York _Times_, or somebody like that.
\par 
\par This escapade of my visit to Overroads I suppose it was that put into
\par the head of the editor of _The Bookman_ the notion that I was a person
\par with ready access to Mr. Chesterton. So I was served with a hurry-up
\par assignment to see him and to deliver an article about my seeing him for
\par the March number of the magazine before that issue, then largely in the
\par hands of the printers, got off the press. Thus my adventures, the
\par termination of which are at present considerably up in the air, began.
\par 
\par I at once wrote to Mr. Chesterton at the hotel where at the moment he
\par was in Boston. At the same time I wrote to Lee Keedick ("Manager of the
\par World's Most Celebrated Lecturers") at his office in New York. I had
\par picked up the impression that a lecture manager of this caliber owned
\par outright the time of a visiting celebrity whom he promoted, and that you
\par couldn't even telephone the celebrity without the manager's permission.
\par I didn't know that you couldn't telephone him anyway. Or that you
\par couldn't telephone the manager either.
\par 
\par Mr. Keedick very promptly replied that he would be very glad to do
\par everything that he could to bring about the interview. Or at least I
\par received a very courteous letter to this effect which bore a signature
\par which I took to be that of Mr. Keedick.
\par 
\par Mr. Chesterton was not to be back in New York until after a couple of
\par days. On the day set for his return to town I attempted to communicate
\par with Mr. Keedick by telephone. I am (I fear) a bit slow at the etiquette
\par of telephones, and I so far provoked a young woman at the other end of
\par the wire as to cause her to demand rather sharply, "Who are you?" This
\par matter adjusted amicably, Mr. Keedick it developed was so utterly remote
\par from attainment that I am not altogether sure such a person exists.
\par However, another gentleman responded cordially enough. Still, it seemed
\par to me (upon reflection) that in a matter of this urgent nature I had
\par been at fault in having failed to obtain more definiteness in the matter
\par of an appointment. So I went round to the manager's office. Very affably
\par received. Presented to a gentleman fetched for that purpose from another
\par room, where he had been closeted with someone else. Mr. Widdecombe, this
\par gentleman's name. Introduced as Mr. Chesterton's secretary. A pronounced
\par Englishman in effect. Said very politely indeed, several times, that he
\par was "delighted." Mr. Chesterton, however, was going away tomorrow. Would
\par return two days hence. Made, Mr. Widdecombe, very careful memorandum of
\par my address.
\par 
\par In due course of time thought I'd better look up Mr. Widdecombe
\par again--his memorandum might have got mislaid. Telephoned lecture bureau.
\par Satisfied young lady of honorable intentions. Explained matters all over
\par again to owner of agreeable masculine voice. Received assurance that Mr.
\par Widdecombe would be reminded at once of pressing state of affairs.
\par Disturbed by uneventful flight of time, called in at lecture bureau once
\par more. Learned that Mr. Widdecombe had not yet turned up. They, however,
\par would try to get him on the wire at the Biltmore for me. Yes, he was
\par there, but the fourth floor desk of the hotel said he had just gone into
\par Mr. Chesterton's room, and so (as, apparently, everyone ought to know)
\par could not be communicated with just now. He would call up shortly.
\par Lecture people suggested that I go round to the hotel. If Mr. Widdecombe
\par called in the meantime they'd tell him I was on my way over.
\par 
\par Thought I recognized the gentleman stepping out of the elevator at the
\par fourth floor. I did not know whether or not it was at all what you did
\par to lay hold of an Englishman in so abrupt a fashion, but concluded this
\par would have to be done. Mr. Widdecombe was all courtesy. The point,
\par however, was that "Mr. Chesterton had had an hour of it this morning.
\par Had had an hour of it." This afternoon he was getting off some work for
\par London. Then tomorrow, of course, would be his lecture. My matter _did_
\par seem to be urgent. But what could "we" do? Mr. Chesterton was a
\par "beautiful man." He had been so hospitable to the gentlemen of the
\par press. But if we should go in to him now he would say, "Dear me! Dear
\par me!" I readily saw, of course, that this would be an awful thing,
\par still....
\par 
\par Mr. Widdecombe was somewhat inclined to think that we "could do" this:
\par Suppose I should come to the Times Square Theatre the next afternoon, at
\par about a quarter to five, call for him at the stage entrance. Yes, he
\par thought we could arrange it that way. I could talk to Mr. Chesterton in
\par the taxi on the way back to the hotel. Perhaps detain him for a few
\par moments afterward. Mr. Widdecombe smiled very pleasantly indeed at the
\par idea of so happy a solution of our difficulties. And I myself was rather
\par taken by the notion of interviewing Mr. Chesterton in a cab. The fancy
\par occurred to me that this was perhaps after all the most fitting place
\par in the whole world in which to interview Mr. Chesterton.
\par 
\par So everything seems to be all right.
\par 
\par        *       *       *       *       *
\par 
\par New complications! (This is the following day.) In the morning mail a
\par letter from Mrs. Chesterton, saying so sorry not to have answered my
\par letter before, but it had been almost impossible to deal with the
\par correspondence that had reached them since they arrived in America. Her
\par husband asked her to say he would very much like to see me. And could I
\par call at the hotel round about twelve o'clock on Sunday morning? No
\par difficulty about meeting Mr. Chesterton in the kindness of that. But
\par Sunday might be quite too late for the purpose of my article. So I'll go
\par to the theatre anyway, and I'll certainly accept all Chesterton
\par invitations.
\par 
\par        *       *       *       *       *
\par 
\par A colored dignitary in a uniform sumptuously befrogged with gold lace
\par who commanded the portal directed me to the stage entrance. I passed
\par into a dark and apparently deserted passage and paused to consider my
\par next step. Before me was a tall, brightly lighted aperture, and coming
\par through this I caught the sound, gently rising and falling, of a rather
\par dulcet voice. A slight pause in the flow of individual utterance, and
\par directly following upon this a soft wave as of the intimate mirth of an
\par audience wafted about what was evidently the auditorium beyond. Just
\par then a figure duskily defined itself before me and addressed me in a
\par gruff whisper. I was directed to proceed around the passage extending
\par ahead, to Room Three. I should have passed behind a tall screen (I
\par recognized later), but inadvertently I passed before it, and suddenly
\par found myself the target of thousands upon thousands of eyes--and the
\par unmistakable back of Mr. Chesterton looming in the brilliance directly
\par before me.
\par 
\par Regaining the passage, I found a door labelled A 3. Receiving no
\par response to my knock, I opened it; and peered into a lighted cubby-hole
\par about one-third the size of a very small hall bed-room. The only object
\par of any conspicuousness presented to me was a huge, dark garment hanging
\par from a hook in the wall. It seemed to be--ah! yes; it was a voluminous
\par overcoat with a queer cape attached. So; I was in the right shop all
\par right.
\par 
\par I thought I ought to look around and try to find somebody. I wandered
\par into what I suppose are the "wings" of the theatre. Anyway, I had an
\par excellent view, from one side, of the stage and of a portion of one
\par gallery. The only person quite near me was a fireman, who paid no
\par attention whatever to me, but continued to gaze out steadily at Mr.
\par Chesterton, with an expression of countenance which (as well as I could
\par decipher it) registered fascinated incomprehension. I attempted to lean
\par against what I supposed was a wall, but to my great fright the whole
\par structure nearly tumbled over as I barely touched it. Perceiving a chair
\par the other side of the fireman, I passed before him, sat down, and gave
\par myself over to contemplation of the spectacle.
\par 
\par My first impression, I think, was that Mr. Chesterton was speaking in so
\par conversational a key that I should have expected to hear cries of
\par "Louder!" coming from all over the house. But from the lighted
\par expressions of the faces far away in the corner of the gallery visible
\par to me he was apparently being followed perfectly. I did not then know
\par that at his first public appearance in New York he had referred to his
\par lecturing voice as the original mouse that came from the mountain. Nor
\par had I then seen Francis Hackett's comment upon it that: "It wasn't, of
\par course, a bellow. Neither was it a squeak." Mr. Hackett adds that it is
\par "the ordinary good lecture-hall voice." I do not feel that this quite
\par describes my own impression of it the other afternoon. Rather, perhaps,
\par I should put the matter in this way. My recollection of the conversation
\par I had with him in 1914 at Beaconsfield is that there was a much more
\par ruddy quality to his voice then than the other day, and more, much more,
\par in the turn of his talk a racy note of the burly world.
\par 
\par Perhaps he feels that before a "representative" American audience one
\par should be altogether what used to be called "genteel." At any rate, I
\par certainly heard the other day the voice of a modest, very friendly,
\par cultivated, nimble-minded gentleman, speaking with the nicety of
\par precision more frequently observed among English people than among
\par Americans. There was in it even a trace of a tone as though it were most
\par at home within university walls. Though, indeed, I am glad to say, Mr.
\par Chesterton did not abstain from erudite, amused, and amusing allusions
\par to the society most at home in "pubs." And I cannot but suspect that
\par perhaps he would have been found a shade more amusing even than he was
\par if ... but, no matter.
\par 
\par One gentleman who has written a piece about his impressions of Mr.
\par Chesterton's lectures here felt that his audience didn't have quite as
\par much of a good time as the members of it expected to have. I heard only
\par a brief, concluding portion of one lecture. The portion of the audience
\par which came most closely before my observation were those seated at the
\par well filled press table, which stood directly between the speaker and
\par me. These na\'efve beings gave every evidence of getting, to speak
\par temperately, their money's worth.
\par 
\par Though Mr. Chesterton turned the pages of notes as he spoke, he could
\par not be said to have read his lecture. On the other hand, it was clear
\par that he did not appreciably depart from a carefully prepared
\par disquisition.
\par 
\par The tumbled mane which tops him off seemed more massive even than
\par before. It did not, though, appear quite so tumbled. I think there had
\par been an effort (since 1914) to brush it quite nicely. Certainly it is
\par ever so much greyer. I think in my earlier article I said something like
\par this: "Mr. Chesterton has so remarkably red a face that his smallish
\par moustache seems lightish in color against it." While Mr. Chesterton's
\par face today could not be described as pale, it looks more like a face and
\par less like a glowing full moon. The moustache is darker against it; less
\par bristling than before, more straggly.
\par 
\par A couple of our recent commentators upon Mr. Chesterton have taken a
\par fling at the matter of his not being as huge as, it seems to them, he
\par has been made out to be. I remember that when I saw him before I was
\par even startled to find him more monstrous than even he had appeared in
\par his pictures. He appears to take part a good deal in pageants in
\par England; and recent photographs of him as Falstaff, or Tony Weller, or
\par Mr. Pickwick, or somebody like that, have not altogether squared up with
\par my recollection of him. True, he has not quite the bulk he had before;
\par but it is a captious critic, I should say, who would not consider him
\par sufficiently elephantine for all ordinary purposes.
\par 
\par He was saying (much to the delight of the house) when I became one of
\par the audience, that he would "not regard this as the time or the occasion
\par for him to comment upon the lid on liquor." A bit later in the course of
\par his answer to the question he had propounded, "Shall We Abolish the
\par Inevitable," he got an especially good hand when he remarked: "People
\par nowadays do not like statements having authority--but they will accept
\par any statement without authority." He concluded his denunciation of the
\par idea of fatalism with the declaration: "Whatever man is, he is not in
\par one sense a part of nature." "He has committed crimes, Crimes," he
\par repeated--with gusto in the use of the word,--"and performed heroisms
\par which no animal ever tried to do. Let us hold ourselves free from the
\par boundary of the material order of things, for so shall we have a chance
\par in the future to do things far too historic for prophecy."
\par 
\par I darted back toward Room Three, ran into Mr. Widdecombe, we wheeled,
\par and saw the mountain approaching. Whereas before, this off-stage place
\par had been deserted, now the scene was populous--with the figures of
\par agitated young women. Mr. Widdecombe, however, with much valiance
\par secured Mr. Chesterton. "Yes, yes," he said, and (remarkable remark!),
\par "I had the pleasure of meeting you in England." He glanced about rather
\par nervously at the dancing figures seeking to obtain him, and led the way
\par for me into the dressing room. Mr. Widdecombe pulled the door to from
\par without.
\par 
\par I am far from being as large as Mr. Chesterton, but the two of us
\par closeted in that compartment was an absurdity. Mr. Chesterton eclipsed a
\par chair, and beamed upon me with an expression of Cheeryble-like
\par brightness. Upon his arrival in New York he had declared to the press
\par that he would not write a book of his impressions of the United States.
\par I asked him if, after being here a week or so, he had changed his mind
\par as to this determination. "Not definitely," he said, "not definitely.
\par But, of course, one could never tell what one might do." He might write
\par a book about us, then? Yes, he might. Did he think it at all likely that
\par he would take up residence over here? A very joyous smile: "One's own
\par country is best," he said. Rumors had several times been afloat that he
\par had entered the Roman Catholic Church. Would he say whether there was
\par any likelihood of his doing this? He was an Anglican Catholic, he
\par replied. Not a Roman Catholic--yet. That was not to say that he might
\par not be--if the English Church should become more Protestant. What was
\par his next book to be? Had he any project in mind of going to Turkey, or
\par Mexico, or some such place? No; the only books he was working on at
\par present were a new volume of short stories and a book (smiling again
\par widely) on eugenics. He knew Mr. Lucas, of course? "Yes, fine fellow."
\par Did he know Frank Swinnerton? No. What was.... But the door was popped
\par open. Several persons were waiting for him, among them Mrs. Chesterton.
\par I helped him into the cape-coat. Stood behind the door so that when it
\par was opened he could get out. "You know Mr. Holliday," he said to Mrs.
\par Chesterton. "Thank you, so much," he said to me. And was whisked away.
\par 
\par        *       *       *       *       *
\par 
\par Sunday at the hotel. He was late in arriving. I thought it would be
\par pleasanter to wait a bit out in front. Expected he would drive up soon
\par in a taxi. Then I saw him coming around the corner, walking, rolling
\par slowly from side to side like a great ship, Mrs. Chesterton with him--a
\par little lady whose stature suggested the idea of a yacht gracefully
\par cruising alongside the huge craft. I wonder if, nowadays when most
\par writers seem to try to look like something else, Mr. Chesterton knows
\par how overwhelmingly like a great literary figure he looks.
\par 
\par When we were seated, I asked if he had any dope on his "New Jerusalem"
\par book. He began to tell me how surprised he had been to find Jerusalem as
\par it is. But the substance of this you may find in the book. He expressed
\par sympathy with the idea of Zionism. Remarked that he "might become a
\par Zionist if it could be accomplished in Zion." All that he could find to
\par tell me about his "New Jerusalem" was that it had been "written on the
\par spot." Seemed very disinclined to talk about his own books. Said his
\par feeling in general about each one of them was that he "hoped something
\par would happen to it before anybody saw it."
\par 
\par His surprise at Jerusalem suggested to me the question, Had he been
\par surprised at the United States--what he had seen of it? But he dodged
\par giving any "view" of us. His only comment was on the "multitudinous
\par wooden houses."
\par 
\par Had he met many American authors? The one most recently met, a day or so
\par ago in Northampton, though he had met him before in England, was a
\par gentleman he liked very much. He was so thin Mr. Chesterton thought the
\par two of them "should go around together." His name? Gerald Stanley Lee.
\par 
\par But there is not a particle more of time that I can spend on this
\par article.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par CHAPTER VI
\par 
\par WHEN IS A GREAT CITY A SMALL VILLAGE?
\par 
\par 
\par How many times you have noticed it! Regular phenomenon. Suddenly, within
\par a few hours, the whole nature of the great city is changed--your city
\par and mine, New York or Chicago, or Boston or Buffalo or Philadelphia.
\par 
\par Though nobody seems to say much about it afterward. Just sort of take
\par the thing for granted.
\par 
\par It is just like Armistice Night, every once in awhile. Total strangers
\par suddenly begin to call each other "Neighbor." Voices everywhere become
\par jollier. Numerous passersby begin to whistle and sing. People go with a
\par skip and a jump. Catcalls are heard. Groups may be seen all around going
\par arm in arm, and here and there with arms about necks. Anybody speaks to
\par you merrily. Merrily you speak to anybody. All eyes shine. Roses are in
\par every cheek. Hurry is abandoned. Small boys run wild. Nobody now objects
\par to their stealing a ride. It is fun to see their swinging legs dangling
\par over the tail of every wagon. Sour human nature is purged. Good humor
\par reigns. Hurrah!
\par 
\par I mean on the night of a big snow.
\par 
\par This year it looked for long as though we were going to be done out of
\par this truly Dickensean festival. Seemed like we were going to be like
\par those unfortunate people in Southern California, who never have any
\par winter to cheer them up. How tired they must get of their wives and
\par neighbors, with it bland summer all the time. Perhaps that is the reason
\par there is such a promiscuous domestic life out there.
\par 
\par Young Will Shakespeare had the dope. He piped the weather for jollity
\par and pep. "When blood is nipp'd"--"a merry note!"
\par 
\par You remember how it was this time: Spring all winter--and spring fever,
\par too, a good many of us had all the while. (My doctor said it was
\par "malaria" with me.) We were congratulating ourselves that we were going
\par to "get by" without any "blizzards" at all this year. We became "softy."
\par We guarded ourselves with our umbrellas against the shower. We became
\par prudent. And what is it Stevenson says of that? "So soon as prudence has
\par begun to grow up in the brain, like a dismal fungus, it finds its first
\par expression in a paralysis of generous acts. The victim begins to shrink
\par spiritually; he develops a fancy for parlors with a regulated
\par temperature, and takes his morality on the principle of thin shoes and
\par tepid milk."
\par 
\par Then one night there came a tinkle in the temperature as of sleigh
\par bells. And the town, the world sank into a soft blanket of white. Were
\par you out then? Ah! you should have been. You were not, I hope, in a
\par parlor with a regulated temperature.
\par 
\par Well, anyhow, everybody else was out. The cross streets of the big city
\par had "all to oncet" taken on the air of a small town "sociable." Shadowy
\par multitudes seemed to sprout up out of the ground. The sidewalks,
\par especially those usually so deserted at this hour, now ahum with dark
\par busy bowing figures, rang and clanged gayly with the sound of scoop and
\par shovel. In the democratic, jovial, village-like spirit of the occasion,
\par many of the workers (those more staid and portly ones) removed their
\par coats. Every here and there an areaway held, in a holiday effect, a
\par cluster of bare-headed maid-servants--the "gallery" of the shovellers,
\par whose presence tended to make of the task of clearing the sidewalk a
\par night-hour lark.
\par 
\par Voices in the street, as you know, and laughter there, is never so
\par musical as above snow-stilled pavements. Then, too, cheery echoes are
\par abroad among the recesses between the houses, in the courts and down the
\par ways where packages are delivered. The shovellers good-naturedly banter
\par one another and pass a cordial jest with those who travel by. And every
\par here and there the rich contralto of negro mirth is heard.
\par 
\par I do not know that the city's parks are not a finer spectacle under snow
\par than in the summer--their dark glistening branches laden \'e0 la Christmas
\par card, and, after dark, their festoons of lamps more twinkling and more
\par yellow than at any other time.
\par 
\par Along Broadway what a whirl! The street like an arena, hordes of
\par gladiators in doughty combat with the onslaught of the storm, snow-carts
\par banging and backing about (horses seem to stomp and snort and rear more
\par in a snowstorm than at any other time), new ridiculously miniature
\par "caterpillar tractors" performing like toy tanks at war, traffic in a
\par hilarious tangle, street cars crawling along looking more than ever
\par before like prodigious cat-eyed bugs. Here with a terrific buzz comes
\par one all dark furiously thrashing the snow from side to side by means of
\par revolving brooms beneath. The crowds an animated silhouette against the
\par whitened air. One wants to hop and shout one feels so much alive.
\par 
\par Lots of funny things happen. A taxicab there has got stuck in a drift.
\par It whirs in a passion. Wallows forward. Runs its nose up a little
\par hillock of hard crusted snow. Stops. Makes a fine hubbub. Slides back,
\par stilled, exhausted. Tries again. Same thing repeated. A pounding is
\par heard on the inside of the door. Chauffeur reaches back his hand to turn
\par handle of door. Something is wrong. He climbs down. Pulls at door.
\par Nothing doing. Door has apparently been sprung somehow. Taxi is now
\par observed to be a bit listed to one side. Pounding, louder than before,
\par again heard from inside. Conductor from nearby car comes to side of
\par chauffeur. Also policeman. All lay hold of each other and pull with
\par united effort at taxi door. Door flies open. Closely knit group of
\par chauffeur, conductor and policeman nearly tumbles backward into snow.
\par From cab door descends tall, elegant figure in evening clothes and top
\par hat. Followed by even more elegant figure of slender lady in opera
\par cloak. For some reason she appears to be very angry, and shakes her fist
\par at her three humble liberators. The couple seek some path, from the
\par trampled oasis where they stand, through the drifts to the sidewalk.
\par There is none. Her dazzling skirt she has caught high from the mess
\par about her feet. Perhaps a yard of pale yellow silken hose is revealed
\par above her satin pumps. Finally in desperation the two plunge forward,
\par taking gigantic steps, sinking knee-deep at every onward move,
\par tottering, swaying and at length fairly scrambling toward the haven of
\par the curb. The dozens along the sidewalk who have been held spellbound by
\par what they have found to be so delicious a comedy turn to one another
\par with delighted smiles--and move along again on their way.
\par 
\par It is things like this always happening all about which make snow-storm
\par nights in the city such a hippodrome affair, and all the world akin.
\par 
\par Over on the Avenue busses are busily pushing plows hitched on before.
\par There one has got stalled in a drift. It whirs and buzzes and backs and
\par starts and whirs and buzzes over and over again. No use, it seems.
\par Still, draped along the curb, the spectators stand, unmindful of the
\par gale, as absorbed as if at a Yale-Princeton game.
\par Buzzzzzzzzz--Whirrrrrrrrrrr--and away. She's off! A feeble cheer goes
\par up. And everybody starts onward again in better humor with himself for
\par having seen so entertaining a show.
\par 
\par It snowed the night through.
\par 
\par In the morning banks of snow breast-high through the side streets.
\par Through a narrow aisle down the middle of the roadway trucks cars and
\par wagons slowly go in single file. Moving thus all in a single line they
\par have something the effect of a circus parade--elephants and lion cages
\par and so on.
\par 
\par And lions remind me. It is always well to look at public statues and
\par outdoor pieces of sculpture the morning after a heavy snow. You are
\par likely to find them very comical apparitions. The celebrated literary
\par lions before the New York Public Library, for instance, wore throughout
\par the day after the first big snow of this winter ridiculous tall caps
\par pulled down very rakishly over their eyes.
\par 
\par Streaming from the direction of the railroad station were coming the
\par swarms of our commuter friends, the legs of many of them hoisting along
\par those prodigious "arctics" which are all the vogue nowadays. Isn't it
\par curious? There was a time when if you were obliged to wear glasses you
\par got them as nearly invisible as possible. If you were a man you felt
\par there was something shameful about having "weak" eyes. If a woman, you
\par "just knew" that glasses made you look "horrid." And when you wore
\par overshoes you got them as inconspicuous as possible. Now you affect
\par shell spectacles that can be seen a block away, and having huge lenses.
\par Now there is nothing smarter, apparently, than for a young woman with a
\par trim foot to come into town swaddled in floppers which fit her slim
\par ankles like a bucket.
\par 
\par Men are still shovelling and scraping away at the streets, a motley
\par army. What is it so many persons are pausing to smile at, others
\par hurrying on but with grinning faces turned back? It is at a gentleman
\par shoveller. Here recruited somehow among this gang of husky laborers is a
\par slim eccentric figure in a--yes, a frock coat, a derby hat, kid gloves,
\par and very tight trousers ... a quaint picture of the shabby genteel.
\par Walking very briskly back and forth, very upright in carriage, the small
\par of his back curved inward, he pushes his scraper before him holding it
\par by the very tip of the long handle--and as well as can be observed
\par doesn't scrape anything at all. His fellow workers regard him with surly
\par disgust and roughly bump into him at every opportunity. What story is
\par there, in that absurd, pathetic scene, what O. Henry tale of mischance
\par in a great city?
\par 
\par A wagon on a side street has got its wheels ground into the snow bank at
\par the side of the narrow cleared way. Such accidents are all about, and
\par everywhere men may be seen leaving their own affairs to give a helping
\par hand to a fellow being in sore straits. The visitation of a great snow
\par storm strikingly unites the bonds of the brotherhood of man.
\par 
\par Stalled for interminable periods in suburban trains and in traffic jams
\par hurried men give themselves up cheerfully to the philosophic virtue of
\par patience.
\par 
\par Vagabonds sent on errands two miles away return after three hours with
\par tales of the awful slowness of trolley cars. And on days of great snow
\par storms meet with Christian forgiveness.
