\par CHAPTER VII
\par 
\par THE UNUSUALNESS OF PARISIAN PHILADELPHIA
\par 
\par 
\par I discovered the other day that Philadelphia is a very great deal nearer
\par to Paris than New York is.
\par 
\par How do I figure out that?
\par 
\par Plain enough. It's because New York women, buds and matrons, thinking
\par they are got up (or as the English say, "turned out") smart as anything,
\par are parading around in fashions today altogether pass\'e9e.
\par 
\par You know the New York scene. And how for some considerable time now its
\par most--well, most apparent feature has been a--er, a hosiery display ...
\par unparalleled off the gay stage of musical comedy. Very, so to speak,
\par exhilarating that once was--the glistening spectacle of, moving all
\par about, those symmetrically tapering lines of pink and rose and orange
\par and pearl and taupe and heather tan and heather green and purple wool
\par and sheen of black and gloss of mottled snake and--and all that.
\par 
\par But, I am afraid, the eye over-long accustomed to the great Metropolitan
\par movie thriller of the fashionable streets had become somewhat dulled.
\par 
\par The Parisienne knew about the peculiar character of the eye, and that it
\par ceases to see with any emotional response at all that which remains
\par within its range of vision for any extended length of time. So she
\par (roguish witch!) alertly changed the picture.
\par 
\par I picked up by chance, during my two-hour run on the train, a copy of
\par one of our most dashing fashion journals. It was the "Forecast of Spring
\par Fashions" number. I opened it, at random, at the headline: "The Short
\par Skirt Has Had Its Day in Paris." Below was a jolly photograph (of a
\par stunning lady at the latest races at Auteuil) illustrating "the new
\par skirt length." Visible beneath the hem--a trim foot, and a bit of tidy
\par ankle.
\par 
\par Who was the fellow (with a gifted eye for the lasses) who spoke with
\par such delight of the tiny feet that "like little mice run in and out"?
\par And there was that other poet (what was his name? I declare! my
\par literature is getting awful rusty), who sang with such relish the charm
\par of feminine drapery "concealing yet revealing." Anyhow, you know what
\par I'm getting at.
\par 
\par I closed the magazine and forgot about the matter--until shortly after I
\par had come out of the Broad Street Station.
\par 
\par The modish scene I apprehended was, to an eye accustomed steadily for
\par some time to the natty abbreviations of Fifth Avenue, a refreshing, a
\par charming spectacle. I seemed suddenly to have left my "orchestra seat."
\par And to have returned again to a view of, so to put it, ladies in private
\par life.
\par 
\par Though, indeed, occasionally in the distance I caught a flashing glimpse
\par of, according to Paris decree, the obsolete skirt length.
\par 
\par Come to think of it, isn't this so, too: that there are in Philadelphia
\par more rose-cheeked damsels of hearty figure and athletic-heel swing than
\par you usually come across in other cities?
\par 
\par At any rate, there are quite a number of very unusual things about
\par "Phila," as I believe intimate friends of the city affectionately call
\par the place. Things which it may be you have not noticed lately--perhaps
\par because you haven't been there recently, or maybe because you live
\par there, and so see them every day.
\par 
\par One of the unusual things about Philadelphia is that so many ladies and
\par "gem'men" who do light housekeeping on and around Manhattan Island (in
\par other words "New Yorkers") apparently find it easier frequently to get
\par to Chicago, or Palm Beach, or London, or Santa Barbara than to journey
\par to Philadelphia. I suppose the reason for this state of mind is the same
\par as the cause of my sometimes feeling that it would be about as simple
\par for me to undertake a trip from the Grand Central to Buffalo as to get
\par from Times Square down to Fulton Street for a luncheon appointment. A
\par place which is only half an hour, or two hours away, is a place, you
\par think, that you can run down to any time. And--well, just at the moment
\par with everything so pressing and all that. To become keyed up about
\par taking a "real" trip is another matter.
\par 
\par And when I myself do get there I always feel that it is an unusual thing
\par that I have allowed so long a time to lapse since I came before. Because
\par it is so unusually pleasant and restful a ride that it makes me sore to
\par think what an unusually deuce of a thing I am put to every night going
\par home in the rush hour to Dyckman Street on the subway.
\par 
\par It is an unusual thing (or, at least, so it seems to me) that in
\par Philadelphia cards in windows advertising rooms to let should be (as
\par they are) labelled "Vacancies."
\par 
\par It is an unusual thing that here so many undertakers' shops should be
\par conducted in what appear to be private residences. It is an unusual
\par thing that there should be so many ways of paying your fare on the
\par street cars--in some you pay when you get on, in others when you get
\par off. It is an unusual thing that in Philadelphia there are more
\par different kinds of street lamps than (I suspect) there are in any other
\par city in the world. There are powerful arc lamps, high on tall poles,
\par cold white in their light. There are lower down, particularly pleasant
\par in the twinkle of their numbers in Washington Square, gas lamps glowing
\par a mellow yellow through their mantles. Various other kinds of lamps,
\par too. But the ones I like best are those squat fellows throughout
\par Independence Square. Octagonal iron-bound boxes of glass, small at the
\par base, wide at the top, with a kind of ecclesiastical derby hat of iron
\par as a lid. They somehow suggest to me the lamps which I fancy before Will
\par Shakespeare's Globe Theatre.
\par 
\par Here golden Diana with her bow does not poise high on her slender
\par Spanish tower. But from far above the "Public Buildings" Brother Penn
\par looks down on more banks, United States Mints, trust companies, firms
\par dealing in securities, places handling investments, and such-like
\par business concerns than (one has a feeling) can be found in any other
\par city in Christendom. There are too, I should guess, in Philadelphia
\par about as many different styles and periods of architecture as in any
\par other municipality between the two great seas: Georgian, Colonial,
\par bay-window, London brick row, ramshackle frame, modern mansion,
\par skyscraper, etc., etc., etc. And certainly I don't know where one could
\par go to count more different kinds of porches. Nor where one could find so
\par many such pleasant oddities of today as hitching-blocks, doorway
\par foot-scrapers, and those old friends of our childhood the front yard
\par stone storks.
\par 
\par And where, Oh, where! (not even in London) can one find so many alleys
\par to the square inch? Many of them, lanes of but a few blocks in length,
\par highly respectable, even aristocratic, quarters of the town. Such as
\par Camac Street, tucked away between Thirteenth and Twelfth Streets, one
\par block of it either side of Locust, and the home or haunt of those of
\par artistic persuasion. Here the famous Franklin Inn Club, the charming
\par Poor Richard Club, and divers other clubs of kindred spirit. Unusual
\par this quaint street of art in this: in fixing it up for its present
\par purpose its quaintness and its "artiness" have not been overdone. Far,
\par far finer in effect than New York's over eccentric alley of painters,
\par Washington Mews, its original loveliness has simply been restored. It is
\par as jolly to look upon as London's artist nook, Cheyne Row. Perhaps even
\par jollier.
\par 
\par Now another unusual thing about Philadelphia is that Philadelphians
\par standing within three blocks of the place can't tell you where South
\par Carlisle Street is. Professional Philadelphians, such as policemen,
\par firemen, postmen, street car men, can't do it. In the attempt they
\par contradict each other, and quarrel among themselves. For the benefit of
\par both Philadelphians and visitors to the city I will set down here
\par exactly the location of South Carlisle Street. West of Broad, south of
\par Pine, it runs one block from Pine to Lombard Street. After a jump, where
\par there isn't any of it, north of Market Street there is more of it.
\par 
\par But what the dickens is South Carlisle Street, and why should anybody
\par care where it is? Well, though it isn't in the books on Historic Shrines
\par of America it is a street you "hadn't ought to" miss. It's about twelve
\par feet (or something like that) from wall to wall. The doorways seem to be
\par about three feet wide. There, in South Carlisle Street, Philadelphia's
\par mahogany doors, fan-lights above, white pillars before, marble steps
\par below, her immaculate red brick, her freshly painted wooden shutters,
\par her gleaming brass knockers are in their most exquisite perfection.
\par 
\par A wealthy and cultivated gentleman or two "took up" the street a year or
\par so ago, decided to make their homes there, and it has become quite
\par "class." Same idea, more or less, that Mrs. W. K. Vanderbilt has
\par concerning the "exodus" of her set from Fifth Avenue to unheard-of
\par Sutton Place over among the tall yellow chimneys by New York's East
\par River.
\par 
\par Considering the great wealth in Philadelphia and its environs,
\par particularly those patrician environs lying toward Harrisburg, it is, I
\par think, unusual that you never see on the streets there a Pekingese or a
\par Pomeranian attended by a personage in livery.
\par 
\par Unusual, too, that in a city of the first class along the eastern
\par seaboard so few canes are "worn."
\par 
\par And, by the way, that's an unusual railroad service from Philadelphia to
\par New York. Conductor calls out: "Train for Newark and New York. Newark
\par first stop." Train slides a few feet--halts at West Philadelphia. Spins
\par along a bit again, and pulls up at North Philadelphia. Stops later along
\par the way at Trenton, Newark, and Manhattan Junction. I really do not see,
\par putting a wreck out of the calculation, where else it could stop.
\par 
\par I took from a boy in the Pennsylvania station a copy of one of New
\par York's most popular evening papers. It came apart in the middle.
\par Straightening it out, I caught a headline on the "Talks to Women" page.
\par It read "Short Skirts Remain." Below a cut of a beaming lass attired,
\par the caption said, in "frock of navy blue ruffled taffeta with short
\par sleeves and 'shorter' skirt."
\par 
\par When I came out onto the street the temperature (in skirts) seemed to
\par have risen since my departure a couple of days before.
