\par CHAPTER VIII
\par 
\par OUR LAST SOCIAL ENGAGEMENT AS A FINE ART
\par 
\par 
\par I have just witnessed a revelation. At least, it was a revelation to me.
\par I'm keen on telling you all about it.
\par 
\par One of my earlier articles in this series had to do with the
\par establishment here and there in a great city of those gentlemen engaged
\par in the estimable business of packing you up for keeps--that is the
\par "parlors" of various sorts of "undertakers." I had been much struck by
\par the vast number of cozy little places catering, so to say, to the poor
\par and humble who have forever (as Stevenson puts it) "parted company with
\par their aches and ecstasies." And I had wondered at how very few places
\par there were in evidence on the streets to take care of the "remains" of,
\par in a manner of speaking, the first-cabin passengers in life, those who
\par have travelled through their days in a fashion de luxe. The
\par establishments of this type which now and then I did see were very
\par palatial indeed--and didn't look at all as though they would
\par countenance the corpse of just an ordinary person such as you and me.
\par 
\par Also, all the undertaking establishments visible to me in my goings and
\par comings about town were quite obviously undertaking establishments. They
\par displayed within and without the air, the accoutrements, the
\par paraphernalia traditionally associated with one's last social engagement
\par on earth, his funeral. They varied only in this: some were rich and
\par haughty in general effect, others simple and perhaps dingy in
\par appearance. But each and all of them looked as much like an undertaking
\par shop as a barber shop looks like a barber shop. You could not possibly
\par have mistaken any one of them for a Turkish bath establishment, or a
\par Carnegie library, or an office for steamship tickets.
\par 
\par As I say, I wrote that article telling all this and that about what
\par anybody may see any day as he goes about on his rounds through the thick
\par of the city. But when the article appeared--originally--it soon
\par developed that I was not abreast of undertaking matters at all. I had
\par not in the least kept track of the remarkable advances which have to
\par date been made in the art of being buried--and a very fine art, in the
\par advanced phases of the affair, it certainly has become. I did not even
\par know the present-day, the correct, name for what I, in so old-fashioned
\par a condition of mind, called an "undertaker's." No.
\par 
\par That word, "undertaker," has long, long ago been discarded by the \'e9lite
\par of the profession. What a queer word as a business title it was, anyway!
\par How did it originally ever come to be used in its mortuary relation? No
\par one in the business that I have asked has been able to tell me. And why
\par in the dim past when names were being given to trades did not this word,
\par undertaker, seem to be equally descriptive of the career of physician or
\par attorney? Indeed, does not he that sets himself the highly hazardous
\par task of saving a living fellow being from disease or the gallows
\par undertake to do more than he who merely performs the quiet office of
\par laying us away?
\par 
\par And then, oddly enough for its tragic associations, the word acquired in
\par our minds something of a ludicrous turn. It was reminiscent of Dickens,
\par of hired professional "mourners," and that sort of thing. At mention of
\par the word, a picture popped into our mind of a grotesquely angular being,
\par of sallow, elongated features and lugubrious manner, garbed in a rusty
\par frock coat and "stove pipe" hat, who put together before him the tips of
\par black-gloved fingers and spoke with a hollow sound. We would say to our
\par friends when they were feeling blue: "What's the matter with you? You
\par act like an undertaker."
\par 
\par Well, as doubtless you have noticed, the term "funeral director" more or
\par less recently pretty well superseded the word undertaker among
\par progressive concerns. It is a phrase much more in the modern spirit,
\par like "domestic science" for (what used to be) "household work,"
\par "modiste" for "dressmaker," "maid" for "hired-girl," "psychic" for
\par "fortune teller," "publicity engineer" for "press agent," and so on. And
\par it has a good, business-like, efficient sound.
\par 
\par Still (I discovered) to be buried by a funeral director is not the very
\par latest, the most fashionable thing. The really smart way nowadays of
\par bidding good-bye to the world is to go to the establishment of a
\par "mortician."
\par 
\par Yes; that's what the gentleman said in his very cordial letter: would I
\par care to look over a "real mortician's establishment in New York City?" I
\par replied that nothing could give me greater pleasure. So at the time
\par appointed a couple of days later his car came round for me.
\par 
\par When I told people of the visit I was about to make, they all laughed,
\par very heartily. Now that brings to one's attention a curious thing: why
\par should they laugh? Honestly, between you and me, think hard and tell me
\par what really there is funny about going to see a burial establishment?
\par 
\par Paradoxical indeed is the attitude of mind of practically everyone
\par toward this subject of being ushered out of life. Sundry totally
\par contradictory emotions are aroused in the very same person by slightly
\par different aspects of the same subject. If you remark that you are going
\par to spend the afternoon at the undertaker's that is awfully amusing. At
\par the same time, is not nearly everyone down in his heart a bit scared of
\par undertakers' shops? Uncomfortable, gruesome places, would not most of us
\par feel, to have next door?
\par 
\par At any rate, as we glided along I was told by the gentleman who had come
\par to fetch me that the feeling was very general that the presence of a
\par funeral director's establishment depreciated the value of property in
\par the immediate neighborhood. Though, he asserted, this popular idea
\par frequently had not at all been borne out in fact.
\par 
\par It developed (from his lively conversation) that nothing so much annoys
\par a funeral director, or a mortician, as for a visitor to pull old gags
\par which he thinks are smart--such, for instance, as the remark: "I see
\par your business is pretty dead." I gathered that this jocular pleasantry
\par was the stock joke of all near-wits who visited undertakers--I mean
\par morticians.
\par 
\par No; there is another thing which annoys these gentlemen (morticians)
\par even more than such punk puns as that. They deeply resent, I discovered,
\par any disrespectful allusion to their silent clients, such as calling them
\par "stiffs," or something like that. How would you, they ask, like to have
\par someone of yours--someone who but yesterday returned your heart's clasp,
\par now dumb and cold--made game of by such ribaldry? Certainly, I cannot
\par say that I should like it.
\par 
\par Another paradoxical contradiction! Tell me (if you can) what strange
\par spring of his being prompts a man to think it big and bold and hearty of
\par him to speak with such cynical contemptuousness of a fellow man returned
\par to rigid clay.
\par 
\par We had arrived at our destination, I was told. But I saw nothing, but
\par what was (seemingly) a rather handsome private residence, set in a
\par pleasant lawn. Though I did discern by the door a modest plate which
\par read (as I recall the name) "Wentworth Brothers," nothing more.
\par Wentworth Brothers might have been, for all the exterior evidence to the
\par contrary, architects, or teachers of dancing and the piano, or breeders
\par of pedigreed dogs, or dealers in antiques, or physical instructors, or
\par almost anything you please.
\par 
\par This I soon learned was the fundamental principle of the sensitive art
\par of the mortician--to scrap all the old stage properties of the bugaboo
\par type of undertaker.
\par 
\par We passed into a charming hall, light and cheerful, furnished in
\par excellent taste, altogether domestic in effect. A number of bright
\par looking people, apparently attached to the premises, were lightly moving
\par about. I had somewhat the sensation of having come to a most agreeable
\par afternoon tea.
\par 
\par I was presented to my host, as cheerful, wholesome and cordial a young
\par chap as anyone would care anywhere to see. The senior, he, of the
\par brothers. I had been a little depressed that morning, having a bad cold
\par and being fretted by a number of gloomy things, but as we proceeded
\par through the house my spirits picked up decidedly. I experienced a
\par feeling of mental and physical well-being, so attractive was everything
\par about.
\par 
\par A dainty reception room opened off the hall at the front. My impression
\par was of a nice amount of charming Colonial furniture. Altogether such a
\par room as you might see in an illustration in the magazine _House and
\par Garden_. Secluded back of this rooms having a brisk atmosphere and
\par serving as offices. Peopled by very trim and efficient looking young
\par people.
\par 
\par We descended to the "stock room," a most sanitary looking place of
\par cement floor, ceiling and walls, where was a large store of caskets of
\par many varieties. Behind this a spick and span embalming room which
\par (except for the two tables) somewhat suggested an admirable creamery.
\par Here I discovered that to the mind of the mortician towels belong to the
\par Dark Ages. The up-to-date way of drying hands is by holding them before
\par a blast of air turned on from a pipe.
\par 
\par We ascended to the third floor. Here were the chapels, rooms which might
\par have been designed to accommodate fashionable audiences attending
\par literary lectures. In connection with them a tiny "minister's study,"
\par not unlike the sanctum of a university professor. Also here small hotel
\par suites, each with bath attached, available for the bereaved from out of
\par town. Here, too, snug quarters for wakes. And a spacious chamber wherein
\par friends may sit for a little last visit with the departed. The dominant
\par article of furniture in this room an Empire lounge such as we see
\par supporting the figure of Madame R\'e9camier in the famous portrait by
\par David. A consummate refinement was shown me on this floor: telephones,
\par concealed behind panels in the wall, with no bells to jangle over-tried
\par nerves, but with a tiny red electric globe on the wall to light as the
\par signal.
\par 
\par The top floor a dormitory for male employees, having much the effect of
\par rooms for boys at college, gay soft cushions, pipes and mandolins
\par scattered about.
\par 
\par I lingered for a smoke and a chat with my host on the ground floor in an
\par oak panelled room like the library of a gentleman's club before leaving.
\par 
\par I came away with (I very much fear) an idea that I should like to go
\par back tomorrow and see some one of my friends so agreeably buried from
\par that place.
\par 
