\par 
\par 
\par CHAPTER IX
\par 
\par WRITING IN ROOMS
\par 
\par 
\par I remember that I was somewhat surprised when E. V. Lucas expressed
\par surprise that I was writing in my room at the hotel where we both
\par happened to be at the same time for several days last summer. He
\par declared with an expression of sharp distaste that he could not write in
\par hotel rooms. But said he had no difficulty in writing on trains. That
\par rather got me, because I can't write at all on trains. And possibly
\par because I was a bit peeved at the easy way in which he spoke of doing
\par that exceedingly difficult thing, writing on trains, I asserted in reply
\par that anybody ought to be able to write in _any kind_ of a room. But I do
\par know, what every writer knows, that the particular room one may be in
\par can make a good deal of difference in the way one is able to write.
\par 
\par Of course, it does appear to be true that there are writers of a kind
\par that can write anywhere in any circumstances, apparently with equal
\par facility and their customary standard of merit, whatever that may be. I
\par suppose war correspondents must be like that, and reporters for daily
\par newspapers. We know that a good many war books were announced as having
\par been written in dugouts, trenches, pill-boxes, tanks, submarines,
\par hospitals, airplanes and so on. In the matter of some of them I should
\par not undertake to dispute that they had even been written in asylums.
\par 
\par I have known, and known well, men of that type of mind which seemed to
\par be so completely under control that at will it could be turned on or
\par off, so to say, like the stream from a water faucet. My friend Joyce
\par Kilmer had such a head. It has been told how some of his most moving
\par poems--for one instance "The White Ships and the Red"--were the result
\par of hurried newspaper assignments: how he could leave a poem in the
\par middle of its composition, go out and lunch heartily for two hours,
\par return and finish the writing of it; how early in his career he would
\par walk up and down a room of his home in suburban New Jersey at two in the
\par morning and dictate (without a pause) to his wife while carrying a
\par shrilly crying child in his arms; how one of the best of his "Sunday
\par stories" was dictated directly after having been taken to a hospital
\par with three ribs fractured by being hit by his commutation train--and how
\par much more. A young man with a brain in perfect practical working
\par condition. But even he was not free from the mysterious tricks of
\par creative writing. For we know that after a daily round sustained for a
\par number of years of high productivity, when he went into the war, which
\par inspired countless others to _begin_ writing, he suddenly ceased to
\par write, practically altogether.
\par 
\par Poets and trains being up, brings to my mind my friend the Reverend
\par Edward F. Garesch\'e9, S. J., a source of amusement to many of his friends
\par because of his method of composition. He travels continually. Frequently
\par he will excuse himself from a group with whom he is talking, go to his
\par own seat, request the porter to bring him a card table, get out his
\par travelling typewriter, rattle off several poems, return to his party and
\par resume conversation at about where he had left off. Some of his poems
\par are very good; some (I'm sorry to have to say) are--not so good.
\par 
\par And so round we come again to the matter of writing in rooms. We know
\par how Booth Tarkington writes: in what he calls a "work spree," in a room
\par upstairs at home, a pile of freshly sharpened pencils ready to his
\par hand--and that, doubtless, he wouldn't be able to write anything in an
\par office if he were to be hanged for not doing it. (Probably never goes to
\par an office.) Meredith Nicholson, on the other hand, declares that the
\par only way it is possible for him to write is to go regularly at nine
\par o'clock every morning to an office he has downtown; where he tells
\par anyone who may ask over the telephone that he'll be there until five in
\par the afternoon.
\par 
\par There are persons who like to have others around them, moving about,
\par while they write. And people there are who find it necessary to lock
\par themselves up, and can have no one else in the room. Though in some
\par cases such persons would not mind the bang of a bass-drum just the other
\par side of the door. I know a man who had an office in lower Manhattan
\par where for a considerable period just outside his open window a steam
\par riveter was at work. Terrific it was, the way the noise of this machine
\par smashed the air into tiny particles like a shower of broken glass.
\par Callers who found this man contentedly writing would hold their ears and
\par look at him with their hair on end from amazement. A man of highly
\par nervous organism, too; one who would be very upset if his typewriter had
\par a pale ribbon, or be spoiled for the day if he couldn't find the right
\par pen--worn over just to his liking at the point. But, after the first day
\par or so, Mr. Soaping (name of the gentleman I'm telling you about) I know
\par didn't hear the riveter at all.
\par 
\par Then those exist, Royal Cortissoz is one, who, dictating all they do,
\par can have in the room while they work only their secretary. Frequently is
\par it the case, too, that none but the amanuensis to whom they have been
\par long accustomed will do. A stranger throws 'em completely off. A
\par novelist I know, the writer of a very good style, who becomes very much
\par fussed up, and is practically destroyed, when he suspects a secretary of
\par giving critical attention to the manner of his prose. An embarrassing
\par thing about most stenographers, I have found, is that they are greatly
\par grieved if you say "'em" for "them," or anything like that. Or else they
\par won't let you do such things at all, and edit everything pleasant back
\par into perfectly good copy-book English. Some of them won't even let you
\par split an infinitive.
\par 
\par Who was it, Voltaire, Richard Brinsley Sheridan, somebody, who could
\par write only when elaborately got up in his satins and ruffles? It is what
\par not long ago was called a bromidium to say that humorists are sad
\par people. I'd probably be thought humorous if I should call myself any
\par particular flier as a humorist, but this I know: wherever in my writing
\par I may have approached being amusing that generally was written when I
\par was considerably depressed. Forenoon is the best time for some to write;
\par late at night for others. "Ben Hur," I seem to recall, was penned
\par beneath a noble tree. At any rate, we frequently see pictures of
\par novelists, particularly in England, at work in their gardens. The most
\par familiar photographs, etchings, medallions and so on of Mark Twain and
\par of Robert Louis Stevenson at work are those of them writing in bed. Now
\par I can't (as some so take their breakfast) eat in bed; and I'm quite sure
\par I should never be able comfortably to write anything there. I do not
\par tell you how it is with me because I regard it as of deep interest to
\par you to hear how it is with me, but merely to aid me in assembling a
\par collection of facts concerning the freakishness of writing, and to
\par suggest to you how very different it may be with _you_.
\par 
\par And I couldn't write under a tree. One writer, perhaps, writes more
\par easily in the winter than in the summer, or it is the other way round.
\par The mind of one, it may be, is stimulated by the companionship of an
\par open fire, and that of another (for aught I know) by the companionship
\par of an ice-box. Personally, I think that it is well in writing for the
\par weather to be cool enough to have the windows down; and that night is
\par the best time, for the reason that your mind (or, at least, my mind) is
\par more gathered together within the circle of light at your desk.
\par 
\par Frequently, however (as you know), after sitting for hours with your
\par mind plumb stalled, it is not until shortly before your bed time that
\par that eccentric engine, your brain, gets buzzed up. Then, probably, you
\par can't call the thing off if you want to. I will tell you a story:
\par 
\par A man there is, of some renown as a writer, who started a new book early
\par last spring. For some considerable time he had been much discouraged
\par about his writing. Hadn't been able to make it go. Could only lift
\par heavily and painfully one stilted sentence after another. Used to take
\par up now and then one or another of his early books and look into it.
\par Marvelled how it was that he ever could have written such clever stuff.
\par Like Swift when late in life he re-read "Gulliver," so did this man
\par exclaim: "What a genius I had at that time!" He felt that the fire had
\par gone out; his inner life seemed to have completely died; he was a hollow
\par shell; could now neither receive nor impart anything worth half a
\par jews-harp. When, one day, he heard rosy, young Hugh Walpole say of
\par himself that of course what he had written was merely a beginning to
\par what he felt he might do, this man looked at rosy, young Hugh Walpole
\par with a deeply gloomy and very jealous eye.
\par 
\par But, lo! as I say, this man started this new book. It began as a series
\par of articles for which he was to be paid--that was _why_ it was begun at
\par all. Now see! With him it was as Professor George Edward Woodberry says
\par of Poe in his admirable "Life"--for a time his genius had "slept." With
\par the start of the new book he awoke. It began to run right out of the
\par ends of his fingers. Took (that book) hold of him completely. He
\par couldn't leave it. Go to bed, have to get up and go at it again. Try to
\par go out for a round of exercise. After a block or so from his quarters,
\par walk slower and slower. Miserable. Tortured. Turn back. Immediately
\par happy again. Soon be back at work. Anybody who entangled him with an
\par invitation anywhere enraged him beyond measure.
\par 
\par New book finished. Everything fine. Got another commission. Easy enough
\par job. Set to at it. Empty vessel again! In despair. He'd make all sorts
\par of excuses to himself to leave his place early in the morning to
\par postpone beginning work. He'd go anywhere, with anybody, to keep as long
\par as possible from facing that task again. Couldn't give any sensible
\par explanation of his prolonged delay to the publishers. Kept putting them
\par off again and again, with one cripple-legged excuse after another, in
\par the hope that he'd come round. Matter became a disgrace.
\par 
\par Still queerer cases than that I know. Fellow who shared an apartment
\par with me one time. When according to the accepted law of nature his mind
\par should have been in a very bad way, then always was he at his best.
\par After leading a regular, wholesome life for a period his mind would
\par become dull, stale and unprofitable. When, following a very different
\par sort of period, he should in all reason have awakened with a splitting
\par head, a swollen eye and a shaking hand, he would get up at about dawn
\par one morning in rattling fine spirits, his mind as clear as a bell, and
\par with an impassioned desire to work. Could, then, write like a streak.
\par But doesn't William James touch upon such a matter as this somewhere?
\par 
\par And Stevenson, how wrong he got the thing! What is it he tells us as to
\par the years of apprenticeship to writing:
\par 
\par      It is only after years of such gymnastic that one can sit down at
\par      last, legions of words swarming to his call, dozens of turns of
\par      phrase simultaneously bidding for his choice, and he himself
\par      knowing what he wants to do and (within the narrow limit of a man's
\par      ability) able to do it.
\par 
\par Only last night it was I was talking to Jesse Lynch Williams. He said
\par nothing of "legions of words swarming to his call," nary a mention of
\par "dozens of turns of phrase simultaneously bidding for his choice."
\par Instead, he asked if I found that writing came easier as time went on.
\par No, he said, it seemed to him that writing became harder and harder the
\par longer one wrote. That he had torn up everything he had done for a long
\par while.
\par 
\par Always the paradox! Again, there are men who write with astonishing
\par ease, or at least with astonishing rapidity, and write well. Not so long
\par ago I began a novel in collaboration with a writer known and admired
\par from coast to coast, a frequent contributor to _The Bookman_, and one of
\par the best. We were to do this thing turn and turn about, a chapter by me,
\par then a chapter by him, and so on. For something like ten days I toiled
\par over chapter one. I labored and I groaned. When it was finished I was
\par spent. I handed him the manuscript; he stuffed it into his overcoat
\par pocket and went whistling away. Returned within a few days and handed me
\par a wad of copy covering, I think, three chapters. Again I toiled in the
\par sweat of my brow. Gave him another chapter. When, after a couple of
\par weeks or something like that, he returned and I had read what he had
\par done I discovered that he had got people married that I hadn't known
\par were yet born. The collaboration busted up.
\par 
\par My excellent friend does not like me to tell this story, because he
\par thinks it represents me as the conscientious artist and him as the
\par shallow scribbler. Well, that was not so; his chapters were far better
\par than mine. Nevertheless, his name I shall not give; I'll merely say
\par that it has very much the sound of a name borne by one of the
\par Elizabethan dramatists.
\par 
\par Then there is that sort of human head-piece which can only write when it
\par absolutely has to. I allude to the magical instrument of coercion known
\par as a "copy date." I know people, dozens of them, who having a month and
\par a half ahead of them in which to do an article can't possibly get
\par started on it until it is almost too late for them to get it in on time
\par to go to press--when a mad frenzy seizes them, their indolence vanishes
\par like mist before the rising sun, their minds open like a flower, and all
\par is well.
\par 
\par And the "galley slaves," those poor devils who for years have lived
\par under the whip of copy day every day. How they dream of the "real"
\par things they might do, given time. If (they think) the Lord would only
\par subsidize them! Now and then the Devil takes one of them and does this
\par very thing. The happy man gets some sort of a sinecure. All he has to do
\par is to go write. And (in all probability) that's all there is to that
\par story. He is like those things Riley tells about who "swaller
\par theirselves." He gets nothing written.
\par 
\par What do you write with? And why do you write with whatever it is you
\par write with instead of with something else? Why did Mr. Howells (in all
\par the writing of his which I have seen) use a script-letter typewriter
\par instead of a Roman-letter machine? Why does Mr. Le Gallienne do so much
\par of his copy (if not all of it) by hand? Why is it that Mr. Huneker could
\par never either dictate or learn to run a typewriter? How is it possible
\par for those Englishmen--Swinnerton and Bennett, for instance--to put forth
\par in a few months whole novels in the monkish hand of an illuminated
\par missal? (I have seen the original manuscript of "The Old Wives' Tale,"
\par every page like a copper-plate engraving, and hardly a correction
\par throughout.) And why is that it seems to me most natural to write some
\par things with a pen, others with a pencil, most things on a typewriter,
\par and yet again mix the use of all three implements in one composition? I
\par cannot tell you.
\par 
\par Some authors, if they are going to write about a slum, have to go and
\par live in a slum while they are writing about a slum. Other authors, if
\par they are going to write about life in an Ohio town, go to Italy to write
\par about life in an Ohio town. In his excellent book "On the Trail of
\par Stevenson" Clayton Hamilton says:
\par 
\par      Throughout his lifelong wanderings, Stevenson rarely or never
\par      attempted to describe a place so long as he was in it. For his
\par      selection of descriptive detail he relied always on the
\par      subconscious artistry of memory. He trusted his own mind to forget
\par      the non-essential; and he seized upon whatever he remembered as, by
\par      that token, the most essential features of a scene--the features,
\par      therefore, that cried out to be selected as the focal points of the
\par      picture to be suggested to the mind's eye of his readers.
\par 
\par The author of the thirteen volumes known as "The Chronicles of
\par Barsetshire," a detailed picture of the English clergy of his time, had
\par never associated with bishops, deans, and arch-deacons; he built them up
\par (to use his own expression) out of his "moral consciousness."
\par 
\par But round to rooms again. Often has it been told how Anthony Trollope
\par worked. How he accomplished so much--thirty-odd novels besides as many
\par tales--by a method he recommended to all who wish to pursue successfully
\par the literary career. In the drawing room of the Athen\'e6um Club, in a
\par railway carriage, or on the ocean, wherever he might be he seated
\par himself for three hours as a limit, with his watch before him; and
\par regularly as it marked the quarter hour he turned off two hundred and
\par fifty words, undisturbed by any distraction about him. We know that the
\par unlettered man of genius, John Bunyan, wrote his immortal allegory "The
\par Pilgrim's Progress" in Bedford jail. And there is being advertised now a
\par book recently written in an American prison. And much writing has been
\par done in garrets. Then here's our old friend George Moore. Again and
\par again he has told of exactly the places it was necessary for him to live
\par in while he wrote certain books. I open at random "Ave"; and I find
\par this:
\par 
\par      I descended the hillside towards the loveliest prospect that ever
\par      greeted mortal eyes.... And I walked thinking if there were one
\par      among my friends who would restore Mount Venus sufficiently for the
\par      summer months, long enough for me to write my book.
\par 
\par Now, to be quite frank with you, I didn't intend to write this paper at
\par all. You may remember that when I set out I was merely in disagreement
\par with Mr. Lucas concerning the matter of writing in a hotel room. One
\par thing (as it will) led to another; and the upshot has been all this
\par pother. However, there are, I hope, no bones broken--and that's saying a
\par good deal for any kind of a discussion in these unsettled times.
\par 
\par What I am coming to is (the fashionable thing to come to nowadays) the
\par psychic. A fellow I know was much puzzled. He recently got back to 16
\par Gramercy Park from a trip around the world. I saw him there having some
\par toast and a pot of tea. He told me these interesting circumstances. He
\par would be at a superbly appointed hotel in some city. Beautiful suite of
\par rooms. Commodious bath-room with lovely bay-window. Everything to make
\par for perfect mental and physical well-being. Impotent to write there.
\par Later runs into some terrible dump of a lodging house. Horrible din of
\par low noises all about. One dirty window looks out on scene of squalor. So
\par cold at night has to put chair on bed and sit there to be nearer gas
\par jet. Gets on wonderfully with writing. Strikes another place, handsomest
\par of all; writes pretty well. Comes to most fearful place yet; can't write
\par at all.
\par 
\par Couldn't make head nor tail of the matter, this fellow. Discussed the
\par thing with many people. Finally found young woman who gave convincing
\par explanation. It's like this: Undoubtedly you are, in any room, affected
\par by something of the spirit which lingers there of former occupants.
\par Maybe they were persons, whatever their station in life, sympathetic to
\par your spirit--maybe not.
\par 
