\par 
\par 
\par CHAPTER X
\par 
\par TAKING THE AIR IN SAN FRANCISCO
\par 
\par 
\par A few days ago, in the warm and brilliant winter sunlight there, I was
\par strolling along the Embarcadero. Now all my life I have been very fond
\par of roving the streets....
\par 
\par And that confession reminds me:
\par 
\par I one time heard a minister (a clergyman of considerable force of
\par eloquence) preach a sermon against streets. His idea seemed to be that
\par streets were not good for one--that they were very bad places. He
\par admonished mothers to keep their children "off the streets." He regarded
\par it as very reprehensible in a wife for her to "gad the streets." The
\par footpad (he said) plied the street at night, while the righteous were at
\par home in bed. What so sad as "a child of the streets"? If we wished to
\par describe a worthless canine we called it a "street dog." The outcast has
\par his home in the streets. The drunkard makes his bed in the street. It
\par was painful (I gathered) for a civilized being to hear the "language of
\par the street." And so on.
\par 
\par But I very much fear that the eloquence of this gentleman was greater
\par than his Christianity. If we are to love our neighbors as we do
\par ourselves, we will find him in greatest variety in the streets. If we
\par are to give away our cloak, the beneficiary, I should think, would be a
\par citizen much accustomed to the streets. And, as far as I can make out,
\par there is more rejoicing in heaven over the arrival of a sister who has
\par "walked the streets" than attends the reception of a nun.
\par 
\par Certainly I admit that roaming the streets (like everything else) can
\par doubtless be overdone. Nevertheless, to most people, people of ordinary
\par ways of life (like myself), I highly recommend the practice, as a most
\par healthful exercise, as a pleasant course of profitable education, as a
\par source of endless amusement, and as a Christian virtue. The trouble, I
\par think, with most of us is not that we see too much of the streets but
\par that we do not see as well as we might the streets we happen to be on.
\par We do not read as we run.
\par 
\par So I would write an article In Praise of Streets.
\par 
\par As I was saying (when that minister switched me off), I was strolling
\par along the Embarcadero. Among all the different sorts of streets there
\par are none I think more beguiling than those which lie along the water
\par front of a town or a city. The water-front streets of all seaport
\par cities, of course, partake very much of the same character. Particularly
\par in the picturesque aspect of the shop windows.
\par 
\par Here along the rim of San Francisco Bay you pass the sparkling pier
\par buildings (now and then of Spanish mission architecture) of the Toyo
\par Kisen Kaisha Oriental S. S. Co., of the American Hawaiian S. S. Co., the
\par Kosmos Line, and the Pacific-Alaska Navigation Co., among others. While
\par on New York's West Street you see the structures of the White Star Line,
\par the Cunard Line, the Red Star Line, erected in masonry of a sort of
\par mammoth and glorified garage architecture, funnels and masts peeping
\par over the top; and further down the frame sheds of the Morgan Line, the
\par Clyde Steam Ship Company, Savannah Line, Lackawanna Rail Road, Hoboken
\par Ferry, and so on. But the tastes of the sailor man as a shopper appear
\par to be very much the same whether he is along the London docks, on West
\par Street, by Boston piers or here on the Embarcadero. In this the West
\par and the East do meet.
\par 
\par The \'e6sthetic taste of the water front inclines, very decidedly, to the
\par ornate. As (presumably) a present to a lady and a decoration for the
\par home the favorite object seems to be a heavy china plate. A romantic
\par landscape, or a moonlight scene, or perhaps a still life study of portly
\par roses is "hand painted" in very thick pigment on its face. Its rim is
\par plaited in effect, like the edge of a fancy pie, and through numerous
\par openings in this rim is run a heavy ribbon by which to hang it on the
\par wall.
\par 
\par Next in prominence in the window displays of water-front bazaars is the
\par set of bleary-colored glass ware (upper edges bound in gold) which I
\par take to be designed for the purpose of serving punch, or perhaps
\par lemonade--a large bowl of warty surface, with a number of cups to match
\par hanging from hooks at its brim.
\par 
\par The water front obviously is strong for the amenities, the arts and the
\par refinements of life. Bottles of perfume (with huge bows of ribbon at
\par their necks) are in great abundance in its shop windows; as also are
\par packets of boudoir soap (Dawn Lilac seems to be the favorite), toilet
\par powders, silk initial handkerchiefs, opera glasses, ladies' garters of
\par very fluffy design, feminine combs ornamented with birds in gilt,
\par exceedingly high stand-up collars for gentlemen, banjos, guitars,
\par mandolins, accordions (of a great variety of sizes), harmonicas, playing
\par cards, dice and poker chips.
\par 
\par As for the rest of the display, it is a multifarious collection: rubber
\par hip-boots, hair clippers, money belts, brogans, bandana handkerchiefs,
\par binoculars, tobacco pouches, spools of thread, pitch-black plug tobacco,
\par hand searchlights, heavy underwear, woolen sox, razor strops, tin
\par watches, shaving brushes, elaborately carved pipes, trays of heavy
\par rings, and here and there some quaint curiosity, such as a little model
\par of a sailing ship in a bottle which it could not have entered through
\par the mouth, or some such oddity as that.
\par 
\par One old friend of mine on West Street I missed on the Embarcadero. And
\par that is (very battered and worn are the specimens of him which remain as
\par the last of his noble race) the cigar-store wooden Indian.
\par 
\par And (I much regret) neither on the Embarcadero nor on any other water
\par front in America do we have the rich costume ball effects that you find
\par about the docks of London. There (as you remember) about the East India
\par and the West India docks may be observed tall, dark visaged figures in
\par loosely flowing robes and brilliant turbans solemnly pushing along high
\par laden trucks and, high above on the decks of ships, hauling away at
\par ropes.
\par 
\par But on the shore side of the San Francisco water front, my fancy was
\par much taken by the salt sea savor of the signs of the houses of
\par entertainment--signs reminiscent of the jovial days of briny romance,
\par echoed in the chantey in "Treasure Island," which has as its refrain:
\par 
\par     Yo, ho, ho, and a bottle of rum.
\par 
\par I passed, among others, the Marine Caf\'e9, the Navy Caf\'e9, the Admiral
\par Caf\'e9, the Harbor Bar, and the Ferry Caf\'e9.
\par 
\par I did not turn up Market Street, but went on around the nose of the
\par peninsula, which is the foundation of San Francisco. I passed a
\par three-masted ship, the _Lizzie Vance_, lying by her wharf, with men
\par aloft in her rigging. Then I clambered up endless relays of rickety
\par wooden stairs mounting Telegraph Hill. On either side of the ladder-like
\par steps, ramshackle cabins bedecked with lines of fluttering "wash." Like
\par the celebrated editor of _Puck_, H. C. Bunner, I might say that in my
\par travels I've missed many a cathedral but I never missed a slum.
\par 
\par I went along through the Latin Quarter, slid down the steep slope of
\par Kearny Street, and found myself wandering into that quaint little park,
\par Portsmouth Square, where R. L. S. in his most stressful days lounged in
\par the sun and listened to the tales of the vagabonds of the Seven Seas.
\par Somewhat bigger than tiny Gramercy Park, hardly as large as little
\par Madison Square, this park. In the center of the bit of rolling lawn,
\par before a towering screen of rustling trees, the graceful little stone
\par ship, buoyant on its curling stone wave, rides atop its tall stone
\par pedestal graved "To Remember Robert Louis Stevenson," and on the face of
\par which is cut that most fragrant of creeds, which (as everyone knows)
\par begins: "To be honest, to be kind, to earn a little and to spend a
\par little less, to make upon the whole a family happier for his presence"
\par ...
\par 
\par Behind the bench on which I rested was the establishment, so proclaimed
\par the legend printed on its front, of Wing Sun, Funeral Director. For, as
\par you know, Portsmouth Square is embraced on one side by prosperous
\par Chinatown, and on the other by the Italian quarter of San Francisco. And
\par the races, Latin and Oriental, mingle in the little park to take the
\par air.
\par 
\par What here is still more colorful and picturesque, frequently there is a
\par striking and amusing mixture of races in the costume of an individual
\par figure. A Manchu lady, it may be, of waxen, enigmatic features, draped
\par in flowing black silken trousers, hobbles along on high-heeled,
\par pearl-colored American shoes. And there a slim reed of an Oriental
\par maiden, with a complexion like a California orange, whisks by in the
\par smartest of tailored suits--without a hat, her gleaming black hair done
\par in Chinese fashion, long ornamented rods thrust through it, a vivid
\par pendant of bright blossoms at one side of the head.
\par 
\par Sitting there, I thought of the nature of public parks and what pleasant
\par places they are.
\par 
\par Splendid thing, elaborate park "systems," whereby you may go for miles
\par through a grimy city, and move among groves and meadows and bosky dells,
\par with inspiriting glimpses of mirror-like ponds and flashing streams all
\par the way. And of course I enjoy the great parks of a great city.
\par 
\par But more appealing to me than the gorgeous spectacle of Hyde Park, or
\par Van Cortlandt, or Fairmont, or Jackson, or Forest Park are the little
\par places tucked here and there in the seething caldron of the town. These
\par are a lovely department of the streets--they are the little parlors of
\par the streets. Here calls are made, and infants sun themselves--they have,
\par these parklets, their social and their domestic life, under the
\par democratic heavens.
\par 
\par Now soon is a time to watch with joy these plots of open space in the
\par city's rushing life. Spring is more winsome on Boston Common and at
\par Union Square than in the country. A tuft of green shoots seen against
\par canyon walls of steel and stone--one must be in the city to savor the
\par tenderness of spring.
\par 
\par And when summer comes and (in our eastern climate) all the town swelters
\par under a blanket of gritty dust and heavy heat, then one comes upon one
\par of these small areas of greenery with the refreshment of spirit with
\par which at the meal hour one greets the appearance of a nice, cool, green
\par salad.
\par 
\par I arose from my seat in Portsmouth Square and wandered off for the rest
\par of the day through the Streets.
