\par CHAPTER XI
\par 
\par BIDDING MR. CHESTERTON GOOD-BYE
\par 
\par 
\par The note, which came altogether as a surprise, read: "My husband
\par suggests that if you have nothing better to do perhaps you would look in
\par upon us on Wednesday evening at about eight-thirty." Mrs. Chesterton
\par further said, in giving the address, that they had a little apartment
\par lent to them for the last week of their stay here. She had asked Mr.
\par Woollcott to come, too, and Gerald Stanley Lee.... "We can only promise
\par you smokes and talk."
\par 
\par I wondered, as I hurried for the 'bus, whether I'd have time to get my
\par shoes polished. It was precisely the hour appointed when I reached what
\par I took to be the door. The hall-man declared that he had "gone out." I
\par insisted that the hall-man telephone up. "No answer," he said, after a
\par bit, and hung up. Now what do you think of that! Well, I'd take a walk
\par and return a little later.
\par 
\par As I was rounding the corner coming back I saw an agile, rotund figure,
\par with a gleam of white shirt-front in the half darkness, mounting the
\par dusky steps instead of descending into the lighted areaway. Looked kinda
\par like Mr. Woollcott. If so, the gentleman was going wrong, so I called to
\par him.
\par 
\par "He has not come back," the hall-man asserted, but assented to our
\par demands to ring up again. No response. "It was about an hour ago he went
\par out," he replied to our question. Standing there, Mr. Woollcott and I
\par contrived several theories. One was that Mr. Chesterton had intended to
\par return by now but had lost track of the time. Another was that possibly
\par Mrs. Chesterton had invited us on her own hook and had overlooked
\par notifying Mr. Chesterton of the matter. "Has a third gentleman been
\par here?" we asked, meaning Mr. Lee. No. We went for a stroll.
\par 
\par It was nine o'clock. And Mr. Woollcott's manner indicated that he was
\par inclined to take some sort of revenge on the hall-man. Was he, the
\par hall-man, certain that he had everything straight? "Sure," he nodded;
\par "it's Mr. Cushman's apartment." Mr. Cushman's apartment! Had we, then,
\par been blundering in the wrong place all this time! "Mr. Chesterton!"
\par roared Mr. Woollcott. Yes, yes; he understood that ... the gentleman had
\par come in yesterday. That was right according to the note I had had from
\par Mrs. Chesterton; so we demanded that the man make another effort at the
\par telephone. Ah!... he heard something. "It's all right," he mumbled;
\par "they are there."
\par 
\par As we got out of the car Mr. Chesterton was cramming the tiny hall. He
\par was in an attitude which I took to be that of a bow, but I later
\par discovered, as he shuffled back and forth about the apartment, that he
\par walks that way all the time now when in the privacy of his own quarters.
\par Mrs. Chesterton greeted us as we entered the room, Mr. Chesterton
\par trailing in behind us and continuing a welcoming murmur which had
\par somewhat the sound of a playful brook. Mrs. Chesterton ensconced herself
\par behind a tea table. Mr. Chesterton lumbered about with cigars. He
\par disclaimed the great easy chair by the electric table lamp in which it
\par was unmistakable that he had been sitting, but was prevailed upon to
\par return to it.
\par 
\par In apology for the lateness of our arrival we mentioned our difficulties
\par in discovering that he was in. Mr. Chesterton seemed bewildered by the
\par circumstance. He shook his head and (evidently referring to the
\par hall-man) said he was not able to understand "that foreigner" at all.
\par "That foreigner?" we smiled at the Englishman. I think it most likely
\par that the explanation of his not having heard our earlier rings was that
\par he was not familiar with the system of bells in the apartment. They had
\par not been out, he declared; oh, yes! they had been out, too, a good while
\par ago, to get something to eat. "We are camping here," he said, "in a
\par rather Bohemian fashion." Didn't they enjoy that as a change from life
\par in fashionable hotels? Oh, yes! Very much.
\par 
\par They wondered if Mr. Lee were not coming. Yes; he had assured me that he
\par was, when I had seen him that afternoon at the club. In fact, we had
\par discussed what we would wear, and had agreed on dinner jackets. Mr.
\par Chesterton was wearing a braid-bound cutaway coat of felt-like material
\par (very much wrinkled in the skirt) and dark striped trousers of stiffish
\par quality, but not recently pressed. His bat-wing collar had a sharp
\par crease extending outward at one side as though it were broken. Though it
\par was a very warm night for early spring--a hot night, indeed--he wore
\par uncommonly heavy woolen sox, which were very much "coming down" about
\par his ankles. His comically small English eye-glasses, with a straight rod
\par joining them across the top, were perpetually coming off his nose. On
\par one finger he wore a rather large ring. I noticed that for so large a
\par man his hands were somewhat small, and were delicately made. At one side
\par of him were three ashtrays (one of them a huge brass bowl well filled
\par with tobacco ash) and at the other side of him one tray.
\par 
\par Well, what sort of a time had he been having? How far west had he got?
\par He had been as far as (I think) Omaha. "Halfway across," he said. He had
\par been much mystified by a curious character he had run into there: a
\par strange being whose waistcoat and coat front were covered by symbolic
\par emblems, crescents, full moons and stars. This person had accosted him
\par in the street saying, "And so you are a lecturer." The man had then
\par informed him that he also was a lecturer. He lectured, he said, on
\par astronomy. "Indeed, in my country," Mr. Chesterton had said, "it is not
\par the custom for astronomers to display on their person devices symbolic
\par of the science in which they are engaged." Next, the man had opened his
\par coat and exhibited the badge of a sheriff, or some sort of officer of
\par the peace. Mr. Chesterton had been astounded to discover the functions
\par of a man of science, a lecturer and a policeman united in one and the
\par same person. It was quite evident that this (as I assume he was)
\par harmless lunatic had made a most decided impression upon Mr.
\par Chesterton's mind; he took the eccentric individual with much
\par seriousness, apparently as some kind of a type; indeed, I feared that we
\par would never get him switched off from talking about him; and I have no
\par doubt that, in the course of time, this ridiculous astronomer will
\par appear as a bizarre character in some fantastic tale, a personage
\par perhaps related to Father Brown, or something like that.
\par 
\par Mr. Chesterton observed that he had enjoyed the opportunity of seeing
\par various grades of American life, that he had been in the homes of very
\par humble people as well as in houses of persons of wealth and social and
\par intellectual position. In a former article I noted how Mr. Chesterton
\par had been greatly startled to find (what he then called) "wooden houses"
\par in this country, and such multitudes of them. He now returned to this
\par phenomenon. What was his one outstanding impression of the United
\par States? Well, he remarked that he had said it before, but he continued
\par to be chiefly struck by the vast number of "frame houses" here.
\par 
\par Mr. Lee arrived. A gentleman who looks very much as though you were
\par looking at his reflection in one of those trick mirrors (such as they
\par have at Coney Island) which humorously attenuate and elongate the
\par figures before them. Or, again, perhaps more justly still, a gentleman
\par who looks as though Daumier had drawn him as an illustration for "Don
\par Quixote." In his evening clothes (to put it still another way), a
\par gentleman who looks much like a very lengthened shadow dancing on a
\par wall. Mr. Whistler would have made something very striking indeed out of
\par Mr. Lee in a dinner coat, something beautifully strange. I do not know
\par that I have ever seen anything finer, in its own exceedingly peculiar
\par way, than Mr. Lee, thus attired, with a cup of tea in his hand.
\par 
\par "Do you like wine?" Mr. Woollcott asked Mr. Chesterton, and told him of
\par a restaurant nearby where this could be obtained. Our prohibition, Mr.
\par Chesterton said, did not bother him so much as might be thought, as for
\par reasons having to do with his health he was (as you or I would say)
\par "off the stuff" at present.
\par 
\par One of us, Mr. Woollcott I think, commented upon the sweep of Mr.
\par Chesterton's fame in the United States. The opinion was advanced that
\par the evening of the day he landed his arrival was known in every literate
\par home in New York. Mr. Chesterton was inclined to think that his
\par "notoriety" in large measure came from his "appearance," his
\par "avoirdupois." Knowledge of him had spread through the notion that he
\par was a "popular curiosity." It was contended that his writing had been
\par well-known over here ten years before his pictures became familiar to
\par us. (Though, of course, I myself do think that the pictorial quality of
\par his corporeal being has been very effective publicity for him.)
\par 
\par Then there was another thing which Mr. Chesterton thought might to a
\par considerable degree account for his American celebrity. That was this
\par "tag" of "paradox." People loved "easy handles" like that, and they went
\par a long way. Somehow or other we let this point pass, or it got lost in
\par the shuffle, and the discussion turned to the question of whether there
\par was an American writer living whose arrival in England would command
\par anything like the general attention occasioned by Mr. Chesterton's
\par entrance into the United States. We could not think of anyone.
\par 
\par Mark Twain, of course; yes. O. Henry, doubtless, too. And, indeed, in
\par the matter of years O. Henry might very well be living now. Mr.
\par Chesterton quite agreed as to the English welcome of Mark Twain or of O.
\par Henry. Tom Sawyer and Huck, he said musingly, certainly were
\par "universal." Then, ponderingly, he observed that English and American
\par literature seemed to be getting farther and farther apart, or more and
\par more distinct each from the other. That is, he remembered that when he
\par was a boy his father and his uncles simply spoke of a new book having
\par come out whether it had been written in England or in the United States.
\par As in the case of the "Autocrat of the Breakfast Table": when it
\par appeared it was enjoyed and talked about by everybody in England; but
\par not spoken of there as a new American book: it was a new book, that's
\par all. Now, however, with Englishmen impressed by the "Spoon River
\par Anthology," "and rightly so," or by "Main Street," "it would not be that
\par way."
\par 
\par He had much liking for O. Henry. But he had begun by not liking him. He
\par had been puzzled by the "queer commercial deals" on which so many of the
\par stories turned--"buying towns, selling rivers." He had, even now, to
\par re-read much of the slang to get the meaning. And so we talked awhile of
\par slang.
\par 
\par "You have an expression here," said Mr. Chesterton, shaking his head as
\par though that were something very remarkable indeed, "_a bad actor_" Much
\par mirth from Woollcott, Lee and Holliday. "Now in England," Mr. Chesterton
\par continued, "we mean by that one who has mistaken his vocation as to the
\par stage. But I discovered that here it has nothing to do with the
\par theatrical profession." Then, it developed, some reporter in the West
\par had referred to him as "a regular guy." At first Mr. Chesterton had been
\par for going after the fellow with a stick.... Certainly a topsy-turvy
\par land, the United States, where you can't tell opprobrium from flattering
\par compliment.
\par 
\par Then one of us told Mr. Chesterton a story of a prize line of American
\par slang. He (the teller of the story) had got a letter in which a friend
\par of his had been spoken of in a highly eulogistic fashion. Thinking this
\par opinion of him would please his friend this man showed the letter to
\par him. The gentleman so much praised in it read the letter and remarked:
\par "Well, whenever I get the hand I always see the red light." Mr.
\par Chesterton looked dazed. "You'll have to translate that to me," he said.
\par It was explained to him that the meaning of this was that whenever this
\par person heard applause of himself he always scented danger. "Oh, oh! I
\par see!" crowed Mr. Chesterton, "the hand, the hand," and he began clapping
\par his hands in illustration of the figure with much glee.
\par 
\par "Glee," yes. And "crowed," also. They are the words, some of the words,
\par to describe Mr. Chesterton's sounds. His utterance was rapid, melodious.
\par The modulations of his softly flowing voice had curiously somewhat the
\par effect of a very cheerful music-box. His easy and very natural command
\par of a great multitude of words was striking. And yet there was something
\par decidedly boyish about the effect of his talk. I think the cause of this
\par was, for one thing, the rather gurgling enjoyment with which he spoke,
\par and for another thing, in his impulsive concern for the point of his
\par idea he frequently did not trouble to begin nor end sentences. He just
\par let 'er go. But the fundamental source of this boyishness of spirit I
\par think was this: I do not believe I have ever seen a man who had borne
\par the brunt of life for some forty-five years and still retained such
\par complete, abounding, unaffected and infectious good humor as Mr.
\par Chesterton.
\par 
\par "As I believe I have said somewhere before," Mr. Chesterton was saying,
\par "it seems to me that the best known character in literature is Sherlock
\par Holmes." Mr. Woollcott was inclined to consider Svengali. Dear me!
\par Svengali may have been in the running at one time, but it strikes me
\par that today he has pretty much gone by the board, somewhat to mix the
\par figure.
\par 
\par As to detective stories: "They are essentially domestic," declares Mr.
\par Chesterton. "Intimate, all in the household, or ought to be. The
\par children's nurse should murder the Bishop. These things where the
\par Foreign Office becomes involved and" (chuckling) "Indian rajahs and
\par military forces come in are never right. They are too big. The detective
\par story is a fireside story."
\par 
\par Had Mr. Chesterton been much to the theatre while here? No; the only
\par thing he had seen was "The Bat." Something like anguish on the face of
\par the dramatic critic of the New York _Times_. Why, he, Mr. Chesterton,
\par had liked "The Bat," a good deal. Speaking of plays, the American
\par presentation of "Magic" came into the conversation. It was remarked that
\par the extremely mystical character of the setting rather crushed the
\par mysticism of the play itself. The idea was advanced that a very simple,
\par matter-of-fact, even bleak setting, would have been the thing to act as
\par an effective foil to this play. Mr. Chesterton seemed to be not the
\par slightest interested in stage-settings. And he knew next to nothing at
\par all about the career of "Magic." He wasn't even sure whether or not he
\par held any proprietary rights in the play. There was, he said as though
\par fumbling around in his mind, something involved about the matter. Friend
\par of his wanted a play. Necessary to finish it in a hurry. He didn't
\par really know, answering a question to this purpose, whether or not he
\par received any royalties from it.
\par 
\par Mrs. Chesterton again handed about some fudge. The collection of
\par ash-trays and bowls surrounding Mr. Chesterton had become jovially
\par freighted with tobacco ash and cigar ends. He smoked his cigars in an
\par economical fashion, down as far as they could comfortably be held.
\par 
\par There was one thing (the talk had turned to his lecturing) Mr.
\par Chesterton "wished you wouldn't do in this country, or that we didn't do
\par in England, either." That was for the gentleman who "introduced" a
\par lecturer to refer to his "message." In his own case, for instance, how
\par ridiculously was this term misapplied. The word "message" conveyed
\par something "quite the opposite of personality." Or, that is, before its
\par popular corruption it had meant something very different. It meant that
\par something was carried. One with a message was a messenger, a vessel, an
\par envelope. It was hard to think of a figure who could rightly be said to
\par have a message. The Old Testament prophets, Mohammed, perhaps. Whitman,
\par now certainly you couldn't say that Whitman had a message.
\par 
\par A ring; and Mr. Cushman came in. Youthfully cropped grey hair. A
\par gentleman who looked like a habitual first-nighter.
\par 
\par Yes, Mr. Chesterton was telling us, it was a curious thing. He had
\par always heard that Americans worshipped machines. A machine everywhere
\par here, and a machine brought to an amazing state of mechanical
\par perfection, was the elevator, as we called it. When he had first got
\par into an American elevator he had been arrested by the fact that the men
\par entering it took off their hats and stood silently with bared heads as
\par it ascended. It is so, he had said to himself, they are at worship, at
\par prayer, this is some religious rite, mystic ceremony, the elevator is
\par their temple.
\par 
\par Had he been in our subway? was asked. No; he had been down in a station
\par one time, but he had not ridden on one of the trains. I wish now that I
\par had thought to cut into the rapid battledore and shuttlecock of the
\par conversation to learn why he had not been. Was he scared of 'em?
\par 
\par What were the things which Mr. Chesterton particularly liked in the
\par United States? Well, for one thing, he very much liked the "elevated."
\par He thought it was grand up in the air that way.
\par 
\par And what had be especially _disliked_? Mr. Lee apparently had knowledge
\par of a memorandum book kept by Mrs. Chesterton, known to their ultimate
\par little circle as her "Book of Likes and Dislikes." She was, with some
\par difficulty, prevailed upon to read from this--which she did very
\par guardedly, clutching the book very firmly before her. Among the things
\par put down in it as not liked were ice cream, ice water, "American boots"
\par (by which was meant women's high-heeled shoes), and interviewers,
\par reporters and camera men. Things especially liked included parlor-car
\par seats. Mr. Chesterton: "I don't dislike it, now. I've got the evil habit
\par of ice water."
\par 
\par "Lift," it was generally agreed, was a happier word than "elevator."
\par Mrs. Chesterton thought that the scientific, technical, correct, or
\par whatever you call them, words for things always took all the feeling of
\par life out of them. "Aviator," for example, had no color at all. But how
\par fine in the spirit of the thing was the popular term "flying-man," or
\par "fly-man"!
\par 
\par The conversation had got momentarily divided into groups. Mr. Chesterton
\par was heard saying to Mr. Woollcott, "The time I mean was when Yeats was
\par young--when mysticism was jazz."
\par 
\par Just how he got started in on them I do not recall. He began with
\par Belloc's most entertaining and highly vivacious ballad which has the
\par refrain, "And Mrs. James will entertain the king"; a kind of a piece
\par among friends, which unfortunately is not in any book. He recited with a
\par kind of joyous unction, nodding his head forward and back from side to
\par side, thus keeping time to the music of the verse, punctuating the close
\par of each stanza with bubble of chuckles. On and on and on and on he went
\par through goodness knows how many bits of rollicking literary fooling.
\par 
\par It was half past eleven. I saw Mr. Chesterton, when someone else was
\par speaking, yawn slightly now and then. The four callers arose to go. Some
\par one of us asked Mr. Chesterton if he expected to be back in America
\par soon. Through a wreath of smiles he replied that he was not getting a
\par return ticket on the boat.
\par 
\par The two of them were framed in their doorway as we got into the
\par "foreigner's" car. Mrs. Chesterton called to us that she hoped to see us
\par all in England, "singly or together." As the car dropped from their
\par floor both were beaming a merry, friendly farewell.
\par 
\par Suddenly it struck me that they were very like a pair of children--they
\par were so happy, so natural, so innocent of guile, and obviously so fond
\par of one another.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par CHAPTER XII
\par 
\par NO SYSTEM AT ALL TO THE HUMAN SYSTEM
\par 
\par 
\par I think I'll tell you about myself. Maybe it's the same way with you.
\par Anyhow, it's a mighty queer thing. And we ought to try to get some light
\par on the matter--why there is, apparently, no reason or logic at all about
\par our systems.
\par 
\par You see, I go along a pretty fair amount of the time feeling all right;
\par nothing wrong with my system; nothing, at any rate, that I can notice.
\par Everybody says: "How well you're looking! Great color, you've got." And
\par so on.
\par 
\par Then, maybe, I see in the paper that there is an epidemic scheduled to
\par devastate the city pretty soon. This news lays hold of me right off. The
\par paper goes on to say that it behooves all citizens to take thought to
\par fortify their systems against the ravages of this terrible disease which
\par is rapidly approaching.
\par 
\par Or I read, say, that Thrift Week was such an enormous success (for
\par everybody else) that a campaign is under way to inaugurate a Health
\par Week, which (I read) will greatly reduce the mortality in the community.
\par The way to reduce my own mortality (I read with considerable attention)
\par is for me to Stop, Look and Listen in the matter of my health. And To Do
\par It Now! I don't like those profane words, like mortality. They disturb
\par me. And occasionally get me into no end of trouble--as you'll see.
\par 
\par Or, perhaps, I notice around in cars and places an unusual number of
\par advertisements instructing you what firm to consult in order to
\par "safeguard the interests of your heirs." A died (one of these cards may
\par say) and left his estate to B, his widow, naming C as executor. C died
\par suddenly shortly afterward. B (the widow) met E, with oil lands in
\par Hawaii--and so on. The advertisement winds up: Are you A?
\par 
\par Not yet; I'm not! But I'd better watch out. I know this is a good
\par advertisement because it gets into my mind the way it does.
\par 
\par Or, again, perhaps there are just a number of little things that I come
\par across. A gentleman one day tells me at luncheon, we'll say, that he
\par can't drink tea because it gives him uric acid so bad. Good gracious!
\par And I (maybe) subject to uric acid!
\par 
\par An octogenarian (we'll suppose) is interviewed. He attributes his
\par longevity to abstemiousness in the use of inexpensive cigarettes. (I at
\par once put mine out.)
\par 
\par A chemist (very likely) gets a lot of publicity by declaring that you
\par are to Look Before You Leap in the matter of drinking water. (And but
\par the night before I drank from the spout in the kitchen!) And so on.
\par Well, things such as these set one to thinking.
\par 
\par I say to myself when I get that way (to thinking, I mean) a stitch in
\par time saves nine; there's no loss so bad as the loss of your health,
\par because if you have that you can obtain aught else; a word to the wise
\par is sufficient; make hay while the sun shines; little drops of water wear
\par away the stone; take heed for the morrow while it is yet May; be not
\par like unto the foolish virgin who spilt the beans. And many other things
\par of this kind, which (doubtless in wise measure) are both good and true.
\par 
\par Well, in short, I determine to "build up," to get myself in thoroughly
\par "good shape."
\par 
\par I swear off smoking. I put away the home brew. I do not eat fresh
\par bread. I procure myself overshoes against the rain. I rise with the
\par lark. I (religiously eating an apple first) go to bed betimes. I walk so
\par many miles a day--also skip a rope. I shun all delicacies of the table.
\par I take those horrid extra cold baths, for the circulation. I do "deep
\par breathing." I "relax" for twelve minutes each day. I shun the
\par death-dealing demon "worry." I "fix my mind on cheerful thoughts." I
\par "take up a hobby," philately, or something like that. I eat the skins of
\par potatoes. I watch the thermometer at the office, and monkey continually
\par with the steam radiator. Everything like that.
\par 
\par When you undertake a thing (even if it's only shelling peas) be thorough
\par in it, that's my motto. I don't, indeed, in this regimen get much work
\par done, but it's better to be slow and sure.
\par 
\par Well, what happens?
\par 
\par When I set out to build up this is what happens to me: First thing,
\par maybe, I get pimples. No; no maybe about it. I sure get pimples. Then,
\par very likely, I get a carbuncle. (I have just asked my assistant how you
\par spell that word. She inquires if I mean the gem, or--or the other. I
\par have told her I mean the other.)
\par 
\par Next, very probably, I "contract" (as they say) a cough. This cough
\par "develops" into a cold.... You have (I trust) had that sort of cold
\par which hangs on for months. Nothing recommended is of any help to you.
\par You become resigned (more or less) to the idea--just as a man who has
\par lost a leg (or his mind) must resolve to do the best he can with the
\par rest of his life without his leg (or his mind), so must you adapt
\par yourself to the stern condition imposed by Fate of always having a cold.
\par That's the kind of a cold I mean that I get. (Only worse!)
\par 
\par My cold branches out into several little side lines, such as acute
\par neuralgia and inflammatory rheumatism. Stiff joints impede my agility in
\par getting down the hill to my morning train to the city. I slip on the ice
\par and break my glasses.
\par 
\par Not having my glasses causes me at the office to greet Mr. Sloover as
\par Mr. Rundle, and this sort of error breathes a chill upon the nice
\par nuances of business.
\par 
\par Or in my personal correspondence (if I were that kind of a person) I
\par might put my letter for Penelope into the envelope for Pauline. This,
\par when I had discovered the calamity, would doubtless perturb my thoughts.
\par My thoughts being perturbed, I might walk out of the restaurant without
\par my change of three dollars and eighty cents. Thoroughly upset by now, I
\par walk under a ladder. Realizing that I have done this, my nervousness is
\par the occasion of my dropping my watch. Enough! I recognize that there is
\par no use in my going back to the office that afternoon. I telephone in
\par that I have gone home to bed with my cold.
\par 
\par On coming out of the cigar store where the telephone booth is, I see
\par Christopher Morley, Don Marquis and Franklin P. Adams walking down the
\par street arm in arm. (I can see very little without my glasses, but well
\par enough to recognize such a spectacle as that.) Something, I say, must be
\par on. And I cheer up considerably. Some cheering up certainly is just what
\par I need. I overhaul the company. And I ask it (the company) where it is
\par bound. It says: "For 'Mecca.' Come along." Don hands me a pocket flask
\par (largely empty), Chris presents me with a large green cigar, and Frank
\par gives me a match. It is agreed that we roll a little pool for a few
\par hours while waiting for the cab.
\par 
\par Well, you see, I've been led to abandon the idea of building up my
\par health--but I don't care, one may as well die happy.
\par 
\par I have a great time at that show. (My cold is immensely better.) I fix
\par on one eye-glass so as to see something desirable. And I cut up a lot.
\par 
\par But--when we turn to leave I discover the president of my company going
\par out just ahead of me. Well, I suppose I'll have to take what is coming
\par to me tomorrow.
\par 
\par That one good meal, anyhow (after the pool), has strengthened my spirit
\par immensely. I plan to have a regular, genuine breakfast in the morning.
\par The kind I used to enjoy before I started in to get myself in fine
\par shape. A breakfast of sliced pineapple, eggs, steak, fried potatoes,
\par cottage-cheese, hot rolls, and two pots of good strong coffee. A pipe
\par afterward.
\par 
\par When I get out to the house I find that my uncle (from whom I had been
\par estranged for years) has died, and left me his fine, ninety carat, forty
\par jewel, repeater watch.
\par 
\par I wake up bursting with joyous life. The girl tells me that those
\par especially handsome glasses I lost last New Year's Eve have been found.
\par Down at the station the station-master comes out to greet me. He says
\par so many people have slipped on our hill that next week the railroad is
\par going to install a free coach service. I see by the morning paper that
\par the horse I took a twelve to one shot on in the Buenos Aires derby came
\par out the length of the stretch to the good. On the train into town I
\par smoke a couple of packages of cigarettes--as I become a bit bothered
\par about the situation at the office.
\par 
\par A girder, or something, had fallen across the track. The train is held
\par up. For a couple of hours it stands there. I become more than decidedly
\par nervous. Now this is awful bad doings. Everything had been coming so
\par right again. It seems as if there is no reward in this world for
\par anything. Here for a whole month or so I had been subjecting myself to
\par the most rigorous and unpleasant kind of discipline solely in order to
\par make myself more efficient in my work, and so more valuable to the
\par house. Nothing else. Then by an accident I am kept away from the office
\par one afternoon, and this has to go and happen just to keep me away
\par probably the whole of the forenoon. Everything will, of course, be
\par misunderstood and misinterpreted. Instead of getting just credit for
\par what I've done, I'll probably get bounced. If anyone wants to have the
\par moral of this story pointed out to him: it is that there is not much use
\par in trying, you can see that.
\par 
\par When I do get to the office my secretary is in quite a flurry. She tells
\par me that Mr. Equity, the president, has been inquiring for me. In
\par fact--she hesitates--wants me to step in to see him as soon as I arrive.
\par 
\par So, there you are!
\par 
\par Mr. Equity (a most unusual thing in any circumstances) shakes my hand
\par with great cordiality. He smiles, not benignantly but rather
\par deferentially. Says that he has recognized for some little time that I
\par have not had a salary commensurate with my services. Times, however, are
\par not of the best. Would I be willing to continue with the firm at--a
\par pause--well, double my present salary? Everything, he adds, would be
\par made as pleasant for me as possible.
\par 
\par His secretary whispers to me in an outer office: "He has been so
\par flustered. He was scared you weren't ever coming back."
\par 
\par I discussed this matter of the strange workings of the human system with
\par a friend of mine outside the office. "Ah!" he said, "you didn't
\par persevere long enough in looking after yourself. If you had kept it up
\par for a year instead of only a month, you'd be a well man today. And," he
\par added seriously, "a successful man, too."
