\par CHAPTER XIII
\par 
\par SEEING THE "SITUATIONS WANTED" SCENE
\par 
\par 
\par "What a lot of things they put in the papers!" Hilaire Belloc observes
\par somewhere in one of his essays. Indeed, it is so!
\par 
\par I fear, however, that one of the features "they" put in the papers does
\par not have anything like as popular a reading as it deserves to have.
\par Those of the governing class, personages who employ people, probably
\par consult fragments of this department of the newspaper now and then. But,
\par it may fairly be claimed, nobody reads, with the delicious pleasure and
\par the abundant profit he might read, that part of the paper fullest of all
\par of, so to say, meat and gravy.
\par 
\par The story it tells is probably the deepest grounding in life to be found
\par in print. There as it stands in today's paper Shakespeare (I fancy)
\par could not have written it, nor Balzac, nor Dickens, nor Arnold Bennett,
\par nor O. Henry, nor Sinclair Lewis. This newspaper feature is called
\par "Situations Wanted." It might just as accurately be called "The Human
\par Scene," or "The Heart of the World," or "The Cry of the Soul." Its tale
\par is of what all men are seeking (and have ever sought), each in his own
\par degree, and after his fashion--bread, a place in the sun, a level higher
\par than that of today.
\par 
\par Let us, briefly, survey this Page of Life.
\par 
\par The most conspicuous figure in the vast and motley throng is the Bold
\par and Confident Man. He that knows his superior worth and does not propose
\par to hide his light, he that has the spirit to attack the conqueror. His
\par method is to fling a large and arresting headline across his "ad." "I AM
\par THE MAN YOU WANT!" he begins. Or, "PAR-EXCELLENCE," he announces in big
\par type. Or, "Mr. Busy Manufacturer," he says in good sized "caps"; in
\par smaller letters asks: "Are you in need of _a competent manager_?" If Mr.
\par B. M. is in such need, it is squarely put up to him: he "will do well to
\par address X." To the employer who hesitates this vital opportunity is
\par lost. The ad says: "Write now--_Right Now!_" Undoubtedly this is the
\par horse to put your money on; the hero to marry your daughter to. He will
\par not want.
\par 
\par Our bold, aggressive friend frequently writes, barring a bit of
\par "bounce," an admirable, clean-cut account of himself. He has, he
\par declares, acted for some of the leading concerns in the country; he has
\par never yet failed to give satisfaction; every employer he ever had will
\par testify to his ability and character. He invites the closest
\par investigation of his record, and he is open for any engagement where
\par faithful work, absolute integrity and devotion to his employer's
\par interests will be productive of "a fair living salary." It is, indeed,
\par difficult to avoid the impression that this man "has the goods."
\par 
\par Akin to him in his method of a bill-board-like headline is another, of
\par whom one is not so sure. He does not so much command attention as seek
\par to beguile it. His particular "lay" is the Ingenious. Here is one
\par example of his style:
\par 
\par                     AN ADVERTISING ADVENTURER
\par 
\par                    offers 16 years' experience
\par 
\par      (scarred by a few notable defeats and a thorough knowledge edge of
\par      what NOT to do) to a manufacturer, for whom he will SAVE more than
\par      his wages; a bad man, who does not drink, never was out of work, is
\par      married and proud of it; age 32; would rather work than eat.
\par      Address: Alert.
\par 
\par Then there is the Challenge Not to Be Denied. Here is a sample:
\par "_Accountant_.--Are you one of the progressive firms? If you are, you
\par want----" etc. Frequently one comes across the Facetious Advertiser. He
\par runs some such headline as this: "_Editor for Rent._" Or perhaps he
\par says: "'_Secretarial Services' For Sale._" In contrast to him is the
\par advertiser with the Tremulous Appeal. He may begin: "_Who Wants My
\par Services?_" And go on to say: "I am hard worker and steady, and willing
\par to go anywhere. Salary about $12 a week." Or perhaps he says:
\par "_Privilege_ of meeting man who can utilize my services." Or maybe it is
\par thus: "$15 per Week and an Opportunity." Such a very human ad as this is
\par likely to continue somewhat like this:
\par 
\par      Can you use a young man of twenty-one--one of really serious
\par      purpose? I have had enough business experience and training to know
\par      that to be of help I must do well whatever I am given to do. Of
\par      course I am looking for a future--but I know that it does not
\par      matter so much what I do as how I do it. Therefore, I believe any
\par      reputable business holds a future. I am from Kansas, in New York on
\par      my own resources and so must have $15 per week to start. I have a
\par      high school education, and have read a great deal, and have
\par      attended Business School.
\par 
\par Next is the Poignant ad. The purest example of this which in my studies
\par I have discovered is headed: "_Who Will Talk With Me?_" A step beyond
\par this we come upon the Altogether Pitiful. I mean like the one I here
\par copy out:
\par 
\par      WILL you please find or give office employment to an educated, with
\par      physical defect, young man; just a chance to work two weeks without
\par      salary desired?
\par 
\par Akin to the poignant situation-wanted advertisement is the Urgent:
\par "_Advertising Writer_, college man (Princeton), urgently needs
\par situation." Or: "_Proofreader_, educated young man, requires position
\par _immediately_." It is, such is the inference, defective philanthropy in
\par an employer to delay. A touching figure, too (because he does not
\par suspect that he is a touching figure), is the Cheery and Hopeful. We
\par have him here: "_Ambitious_ young American (28) desires position; will
\par try anything; moderate salary to start."
\par 
\par A wily fellow is the Ingratiating advertiser. Sometimes he is a "Spanish
\par young man" who offers to work altogether without salary as Spanish
\par correspondent in some export house "where he could practice English."
\par Occasionally he is a "copy writer" who, wishing a position with an
\par agency or mercantile firm, is "willing to demonstrate ability for two
\par weeks before drawing salary." Now and then a still more positive
\par character baits the hook with the offer of gratis services. In this
\par morning's paper a stenographer releases the seductive declaration that
\par "one trial will demonstrate my value to you."
\par 
\par A r\'f4le played on the stage of the "Situations Wanted" page which I have
\par always much admired is that of the Highly Dignified. The Bold and
\par Confident Man, the Ingenious, the Tremulous, the Poignant, the Hopeful,
\par the Ingratiating--the voices of all these figures touch one with a sense
\par of the harsh clash of life, its trickiness, its vicissitudes, its pathos
\par and its tragedy. But "_A Gentleman_ of 50," who, "having a considerable
\par private income, desires dignified occupation; salary unimportant,"
\par revives the poetic idea that (at any rate, now and then) God's in His
\par heaven and all's right with the world. The highly dignified advertiser
\par certainly is a very enviable character. It must be very nice to be able
\par to say, as in this advertisement before us: "_Light Occupation of an
\par Important Nature_ is sought by middle-aged gentleman capable of assuming
\par control and conducting any normal business enterprise."
\par 
\par A very colorful feature of the "Situations Wanted" page is the
\par interesting qualifications frequently set forth. Glancing at the paper
\par in hand I find a young man of twenty-five who seeks a "permanent
\par position" with a publisher recommending himself as being "affable." Also
\par here is a "refined gentleman" who desires a "compatible" position and
\par lists among his accomplishments skill in the art of "tasty drawing." A
\par "keen discreet American" looking for a job with a "corporation" mentions
\par his "suave manners." A butler unemployed regards himself as "very nice."
\par A college graduate of twenty-eight who wants to "begin at the bottom"
\par asserts that he is a "fluent talker." A "young man with literary
\par ability" flings out the intimation that he "desires position where it
\par will be of some use." A dressmaker states that in her calling she is
\par "perfect." A clerk is "very smart at figures." A nurse puts forward her
\par asset as a "plain writer." You are pleased to discover that so many
\par people have a "pleasing personality." And that among stenographers there
\par are so many who may be described (they say) as an "attractive young
\par girl." Here is one who introduces herself as both "prepossessing" and
\par "brainy." A "woman of education" who seeks occupation at "anything
\par useful if there is friendliness" gives as her leading characteristic a
\par "sense of humor." Now and then the recommendations offered somewhat
\par mystify me, as in the advertisement of the lady, "age 29, fine
\par personality (widow of P. M. of F. and A. M.)." Then there is that great
\par company who have but one merit to display. They may be represented in
\par the "Female" column by the "_Respectable_ young woman" who "wishes day's
\par work." And in the "Male" column by the "_Sober_ man" who (simply)
\par "desires position." Sometimes here it is difficult to determine the
\par degree of sobriety maintained, as in the frequent advertisement of the
\par chauffeur who discreetly states that he is "temperate."
\par 
\par In case you should write down your idea of your own "appearance," what
\par would you say? I confess that such a problem would puzzle me. It does
\par not puzzle some. "Situation Wanted" ads record that there are numerous
\par young men of "exceptional appearance." Though occasionally we come upon
\par a young man of almost painful conscientiousness who feels that he should
\par not go further than to say that he is of "fair appearance."
\par 
\par The queer dissimilarity of human aspirations echoes through the
\par "Situations Wanted" page. Here is a "_Gentleman_, excellent education
\par and personality, linguist," who wants a position as a companion, or
\par "courier, &c." A "_Highly_ educated French lady would gladly take a
\par child for walks every day from 10 to 12." A "_Lady_, 27, of literary
\par bent desires position as companion around the world." It is remarkable,
\par the number of persons there are in the world of "literary" tendency.
\par Remarkable, too, how many people with an inclination to travel. Here is
\par a "_Cornell Graduate_" who has, apparently, no aversion whatever to
\par spending the winter in "a warm climate." There are "_Two_ young men,
\par partners," who "wish to join an expedition, any destination." But there
\par are home-keeping souls, too. A "_Cultured_ elderly man, neat," craves
\par "household duties." And so on.
\par 
\par What a rich variety of characters throng the populous scene of the
\par "Situations Wanted" page! Here, in today's paper, following the
\par advertisement of a "sculptor" comes that of a "former policeman." A
\par "_Physician_, practicing twenty years in Paris, speaking English,
\par French, Spanish, German, Italian, seeking situation," is cheek by jowl
\par with a "_Plumber_, good all round man." A young man who has "put 9 years
\par at sea as steward" nonchalantly asks "What have you?" A "_Former
\par College Professor_, 30, seeks field of occupation in advertising." And a
\par "_Cavalry_ man, excellent record, wishes position at anything." A
\par "_Cultured Visiting Governess_ of good family, social position, trains
\par ladies, English, grammar, literature, elegant correspondence, art of
\par conversation, current events, social etiquette." A remarkable
\par "gentleman" presents himself as "qualified to do most anything." And a
\par "Christian, age 38," wishes a position as "manager of a laundry."
\par 
\par A strategic device frequently employed by the humble is that of getting
\par someone whose position has weight to present them. For instance, "Rev.
\par Dr. Moffett recommends a colored man for janitor of a loft building."
\par And numerous are the gentlemen who, laying up their cars, are interested
\par in placing their chauffeurs elsewhere.
\par 
\par "_Boy_" is perhaps the word which dominates the page. Most boys,
\par apparently, are not particular in their choice of a calling. They are
\par "willing to do anything." Now and then one declares that he is a "good
\par fighter," or something like that. Here is one who demands a "position
\par where mental ability will be necessary." Here is another who is very
\par specific, thus: "15-1/2 years old, 5 feet 8-1/4 inches tall."
\par 
\par Sometimes one meets a very extraordinary character in these columns. The
\par other day no less a distinguished person than this put in an ad:
\par 
\par      I am compelled, through severe strain, to discontinue my work
\par      (involving the mental faculties) with which I have puzzled the
\par      scientific world for several years, and which has netted me a
\par      weekly income of over $200; I have no other source for a livelihood
\par      and consequently appeal to the business world for an opportunity to
\par      grow up in a new endeavor. WHY NOT MEET ME AND TALK IT OVER?
\par 
\par A genuinely touching ad, sensible and obviously quite sincere, in which
\par you hear the appealing voice of a fellow being in trouble, but an ad
\par which I fear is rather futile, is one like this:
\par 
\par      Am 43 years old; defective hearing prevents continuation of
\par      salesman's career; I want situation where this impairment does not
\par      prevent satisfactory discharge of required duties.
\par 
\par A great, and a grave, lesson may be learned from the "Situations Wanted"
\par page. And that is to be found mainly in the section where the first word
\par of each advertisement is simply "MAN." Men there are in it of every age.
\par I mean in considering the plight of the world one should ponder that
\par great army whose business is "anything."
\par 
