\par 
\par CHAPTER XIV
\par 
\par LITERARY LIVES
\par 
\par 
\par "My God!" exclaimed the old lady in the railway carriage to Mr. Le
\par Gallienne, "Tennyson is dead!"
\par 
\par Have not many of us as we have turned the daily papers these last
\par several years frequently experienced the sensations of this dear old
\par lady? Whistler, Swinburne, Meredith, Henry James, Howells. They are
\par dead. Walt Whitman (wasn't it?), when he heard that Carlyle was dead,
\par went out, and looked up at the stars, and said he didn't believe it.
\par 
\par We have been stirred to these emotional reflections by chancing to come
\par early this afternoon in the Main Reading Room of the New York Public
\par Library upon what would commonly be called a well-known book of
\par reference. We had no intention of doing more than peer into it. Night
\par found us there--the book still open before us.
\par 
\par The excellent Solomon Eagle (otherwise known as J. C. Squire), in one of
\par his delightfully gossipy, though erudite, papers contributed to _The New
\par Statesman_ of London (collected, many of them, into a volume, bearing
\par the title "Books in General"), remarks of works of reference that they
\par "are extremely useful; but they resemble Virgil's Hell in that they are
\par easy things to get into and very difficult to escape from." He
\par continues:
\par 
\par      Take the Encyclop\'e6dia. I imagine that my experience with it is
\par      universal. I have only to dip my toe into this tempting morass and
\par      down I am sucked, limbs, trunk and all, to remain embedded until
\par      sleep or a visitor comes to haul me out. A man will read things in
\par      the Encyclop\'e6dia that he would never dream of looking at
\par      elsewhere--things in which normally he does not take the faintest
\par      interest....
\par 
\par      "Who's Who" takes me in the same way. Ordinarily I have no
\par      particular thirst for it. I should not dream of carrying it about
\par      in my waistcoat pocket for perusal on the Underground Railway. But
\par      once I have allowed myself to open it, I am a slave to it for
\par      hours. This has just happened to me with the new volume, upon which
\par      I have wasted a valuable afternoon. I began by looking up a man's
\par      address; I then read the compressed life-story of the gentleman
\par      next above him (a major-general), wondering, somewhat idly, whether
\par      they read of each other's performances and whether either of them
\par      resented the possession by the other of a similar, and unusual,
\par      surname. Then I was in the thick of it.
\par 
\par Even so. But an afternoon spent in reading, straight along, the work of
\par reference we have in mind could not be called wasted. Indeed, quite the
\par contrary; such an afternoon could be nothing less than one of those
\par spiritual experiences which suddenly give a measure of growth to the
\par soul.
\par 
\par The work which we came upon, in the circumstances indicated, was "The
\par Dictionary of National Biography"; and the volumes which, by chance, we
\par took down were Volumes II. and III. of the Second Supplement of the
\par Dictionary. They contain, these volumes, memoirs of 1,135 noteworthy
\par English persons dying between January 22, 1901, and December 31, 1911.
\par The alphabet extends from John Faed, artist, to George, Lord Young,
\par Scottish Judge. The contributors number 357; the list of these names is
\par a roll of the most distinguished, in all departments, in the English
\par Nation of our day. This publication, we should say, is the most
\par interesting to English-speaking people, as in all probability it is the
\par most important, generally, issued within at any rate the year of its
\par publication. And though we cannot rid ourselves of a melancholy feeling
\par in contemplating this survey of the great stream of brilliant life
\par ended, we feel there is more good reading for the money in these pages
\par than in any other book one is likely to come across at random.
\par 
\par The toll these ten years have taken! The chronicle is here of some born
\par to greatness, like Queen Victoria; of those, like Cecil Rhodes, who have
\par achieved it. And the stories are told of some whom the world's fame
\par found but within the last hour, then dead: John Millington Synge
\par (contributed by John Masefield), and Francis Thompson (by Everard
\par Meynell).
\par 
\par The proportion of biographies of men of letters predominates in
\par considerable measure. Science follows in the list, then art. The least
\par but one, sport, is the law. Among the names of women, forty-six in
\par number, are Florence Nightingale, Kate Greenaway, Charlotte Mary Yonge,
\par and Mrs. Craigie (John Oliver Hobbes).
\par 
\par Three illustrious lives entered the twentieth century in England as full
\par of years as of honors. Meredith, Whistler, and Swinburne were born in
\par the Spring of the nineteenth century, in 1828, 1834, and 1837
\par respectively, and the bloom of their days was with the giants, now
\par legends, of the Victorian reign. The Kings in the history of art and
\par letters have been--have they not?--gallant men. We suspect that it takes
\par a gallant man to be a King in these callings. Of these three--two
\par wished to be soldiers--the most gallant spirit was the great-grandson of
\par a rather grand tailor.
\par 
\par He won what men can and he bore what men must, is some ancient line.
\par 
\par The most extensive article in these volumes is the "Meredith," by Thomas
\par Seccombe. It is the richest. Twelve pages is its compass. As a biography
\par we are disposed to rank it with--let's see?---Froude's "Carlyle" (4
\par vols. 8vo.). Perhaps, on the whole, it is better. To go into any detail
\par in our notice of the appearance of these books, and maintain any
\par perspective, would carry us to a vast length. The bibliographer is
\par deeply impressed with the character of Meredith, as a man, throughout
\par his life, of noble aspect. His critical verdict reduced to one word is:
\par "Thoroughly tonic in quality, his writings are [as Lamb said of
\par Shakespeare] essentially manly." This is one of the pictures which most
\par brightly sticks in our head:
\par 
\par      On the terrace in front of the chalet, whence he descended to
\par      meals, he was often to be heard carrying on dialogues with his
\par      characters, and singing with unrestrained voice. Whimsical and
\par      sometimes Rabelaisian fabrications accompanied the process of
\par      quickening the blood by a spin [a favorite word with him] over
\par      Surrey hills. Then he wrote his master works, ... and welcomed his
\par      friends, often reading aloud to them in magnificent recitative,
\par      unpublished prose or verse.
\par 
\par If there is anything upon which an article could be "based" not included
\par in Mr. Seccombe's list of sources, it's a queer thing.
\par 
\par The "Swinburne" is furnished by Edmund Gosse, whose adequate equipment
\par for the task includes "personal recollections extending over more than
\par forty years." Passages of his portrait of the radiant poet are the most
\par colorful in these volumes of the Dictionary. By way of critical
\par discussion the writer says: "It is a very remarkable circumstance, which
\par must be omitted in no outline of his intellectual life, that his
\par opinions, on politics, on literature, on art, on life itself, were
\par formed in boyhood, and that though he expanded he scarcely advanced in
\par any single direction after he was twenty. If growth had continued as it
\par began, he must have been the prodigy of the world. Even his art was at
\par its height when he was five and twenty." The Whistler article is by Sir
\par Walter Armstrong (who writes also on Holman Hunt) and is, one feels, the
\par most judicial summary that has appeared on the most controversial
\par subject, one can readily recall, of the epoch closed. A very clear
\par statement of a principle of the art of painting is this: "For years his
\par work bore much the same relation to Japanese art as all fine painting
\par does to nature. He took from Japanese ideals the beauties he admired,
\par and re-created them as expressions of his own personality."
\par 
\par There is one delightful anecdote, in E. V. Lucas's sketch of Phil May.
\par His Punch editor, Sir Francis Burnand, tells a story to the effect that
\par on being asked at a club for a loan of fifty pounds, May produced all he
\par had--half that amount--and then abstained from the club for some time
\par for fear of meeting the borrower, because he felt that "he still owed
\par him twenty-five pounds."
\par 
\par Sensible persons will read with satisfaction the just article by T. F.
\par Henderson on that fine figure Henley, "one of the main supports," said
\par Meredith, "of good literature in our time." Many good folks will like to
\par look up Leslie Stephen, the first editor of this Dictionary, "who
\par enjoyed the affectionate admiration of his most enlightened
\par contemporaries." The article is by the present editor, Sir Sidney Lee.
\par \'c6sthetically minded persons may read about William Sharpe. Among the
\par painters are Watts (biographer, Sir Sidney Colvin) and Orchardson. The
\par "Seymour Haden" is furnished by A. M. Hind. Memoirs of Sir Henry Irving,
\par Sir Theodore Martin, and Herbert Spencer come in this supplement. And so
\par on. A piece of American history is related here, too, in the account of
\par Edward Lawrence Godkin, founder of _The Nation_.
\par 
\par A subject of emotional literary controversy at the present moment is
\par treated by Thomas Seccombe in his article on George Gissing. The general
\par qualities of the Dictionary may be clearly observed in this notice. When
\par the first volume of this second supplement--A to Evans--was issued not
\par long ago rumors reached us of some agitation occasioned in England by
\par the unepitaphical character of the memoirs of Edward VII. Well,
\par discrimination was not made against a King. The frankness of this high
\par tribunal in its calm recital of facts is striking.
\par 
\par After some steady reading of the great Dictionary we wonder if printed
\par forms had been sent to the contributors, upon which they composed, in
\par answer to the questions there, their articles: the order of progress of
\par all the memoirs is, in effect, so uniform. Each says at (it appeared)
\par about the same point: His appearance was this. Each seems to conclude
\par with a list of the portraits.
\par 
\par And this idea recalled to us a story. A foreigner entering our country's
\par gates, upon being asked to fill out papers setting forth his
\par nationality, age, color, and so on, wrote beside the query,
\par "Business?"--"Rotten." In this intelligent interpretation of the
\par question, the "business" of many whose lives are recorded in honor here
\par was "rotten" for many a long year.
\par 
\par The story of literature has not ceased to be a sorry story; still, as
\par was said on a time, comparable to the annals of Newgate. A tale it
\par continues, in a large measure, of outcast experience, of destitution,
\par "seeking a few pence by selling matches or newspapers," or development
\par through suffering, of hospital sojourns, of contemplated suicide, of
\par unfortunate "amorous propensities," of "ill-considered" marriage, of
\par that immemorial "besetting weakness," of "a curious inability to do the
\par sane, secure thing in the ordinary affairs of life," of "ordering his
\par life with extreme carelessness in financial matters," of the weariness
\par of reward for work of high character long deferred, of charitable
\par legacies "from a great-aunt."
\par 
\par Mr. Wells speaks somewhere of the amazing persistency of the instinct
\par for self-expression. Where it exists, one reflects in musing on these
\par biographies, you can't kill it with a club.
\par 
\par Very imposing we felt the literary style of this Dictionary to be. It
\par treats of a man much as if he were a word, say, in the Century
\par Dictionary. This is the sort of biographical writing, we said, that a
\par man with whiskers can read. It does sound something like a court
\par calendar. Its tone is omniscient, indeed. But the Recording Angel here
\par does not drop a tear upon the oath of any Uncle Toby and blot it out
\par forever. No. He says, of one we tremble to name, "his language was often
\par beyond the reach of apology." Fine is the dignity with which sordid
\par things are related. "The return journey he was under the necessity of
\par performing on foot." Almost grotesque is the neglect of the caressing
\par touch of sentiment. "His own wish was to be a jockey." The treatment of
\par the theme of love is entertaining. "At the age of nineteen he married."
\par 
\par August is the passivity in the presence of the Reaper who mows the
\par golden grain. Without poetry, oh, Death, where is thy sting! In these
\par volumes, of none is it sighed: At twilight his spirit fled. Had he but
\par lived ...! It is: He died December 14, 1908. He left no issue. A fair
\par portrait of him by Charles Ricketts is in the possession of Mr. Edmund
\par Gosse.
\par 
\par We arose after several hours' reading with a sense of having perused for
\par a space two recent volumes of the Book of Judgment. We were full of
\par emotion. We felt the mystery of the destiny of man. How admirable he is
\par and how pitiful! Throbbing, we went forth into the throbbing city.
