\par CHAPTER XV
\par 
\par SO VERY THEATRICAL
\par 
\par 
\par There is a young woman I thought of taking there for luncheon the other
\par day, but when I called for her it did not seem to me that she had used
\par her lip-stick that morning--and so we went somewhere else.
\par 
\par She is pretty good-looking and was dressed not at all unfashionably. She
\par would have done all right at the Waldorf, or at the Vanderbilt, or
\par Biltmore, or Ritz-Carlton, or Ambassador. Indeed, I don't know but that
\par at some such place as that I should have been rather proud of her.
\par 
\par But, you see, for the place I had in mind her skirt was a little too
\par long--it came almost halfway to her ankles. Her bosom was quite covered.
\par She moves with fair grace, but without striking sinuousness. And I
\par suddenly recollected that she does not smoke much.
\par 
\par No; I saved myself just in time; I should have been chagrined,
\par embarrassed, most decidedly uncomfortable; she would have been
\par conspicuous. I should probably have lost caste with the waiters, too;
\par and not again have been able to get a table after the plush rope had
\par been thrown across the entrance to the dining-room; which, so keen is
\par competition for places there, is shortly before one o'clock.
\par 
\par If you know where this place is, why, of course, all right. But nobody
\par has any business to go shouting all over the housetops exactly where it
\par is. People who aren't just naturally by temperament a part of the
\par picture oughtn't to know how to find it. Though it is a perfectly good
\par bet that bunches of them would like to know.
\par 
\par But that's just the way so many of these havens of the elect get ruined.
\par A lot of curious "visitors" go piling in right along; the scene soon
\par loses all its authenticity; and shortly becomes bogus altogether. Why, I
\par can remember when artists--painters and writers--lived in Greenwich
\par Village. There, in those days.... But all that was years ago.
\par 
\par This much only will I tell you about the location of the most
\par _distingu\'e9_ place there is in which to have luncheon. The centre of the
\par inhabited world is, of course, Longacre Square, that widened curving
\par stretch of Broadway looking north several blocks from the narrow stern
\par of the gracefully towering Times Building, rising from its site of a bit
\par of an island surrounded by four surging currents of traffic. A few miles
\par away (from Longacre Square) the provinces begin. But there, the most
\par gleaming spot on this our globe under the canopy of the purple night, is
\par the quintessence, the apex of human life.... I am here speaking, of
\par course, in the spirit of those of that nomad race whose hopes for gold
\par and fame lie through the "stage entrance"--I mean the ladies and
\par gentlemen of the theatre.
\par 
\par To the east just off Longacre Square along the crosstown streets is a
\par medley of offices of divers theatrical and screen journals, chop-houses,
\par and innumerable band-box hotels whose names doubtless only a district
\par messenger boy could recite in any number. The particular one for which
\par we are headed is famous enough to those familiar with fame of this
\par character. Here the "Uncle Jack" of the American stage, Mr. Drew, for
\par some time made his residence. It is always the stopping place in New
\par York of perhaps the finest of our novelists, Joseph Hergesheimer. That
\par mystical Indian gentleman, Mr. Rabindranath Tagore, has found it a not
\par unworthy tent on his western pilgrimages. And so on.
\par 
\par You cannot be long in its rich little lobby without overhearing struck
\par the high note of its distinctive clientele. "Where do you open?" asks
\par someone of someone else. And the answer is not unlikely to be: "At
\par Stamford. When do you close?" In the subdued light bare satin arms and
\par enspiriting lengths of colorful stocking flash from the deep chairs
\par where feminine forms are waiting. A graceful hand opens a telephone
\par booth to expel a smoking cigarette.
\par 
\par Here enters Walter Prichard Eaton, come down from his Berkshire farm for
\par the height of the theatrical season. A tall, leisurely, very New
\par Englandish, smooth-shaven young man, now coming decidedly grey just over
\par the ears. Entering the dining-room we come plump against our old friend
\par Meredith Nicholson lunching with a bevy of friends. A youthful fifty
\par perhaps now, the author of one of the best sellers of any day, "The
\par House of a Thousand Candles." Clean-shaven, with a physiognomy
