\par CHAPTER XVI
\par 
\par OUR STEEPLEJACK OF THE SEVEN ARTS
\par 
\par 
\par There is a rather frisky looking apartment house there now, a pastry
\par shop and tea room occupying the ground floor--behind it, the other side
\par of a venerable brick wall, a tiny, ancient burying ground. But in days
\par of yester-year here stood a tavern of renown, the Old Grape Vine, which
\par on this site, Sixth Avenue at Eleventh Street, had given cheer since
\par Sixth Avenue was little more than a country road. A sagging, soiled
\par white, two-story frame structure, with great iron grill lamps before the
\par door. Within, the main room was somewhat reminiscent of London's Olde
\par Cheshire Cheese.
\par 
\par The proprietor was a canny Scot, one MacClellan. ("Old Mac"! Whither has
\par he gone?) I was coming along by there the other day, and I asked a man
\par with whom I chanced to walk if he remembered the Old Grape Vine. "Ah!
\par yes;" he said; "they had mutton pies there." They did. And excellent
\par ale, also, served in battered pewter mugs. "They" had here, too (some
\par fifteen years ago), excellent society beneath the dingy light. Roaring,
\par roistering George Luks (as he was then) very much to the fore. At the
\par rickety mahogany table where Frans-Halsian George held forth frequently
\par was to be found the painter William J. Glackens and his brother "Lew,"
\par humorous draughtsman for _Puck_. Ernest Lawson sometimes came in. A Mr.
\par Zinzig, a very pleasant soul and an excellent pianist and teacher of the
\par piano, often was of the company. A Mr. FitzGerald, art critic in those
\par days of the _Sun_, sometimes "sat in." And a delightful old cock, Mr.
\par Stephenson, art critic then of the _Evening Post_. Among the most
\par devoted habitu\'e9s of the place was an old-school United States army
\par officer turned writer of military stories. (When the proceedings had
\par progressed to a certain stage of mellowness it was his habit to go home
\par and return directly arrayed in his uniform.) There was, too, a queer
\par figure of a derelict journalist associated with _Town Topics_. There was
\par an inoffensive gentleman of leisure whose distinction was that he was
\par brother to a famous Shakespearean scholar. (As the hour grew late he
\par would begin to whistle softly to himself through his teeth.) There was a
\par rotund being of much reading who perpetually smoked a very old pipe and
\par who was editor of a tobacco journal. There was a man of the sea who
\par continually told stories of Japan. (After eleven he was somewhat given
\par to singing.) There was an illustrator for a tu'penny magazine, who (so
\par as to seem to be a large staff) signed a variety of names to his work.
\par From the land of R. L. S., he. One time while in a doze (somewhere else)
\par he was robbed. His comment upon his misfortune became a classic line. It
\par was: "By heaven! As long as whiskey is sold to lose ten dollars is
\par enough to drive a Scot mad!" (This was long before anybody had ever
\par heard of the now illustrious Mr. Volstead.) And many more there were.
\par Ah, me! ah, me! How the picture has changed!
\par 
\par Well, the point of all this (if it have any point) is that it was in the
\par Old Grape Vine (of tender memory) that I first saw James Gibbons
\par Huneker. I think that, in his promenades as an impressionist, he was
\par there but seldom. Though we know that high among the Seven Arts he rated
\par the fine art of drinking Pilsner. The old places of Martin's and
\par L\'fcchow's (headquarters on a time for the musical cognoscenti) were ports
\par of call on his rounds; and he moved freely, I believe, among the places
\par of refreshment along the foreign quarter of lower Fourth Avenue. At the
\par Grape Vine, I understand, he was an especial friend of Luks, and
\par probably of Glackens and Lawson. And, though he was a very famous man,
\par he seemed to like the motley company.
\par 
\par Ten or twelve years ago I was earning a living more honestly than
\par perhaps I have been making one since. I was a clerk in a book store--the
\par retail department, it happened, of the house which publishes Mr.
\par Huneker's books. And there, from my position "on the floor," I
\par frequently saw him moving in and out. Moving rather slowly, with the
\par dignity of bulk. A distinguished figure, quietly but quite neatly
\par dressed, very erect in carriage, head held well back, supporting his
\par portliness with that physical pride of portly men, a physiognomy of
\par Rodinesque modelling--his cane a trim touch to the ensemble. He was, I
\par distinctly remember, held decidedly in regard by the retail staff
\par because he was (what, by a long shot, a good many "authors" were not)
\par exceedingly affable in manner to us clerks.
\par 
\par The moment I have particularly in mind was when Samuel Butler's volume
\par "The Way of All Flesh" first appeared in an American edition. We all
\par know all about Butler now. But, looking back, it certainly is
\par astonishing how innocent most all of us then were of any knowledge of
\par the great author of "Erewhon." Even so searching a student of literature
\par as W. C. Brownell was practically unacquainted with Butler. He was
\par taking home a copy of "The Way of All Flesh" to read. Mr. Huneker was
\par standing by. In some comment on the book he remarked that Butler had
\par been a painter. "A painter!" exclaimed Mr. Brownell, in a manner as
\par though wondering how it came about he knew so little of the man. "But
\par this," said Mr. Huneker, referring to the novel, "is not his best stuff.
\par That is in his note-books." Brownell: "And where are they?" Huneker: "In
\par the British Museum." Mr. Brownell made a fluttering gesture (as though
\par to express that he "gave up") toward Mr. Huneker: "He knows everything!"
\par he ejaculated.
\par 
\par We should, of course, be surprised now that anybody _did not_ know that
\par Butler had been a painter. When, just a short time ago, W. Somerset
\par Maugham adapted for the purposes of his sensational novel "The Moon and
\par Sixpence" the character and career of Paul Gauguin, it was in the pages
\par of Huneker that many first looked for, and found, intelligence
\par concerning the master of the Pont Aven school of painting. Well, Gauguin
\par is now an old story. And Ibsen, Tolstoy, Wagner, Richard Strauss,
\par Rimbaud, De Gourmont, Nietzsche, Meredith, Henry James, William James,
\par Bergson, Barr\'e8s, Anatole France, Flaubert, Lema\'eetre, Huysmans,
\par Maeterlinck, Baudelaire, Stirner, Strindberg, Faguet, Shaw, Wilde,
\par George Moore, Yeats, Synge, Schnitzler, Wederkind, Lafargue, Rodin,
\par C\'e9zane, Matisse, Picasso, Van Gogh, George Luks, that wondrous "flock of
\par Unicorns"--they all are old stories, too ... now. But it was our
\par Steeplejack, James Huneker, who was our pioneer watcher of the skies.
\par And what in the large sweep of his vision of the whole field of the
\par world's beauty he saw, he reported with infinite gusto. "Gusto," as H.
\par L. Mencken in the Huneker article of his "Book of Prefaces" says,
\par "unquenchable, contagious, inflammatory."
\par 
\par The extent of the personal contact which Mr. Huneker enjoyed and
\par maintained with the first-rate literary men of the world was amazing.
\par While I was with the book shop I speak of, "presentation copies" of each
\par new book of his, to be sent out "with the compliments of the author,"
\par were piled up for forwarding literally several feet high. They went to
\par all the great in letters, in every country, that you could think of.
\par Anatole France, Joseph Conrad, Henry James, George Brandes, Edmund
\par Gosse, George Moore--people like that.
\par 
\par Vast was the incoming stream of books to him, presentation copies,
\par review copies, "publicity" copies; so great a flood that it was
\par necessary for him periodically to call in an old book man to clear his
\par shelves by carting away a wagon-load or two of--genuine treasure. A
\par catalogue I one time saw of such volumes "from the library of James
\par Huneker" was sufficient in riches to have been the catalogue of the
\par entire stock of a very fair shop dealing in "association" volumes, first
\par editions, and so forth. And a survey of the books themselves made it
\par quite apparent that a reader who has read every word that Huneker ever
\par printed (and that would be a person who had read a good deal) may yet
\par (very likely) be a reader who has not read some of the best of Huneker.
\par I refer to "Jimmie's" humorous, pungent marginalia.
\par 
\par Mr. Huneker's close friends have taken occasion since his death to speak
\par warmly of his kindness toward obscure, struggling talent. There was a
\par side to him, akin to this, which I have not seen commented upon.
\par Huneker's fame as a critic had been for years accepted throughout
\par Europe. When his "New Cosmopolis" was published (a book I did not myself
\par think so highly of) Joyce Kilmer, then newly come to journalism,
\par reviewed it for the New York _Times_, very eulogistically. Mr. Huneker
\par went to the trouble of looking up Kilmer to thank him very simply for
\par his praise.
\par 
\par Mr. Huneker was a loyal and disinterested servant of good literature
\par wherever he found it, and his happily was the power to be an ambassador
\par to success. So short a time as about four years ago very few people had
\par heard of William McFee. "Aliens," his first book, had met with no
\par appreciable success. The manuscript of "Casuals of the Sea" (or the
\par English "sheets" of the book, I do not recall which) came into the hands
\par of a publishing house at Garden City. A member of the editorial staff of
\par this house at this time was Christopher Morley. And I happened at the
\par moment to have a job as sort of handy man at editorial chores around the
\par premises. Morley immediately became a great "fan" for the book.
\par Undoubtedly a fine book, and it was accepted, but (there was a question)
\par could it be "put across"? It was very long, not of obviously popular
\par character, and the author's name commanded no attention at all.
\par 
\par The first "advance" copy of the book sent out went (at Morley's
\par direction) to Mr. Huneker. He was then writing regularly critical
\par articles for something like a half dozen publications. "Casuals of the
\par Sea" (such things did not turn up every day) was a "find" for his
\par enthusiasm, He "pulled" two columns of brilliant Hunekerean firecrackers
\par about it in the New York _Sun_; wrote another article of length on the
\par book for the New York _Times_; gave the volume a couple of paragraphs of
\par mention in his department on the Seven Arts at that time running in
\par _Puck_, and perhaps mentioned the book elsewhere also. With the weight
\par of such fervor and authority "Casuals" was most auspiciously launched.
\par It could not now, by any chance, be passed by.
\par 
\par I do not, of course, mean to imply that there was anything artificial or
\par "manufactured" about the "vogue" of "Casuals." First, Mr. Huneker was
\par not a reviewer but a critic, if not thoroughly a great one, certainly a
\par very real one; and about the last man going who could be got to "push"
\par anything he did not whole-heartedly believe was fine. And secondly,
\par "Casuals" had "the goods."
\par 
\par Through my connection with the matter of "Casuals" I suppose it was that
\par a correspondence came about between Mr. Huneker and me. And in all my
\par days I have never seen so energetic a correspondent. It seems to me that
\par I got a letter from him about every other morning. I dropped out of the
\par publishing business and went to Indiana for a time. I let him know when
\par I got there, my motive in this being mainly to notify him that I _was_
\par out of the publishing business and so was no longer in a position to
\par give any business attention to letters relating to books. But letters
\par from him continued to reach me with the same regularity. While, I
\par hardly need say, I enjoyed this correspondence enormously, I was
\par decidedly embarrassed by it, as I could not but keenly feel that I was
\par taking up his time to no purpose. Still, of course, I felt that I should
\par answer each letter of his without an impolite delay, and no sooner did
\par he get my reply than he answered back again. Gradually, however, we got
\par the thing slowed down.
\par 
\par His letters were prodigal of witty things. I am afraid I have not kept
\par them; if so I do not know where they are--I move about a good deal. One
\par neat play of words I remember. I do not know whether or not he himself
\par ever used it elsewhere. I did use it in a book, giving due credit to Mr.
\par Huneker. I had told him that I was going in for writing on my own. His
\par comment was: "He that lives by the pen shall perish by the pen." Some of
\par his letters, I recall, were signed, "Jim, the Penman."
\par 
\par And it was no simple trick to read them. He used a pale ink. The
\par handwriting was small, curious, and to me almost illegible. Why
\par compositors did not mob him I do not know. He wrote everything by hand;
\par never would learn to use a typewriter, and declared that he could not
\par acquire the faculty of dictation.
\par 
\par This leads me to the story of one of the articles he contributed to _The
\par Bookman_. When, upon my return to New York, I became (for a time) editor
\par of this magazine I pursued him for contributions. Yes, later on he would
\par send us something, but always it was later on, later on. I had about
\par given up hope of ever getting anything from him when a bulky wad of
\par closely-written "copy" on yellow paper arrived. Expecting that it would
\par take me a couple of days to decipher the manuscript, I joyously
\par acknowledged receipt of it at once, without a thought of questioning the
\par nature of the article. When I tried to read the article, after I had
\par held the first page sidewise, next upside down, then examined it in a
\par mirror, I "passed the buck" and sent the copy straight on to the
\par printers. If printers had read him before printers ought to be able to
\par do so again. I advertised the article to appear in the next number of
\par the magazine. When I got the article back in galley proofs--I got a
\par jolt. It wasn't "_Bookman_ stuff" at all, all about a couple of "old
\par rounders," as Mr. Huneker called them, taking a stroll.
\par 
\par I do not think that Mr. Huneker has as yet since his death, to the time
\par these rambling remarks are being written, received anything like
\par adequate recognition in the press. The "obituary" articles in the
\par newspapers have carried the air that he was hardly more than an
\par excellent "newspaper man"--somewhat older, but something like (dare I
\par say?) Heywood Broun or Alexander Woollcott. Ah! no; James Huneker was a
\par critic and an artist, and a figure, too, in our national life. Though he
\par was all his days until almost his last breath a hard-working journalist
\par with an immediate "copy date" before him. And though he most naturally
\par thought of himself, with common-sense pride in his calling, as a
\par journalist. I remember his one time speaking of Arnold Bennett as "a
\par hard-working journalist as well as a novel writer." Indicating his great
\par esteem for the character of journalist. And he used to speak, too, with
\par fraternal pride and affection in inflection, of young men who had
\par written good books, as being among "our men," meaning associated with
\par the same paper as himself.
\par 
\par At the remarkable funeral service held in the new Town Hall in New York
\par high and touching honor was done his memory by the stage and the musical
\par profession, but literature seemed to be officially represented by the
\par person of Richard Le Gallienne alone, and painting and sculpture not at
\par all. The articles by Mr. Huneker's colleagues among music critics have
\par seemed very largely to claim him as quite their own. True, no doubt, his
\par most penetrating writing was done in the field of musical criticism.
\par But, also, Huneker was an evangel who belongs to the Seven Arts.
\par 
\par One thing should be added. It is a sad thing, but it is of the nature of
\par life. A good editorial in _The New Republic_ began: "James Huneker named
\par one of his best books 'The Pathos of Distance.' In a single day his own
\par figure is invested with the memorial gentleness there described." No,
\par not altogether in a single day. He had already begun, and more than
\par begun, to recede into the pathos of distance. His _flair_ was for the
\par championship and interpretation of the "new" men. And, for the most
\par part, his new men had become old men. His stoutest admirer must admit
\par that Mr. Huneker's work was "dated."
\par 
\par But where (and this is sadder still) is his like today?
