\par CHAPTER XVII
\par 
\par FORMER TENANT OF HIS ROOM
\par 
\par 
\par There are certain things which must be done, to yield their best, when
\par one is young. For one thing, there is only one time in life to run away
\par to sea. If you did not run away to sea when you were a lad, it is too
\par late now for you to get any sport out of it. 'Tis something the same
\par with living in a garret or in a hall bedroom. If you did not read
\par "Robinson Crusoe" when you were a boy there is no use for you to read it
\par now; you will not understand it. There are some other things you can
\par enjoy when you are old--grandchildren, for instance. But the time to
\par come up to a great city is when one is young. The time to walk up
\par Broadway at night, and feel a gusto about it, and Fifth Avenue by day,
\par is when one is young. That is an enchanted time, when it is a fine
\par dashing thing to be doing, to live at a second-rate boarding house; when
\par discouragement is adventure; when it is worth while even to be poor;
\par when one makes life-long friends at sight; when young love is sipped;
\par when courage is ever stout in one's breast; when one's illusions are
\par virgin yet; and all's right with the world. At that season one can swell
\par with a rich personal pride in "Shanley's" and, almost at the same time,
\par eat one's own theatre supper in a "Dairy Lunch" room, where every
\par customer is his own waiter as well, and where his table is the broadened
\par arm of his chair against the wall.
\par 
\par Richard Day, student at the law, munched his egg sandwich (egg sandwich
\par was the favorite dish at the "Dairy Lunches" until eggs got so high) and
\par drank his coffee from a cup that remarkably resembled in shape a shaving
\par mug and was decorated in similar fashion. The blocks of sugar (two for
\par Richard) for this stimulating beverage (made out of chicory) were taken
\par by the customer with his fingers from a heaping-full sort of great
\par punch-bowl mounted on a pedestal in the middle of the room. It was drawn
\par from a nickel-plated engine with glass tubes by a young man in a white
\par coat like a barber's, who served it, with crullers, piece of pie, or
\par sandwich, across a kind of little bar at the rear end of the long room.
\par 
\par Day scorned the packed, parading trolley cars, and swung vigorously up
\par the street. Far up the thoroughfare an enormous electric sign (in its
\par size suggesting that it had been somehow brought back by Gulliver from
\par the country of Brobdingnag and mounted here upon a sturdy little
\par building for awful exhibition) its gigantic illuminated letters spelling
\par "Arthur Pendennis Ten Cent Cigar," lighted the mist for blocks
\par approaching it, and marked the north boundary of the dominion for
\par revelry. The sidewalks were much quieter now. One of those birds of the
\par urban night deftly wheeled his vehicle alongside our pedestrian and
\par pulled his clattering quadruped violently back upon its haunches until
\par it slid along the slippery pavement. "Cab, sir? Cab?" Then he whisked
\par away again. It was not long before Richard had entered into the district
\par of slumbering residences, and not much longer until he ran up the steps
\par before his own door, or, speaking more literally, his own landlady's
\par door. It is not much to mount three pairs of stairs in the brave days
\par when one is twenty-one, and Day was in the little room, where, rich only
\par in the glory of his rising sun, in his youth, he weathered it so long.
\par 
\par This apartment was the width of the dark hall, which was face to face
\par with it, about fourteen feet long, and furnished in tune, so to speak.
\par An uncommonly small, old-fashioned, wooden bedstead, a bantam-size
\par "dresser," a washstand its shorter brother, a small table or "stand,"
\par and two half-grown chairs, mature before their season, were the
\par principal articles of furniture. The room was heated by an oil stove
\par that had passed the age of vanity in one's appearance; it was lighted at
\par night by a gas-jet, without a globe; by day through a single window,
\par which occupied between a half and a third of the wall space of the front
\par end of the room, and which balanced in decorative effect with the door
\par at the other end. A row of books was arranged along the dresser top
\par against the lower part of the small looking-glass. Two pictures (the
\par property of Day), one of Lincoln and one of Roosevelt squinting in the
\par sunlight (this is a land where every young man may hope to be
\par President), were tacked on the walls. In company with these were a
\par combination calendar and fire-insurance advertisement and a card
\par displaying a lithographed upper part and idealistic legs of a blithe
\par young woman wearing, stuck on, a short, bright skirt made of sandpaper
\par and streaked with match-scratches, who in fancy letters was ingeniously
\par labelled "A Striking Girl." These bits of applied art were properties of
\par Mrs. Knoll's establishment.
\par 
\par Day's dresser had several small drawers and a little square door. He had
\par one day discovered adhering to the back of this door a hardened piece of
\par chewing gum, and from this he had deduced that a former tenant of the
\par room had been a woman, presumably a young one (for surely there is an
\par age after which one knows better). He sometimes speculated on the
\par subject of the former tenant, and he was of three minds about her
\par vocation. Sometimes he thought she had been a school-teacher, sometimes
\par he thought an art student, and again a clerk in a store. He
\par reconstructed her as having had red hair and having been a bit frowsy.
\par But whatever she had been she had slept on a mighty hard little bed, and
\par he felt something like a tenderness for her on that account.
\par 
\par When he had got home from the theatre, Richard sat on the edge of his
\par bed (it seemed always somehow the most natural place in the room to
\par sit), and smoked his pipe. One Christmas Day he and his bosom friend had
\par gone together and bought pipes exactly alike, then each had given his
\par to the other. Years later Day was compelled to give up smoking, and he
\par was never exactly the same again. But when he was young the gods blessed
\par him. He smoked his pipe out, then he slowly pulled off his shoes. That
\par is, he pulled off one shoe and sat abstractedly a considerable while
\par with it in his hand. He had many thoughts, mainly associated with an
\par unknown young lady he had seen that evening at the theatre. He wished he
\par had had on a different style of collar--and he would have had if his
\par laundryman had kept his word. However, he thought rather sadly what
\par booted it to him now. Then he roused himself, slowly undressed, put on
\par his pajamas (his mother had made them for him), turned off his light,
\par pulled up his window curtain (so the morning light would waken him), and
\par got into bed.
\par 
\par Richard fell into a great many adventures in his night's sleep. He
\par fought bandits, with never any cartridges in his gun; he travelled
\par across plains that appeared to be constructed on the principle of a
\par treadmill; he visited sundry peculiar places and did divers queer things
\par with solemnity and without surprise. After a while it seemed to him
\par that he was somewhere talking with, or rather to, the former tenant of
\par his room. But the former tenant did not have red hair; her hair was the
\par loveliest brown; nor was she the least bit frowzy; she was the very
\par opposite extreme to that. Nor clerk nor teacher nor student was she. She
\par was a bright princess. Her complexion had rather more of the rose than
\par of the lily. Her pure and eloquent blood spoke in her cheeks. She and
\par the lady he had seen at the theatre were one and the same person. He
\par could not make out exactly how he came to know she was the former
\par tenant, but that seemed to be considered so very well understood he felt
\par ashamed to speak about it.
\par 
\par He was saying to her some of the cleverest things he had ever heard. He
\par surprised himself as he listened to himself; and he was much elated; for
\par if ever he wished to speak well, now was the time. Now Day was really a
\par very clever fellow, as well as a comely one (this is only a story of his
\par youth, but in after life he became a distinguished man), and, like all
\par very clever fellows, he was never perfectly happy except when his
\par talents were recognized and appreciated. Here in his dream he had come
\par into his own. It was a night to be marked with a white stone. One of the
\par things that particularly impressed him in this dream was his impression
\par that it was not a dream.
\par 
\par In the morning it was always colder in Day's room than at night, and
\par always it seemed somehow lonesomer. It was bare then, and not cozy. To
\par come directly from such an especially comfortable dream into the cold,
\par grey dawn, and find one's window opaque with frost and one's breath like
\par steam in the air, requires a little time for one to adjust oneself to
\par the transition. Richard lay a little time generating courage to get up.
\par He did not immediately shake off his dream entirely; but crumbs of it
\par stuck to his mind, like the last of a fine cake on the face. But it was
\par as if his cake had turned cold in the mouth. He squirmed in bed with
\par embarrassment when he reviewed those clever things, on which he had so
\par plumed himself, that he had said to the former tenant. They were so very
\par poor and flat that he tried to stop his mind against the recollection of
\par them. And even the former tenant herself, as she faded now more into the
\par night, and he came more out into the morning, was like Cinderella as
\par she fled from the hall back to her kitchen. But Richard caught up the
\par crystal slipper that remained to him and in his bosom bore it forth into
\par the day.
