\par 
\par CHAPTER XVIII
\par 
\par ONLY SHE WAS THERE
\par 
\par 
\par Directly in the intense emphasis of white light from an arc lamp
\par overhead, and standing about midway in the long, dark, thickly-packed
\par line of people waiting, was a young man decidedly above the middle
\par stature, in a long outer coat. He was broad in the shoulders, formed in
\par excellent proportion, apparently in about the first or second and
\par twentieth year of his age. His forehead was intelligent, his nose
\par exceptionally good, his mouth rather big and lips full, his chin round
\par and with a cleft in the centre. His hair, chestnut, moderately cropped,
\par discovered, what of it was visible below his hat, a decided inclination
\par to curl. He was redolent of health and the unmined masculine vigor
\par pertaining to his time of life. As the earliest ancestor of this kind of
\par historical writing would have said, "He was one of the handsomest young
\par fellows that hath ever been seen"; in short, he was not unlike one
\par Jones, Christian-named Tom. This young man was Richard Day, student of
\par the law, and he had come from his silent "furnished room" to refresh
\par himself, at a minimum cost, at the dramatic presentation of an immortal
\par story of love.
\par 
\par On the occasions when the entertainment to be is of a superior order,
\par the price of admission is doubled or trebled, and the patrons of the
\par theatre gallery are of an exceptional character. They comprise school
\par teachers in abundance, miscellaneous students, matin\'e9e girls driven high
\par by the prohibitory prices below, young clerks, and a sprinkling from the
\par usual ranks of the gallery-god, the better sort of them, however, the
\par more wealthy and more aspiring. The original line containing Richard Day
\par had assembled an hour or so before time, to be on the spot at the
\par opening of the doors at a commendable production of "Romeo and Juliet."
\par 
\par There came a sudden jolting, like the coupling of railroad cars, then a
\par denser packing of the line, a being pushed off one's balance and being
\par pressed back into it again, and slowly, jerkily, the crowd began to move
\par forward; then swept toward the entrance. The doors had been opened. As
\par the throng began to move, a woman's voice rose near Day ejaculating
\par breathlessly, "Oh! Oh!" Simultaneously a shrill cry arose, "Oh, there's
\par a sick lady here! a sick lady! Oh, please! Oh, please! Won't you make
\par room for a sick lady!" Day with all his force made what room he could,
\par conceiving that the thing desired was to get the stricken lady out in
\par the open as quickly as possible. A little peaked woman in a light coat
\par took instant advantage of the slight breach then opened, impetuously to
\par advance herself in the line. When the momentary gap had closed again,
\par piteously the crying was resumed, and it continued at intervals almost
\par the entire distance to the box-office, though it was in a slightly
\par different neighborhood and observably proceeded from exactly the point
\par of vantage gained by the little peaked woman; who, it might be inferred,
\par was a dual personality, comprising in the same lady both a sick lady and
\par another who was her good Samaritan and assumed the care of her.
\par 
\par Nothing railed the crowd into a straight line on one side, though on the
\par other a wall held them so. The impatient crowding forward from the rear
\par convexed the outer edge of the line of people, much against the will of
\par those persons who found themselves being swept out of the direct way
\par and felt the main current surging past them. What was yet more agitating
\par to these was that ahead of them an iron railing did begin, at the foot
\par of some steps, fencing in a narrow approach to the ticket office. If
\par they should be swept past the mouth of this lane on the outside, their
\par chance of admittance was hopeless. Day stemmed the swerving current
\par himself by the strength of his body and by a kind of determined exercise
\par of his will. But he felt directly behind him someone less strong losing
\par hold with every step of advance; then suddenly this despairing someone,
\par realizing herself pushed quite to one side, with a little scream, caught
\par at his crooked arm; which he instantly, involuntarily clapped firmly
\par against him, hooking on in this manner and towing safely and rapidly
\par along someone frailer than himself. When they had come to the rail he
\par saw that he would get in by so narrow a margin himself that, himself
\par inside, he would then but tow her along outside, which of course would
\par be a less than useless thing for her. So he backed water, so to speak,
\par with all his might, bracing himself against the end of the rail, until
\par he had got a little space before him, around into which he drew her
\par whom he thought robbed of her place by the frantic selfishness of the
\par crowd.
\par 
\par But in doing this, it seemed he had inadvertently held back for a moment
\par the little peaked woman, who was at his inside elbow. She, finding
\par herself delayed for a brief period almost at the goal in her desperate
\par bargain-counter sort of rush for the ticket-window, blew out into a
\par spitting cat kind of impotent fury. "Ain't you got no semblance of
\par decency! you great big brute!" she screamed in his ear. "Ain't you got
\par no ideas of gentlemanliness at all! If I was a man I'd teach you some
\par shame, tramplin' on a woman, a poor weak woman! a woman!" She fairly
\par writhed with scorn at this depravity. Day attempted to humble himself to
\par her, for her pacification; but another woman's getting in ahead of her
\par at that instant drove her almost mad, and her frenzy interfering for the
\par moment with her articulation she could only glare at him with an
\par expression suggesting some kind of feline hydrophobia. When her breath
\par returned more to her command she continued to revile him as they went
\par along. Although Day had done nothing to merit shame, he squirmed
\par inwardly with something not unlike that feeling, and he blessed the
\par general commotion which drowned a vixen's voice. He felt ashamed, too,
\par to be where he was, though he had not thought of it that way before; he
\par should not have brought himself into a crowd more than half of women.
\par 
\par His reflections became rather abstract and levelled themselves somewhat
\par against the feminine temperament in general. He felt the littleness of
\par it (so he saw it), the peevishness of it; its inability to take
\par punishment good-naturedly; its incapacity for being a "good loser"; its
\par lack of the philosophic character which accepts humorously discomforts
\par and injustice, real as well as imagined; its lack of broadness of view;
\par its selfish lack of the sense of fair play; its
\par not-being-square-and-above-board way; its sneakiness, its deceitfulness;
\par the contemptible devices that it will resort to, assuming them to be its
\par natural weapons against a superior strength, both physical and of the
\par understanding. He knew that in a crowd of men if anyone of them had had
\par the despicable disposition of this woman his dread of the hearty,
\par boisterous ridicule of his fellow brutes which would inevitably have
\par followed his meanness would have forced him to stifle his temptation in
\par silence. He knew that there is no place where one may better learn to
\par appreciate what may be called the good-natured easy-goingness of the
\par male animal generally than in an uncomfortable crowd of men. He thanked
\par heaven he was of the superior sex. When a young man thanks heaven that
\par he is of the superior sex it may not be uninteresting to observe in what
\par manner he conducts himself subsequently.
\par 
\par As fast as the crowd was served with tickets it ran up the multiplied
\par flights of stairs, moved in single file past the ticket-chopper, then on
\par to come out, high up, into the vast bowl of the theatre. Here from one's
\par seat the impression of the weird, ship-at-sea like effect of the curves
\par of the galleries, balconies, and tiers of boxes, sweeping back from the
\par light in front, dropping away from the vaulted ceiling; the impression
\par of being high up close under a great roof and far from the stage; the
\par impression of the myriads of vague elusive faces in the half-lit, thick,
\par scintillating atmosphere of the hot, crowded place; the impression of
\par the playhouse scheme of decoration, red walls and tinsel in the dusk,
\par cream color and tinsel bas-relief in the highly artificial yellow light,
\par casting purplest shadows, and the heroic mural paintings in blue and
\par yellow and green, the sense of the infinite moving particles of the
\par throng; the sense of its all facing one way, of the low hum of it, and
\par of its respiration--all this is stuff that puts one in the mood for a
\par play. The keen actualities fade and become the shadows; sense of one's
\par own life and vanity and disappointment slips away; one is to enjoy a
\par transmigration of soul for a brief time. "Now for the play!" thought
\par Richard.
\par 
\par A man was climbing up the steps of the aisle, some distance away,
\par flinging an inadequate number of fluttering programs into the crowd.
\par None fell in Day's neighborhood, to the indignant consternation of all
\par there. A chorus of exclamatory sighs went up from a feminine flock just
\par settled at his right, all faces following the disappointing program
\par distributor. A stocky young man at Day's left hand arose, and clambering
\par out between the parallel two rows of seats, occupants getting on their
\par feet to allow him passage, started after the disappearing man of
\par programs.
\par 
\par A full-throated feminine voice burst almost in Day's right ear: "Oh,
\par please tell him to get one for us!" Day lunged after the stocky young
\par man, reaching for his coat-tails, and cried out, "Hey there! Hey!
\par Fellow! Hold on!" until it was quite hopeless to continue. The sea of
\par people closed in between him and his quest; the stocky young man, his
\par ears plugged with the multitude of voices, shook himself free from the
\par narow, clogged passage, and was gone. Day turned to the owner of the
\par feminine voice, "He will bring a lot, I think; if not I'll get you
\par some," he said. And he caught an elusive impression of cheeks precisely
\par the color of cheeks that had just been smartly slapped, suggesting the
\par idea that if one should press one's finger against them one's finger
\par would leave streaks there when taken away; and he caught an impression
\par of eyes that were like deep, brimming pools reflecting lights; and an
\par impression of a cloud of dusky brown-like hair which reminded him of a
\par host of rich autumn leaves. She of these cheeks and eyes and this hair
\par was, apparently, in a party with two companions, whose peering faces
\par showed indistinctly beyond her. In one significance of the word, she
\par might have been called a girl, or she was a young woman, a miss, a lass,
\par a young lady, as you please; as were they her companions. Merry
\par school-girl spirits lingered in them all, supplemented by the grace and
\par dawning dignity of young womanhood. She was at that sweet nosegay
\par period when young ladies are just, as it is sometimes said, finishing
\par their education. Her age was that enchanted time, holiest of the female
\par seasons, which hangs between mature girlhood and full womanhood. Day
\par felt a suspicion, though without perceptible foundation, that this was
\par the very person he had towed along outside.
\par 
\par The stocky young man returned presently, showing an uncommonly blunt
\par face and with the programs, which proved sufficient in number. There was
\par an interval in which to read them; then the huge place fell suddenly
\par much darker, except directly to the fore, which burst into great light;
\par the immense curtain majestically ascended, and the time was that of the
\par quarrels of the houses of Capulet and Montague in the sixteenth century.
\par Richard Day passed out of his body sitting upright on the seat and lived
\par in this incarnation of the master dramatist.
\par 
\par But unwittingly he had inhaled a liquor, that was even then feeding his
\par blood; he was even then continuing to inhale it; it crept in at the
\par pores of his right side; it was stealing its sweet breath about his
\par brain. This liquor was the magnetism of a powerful pleasant young
\par feminine presence near to him--too near. Too near for a clean-cut young
\par man, in his second and twentieth year, redolent of health, with
\par moderately cropped chestnut hair inclined to curl, intelligent forehead,
\par good nose, rather big mouth, full lips, and round chin with a cleft in
\par the centre--too near for him even to remain in the hands of the master
\par dramatist. A warm glow suffused him. His intellectual perception of the
\par illuminated, noble spectacle before him in a frame of night numbed in
\par his brain and he was conscious only of the rich sensation that
\par circulated through him. Metaphorically, senses and emotions lolled on
\par rich colored divans, spread with thick rugs, in the tropical atmosphere
\par of his head. The magically spoken lines of Shakespeare became as so much
\par unfelt, unrecognized, distant sounding jargon. What he had come to be
\par thrilled by, as the dark, breathless audience like a sea about him was
\par thrilled, was in a moment nothing to him. And yet he had not touched
\par her, nor again spoken with her, nor glanced at her.
\par 
\par Only she was there!
