\par 
\par CHAPTER XIX
\par 
\par A HUMORIST'S NOTE-BOOK
\par 
\par 
\par I admit that (though, indeed, I can claim a very fair collection of
\par authors as acquaintances) I share the popular interest in the
\par idiosyncratic nature of the literary profession. I am as curious as to
\par the occult workings of the minds of authors, the esoteric process by
\par which subtle insinuations of inspiration are translated into works of
\par literary art, as though I had never seen an author--off a platform. I
\par would read the riddle of genius. I am fascinated by its impenetrable
\par mysteries. I would explore the recesses of the creative head.
\par 
\par Therefore, in the presence of the treasure of such incalculable value
\par which is before me, I experience tense intellectual excitement. In the
\par thought of its possession by myself I find the uttermost felicity. What
\par it is is this: it is _a humorous writer's note-book_.
\par 
\par I must tell you the wonderful story--how this came into my hands, and
\par how, romantically enough, it is, so to say, by the bequest of the author
\par himself, your own possession. The strange circumstances are as follows:
\par 
\par Something like a week ago I received through the post at my place of
\par residence an oblong package. It was similar in shape to an ordinary
\par brick; not so heavy, and somewhat larger. I had ordered nothing from a
\par shop, and so, as the parcel was plainly addressed to myself, I concluded
\par that it must contain a present. As I am very fond of presents, I was,
\par with much eagerness, about to open the package, when I suddenly
\par recollected the newspaper reports of the recent dastardly Bolshevist
\par bomb plots; the sending through the mails, by some apparently organized
\par agency, to prominent persons in all parts of the country these
\par skillfully disguised engines of death and destruction. They were
\par outwardly, I recalled, innocent looking parcels, which when opened blew
\par housemaids to bits, demolished dwellings and, in some instances,
\par accomplished the murder of the personage who had incurred the enmity of
\par the criminals.
\par 
\par I bounded some considerable distance away from the object before me.
\par Though, after a moment, I did, indeed, reflect that I was not what
\par would probably be regarded as an eminent citizen, and had never felt a
\par sense of power in the government of my country, I could not dissolve a
\par decided distaste toward my undoing this mysterious parcel. Also I did
\par not enjoy seeing it remain there on my table. And, further, I had no
\par inclination to carry it from the room.
\par 
\par In this dilemma it occurred to me to summon the janitor of the apartment
\par house where I reside. When I had explained to him that, because of my
\par having a sore thumb (which made it painful for me to handle things), I
\par wished him to open this package for me--, when I had explained this to
\par him, he told me that he was very much occupied at the moment mending the
\par boiler downstairs, and that he must hasten to this occupation, otherwise
\par the lower floors would shortly be flooded. And he withdrew without
\par further ceremony.
\par 
\par I sat down to consider the situation. I realized that it was a
\par bothersome moral responsibility--placing the lives of others (even if
\par janitors) in jeopardy. But something must be done; and done
\par soon--perhaps there was a time fuse in this thing. A thought came to me
\par (the buzzer of our dumb-waiter sounded at the moment); I decided to go
