\par Among the longer entries in this note-book is the following remarkable
\par psychological study, having as its title
\par 
\par     TEMPERAMENT
\par 
\par "That morning Kendle had seen himself famous. As he worked he began to
\par feel good in his brain and in his heart and in his stomach. He felt
\par virile, elated, full of power, and strangely happy. The joy of creating
\par a thing of art was upon him. Thrills ran down his spine and into his
\par legs. As he looked at his work he admired it. He knew that this was good
\par art. He felt that here was genius. He saw himself in a delectable
\par picture, an idol applauded of the multitude, and loved by it. For he
\par believed that the multitude was born, and ate and slept, and squabbled
\par among itself, and acquired property, and begot offspring, but to await
\par the arrival of genius. And the only genius he knew was genius in
\par eccentric painting. The only genius worth while that is, for there is a
\par genius that invents labor-saving machines, telephones, X-rays, and so
\par forth; but nobody loves that genius. It occurred to him that he was a
\par very lovable man, with all his faults (his faults were the lovable ones
\par of genius), and he would soon have achieved a distinction that would
\par make any woman proud of him. He determined to renew his addresses
\par to----.
\par 
\par "Somehow in the evening his intoxication had died down. He felt very
\par sad. His work lay before him with so little eccentricity to it that he
\par was ashamed. His sense of power had quite departed. And now he dismally
\par felt that he would never amount to anything. He was a failure. An idle,
\par wicked, disgraceful fellow, no good in the world, and not worth any
\par woman's attention. His heart felt sick when he thought this. He was very
\par miserable. He despised himself. So he sighed. It would have been better,
\par he thought, if he had apprenticed himself to the plumber's trade in his
\par boyhood. He would in that case have grown up happy and contented,
\par remained at home and done his duty, respected by his neighbors and
\par himself, though only a plumber. A plumber is a good honest man that pays
\par his debts.
\par 
\par "At home! Why was he not there, anyway? What good was he doing away from
\par there? There was his mother, in her declining years. Was his place not
\par by her side? He would never desert his mother, he thought. And Sis!
\par there was Sis. He would never desert Sis. How good they had been to him!
\par How they believed in him! (he squirmed) how they believed in him still.
\par He imagined them showing his most sensible pictures around to the
\par neighbors. 'My son is an artist,' he heard his mother say. His flesh
\par crawled. How mad he had been! How contemptible he was! Still a man was
\par not hopeless who had a soul for such feelings as he had now. He would
\par reform. He would henceforth eschew the company of such as Walker. He
\par enumerated his vices and renounced them one by one. He began life over
\par again. He would bask in the simple domestic pleasures of his mother in
\par her declining years, and Sis. He would get up very early every morning
\par and go to his humble toil before it was quite light. He felt himself
\par walking along in the chill of dawn--the street lamps still lit. He would
\par work hard all day. He would always tell the truth. Every Saturday night
\par he would come home tired out, with fifteen dollars in his pocket. This
\par he would throw into his mother's lap. 'Here, mother,' he would say in a
\par fine manly voice, 'here are fifteen dollars.' His mother would put her
\par apron to her eyes, and look at him through tears of pride and joy. He
\par would wear old clothes and be very honest and upright looking, the sort
\par of young man that Russell Sage would have approved, that Sis might
\par dress. He would not mind the sneers and gibes of the world, for he would
\par be _right_.
\par 
\par "He looked defiantly around the room for a few sneers and gibes."
