\par CHAPTER XX
\par 
\par INCLUDING STUDIES OF TRAFFIC "COPS"
\par 
\par 
\par The other day it was such a pleasant April day I thought I'd take the
\par afternoon off. It was such a very pleasant day that I didn't want to go
\par anywhere in particular. Do you ever feel that way? I mean like you just
\par wanted to be by yourself and sit down and think awhile.
\par 
\par Later on, you have an idea, you'll come back into things much refreshed.
\par But the thought of answering these letters now, or of doing this or
\par doing that, kind of lets you down inside your stomach. Your brain seems
\par to have dropped down somewhere behind your ears. If that fellow across
\par the office comes over to pull another of his bright ideas on you you
\par think you'll probably scream, or brain him, or something. He's getting
\par terrible, anyhow.
\par 
\par You have any number of excellent friends, and (ordinarily) you are quite
\par fond of them. Perhaps you will go to see one of them. There's Ed, you've
\par been wanting for you don't know how long to go round and see him. Never
\par seemed to have time. But no; you don't want to see Ed--today. Same way
\par with all the others, as you go over the list of them in your mind.
\par Couldn't bear to see any of 'em--not this afternoon. For one thing,
\par they're all so selfish.... So interested in their own affairs.
\par 
\par As I was straightening up my desk an idea came to me about jobs. Seems
\par to me that when I have a job I'm all the while worrying about how to
\par break out of it. I think: Well, I'm tied up here until the first of the
\par year; but I'll sure shake it after that; too cramped and limited. And
\par then when I am out of a job I immediately begin to worry about how to
\par get another one. That's Life, I guess.
\par 
\par I turned uptown and floated along with the current of the Avenue throng.
\par It was a glittering April throng. The newest stockings were out. I had
\par not seen them before. The newest stockings (you will have noted) are so
\par very, very thin and the pores (so to say) in them are so large that they
\par give the ladies who wear them the agreeable effect of being bare-legged.
\par 
\par At Thirty-fourth Street the traffic policeman on post at our side of
\par this corner, by an outward gesture of his arms pressed back the
\par sidewalk stream for a couple of moments of cross-town vehicular traffic.
\par He stood within a few inches of the front row of the largely feminine
\par crush. Whenever an impatient pedestrian broke through the line he had
\par formed and attempted to dart across the street he emitted a peculiar
\par little whistle followed by the admonishment, "Hold on, lady!" or "Hey
\par there, mister!" Thus having returned the derelict to cover, he would
\par smile very intimately, with a kind of sly cuteness, at the more handsome
\par young women directly before him--who invariably tittered back at him.
\par And thus, frequently, a little conversation was started.
\par 
\par Now as a vigilant historian of the social scene this matter of the
\par gallant relations of traffic policemen to perambulating ladies of
\par somewhat fashionable, even patrician aspect, I find highly interesting.
\par It is a subject which does not seem to have been much examined into.
\par 
\par Why, exactly, should flowers of d\'e9butante-Bryn-Mawr appearance look with
\par something like tenderness at policemen? Seems to me I have read now and
\par then in the papers strikingly romantic stories wherein a mounted
\par policeman in the park (formerly a cowboy) saved the life of an
\par equestrienne heiress on a runaway mount, and was rewarded the next day
\par (or something like that) with her hand. Such a story my mind always
\par gladly accepts as one of the dramatic instances where life artistically
\par imitates the movies. Crossing Thirty-fourth Street, however, seems to me
\par another matter.
\par 
\par And what system of selection operates in the Department whereby this
\par officer or that is chosen from among all his brethren for the
\par paradisaical job of being beau of a fashionable crossing? And would you
\par not think that a more uniform judgment would be exercised in the
\par election of men to such Brummellian duties? Adonises in the traffic
\par force I have, indeed, seen (there is one at Forty-second Street), but
\par this chap of whom I have just been speaking (the whimsical whistler)
\par certainly was not one of them. He was what is called "pie-faced."
\par Hunched up his shoulders like an owl. Yet his ogling of loveliness in
\par new spring attire was completely successful, was in no instance that I
\par observed resented, was received with arch merriment. Indeed, his heavy,
\par pink-tea attentions were obviously regarded as quite flattering by the
\par fair recipients! As he let the tide break to cross the street it was
\par plain, from bright glances backward, that he had fluttered little hearts
\par which would smile upon him again. And so, in such a Romeo-like manner,
\par does this bulky sentimentalist, armed with concealed weapons, have
\par dalliance with the passing days. What you 'spose it is about him gives
\par him his fascination in flashing eyes haughty to the rest of the
\par masculine world--his bright buttons, or what?
\par 
\par Yes; these curious and romantic little relationships between traffic
\par cops on social duty, so to say, and their dainty admirers are not (in
\par some instances at least) so transient as to be merely the exchange of
\par roguish words and soft glances of the moment. There is that really
\par august being of matinee-idol figure at--well, let us say at Forty-second
\par Street. Sir Walter Raleigh could not with more courtliness pilot his
\par fair freight across the Avenue. So it was the day after Christmas I saw
\par not one but several of his young friends blushingly put dainty packages
\par into his hands.
\par 
\par Is there not an excellent O. Henry sort of story in this piquant city
\par situation?
\par 
\par Well, floating like a cork upon a river I drifted along up the Avenue. I
\par passed a man I had not seen for several years. Yes; that certainly was
\par the fellow I used to know. And yet he was an altogether different being
\par now, too. The sort of a shock I got has perhaps also been experienced by
\par you. Only a short time ago, it seemed to me, this friend of mine had
\par been robust and ruddy, masterful and gay, in the prime of his years. I
\par had somehow innocently expected him always to be so. Just as I find it
\par very unreal to think of myself in any other way than I am now. Don't
\par you? As to yourself, I mean. He was quite grey. His shoulders hung
\par forward. His chest seemed to have fallen in on itself. His legs moved
\par back and forth without ever altogether straightening out. He had a
\par whipped look. Wrinkled clothes and dusty black derby hat, he was
\par conspicuous in the peacockean scene. And yet on a time he had been, I
\par knew, as much a conqueror of hearts as any policeman. So would it
\par sometime be with me--like this?
\par 
\par What do you know about that! In the next block another acquaintance of
\par old I saw. But when I had known him he was stooped and little and thin
\par and dried up and cringing. He worked in a basement and did not wear a
\par collar, at least by day. He used to look very old. Now here he was
\par swinging along looking very much like Mr. Caruso, or some such personage
\par as that.
\par 
\par How may this phenomenon be accounted for, what was the misfortune of one
\par of these persons and the secret of the other? I know a man who has a
\par theory which, at least, sounds all right. It is not buttermilk nor
\par monkey glands, he contends, which will keep a man young and stalwart so
\par much as (what he calls) an objective in life--a distant rampart to take,
\par a golden fleece to pursue. That is why, he declares, scientists and
\par artists frequently live happy and alert to such a great age: Thomas A.
\par Edison, Leonardo Da Vinci and the Jap chap (what's his name? Hokusai)
\par who at a hundred and ten or thereabout was called "the old man mad about
\par painting."
\par 
\par Maybe it was thinking of that idea, maybe it was the fearsome thought of
\par that dusty derby hat of my friend's which haunted my mind, or maybe my
\par competitive instincts had been aroused from spring slumber by the
\par spectacle of my Caruso-like friend careering along, anyhow a decidedly
\par bugged-up feeling began to flow through me; I wavered in my loitering, I
\par turned, my sails (so to speak) caught the wind, and I laid my course
\par abruptly back to the office. I had suddenly a great itch to get at all
\par those letters.
\par 
\par I was very glad to see that fellow across the office from me. He is a
\par good fellow and very helpful. I said to him, "Look here, what do you
\par think about this idea for getting business?"
\par 
\par "Oh, my goodness!" he said; "it's altogether too fine a day to think
\par about work. I'd just like to go out and wander up the Avenue with
\par nothing on my mind but my hair."
