\par CHAPTER XXI
\par 
\par THREE WORDS ABOUT LITERATURE
\par 
\par 
\par A friend of mine (and aside from this error a very fine friend he is,
\par too) not long ago published a book which he declared, in his Preface,
\par should be read in bed. He insisted, to such an extent was he the victim
\par of a remarkable and pernicious fallacy which I find here and there, that
\par this book could not otherwise be properly enjoyed.
\par 
\par Now the difficulty about this particular book, that is the circumstance
\par wherein my friend has got me in a position where it is not so easy for
\par me to overturn him all at once, is this: one, not knowing any better,
\par might take the author's advice, and find pleasure reading the book in
\par bed, not being aware that this simply was because here was a book that
\par one would find pleasure in reading anywhere. But because you have got
\par hold of a book which it is possible to enjoy reading in the wrong way,
\par it naturally follows (does it not?) that you'd enjoy it much more
\par reading it in the right way. That, I should say, was simple and logical
\par enough.
\par 
\par I know, I know! I'm coming to that: there are plenty of other people who
\par have this ridiculous reading-in-bed idea. There, for instance, is
\par Richard Le Gallienne. I had a letter from him awhile ago, in which he
\par remarked that it was his practice to do most of his reading in bed. Then
\par I had a letter recently from Meredith Nicholson, in which there was some
\par such absurd phrase as "going to bed and reading until the cock crows."
\par Also I one time read an essay, a very pleasant essay outside the
\par mistaken notion of its main theme, by Michael Monahan, which was largely
\par about the pleasure of reading in bed. Spoke of the delights of being
\par tucked in, with what satisfaction you got the light just right, and all
\par that.
\par 
\par It must, of course, be acknowledged that all these gentlemen are, if
\par perverse in their method, persons of some reading. However, a fact such
\par as that, an accident as you might say, cannot be permitted to upset the
\par course of a profound argument. Why! as to that, a suspicion just occurs
\par to me that maybe someone could dig up Lamb, Hazlitt, Mark Twain,
\par Coleridge, Leigh Hunt, Cowper (perhaps all of them, and more) to the
\par effect that it is pleasant to read in bed. Didn't Thackeray have some
\par nonsense about "bedside books"? _I_ haven't time to refute each of these
\par persons separately. It is sufficient, I take it, to roll into one point
\par of attack all this bed-reading heresy, from whatever quarters it comes,
\par and put an end to that.
\par 
\par Understand me; I have no complaint against the reading in bed of persons
\par confined there through physical disability. The world war which brought
\par more people to bed for indefinite periods than any other matter since
\par time began thereby probably got more souls into the way of reading than
\par seventeen times several hundred schools ever did. All of them, however,
\par would find that they were much better off in the matter of reading when
\par they had got out of bed. What I say is that, in a manner of speaking,
\par there is no use in taking the air in a wheel-chair if you can take it on
\par horseback. Why do a thing in a halfway fashion when you can go to it
\par right?
\par 
\par Another thing. There are people (I've seen them at it) who read on
\par porches. Sometimes in swings, rocking to and fro. Even in hammocks,
\par slung above the ground from trees. On trains, too. I have (with my own
\par ears) heard people say that they would "take a book" and go out into the
\par park, or into the woods, or out in a boat, or up on the mountain, or by
\par the sea, or any conceivable place except where one should go to read.
\par 
\par All of these ways of reading are worse, if anything can be worse than
\par that, than reading in bed. Because in bed you do, at least, have your
\par mind sandwiched within doors. You do not feel the surge and rumble of
\par the world--the sound and movement of the things of which literature is
\par made; but any contact with which (at the moment of reading) is
\par destructive to the illusion which it is the province of literature to
\par create.
\par 
\par For literature (reading it, I mean here) is, in this, like love: Richest
\par are the returns to that one whose passion is most complete in its
\par surrender. And a man lapping his frame in soft indolence, though he have
\par a book in his hand, is indulging in sensuous physical pleasure at least
\par equally with intellectual receptivity or aesthetic appreciation. No.
\par Reading should not be taken as an opiate.
\par 
\par The way to read, then--but, a moment more; a couple of other points are
\par to be cleared up. There is much babble of slippers and dressing-gowns,
\par easy chairs and "soft lights" in connection with the comments about the
\par pleasures, the "delights" as I believe some people say, of reading.
\par 
\par What is wanted to _know_ the relish to be got from reading is, first (of
\par course), an uncommon book. And by that term is meant merely one
\par uncommonly suited to the spirit of the reader. (The only perfect
\par definition, that, of a "good book.") Some people still read Stevenson.
\par Well, there's no great harm in that. Providing you read him (or anybody
\par else) as follows:
\par 
\par You should read as you should die--with your boots on. You take a wooden
\par chair, without arms, such (this is the best) as is commonly called a
\par "kitchen chair." It has a good, hard seat. You sit upright in this,
\par crossing and recrossing your legs as they tire. Nearby you is a good,
\par strong light, one with a tonic effect, a light that keeps your eyes wide
\par open. You sit facing a dull, blank wall. No pictures or other ornaments
\par or decorations should be on this wall, as, in case such things are
\par there, and you happen to raise your eyes for an instant, in ecstasy or
\par in thought, your vision lights upon one of these things; and the heart
\par which you have given your author is, certainly in some measure,
\par alienated from him. Maybe, indeed, you go back to him almost at once.
\par But then harm has been done--you have not read with supreme abandon.
