\par CHAPTER XXII
\par 
\par RECOLLECTIONS OF LANDLADIES
\par 
\par 
\par There is no figure in the human scene which makes so unctuous an appeal
\par to our relish of humanity as the landlady. When the landlady comes upon
\par the stage at the theatre, we all awaken to an expectation of delight in
\par the characteristic manifestations of her nature, and seldom are
\par disappointed. The genius of the greatest of authors always unfolds with
\par particular warmth in the presence of their landladies. A moment's
\par reflection will recall a procession of immortal landladies. Whether it
\par is that the colorful calling of landlady cultivates in one a peculiar
\par richness of human nature, or whether landladies are born and not
\par made--those with characters of especial tang and savor instinctively
\par adopting this occupation,--I cannot say, but the fact is indisputable
\par that landladies are not as other persons are. No one ever saw a humdrum
\par landlady. A commonplace person as a landlady is unthinkable.
\par 
\par Now I think I may say that all my life, or nearly all, I have been an
\par eager and earnest student of landladies. I am, indeed, much more
\par familiar with the genus landlady than with courts and kings, or with
\par eminent personages generally such as supply the material for most of
\par those who write their recollections. Thus I am competent, I think, to
\par speak on a subject curiously neglected by the memorist.
\par 
\par One who makes a culture of landladies comes in time to have a flair for
\par these racy beings, and is drawn by a happy intuition to the habitats of
\par those most resplendent in the qualities of their kind. Of course, one
\par never can tell what life will bring forth, but it seems to me that my
\par present landlady marks the top of my career as a connoisseur, an
\par amateur, of landladies. She is strikingly reminiscent of an English
\par landlady. And England, particularly London, is, as all the world knows,
\par to the devotee of landladies what Africa is to the big game
\par sportsman--his paradise. There the species comes to luxuriant flower, so
\par that to possess with the mind one or two well-developed London
\par landladies is never to be without food for entertainment. My present
\par landlady, to return, is of course a widow. While it may be, for aught I
\par know, that all widows are not landladies, with very few exceptions all
\par landladies worthy of the name are widows. Those who are not widows
\par outright are, as you might say, widows in a sense. That is, while their
\par husbands may accurately be spoken of as living, and indeed are visible,
\par they do not exist in the normal r\'f4le of husband. The commercial impulses
\par of the bona-fide husband have died in them, generally through their
\par attachment to alcoholic liquor, and they become satellites, hewers of
\par wood and drawers of water, to the genius awakened by circumstances in
\par their wives.
\par 
\par I one time had a landlady of this origin in Norwalk, Connecticut. She
\par was a woman of angular frame, with a face of flint, a tongue of vinegar,
\par and a heart of gold. This, I have found in my travels, is the type of
\par the semi-widowed landlady. I had another such an identical one in
\par Topeka, Kansas. The asperity, doubtless, is occasioned by biting
\par disillusionment in the romance of long ago, but it is external; frost on
\par the window; at the heart's core wells the sense of universe-embracing
\par maternity which makes the character of the landlady by vocation
\par sublime. All semi-widowed landladies have (it is their divine
\par inspiration) large families of half-grown sons. My landlady of Norwalk
\par grumbled continually; she could be heard out in the kitchen complaining
\par in a shrill, querulous tone that, with things as high as they were,
\par people would be crazy to expect meat twice a day. Yet she had at her
\par board the meanest, most low-down, ornery, contemptible, despicable cuss
\par in human form I ever knew, and the only fault I ever heard her find with
\par him was that he didn't eat enough.
\par 
\par The erudite in landladies have, of course, cognizance of a class which
\par are in no degree widows. Those of this department of the race, however,
\par frequently are not landladies in fibre, but merely incidentally. They
\par are young wives who for a transient period seek to help out in the
\par domestic economy by taking a few lodgers who come with unexceptionable
\par references. As wives doubtless they are meritorious; but no monument
\par need be erected to them as landladies. Though I should like to see in
\par the principal public square of every town and city a monument designed
\par by an artist of ability placed to the enduring glory of the landladies
\par of that place. For are not landladies ancient institutions fostering
\par the public weal, and in their field not a whit less deserving of homage
\par than governors and soldiers? I would say to a nation, show me your
\par landladies and I will tell you your destiny. I should be remiss,
\par however, in my chronicle did I not note that among these partial and
\par ephemeral landladies occasionally are to be found pronounced landlady
\par potentialities. I recall a landlady I had on Montague Street, Brooklyn
\par Heights, whose passion for cleaning amounted to a mania. This young
\par person's housewifery frenzy always put me in mind of another soul who
\par could not rest--Hokusai, who at about a hundred and ten was spoken of as
\par "the old man mad about painting."
\par 
\par Hovering about, tortured by a desire to begin, when I left for my
\par breakfast, she was still at it upon my return from my morning stroll, my
\par door barricaded by articles of dismembered furniture; still at it when I
\par came back a bit impatiently from a second walk; still at it while I read
\par the paper in her dining-room. And so without surcease throughout the
\par march of days and seasons. She unscrewed the knobs of the bed to polish
\par the threads thereof; she removed penpoints from penholders and made them
\par to shine like burnished gold. I had another landlady moved by the same
\par springs of feeling, on Spruce Street, Philadelphia. Later, I heard, her
\par husband died, and she espoused her latent career.
\par 
\par There is in the galaxy of landladies quite another type, an exotic plant
\par in the wondrously competent sisterhood, specimens of which may be found
\par blooming here and there like some rare orchid. I mean the fragile, lady
\par landlady, the clinging vine bereft of the supporting husband oak. Such
\par was Mrs. Knoll, of Central Avenue, Indianapolis, a little, plump,
\par rounded body, exceedingly bright, pleasant, intelligent, amiable, and
\par helpless; all of which qualities shone from her very agreeable face and
\par person. In her youth no doubt she was a type of beauty, and she remained
\par very well preserved. "Life and vanity and disappointment had slipped
\par away" (in the Thackerian words) from Dr. Knoll some years before; and
\par his widow and only child, Miss Knoll, were left in possession of the old
\par family home, and nothing more. They could not bear to leave it, that
\par would "break their hearts," said good, ineffectual Mrs. Knoll; so it was
\par viewed by them, unfortunately somewhat fallaciously, in the light of a
\par possible support.
\par 
\par The Doctor evidently was a man of books, and his widow had sought, more
\par and more, companionship in reading. Life--the actual world about her,
\par that is--, and vanity, but not disappointment, had, in a manner of
\par speaking, slipped from her, too. And she had turned to that great world
\par of shadows. "In books," she said, "I can choose my own company." She had
\par plighted her troth in youth to Dickens and to Thackeray, and to these
\par she had remained ever faithful. In a world of false books and unsafe
\par friends she knew that she had by the hand two true spirits. Jane Austen
\par she loaned me with tremulous pleasure. And she was very fond of Mr.
\par Howells, with whom, she said she lived a great deal; and the Kentons,
\par the Laphams, and the Marches, were characters better known to her "than
\par her next-door neighbors." But it must be confessed that the tender
\par perfume of Mrs. Knoll was not altogether an equivalent in the sphere of
\par her passive efforts to the homely vegetable odor of the authentic
\par landlady.
\par 
\par In great cities, amid the sheen of civilization is to be found just
\par adjacent to smart quarters of the town the tulip in the variegated
\par garden of landladies--the finished, polished stone gathered from the
\par mine, the bird of plumage of the species; I mean, of course, the
\par landlady _du beau monde_, the modish landlady, or perhaps I should say,
\par the professional hostess, as it were. For it seems rather vulgar, a
\par thing repellent to the finer sensibilities, to touch this distinguished
\par figure of immaculate artificiality with the plebeian term of "landlady."
\par The personages of this type are, so to say, of the peerage of their
\par order. Such a Lady Drew it was whose guest I became for a time on
\par Madison Avenue, New York. With silvered hair like a powdered coiffure;
\par softly tinted with the delicate enamel of cosmetic; rich and stately of
\par corsage--this expensive and highly sophisticated presence presided, in
\par the subdued tone of the best society, over the nicely adjusted machinery
\par of her smart establishment by the authority of a consciousness of highly
\par cultivated efficiency and an aroma of unexceptionable standards.
\par 
\par This consummate hostess type of landlady is, of course, one which the
\par passionate collector will preserve in the cabinet of his mind with
\par tremulous happiness in the sheer preciosity of it. I cannot but feel,
\par however, myself, that this type fails of complete perfection as a work
\par of art in this: that in every work of the first genius, it cannot be
\par denied, there is always a strain of coarseness. And perhaps I should
\par confess that my own taste in landladies, though I hope it is not
\par undiscriminating, leans a bit toward the popular taste, the relish of
\par the Rabelaisian.
\par 
\par Stevenson has observed that most men of high destinies have even
\par high-sounding names. And anyone who has reflected at all upon the
\par phenomenon of landladies must have been struck by the singularly
\par idiosyncratic character of their names. Indeed, an infallible way to
\par pick out a competent landlady from an advertisement is by her name. Is
\par it a happy name for a landlady? Go there! As her name is, so is her
\par nature. I one time had a landlady on Broome Street, New York, whom the
\par gods named Mrs. Brew. I one time had a landlady (in Milligan Place,
\par Manhattan) of the name of Mrs. Boggs. One time I had a landlady just off
\par the East India Dock Road, London, whose name was Wigger. I shall always
\par cherish the memory of the landlady I had down in Surrey, Mrs. Cheeseman.
\par One and all, these ladies, as landladies, were without stain.
\par 
\par Regarded as a bibelot, Mrs. Wigger was, I think, of the first
\par perfection. In her own genre, so to say, she was as finished, as
\par impossible of improvement, as an Elgin marble, a Grecian urn, a bit of
\par Chinese blue and white, a fan of old Japan, a Vermeer, a Whistler
\par symphony, a caricature by Max Beerbohm. She was of massive mould and
\par very individually shapen. Her face was very large and very red and
\par heavily pock-marked. In her bizarre garments, in some indefinable way
\par she imparted to the character of the born slattern something of the
\par Grand Style. Her utterance was quavered in a weird, cracked voice, which
\par had somewhat an effect as of the wind crying high aloft in a ship's
\par rigging. She slipslod about, always a bit unsteadily. Her movements and
\par her manner generally, I felt, made it not unreasonable to suppose that
\par she had in secret certain habits no longer widely approved by society.
\par The apple of her eye was an unkempt parrot which spent its days in
\par vainly attempting to ascend the embracing sides of a tin bathtub.
\par 
\par Landladies, beyond all other persons, have the esoteric power of
\par becoming for one the geniuses of places. It would, for instance, be
\par quite impossible for anyone to visualize my Mrs. Cheeseman torn from, as
\par you might say her context. If you were asked to describe Mrs. Cheeseman
\par you would naturally do it in this way: You would say, "Well, I wonder
\par what has become of the sweetest, quaintest, fairest old inn in all
\par England!" And into your mind would come a rapid cinematograph picture:
\par 
\par A highway winding out of Dorking, stretching its way between hills to
\par the sea. You round a turn and see before you long, low, glistening white
\par stables--the stables, evidently, of a coaching inn. And presently you
\par come into view of an ancient, white, stone building with a "Sussex
\par roof." From a tall post before the door swings the board of the "King's
\par Head." White ducks ride in a pond at the roadside there. Round this inn
\par which you are approaching is the greenest, handsomest hedge ever seen.
\par And along the road beyond you perceive the cottages of a wee village.
\par 
\par "We know that all things work together for good to them that love God."
\par The romance of destiny which in its inscrutable way has been leading you
\par all your long life long to the bosom, if I may so put it, of Mrs.
\par Cheeseman, reveals its beneficence now by carefully graduated steps. At
\par the other side of the main bulk of the "King's Head," which it was given
\par you first to see, you come upon a delicious little flagged yard leading
\par to another arm of the house, older still, very venerable, with a high
\par roof low descending, a roof which tucks under its projecting wing many
\par oddly placed little latticed windows gayly sporting innumerable tiny
\par panes. Like a miniature cathedral spire, a tall, quaint chimney stands
\par sentinel at one corner, and several chimney-pots peep over the roof's
\par dark crown.
\par 
\par Up this little yard, bounded on one side by a multicolored flower garden
\par whose fragrance bathes you in a softening vapor of perfume, you enter,
\par by a door which requires you to stoop, the wee taproom. Here: a
\par cavernous fireplace, settles are within against its sides, a gigantic
\par blackened crane swung across its middle, and a cubby-hole of a window at
\par its back. Above it is swung an ancient fowling-piece. The stone floor of
\par the room, like the ancient flags without, is worn into dips and hollows.
\par Along the window-sill of an oblong window measuring one wall is a bright
\par parade of potted plants.
\par 
\par It is impossible to avoid the conclusion that there is something psychic
\par about landladies. As you look about you at the environment in which you
\par find yourself, you experience a premonition that you are nearing an
\par affinity in the landlady world. It is strange, too, that there are
\par places where you have never been before (in the life which you
\par consciously remember) that give you at once completely the feeling of
\par your having arrived at the home familiar to your spirit. And there
\par presently occurs here an event in your career predetermined (I doubt
\par not) \'e6ons and \'e6ons ago. A buxom body with the most glorious complexion
\par (you ween) in all England--which is to say in the world--enters the
\par ancient room: a lass whose rosy, honest, pedestrian face and bursting
\par figure are to become forever more for you the connotation of the name
\par "Maggie." The daughter, this, (you later learn) of your Mrs. Cheeseman.
\par 
\par Soon it is all arranged, and you are having your tea--a "meat tea"--in
\par the sitting-room of the "King's Head," your sitting-room now. A bucolic
\par slavey--a person whose cheerful simpleness is like to that of the little
\par creatures of the field--attends you. In this commodious apartment of
\par yours is a great scintillation of chintz; flowers, in pots and vases,
\par everywhere caress the eye; and the fancy is kindled by the spectacle of
\par many stuffed birds in glass cases. On the heavily flowered wall hangs a
\par handsome specimen of the "glass" (invariably found in England) for
\par forecasting the weather; a "pianoforte," as piquantly old-fashioned as a
\par cocked hat, crosses one end wall; and venerable paintings (which time
\par has mellowed to the richness and the general color effect of an old plug
\par of tobacco), bright sporting prints, and antique oddities of furniture
\par to an extent that it would require a catalogue to name, all combine to
\par give an air of true sitting-room opulence to the chamber.
\par 
\par But of landladies, and the connotations of landladies, one could write a
\par book of several volumes; and it being a very fair day, and a Sunday, and
\par the first cool breath after a very hot summer, I do not think I shall
\par write those volumes this afternoon; I shall go out for a bit of air and
\par a look at the world.
\par 
