\par CHAPTER XXIII
\par 
\par AN IDIOSYNCRASY
\par 
\par 
\par Then there's the matter of these dedications. Several weeks ago I
\par received a communication. I think it was sent by Miss Katherine Lord, or
\par maybe it was Hamlin Garland. Anyhow, it was an invitation. The upshot of
\par this invitation was that the annual exhibit of the "best books of the
\par year" held at the National Arts Club, New York City, under the auspices
\par of the Joint Committee of Literary Arts was now going--or was just about
\par to go. Further, it was conveyed that the opening evening of the exhibit
\par would be devoted to a reception for the authors of the books exhibited.
\par Also, that on this evening speeches would be made by a number of
\par distinguished persons acquainted with this matter on the subject of the
\par idiosyncrasies of authors and editors. Further than this, this
\par invitation made clear beyond all manner of reasonable doubt that the
\par pleasure of the evening would be generally felt to be sadly incomplete
\par without the presence there among the speakers of myself.
\par 
\par The reasons why I was (I am sorry to say) unable to rise to this
\par occasion were two. For one thing, I have known long and intimately a
\par considerable number of authors and editors. Also, I have had the honor
\par of having been several times to the National Arts Club. And (such is my
\par tact and delicacy) I could not feel that this was any fit place for me
\par to discuss the (as the term is) idiosyncrasies with which a decidedly
\par checkered career has acquainted me. Then, as to one of my own
\par idiosyncrasies: I am like George Moore in this which he says, that he is
\par "the only Irishman living or dead who cannot make a speech"--except that
\par I am not an Irishman.
\par 
\par All of this, however, is merely picking up the threads of my thought.
\par What I have in my eye is an idiosyncrasy of authors which doubtless I
\par could have discussed with some propriety. That is, if I were able to
\par discuss before an audience anything at all. Though with this subject, as
\par many of those present were authors (who had their toes along with them)
\par I should have had to exercise more than a little caution, and
\par considerable skill in maintaining a honeyed amiability. Maybe this
\par theme wouldn't have done at all either.
\par 
\par You see, it's this way: Many people, I believe, do not read the
\par introductions, prefaces, forewords (and whatever else such things are
\par called) to books. I always do. Perhaps this is a habit formed during a
\par number of years spent as a professional reviewer. If you read the
\par introduction, preface (or whatever it's called), to a book you can
\par generally pick up pretty much what the author thought he was about when
\par he wrote it, the points he intended to make in the work, the
\par circumstances in which he wrote it, and so on. This is a great time and
\par labor saving procedure. All you've got to do then is to read a bit in
\par the volume here and there to taste the style, pick up a few errors of
\par fact or grammar, glance at the "conclusion," where the author sums up,
\par to see whether or not he got anywhere--and so far as you are further put
\par out by having this book on your hands it might just as well never have
\par been written. But I am drifting. That's one reason I can't make a
\par speech. Never can recollect what it was I set out to say.
\par 
\par Oh, yes! About these dedications. Less people than read prefaces, I
\par fancy, read the dedications of books. I always read 'em. I read them
\par when I have no intention whatever of reading the volumes which
\par they--well, dedicate. They are fine--dedications. Better, far better,
\par than old tombstones. But never judge a book by its dedication.
\par 
\par I one time knew a man, of a most decidedly humorous cast of mind, who
\par was a great spendthrift, an A 1 wastrel. He ran through everything his
\par father left him (a very fair little fortune), and then when he had run
\par through, in advance of that gentleman's death, everything his wife was
\par to inherit from his father-in-law he had no means whatever. He had a
\par daughter. Without, it was clearly evident, the least suspicion of the
\par pleasant humor of this, he named her Hope. She was a small child.
\par And--it's absurd, I know; but 'tis so; there was not a particle of
\par conscious irony in it; this child's name was the one blind spot in her
\par father's sense of the ridiculous--her parents frequently referred to her
\par affectionately as "little Hope."
\par 
\par So, quite so, with dedications. Whenever, or perhaps we had better say
\par frequently, when a man writes a particularly worthless book he lays the
\par deed (in his dedication of it) onto his wife, "without whose constant
\par devotion," etc., etc., etc., "this work would never have come into
\par being." Amen! Or he says that it is inscribed "To--my gentlest
\par friend--and severest critic--my aged Grandmother." Or maybe he accuses
\par his little daughter, "whose tiny hands have led me." Again he may say
\par benignantly: "To--my faithful friend--Murray Hill--who made possible
\par this volume"; or "the illumination of whose personality has lighted my
\par way to truth."
\par 
\par Doubtless he means well, this author. And, in most cases, highly
\par probable it is that his magnanimous sentiments are O. K. all round. For
\par to the minds of what would probably be called "right-thinking" persons
\par is not having a book dedicated to you the equivalent, almost, of having
\par a career yourself? I know a very distinguished American novelist--well,
\par I'll tell you who he is: Booth Tarkington--who has told me this: Time
\par and again he has been relentlessly pursued by some person unknown to him
\par who, in the belief that did he once hear it he would surely use it as
\par material for his next book, wished to tell him the story of his life.
\par This life, according to the communications received by the novelist,
\par was in every case one of the most remarkable ever lived by man. It was,
\par in every case, most extraordinary in, among a variety of other singular
\par things, this: the abounding in it of the most amazing coincidences. And
\par so on, and so on, and so on. One of these romantic personages nailed the
\par novelist somewhere coming out of a doorway one day, and contrived to
\par compel him to sit down and listen to the life story. He was an old, old
\par man, this chap, and firmly convinced that the tale of his many days (as
\par simple, commonplace, dull and monotonous an existence as ever was
\par conceived) was unique. Now he did not want any pay for telling his
\par story; he had no design on any royalty to come from the great book to be
\par made out of it; no, not at all. All he asked--and that, he thought, was
\par fair enough--was that the book be dedicated to him. And so it was with
\par them all, all of those with the remarkable, obscure, romantic, humdrum
\par lives. So much for that.
\par 
\par Dedications run the whole gamut of the emotions. A type of author very
\par tonic to the spirit is that one whose soul embraces not merely an
\par individual but which enfolds in its heroic sweep a nation, a people, or
\par some mighty idea. What, for instance, could be more vast in the
\par grandeur of its sweep than this--which I came upon the other day in a
\par modest little volume? "To the Children of Destiny." The Great War, which
\par has wrought so much evil and inspired so much literature, is responsible
\par for a flood of noble, lofty dedications. The merest snooping through a
\par bunch of recent war books turns up, among a multitude more, the
\par following: "To the Mothers of America." "To--the Loyalty and
\par Patriotism--of the--American People." "To the Hour--When the Troops Turn
\par Home." "To All the Men at the Front."
\par 
\par I should not affirm, of course, that there is anything new under the
\par sun. And it is very probable that ever since this psychic literature
\par began (whenever it began) authors resident beyond the stars have,
\par naturally enough, dedicated their manuscripts submitted to earthly
\par publishers to folks back in the old home, so to say. But with the War,
\par which has so greatly stimulated literary activity on the other side of
\par life, the dedications of these (to put it so) expatriated authors have
\par perhaps become (in a manner of speaking) loftier in tone than ever
\par before. As a sample of the present state of exalted feeling of authors
\par of this sort I copy the following dedication from the recently published
\par book of a writer "gone West": "To the heroic women of the world, the
\par mothers, wives and sweethearts who bravely sent us forth to battle for a
\par great cause:--we who have crossed the Great Divide salute you."
\par 
\par I wish, I do wish, I had at hand a book which I saw a number of years
\par ago.... As examples of persons to whom books have been dedicated may be
\par specified The Deity, The Virgin Mary, Royalty and Dignitaries of Church
\par and State, "The Reader," and the author himself. Many of the pleasantest
\par dedications have been to children. Besides armies and navies, countries,
\par states, cities and their inhabitants, books have also been dedicated to
\par institutions and societies, to animals, to things spiritual, and to
\par things inanimate. An attractive example of a dedication to Deity is
\par furnished by one John Leycaeter, who, in 1649, dedicated his "Civill
\par Warres of England, Briefly Related from his Majesties First Setting Up
\par his Standard, 1641, to this Present Personall Hopefull Treaty"--"To the
\par Honour and Glory of the Infinite, Immense, and Incomprehensible Majesty
\par of Jehovah, the Fountaine of all Excellencies, the Lord of Hosts, the
\par Giver of all Victories, and the God of Peace." He continued in a poem,
\par "By J. O. Ley, a small crumme of mortality."
\par 
\par But about that book I saw some time ago. You, of course, remember that
\par prayer in "Tom Sawyer" (or somewhere else in Mark Twain) where the
\par great-hearted minister called upon the Lord to bless the President of
\par the United States, the President's Cabinet, the Senate of the United
\par States, the governors of each of the states, and their legislatures, the
\par mayors of all the cities, and all the towns, of the United States, and
\par the inhabitants--grandmothers and grandfathers, mothers and wives,
\par husbands and fathers, sons and daughters, bachelors and little
\par children--of every hamlet, town and city of the United States, also of
\par all the countryside thereof. Well, this book of which I am
\par speaking,--this minister in the august range and compass of his prayer
\par had nothing on its dedication. It was published, as I recollect, by the
\par author; printed on very woody wood-pulp paper by a job press, and had a
\par coarse screen frontispiece portrait of the author, whose name has long
\par since left me. What it was about I do not remember. That is a little
\par matter. It lives in my mind, and should live in the memory of the
\par world, by its dedication; which, I recall, in part was: "To the Sultan
\par of Turkey--the Emperor of Japan--the Czar of Russia--the Emperor of
\par Germany--the President of France--the King of England--the President of
\par the United States--and to God."
\par 
\par But it was in an elder day that they really knew how to write sonorous
\par dedications. If I should write a book (and the idea of having one to
\par dedicate tempts me greatly) I'd pick out some important personage, such
\par as Benjamin De Casseres, or Frank Crowinshield, or Charles Hanson Towne,
\par or somebody like that. Then I would take as the model for my dedication
\par that one, say, of Boswell's to Sir Joshua Reynolds. I am afraid you have
\par not read it lately. And so, for the joy the meeting of it again will
\par give you, I will copy it out. It goes as follows:
\par 
\par      My Dear Sir,--Every liberal motive that can actuate an Authour in
\par      the dedication of his labours, concurs in directing me to you, as
\par      the person to whom the following Work should be inscribed.
\par 
\par      If there be a pleasure in celebrating the distinguished merit of a
\par      contemporary, mixed with a certain degree of vanity not altogether
\par      inexcusable, in appearing fully sensible of it, where can I find
\par      one, in complimenting whom I can with more general approbation
\par      gratify those feelings? Your excellence not only in the Art over
\par      which you have long presided with unrivalled fame, but also in
\par      Philosophy and elegant Literature, is well known to the present,
\par      and will continue to be the admiration of future ages. Your equal
\par      and placid temper, your variety of conversation, your true
\par      politeness, by which you are so amiable in private society, and
\par      that enlarged hospitality which has long made your house a common
\par      centre of union for the great and accomplished, the learned, and
\par      the ingenious; all these qualities I can, in perfect confidence of
\par      not being accused of flattery, ascribe to you.
\par 
\par      If a man may indulge an honest pride, in having it known to the
\par      world, that he has been thought worthy of particular attention by a
\par      person of the first eminence in the age in which he lived, whose
\par      company has been universally courted, I am justified in availing
\par      myself of the usual privilege of a Dedication, when I mention that
\par      there has been a long and uninterrupted friendship between us.
\par 
\par      If gratitude should be acknowledged for favours received, I have
\par      this opportunity, my dear Sir, most sincerely to thank you for the
\par      many happy hours which I owe to your kindness,--for the cordiality
\par      with which you have at all times been pleased to welcome me,--for
\par      the number of valuable acquaintances to whom you have introduced
\par      me,--for the _noctes c\'e6n\'e6que De\'fbm_, which I have enjoyed under your
\par      roof.
\par 
\par      If a work should be inscribed to one who is master of the subject
\par      of it, and whose approbation, therefore, must ensure it credit and
\par      success, the Life of Dr. Johnson is, with the greatest propriety,
\par      dedicated to Sir Joshua Reynolds, who was the intimate and beloved
\par      friend of that great man; the friend, whom he declared to be "the
