\par 
\par        *       *       *       *       *
\par 
\par In a more modern style of composition the epistolary form of dedication
\par is still employed. I wish I had not (one time when I was moving) lost
\par that copy I had, English edition, of George Moore's book "The Lake." I
\par have a feeling that the dedicatory letter there, in French, was an
\par admirable example of its kind of thing. If you happen to have a copy of
\par the book, why don't you look it up?
\par 
\par When poems are written as dedications an established convention is
\par followed. You affect at the beginning (in this formula) to be very
\par humble in spirit, deeply modest in your conception of your powers. You
\par speak, if your book is verse, of your "fragile rhyme," or (with Patmore)
\par you "drag a rumbling wain." Again perhaps you speak (in the words of
\par Burns) of your "wee bit heap o' leaves an' stibble," or you call
\par Southwell to witness that:
\par 
\par     He that high growth on cedars did bestow,
\par     Gave also lowly mushrumps leave to grow.
\par 
\par And so on. At any rate, you always do this. Then you say that his (or
\par her) eyes for whom the book was written will change the dross to gold,
\par the "blind words" to "authentic song," the "mushrump" to a flower, or
\par some such thing. So, after all, you skillfully contrive to leave your
\par book to the reader on a rather high, confident note. Any other way of
\par writing a dedicatory poem to a book of verse (being out of the tradition
\par altogether) is, I take it, bad, very bad, literary etiquette.
\par 
\par Numerous dedications have considerable fame. There is that enigmatical
\par one to "Mr. W. H.," prefixed by Thomas Thorpe, bookseller of London, to
\par Shakespeare's Sonnets. And Dr. Johnson's scathing definition of a patron
\par when Lord Chesterfield fell short of Johnson's expectations in the
\par amount which he contributed to the publication of the famous dictionary
\par men will not willingly let die. Another celebrated dedication is that of
\par "The Gentle Art of Making Enemies"--"To the Rare Few, who, early in
\par life, have rid themselves of the Friendship of the Many." Laurence
\par Sterne's solemn "putting up fairly to public sale" to an imaginary lord
\par a dedication to "Tristram Shandy" is not without merit. John Burroughs
\par was felicitous in his dedication of "Bird and Bough"--"To the kinglet
\par that sang in my evergreens in October and made me think it was May." And
\par a very amiable dedication prefixed to "The Bashful Earthquake," by
\par Oliver Herford, illustrated by the author, is this: "To the Illustrator,
\par in grateful acknowledgment of his amiable condescension in lending his
\par exquisite and delicate art to the embellishment of these poor verses,
\par from his sincerest admirer, The Author." Mr. Herford's latest book (at
\par the time of this writing), "This Giddy Globe," is dedicated so: "To
\par President Wilson (With all his faults he quotes me still)."
\par 
\par A clever dedication, I think, is that of Christopher Morley's
\par "Shandygaff"--"To The Miehle Printing Press--More Sinned Against Than
\par Sinning." A dedication intended to be clever, and one frequently seen,
\par is, in effect, "To the Hesitating Purchaser." A certain appropriateness
\par is presented in a recent book on advertising, "Respectfully dedicated to
\par the men who invest millions of dollars a year in national advertising."
\par And some nimbleness of wit is attained in the inscription of the book
\par "Why Worry"--"To my long-suffering family and circle of friends, whose
\par patience has been tried by my efforts to eliminate worry, this book is
\par affectionately dedicated." As cheerful a dedication as I have come
\par across is that prefixed by Francis Hackett to his volume "The Invisible
\par Censor"; it is: "To My Wife--Signe Toksvig--whose lack of interest--in
\par this book has been my--constant desperation."
\par 
\par Miss Annie Carroll Moore, supervisor of work with children at the New
\par York Public Library, tells me that the other day a small boy inquired,
\par "Who was the first man to write a book to another man?" I'm sure I don't
\par know. Perhaps this is told somewhere. A number of books and articles
\par concerning dedications, I have heard, are to be found in studious
\par places. I have never read any of them. I remember, however, reviewing
\par for a newspaper a number of years ago (I think it was in 1913) a book,
\par then just published, called "Dedications: An Anthology of the Forms Used
\par from the Earliest Days of Bookmaking to the Present Time." It was
\par compiled by Mary Elizabeth Brown. The volume made handy to the general
\par reader a fairly representative collection of dedications.
