\par CHAPTER XXIV
\par 
\par THE SEXLESS CAMERA
\par 
\par 
\par There is no nicer point, perhaps, in the study of photography as the one
\par true, detached observer of mankind than here: It sees, what man has not
\par seen--as his own representations show, his paintings, his drawings, his
\par sculptures--the feminine underpinning with a quite passive, sexless eye.
\par 
\par In this interesting matter there are two human conceptions. There is the
\par chorus girl style of leg, the expression of piquancy, which does not
\par perhaps appeal to the noblest emotions, but the fascination of which has
\par always haunted man whenever he has delineated anything in a stocking.
\par Then there is the chaste, nude feminine limb of the painter and the
\par sculptor. Both photography shows to be idealization.
\par 
\par When the camera reproduces the chorus girl herself, suddenly strangely
\par plain and painted, there is to the observing and reflective instead of
\par sauciness the hollowness of sauciness. There can be few things more
\par awful than those silent photographs of some gay chorus, reproducing, as
\par they do, the spectacle with solemn critical aloofness from the spirit.
\par It is as though the dawn of Judgment Day had suddenly broken upon the
\par unspeakably wretched and tawdry scene. There is something, it would
\par seem, indescribably tender, affectionate, in the irony of the gods which
\par arranges that men should display in theatre lobbies, as an inducement to
\par buy tickets of admission within, these death's heads of frivolity. As if
\par the Comic Spirit itself were touched by the charm of the naivet\'e9 of man.
\par 
\par But, indeed, twinkling in the sympathetic light upon the Broadway stage,
\par the professional chorus girl leg, well selected no doubt to begin with,
\par and shaped with all the science of art, has beguiled even the
\par reflective. A light intoxicant, it swirls in the veins like champagne
\par for the careless moment it makes. It is pleasant because it is false.
\par 
\par The real leg, remarks the camera, is the amateur leg; it is depressing,
\par but terribly convincing. As it stands in the raw light of the cheap
\par photographer (and this too, too human document, the likeness of the
\par poor girl who has performed somewhere in curiously home-made looking
\par "tights," and been photographed thus afterward, is one of the stock
\par exhibits of that most realistic of historians, the cheap photographer)
\par the amateur leg decidedly lacks dash. The knee joint somehow seems to
\par work somewhat the wrong way. Sometimes, in circumference, this limb is
\par immense, sometimes the reverse. But the terribleness of it always is
\par that it is so human. That is, it is the leg of an animal. Subconsciously
\par it suggests surgery.
\par 
\par Conspicuous among the postures assumed for its iconoclastic purpose by
\par the genius of photography is that of "art." That fetish of the great
\par body of the unenlightened, the dim feeling that to the enlightened
\par bodily nakedness in pictorial representation is something very fine, is
\par played upon. The "art photograph" is an ironic tour de force. If
\par specimens of this have ever fallen in the way of your observation, then
\par you have reflected upon the strange discrepancy between the female nude
\par as presented in painting and sculpture and in photographs. (Oh, souls of
\par Fragonard, Boucher, Watteau, what romantic rogues you were!) You will
\par have perceived, with some grim humor, that until the invention of
\par photography, nobody, apparently, had ever seen a nude female figure.
\par 
\par Now there is Edgar Degas,--and it is a curious reflection that in
\par comparison with the work of this pessimist genius who has deliberately
\par brought cynicism to bear upon the female nude, photographs purporting
\par (over their sneer) to be reflections of beauty, give by far the most
\par distressing impression. In the painful realization that they have a kind
\par of truth beyond human art these abominable humbugs are a kind of art.
\par What (you exclaimed) was Schopenhauer's remark about the clouded
\par intellect of _man_ which could give the name of the "fair sex" to "that
\par under-sized, narrow-shouldered, broad-hipped, knock-kneed race"?
\par 
\par It may be a long "drive," but it strikes you as a thoughtful observer
\par that there is some biological analogy between "art photographs" and the
\par photographs, to be seen in travel books, of native African women. What a
\par philosopher the camera is! The French savant was very probably
\par contemplating the photograph of some member of a savage tribe when he
\par wrote, in "The Garden of Epicurus" (addressing modern ladies): "But
\par never think too highly of yourselves, my sisters; you were not, at your
\par first appearance in the world, perfect and fully armed. Your
\par grandmothers in the days of the mammoth and the giant bear did not wield
\par the same dominion over the prehistoric hunters and cave-men which you
\par possess over us. You were useful then, and necessary, but you were not
\par invincible. To tell the truth, in those far-off ages, and for long
\par afterwards, you lacked charm. In those days you were like men, and men
\par were like brutes. To make of you the fearful and wonderful thing you are
\par today--veils: the Empire, crinoline, d\'e9collet\'e9, tube, pannier." And, the
\par sexless camera explains, the poetry of man.
