\par CHAPTER XXV
\par 
\par I KNOW AN EDITOR
\par 
\par 
\par I know a young woman--a very handsome young woman she is, too. (I have a
\par decided penchant for handsome young women.) But that is beside the
\par point. As I was about to say (when a pleasant but an extraneous idea
\par interrupted me): this young woman the other day took her young husband
\par by the hand and conducted him to the offices of a publisher. Here she
\par mounted him upon a chair (very much, I fancy, as though the child were
\par about to have his hair cut), and she said to the barber--I mean she said
\par to the editor, with whom she had some acquaintance--she said: "This is
\par my husband. He is just out of the army. I have brought him in to have
\par his head shingled"---- No, no! that isn't what she said; I am getting my
\par wires crossed. She said, "I have brought him in to get him a position
\par here."
\par 
\par Said the editor, "What would your son, I mean your husband, like to
\par do?"
\par 
\par "I want him," replied the young woman, "to be an editor."
\par 
\par "Has he ever been an editor?" inquired the editor kindly, as he admired
\par the shape of the young woman's nose.
\par 
\par "No," she answered, stroking his hand (the hand, that is, of her
\par husband), "why, no."
\par 
\par "What has been his experience?" asked the editor, as the thought of all
\par the hard work he had to do in the next hour and a half wrestled in his
\par mind with his pleasure in the young woman's voice.
\par 
\par "Why," she said, "before he went into the army I don't know that he had
\par any particular experience. He was just out of college, you see."
\par 
\par "Oh!" said the editor, "I see. And why," he asked musingly, "do you want
\par him to be an editor?"
\par 
\par "Well, I don't know exactly," answered the young woman, "I just thought
\par it would be rather nice to have him be an editor."
\par 
\par Even so. Day after day, come into publishing houses young persons, and
\par indeed people of all ages, who have a hunch (and apparently nothing more
\par to go by) that they would like to be "an editor." Also, in every other
\par mail, come letters from aspirants in distant parts setting forth (what
\par they deem) their qualifications.
\par 
\par Now and then someone makes such an application who has been an editor
\par before. It (editing) is probably the only business he knows, and perhaps
\par it is too late (or his spirit is too broken) for him to take up another.
\par So, disillusioned but not misguided, for him there is charity of
\par thought. But the fledglings are in the great majority. Their
\par qualifications (is it necessary to say?) usually are: a university
\par degree, perhaps some association with a college paper, maybe the credit
\par of an article (or a poem) or two published in a minor magazine issued
\par for the Intelligentzia, a very sincere attachment to books of superior
\par worth, a disdain for empyreal literature, openness to a modest salary
\par (to begin), and an abysmal lack of any comprehension of the business of
\par publishing books or magazines. Every little bit turns up one who (it
\par develops) wants a job on the side, as it were, merely to sustain the
\par real business of life, which (maybe) is taking a graduate course at
\par Columbia, or some such thing. And in many cases (it is obvious) the real
\par business of life is writing poetry, or fiction, though to this end a
\par job must be endured--doubtless temporarily.
\par 
\par Now why anyone should want to be an editor beats me. No, I retract. 'Tis
\par quite plain. Ignorance, ma'am, sheer ignorance of the calamity. I know
\par an editor; in fact, I know six. One, indeed, is a brother of mine,
\par another is a cousin, a third an uncle. Before they became editors they
\par used to read books and magazines--for pleasure, sometimes; or again for
\par profit to their souls. Now they do neither. They read only
\par professionally. They can't read anything unless they have to, in the way
\par of business. Before they became editors they led intellectual lives;
\par spiritually they grew continually. They used to be perfectly delighted,
\par excited (as people should be), by hearing of books, of authors, new to
\par them. They were fascinated by the journey of their minds. They might
\par have gone on thus through their years, interested in themselves,
\par interesting to others, pillars of society. They might even, for all
\par their thoughts (then) were inspirations, have written delightful things
\par themselves. In fact, two of them did. But they became editors.
\par 
\par Now they, subconsciously, count the words of manuscripts. They cut
\par articles, like cloth, to fit. They gauge the "rate" to be paid for
\par this, for that. They cannot take an interest in this because something
\par like it has just appeared somewhere else. They can't take an interest in
\par that because it is not like something that has just made a hit somewhere
\par else. Now when they have something to read they say (like Plim, Bimm,
\par whatever his name was, the veteran hack novelist in the early Barrie
\par story), "I'll begin the damn thing at eight o'clock."
\par 
\par Worst of all, they have lost, totally lost, that shield against
\par adversity, that great joy in days of prosperity, that deep satisfaction
\par of life. I mean, of course, the relish of _buying_ books. Everyone knows
\par that to revel in the possession of a book one must covet it before one
\par feels one should buy it. Everyone knows that to love a book jealously
\par one must have made some sacrifice to obtain it. That a library which
\par supplies unending strength to the spirit means in all its parts, a
\par little here, a little there, some self-denial of other things.
\par 
\par But editors, poor fish, are impotent in this high and lasting pleasure;
\par they have lost the power to spend their money for books. They expect
\par books to be given to them free by the publishers. Their money goes for
\par Kelley pool and cigars.
