\par CHAPTER XXVI
\par 
\par A DIP INTO THE UNDERWORLD
\par 
\par 
\par "When I go back home," he said, "and tell them about this they won't
\par believe it."
\par 
\par It was a pleasant April Sunday afternoon. We were sitting very
\par comfortably in a saloon over Third Avenue way about the middle of
\par Manhattan Island. Throngs of customers came and went through the front
\par door, whose wicket gate was seldom still. Whiskey glasses twinkled and
\par tinkled all along the long bar. Only here and there in the closely
\par packed line of patrons stood one with a tall "schooner" of beer before
\par him. Harry and Ed, in very soiled white jackets, led an active life.
\par 
\par You see, since theoretically intoxicants were not being sold, there was
\par no occasion for the pretence of being closed on Sunday and confining
\par business to the side door and the back room. On the table between us lay
\par a newspaper. Its headlines proclaimed yesterday's "liquor raids,"
\par thousands upon thousands of dollars worth of "rum" confiscated by the
\par city police in the progress of the campaign resulting from the recent
\par passage of the New York State "dry" law.
\par 
\par At the bottom of the page was a little story of the conviction of a
\par delicatessen dealer somewhere on the outskirts of Brooklyn on whose
\par premises had been discovered by the authorities a small amount of wine
\par containing more than one-half of one per cent alcohol.
\par 
\par Pete came in hurriedly. Harry and Ed glanced at him questioningly. He
\par nodded to them as though to say "yes," and dropped into the chair before
\par us. "They're comin'," he remarked. "About half a block off." Every
\par whiskey glass had suddenly disappeared from the bar.
\par 
\par Pete, a little grey man now of about fifty who arises for the day at
\par about noon, has had an interesting career. Once upon a time he was a
\par "bell-hop" in Albany. He is a devoted patron of the silent drama and a
\par man of intellectual interests--making a hobby of clipping from
\par newspapers poems and editorials which impress him and reading them
\par several months later to chance acquaintances who are too drowsy to
\par oppose him. His connection with this establishment is light and
\par picturesque. His duties are chiefly social. That is, he sees home one
\par after another customers who require that friendly attention. He is
\par perpetually agreeable to the suggestion of gratuitous refreshment. He is
\par very cheerful and gentlemanly in the matter of accommodating his tastes
\par to any liquid from ten-cent beer to ninety-cent Scotch which the
\par purchaser is disposed to pay for.
\par 
\par Here they were! The two police officers strolled in slowly, smiling. In
\par their blue and their gold buttons they looked very respendent against
\par the somewhat shabby scene. Ranged along before the bar were a number of
\par young men in the uniform of private soldiers. There were several
\par sailors. Here was a postman cheering himself on his rounds. There was a
\par huge fellow the nickel plate on whose cap announced that he was a piano
\par mover. The centre of a group, there was a very large man who looked as
\par though he had something darkly to do with ward politics. At one place in
\par the line was a very dapper little Japanese, who produced his money from
\par a wallet carried in his breast pocket. But mostly the motley company was
\par of the riff-raff order of humanity. That is another one of the curious
\par developments of "prohibition." Here, in all places of this character,
\par you may find an endless number of the sort of men who used to be
\par accustomed to paying as little as ten cents for a drink of very fiery
\par and inferior whiskey, now standing before the bar by the hour and paying
\par from fifty to seventy-five cents for whiskey (if you can call it that)
\par considerably worse. How on earth can they do it? I do not know.
\par 
\par The two policemen moved the length of the room, and came to a halt at
\par the open end of the bar. Here they stood for a couple of moments,
\par observing (I felt with some amusement) Harry and Ed serving their
\par beakers of beer. Then, as though suddenly having a bright idea, one of
\par them made his way along back of the bar to the cigar case at the front
\par end. He stooped, opened the sliding panel at the bottom of this and
\par poked around inside with his club. As he came along behind the bar back
\par to the open end he stooped several times to peer at the shelf below. He
\par joined his comrade, the two of them thrust their heads into the back
\par room, and then moved out through the side door.
