\par looking young males, and (in their best black silk) a populous
\par representation of those highly honorable and very ample figures who have
\par generously mothered the young sons and daughters of the American
\par prairies.
\par 
\par Suddenly from the side lines they popped out--a whole battery of them,
\par with their bug-like machines on tall stilts. The motion picture camera
\par men were taking no chances that anything important would escape their
\par fire. Evidently they couldn't quite place us, however, so we got through
\par the door without further incident.
\par 
\par When we had entered the grounds through the gate at the far side of the
\par lawn my thoughtful friend had thrown away his lighted cigar, feeling
\par that promiscuous smoking here would be taboo from danger of fire to so
\par precious a national jewel as the White House. Within the anteroom to the
\par executive offices the scene very decidedly suggested one of those jovial
\par masculine gatherings termed a "smoker." The seething and motley company
\par of (obviously) newspaper men put one in mind of the recent arrival at a
\par military training camp of a nondescript batch of drafted men not yet got
\par into uniform. General air about the room of loafing in a corner cigar
\par store.
\par 
\par Then, suddenly, a rising murmur and a pell-mell push toward the door. My
\par friend and I were swayed out upon the step, and saw at the gate directly
\par at the street corner of the building the movie camera men very
\par vigorously clearing for action. They had halted close before them a
\par tall, striking and very distinguished figure. You instantly recognized
\par him by the insignia which he wore on the slope toward his chin of his
\par under lip--a wisp of whisker (light straw color) such as decorated the
\par illustrious countenance, too, of the late James Abbott McNeil Whistler.
\par 
\par He was, this gentleman, looking very sheepish, continually bowing in a
\par rather strained manner to the camera men and lifting his black derby hat
\par to them. They were scrambling about the legs of their engines and
\par cranking away with a rattle. "Over this way a little, Mr. Paderewski!"
\par yelled one. "Hold on, Mr. Paderewski, there you are!" bawled another.
\par Boisterous mirth about the doorway.... "That's good!" "Sure, he's only a
\par premier."
\par 
\par Then, a deferential scattering to make way for him as he approached.
\par Held him up again, the camera guerrillas, on the steps. He was bowing
\par with an effect of increasing strain and the intensity of his
\par sheepishness becoming painful to contemplate. His hair a white bush
\par thrusting out behind. Ghostly white bow tie. His black clothes
\par beautifully sleek and pressed. At close up, his features blunter, less
\par sensitive in chiselling than appears in his photographs. The flesh of
\par his face striking in the degree of the pinkness and fairness of
\par complexion of the races of Northern Europe.
\par 
\par My friend and I had not yet seen Mr. Christian. Had that morning called
\par upon Mr. Tumulty on a matter of business. Found he had set up shop in a
\par business structure called the Southern Building. Transom Legend: Law
\par Offices ... Joseph P. Tumulty. On entrance door: Joseph P. Tumulty,
\par Charles H. Baker. Outstanding feature of ante-chamber a life-size cream
\par plaster bust, on tall polished wood pedestal, of Woodrow Wilson. Mr.
\par Tumulty, stocky of stature, driving in manner, bustled forth from his
\par private office. Exhaled atmosphere of ruddiness.
\par 
\par My friend at times (I fear) speaks with some circumlocution. Our real
\par business here settled, he was ambling on toward the expression of his
\par hope that we might possibly be able sometime, just for a moment, to see,
\par just get a glimpse of....
\par 
\par "The President," Mr. Tumulty cut in, with an anticipating nod. My friend
\par looked a bit confused as (I could see) the words "the ex-President" were
\par about to come from him. But, undoubtedly, both of them meant the same
\par gentleman.
\par 
\par In the executive offices we trailed along with the newspaper men for
\par their daily afternoon interview with Mr. Christian, my friend bathing
\par himself in tobacco smoke as complacently as anyone of the party. Entered
\par a sort of council chamber. Long table down the middle. Conspicuous
\par ornament of the apartment, on a mantel, a plaster cast of a humorous
\par Uncle Sam in a dress coat, holding aloft an American flag, and flanked
\par by a turkeyfied looking eagle.
\par 
\par Congregation pressed close about the table, behind which in a swivel
\par chair sat in a relaxed and rather pensive attitude an angular figure,
\par swinging leisurely looking legs which terminated in very white sox and
\par low-cut shoes. A rather thick thatch of greying hair, large aquiline
\par features, a rather melancholy cast of expression, eyes cast downward at
\par the table, clothes not recently pressed and which no one would be
\par inclined to call dapper, Mr. Christian in general effect suggested a
\par good deal one's impression of a somewhat dusty "reference librarian" at
\par the information desk of the New York Public Library being besieged by an
\par unusually large number of questioners.
\par 
\par "Well, gentlemen," he uttered very quietly and slowly, "what have you
\par got on your mind?"
\par 
\par "George," asked a figure with pad and pencil in hand, "what about this?"
\par Mr. Christian appeared to ponder the matter a good while, and the upshot
\par of his cogitation appeared to be that there wasn't much of anything
\par about it. "And what is there to that?" inquired another. Well at length
\par there didn't seem to be much to that either. A few items of information
\par were given. And the audience briefly closed.
\par 
\par When we had filed out with the company from the room my friend and I
\par took seats in the corridor. He had given his letter to the doorman. A
\par couple of soldiers in uniform, a group of very spruce, robust and
\par cheery-looking Catholic priests, an elderly individual of very dejected
\par pose, and a miscellaneous assortment of humanity also were waiting. The
\par doorman was being continually accosted. "Just want to shake hands with
\par him, that's all," and "Just want to say 'How de do'," were solicitations
\par frequently overheard.
\par 
\par The doorman beckoned to us and told us to go into an apartment which he
\par indicated and "take a seat." Probably my friend didn't hear that
\par instruction, as he marched straight up to Mr. Christian directly upon
\par entering the room flooded with afternoon light pouring through an
\par imposing row of tall and beautiful windows. Mr. Christian slowly arose
\par from his desk, coming gradually to his full height, and yielded a
\par cautious hand to my friend. He looked at the bright and somewhat
\par flustered countenance of my friend rather sadly, as it seemed. Though at
\par some sally of my friend's about the pronunciation of his name he smiled
\par with considerable natural human warmth. Then very gravely he stated that
\par with so many appointments at present to be made, and with the
\par multitudinous labors now upon him, and so forth and so on, it was hardly
\par possible that he could just now arrange for my friend to have a word
\par with, as he said, ... "the Senator."
\par 
\par My friend was, obviously, a bit taken aback by the term, as his mind
\par had been careering along with visions of his seeing no less a person
\par than the President. But there was no doubt that both he and Mr.
\par Christian were referring to the same gentleman.
\par 
\par I should add that my friend's self-imposed mission of shaking hands with
\par Mr. Harding and writing an article about his impressions of him before
\par the President had yet given an audience to the accredited
\par representatives of the press was more or less audacious. And I should
\par add still further that Mr. Christian seemed genuinely reluctant to
\par dismiss my friend without a ray of hope, and suggested that he call
\par again after a few days. Suggestion was at Mr. Christian's own volition.
\par 
\par As we turned to leave the room we saw that the bevy of Catholic Fathers
\par and several other persons had also been admitted, and were all beaming
\par with bland cheerful confidence.
\par 
\par We strolled along the driveway leading by the front entrance to the
\par White House. The baggy looking policeman lazily sunning himself beside
\par the portico recalled to my mind with amusing contrast the snappy
\par Redcoats who briskly pace back and forth before Buckingham Palace.
\par 
\par They are superbly haughty and disdainful beings. A charmingly democratic
\par character, this policeman. "'At a fierce cloud over there," he observed
\par to us as we paused nearby.
\par 
\par A splendid looking army officer together with a caped naval commander
\par emerged with springy step from the White House door, both carrying an
\par air of high elation. A sumptuous car rolled up and halted beneath the
\par portico roof extending over the driveway. From it a lady leaned out
\par extending a card. Out pranced a gleaming negro flunky to receive it with
\par bows of elaborate courtliness. As he turned to re-enter the White House
\par it struck me that I did not believe I had ever seen a happier looking
\par human being. Also, in his beautiful dark blue tail coat with bright
\par silver buttons, and delicately striped light waistcoat, he brought to my
\par mind (incongruously enough) the waiters at Keen's Chop House. The lady
\par rolled on.
\par 
\par A bumptious looking character mounted to the entrance, and sent in a
\par card. It was evident in his bearing that he expected within a moment to
\par stride through the doorway. A figure in a skirt coat emerged. Bumptious
\par being springs upon him and begins to pump his hand up and down with
\par extraordinary verve, straining the while toward the doorway. Skirt coat
\par (his hand continuing to be pumped) deferentially edges bumptious
\par character outward toward descending steps.
\par 
\par It had been an exceedingly hot day for early spring. Traffic policemen
\par had stood on their little platforms at the centre of the street
\par crossings under those mammoth parasols they have to shield them from the
\par rigors of the Washington sun. As we proceeded toward our exit from the
\par grounds, approaching to the White House came a diminutive and decrepit
\par figure muffled in an overcoat extending to his heels, bowed under a tall
\par top hat, a pair of mighty ear-muffs clamped over his ears.
\par 
\par We had that morning visited the Capitol. My friend had been much more
\par interested in the guide-conducted touring parties than in the atrocious
\par painting of the Battle of Lake Erie, and so on, expatiated on to them.
\par Parties which, he said, made him feel that he was back again at the
\par Indiana State Fair. We had sat, in the visitors' gallery of the Senate,
\par in the midst of a delegation of some sort of religious sect, whose
\par beards had most decidedly the effect of false whiskers very insecurely
\par attached. Had been much struck by the extreme politeness of a new
\par Senator who bowed deeply to each one in turn of a row of pages he passed
\par before. Had responded within a few minutes to the command of "All out!"
\par because of executive meeting, and sympathised with the sentiments of
\par fellow citizens likewise ejected who went forth murmuring that they
\par hadn't "got much."
\par 
\par We had wandered through the noble and immaculate Senate Office building,
\par and been much impressed by the scarcity of spittoons there, an abundance
\par of which articles of furniture we had since boyhood associated with all
\par public buildings. We had sat in the outer office of our state's senator,
\par and listened to one lady after another explain to his secretary in this
\par wise: "I just made up my mind ... I just decided to go right after it
\par ... I just determined ... I just thought ... Otherwise, of course, I
\par shouldn't presume to ask it."
\par 
\par In the Library of Congress we had been much interested to hear an
\par European gentleman of vast erudition connected with the Library declare
\par that "there was more intellectual life in Washington than in any other
\par city in America--that it was an European city, in the best sense." We
\par had been accosted on the street by a very portly and loud-voiced man who
\par introduced himself by inquiring where we were from; who confided that
\par his business in Washington had to do with an alcohol permit; and who
\par asked to be directed to Corcoran Gallery. We had run into an old actor
\par friend who was here playing, he said, "nut stuff"; and who observed that
\par Washington was "more of a boob town than ever." We had been assured by a
\par newspaper friend that Washington was so full of inventors and blue law
\par fans that if you "dropped a match anywhere a nut would step on it."
\par 
\par We had been charmed by the vast number of elderly couples apparently on
\par a final mellow honeymoon before the fall of the curtain. At lunch had
\par overheard an inland matron inquire of a waitress if scollops were
\par "nice." Had enjoyed hot corn bread with every meal. Had been unable to
\par account for the appearance on the streets of so many wounded soldiers.
\par Had made the mistake of getting up so early that in the deep Washington
\par stillness of half past seven we were scared to run the water for our
\par baths for fear of rousing the sleeping hotel to angry tumult. Had noted
\par that nowhere except in London is the fashion of freshly polished shoes
\par so much an institution. Had speculated as to why the standard model of
\par the American statesman's hat should be a blend of an expression of the
\par personalities of W. J. Bryan, Buffalo Bill and Colonel Watterson.
\par 
\par And, finally, listening in the evening to the orchestra in the corridor
\par of the New Willard, we discussed the large opportunities for a serious
\par literary work dealing with the varieties and idiosyncrasies of the
\par Washington hair cut. There is the Bryan type, with the hair turned
\par outward in a thick roll above the back of the neck, and forming a neat
\par hat rest. There is the roach back from a noble dome. There is the grey
\par curly bushy all around. There is the heavy grey wave mounting high over
\par one side. And--well, there seem to be an almost endless number of
\par styles, all more or less peculiar to the spirit of Washington, and all
\par of distinct distinction.
\par 
\par 
\par II
\par 
\par "Who's the old bird gettin' so many pictures took?" inquired a loitering
\par passerby.
\par 
\par A hum of much good nature was coming from the motley throng about the
\par steps before the executive office of the White House. "Beer and light
\par wine," called out someone, apparently in echo to something just said by
\par the queer looking character being photographed by the battery of camera
\par men, and a rattle of laughter went around through the group.
\par 
\par "That's old Coxey," replied someone. "He's down here to get Debs out,"
\par he added. The amiable and celebrated "General" who a number of years ago
\par had led his "army" on to Washington was smiling like a very wrinkled and
\par animated potato into the lenses of the cameras which had been moved to
\par within a couple of feet or so of his nose.
\par 
\par My friend and I crossed the street to the State, Army and Navy building.
\par We had been there the other day to see a young man in the State
\par Department to whom he had a card. Had been much struck by his beauty.
\par And had wondered if handsomeness was a requisite for a statesman in this
\par Administration.
\par 
\par Now we sought the press room. Presented our credentials to a press
\par association man there. Cordial chap. Said, "Stick around." Others
\par floated in. Pretty soon press association man heartily calls out to my
\par friend (whose name is Augustus), "George. Come on!" And we trail along
\par with about fifty others into the ante-chamber of the new Secretary of
\par the Navy, who at half past ten is to give his first interview to the
\par newspaper men.
\par 
\par Funny looking corridors, by the way, in this building. Swing doors all
\par about, constructed of horizontal slats, and in general effect bearing a
\par picturesque resemblance to the doors of the old-time saloon.
\par 
\par I noticed that as we went along my friend punched in one side of the
\par crown of his soft hat and raked it somewhat to one side of his head. He
\par felt, I suspected, uncomfortably neat for the society of this bonhomie
\par crowd of bona fide newspaper men, and did not wish to appear aloof by
\par being too correct in attire.
\par 
\par The company passed along the corridor and into the anteroom under a
\par heavy head of tobacco smoke. There the press association man presented
\par each of the flock in turn to a chubby little fellow behind a railing,
\par whom I took to be secretary to the Secretary; and presently the
\par delegation was admitted to the inner office, a spacious apartment where
\par one passed first an enormous globe, then a large model of the _Old
\par Kearsarge_ in a glass case; and at length we ranged ourselves closely
\par before a mountain of a man in a somewhat saggy suit. Clean shaven,
\par massive features, very bald dome, widely smiling, Secretary Denby looks
\par just a bit (I thought) like Mr. Punch. His voice comes in a deep rumble
\par and he has entirely ample ears. Trousers too long.
\par 
\par No; he had not seen the story in that morning's paper which was handed
\par to him by one of the reporters. He would not confirm this; he would not
\par deny that. After all, he had been "only a week in the job." And one
\par might so very easily be "injudicious." "Wily old boy," was one comment
\par as the party trailed out and made for the press telephones, discussing
\par among themselves "how would you interpret" this and that?
\par 
\par Next, at eleven o'clock, the Secretary of State was down on the
\par newspaper men's schedule. We went into a kind of waiting room across the
\par corridor from the real offices of the Secretary. Most conspicuous
\par decoration a huge painting of a Bey of Tunis, the presentation of which
\par (the inscription said) had something to do with condolences from France
\par on the death of Lincoln. Also on one wall a portrait of Daniel Webster.
\par 
\par Mr. Fletcher, Under Secretary of State, appeared before us. Very dapper
\par gentleman. Athletic in build. Fashionable clothes. Grey hair but
\par youthful in effect. Handsome, smooth-shaven face. Suggested an actor, or
\par perhaps a very gentlemanly retired pugilist. Held beautiful shell
\par spectacles in hand before him. Stood very straight. Had another fellow
\par alongside of him to supply information when himself in doubt. When asked
\par concerning someone who was in jail, inquired "Where is the old boy?"
\par Smiling cordially, seeking continually for an opportunity for some joke
\par or pleasantry, trying bravely to keep up a strong front, but obviously
\par becoming more and more uneasy under the ordeal of rapid-fire questions
\par about Russia, Germany, Japan and so on and so on. On being asked
\par concerning diplomatic appointments under consideration, bowed briskly,
\par replied "A great many," and escaped--almost, it might be said, fled.
\par 
\par Secretary of War next on the list. Full length portraits in his offices
\par of Generals Pershing, Bliss and Petain. Many flags, historic ones
\par (presumably) in glass cases. Heavy build, Secretary Weeks, very wide
\par across the middle. Straggling moustache, drooping. Very direct and
\par business-like in manner. Entered room saying, "Well, there are a number
\par of things I have to tell you gentlemen." Frank and positive in his
\par statements and denials. Stood twisting a key-ring as he talked. Wore
\par neat pin in tie. When told that the War Department was supposed to have
\par such and such a thing under consideration, he replied, tapping himself
\par on the breast, "Not this part of the War Department." One questioner
\par sought to obtain from him a more direct reply to a question that had
\par been put to the Secretary of the Navy. He answered, "I know nothing
\par about the navy." When there was apparently nothing more that he had to
\par say, he concluded the audience very deftly.
\par 
\par "He's a different guy, ain't he?" was one correspondent's observation as
\par we passed out of the room. "One of the biggest men in the government,"
\par he added. "Gives the impression of knowing as much about that job now as
\par Baker did when he left."
\par 
\par To the National Press Club we went for lunch. It is pleasant to see in
\par what esteem this club holds those two eminent journalists, Eugene Field
\par and Napoleon Bonaparte, whose portraits hang framed side beside on one
\par of its walls. Napoleon, however, is held in such very great regard as a
\par newspaper man that another and larger picture of him hangs in another
\par room.
\par 
\par The newspaper army had shifted to the business office of the White
\par House. As we entered Secretary Weeks was departing. He pressed through
\par the throng of reporters clustered about him. "Nothing to say," was
\par apparently what he was saying. "We are referred to Warren," said one of
\par the men. "Looks like we really were going to see him," said another. The
\par President had not yet given an interview to the press men. So we took
\par seats among the rows of figures ranged around the walls.
\par 
\par While waiting we were given an audience, so to say, by Laddie, the White
\par House Airedale. Curly haired breed. "How old is he?" we asked the small
\par colored boy whose office includes charge of him. "A year," he said. The
\par dog stands well, and holds his stump of a tail straight aloft, correctly
\par enough. But there is altogether too much black on him, we observed;
\par covers his breast and flanks, instead of being merely a "saddle" on his
\par back. "Yes, everybody says it," answered the boy.
\par 
\par Secretary Hughes was seen coming down the corridor on his way out. The
\par newspaper men pressed forward forming a narrow line through which he
\par walked, very erect, smiling broadly, bowing to right and left, and
\par continually moving his black derby hat up and down before him. "Gets a
\par great reception, don't he?" said one reporter, glowing with a sort of
\par jovial pride at Mr. Hughes.
\par 
\par "You'll have to see the boss," Mr. Hughes repeated a number of times as
\par he came along, and turning slightly made one last very good-natured bow
\par as he moved out through the door.
\par 
\par "Are they all here?" called out Mr. Christian, then marshalled us
\par through his office and into the large, circular and very handsome office
\par of the President.
\par 
\par While we awaited him he could be seen, through a doorway, talking, on a
\par porch-like structure opening out along the back of the building. He was
\par very leisurely in manner. I think my first outstanding impression of my
\par glimpse of him was that he was a very handsome man, most beautifully
\par dressed in a dark blue serge sack suit, very sharply pressed.
\par 
\par He came in, moving slowly, stood close behind his desk, and said,
\par "Well, gentlemen, what is there that I can tell you?" He spoke very
\par quietly and deliberately. The Cabinet he said had discussed problems
\par relating to the "hang-over" (as he put it) of the War, in particular the
\par trade situation of the world. He mentioned that he did not desire to be
\par quoted directly. He had not been "annoyed" but he had been "distressed,"
\par he said, by having been so quoted not long ago. The top button of his
\par coat was buttoned. His cuffs were stiffly starched. He inclined his head
\par a good part of the time to one side. Sometimes half closed his eyelids.
\par Then would open them very wide, and make an outward gesture with his
\par hands, accompanied by something like a shrug of the shoulders. Close up
\par I was struck by the bushiness of his eyebrows. He wore a single ring,
\par mounting a rather large light stone. No pin to his tie. He swung
\par backward and forward on his feet. Put on shell-rimmed nose glasses to
\par read. Sometimes pursed his lips slowly. As he talked absently rolled a
\par small piece of paper he had picked up from his desk into the shape of a
\par cigarette. His talk had a slightly oratorical roll. He was exceedingly
\par patient and exceedingly courteous. His general atmosphere was one of
\par deep kindness. In conclusion he said, "Glad to see you again."
\par 
\par "That's pretty nice," was the comment of one of the newspaper men as we
\par emerged from his presence.
\par 
\par As we moved away through the grounds my friend dilated on a somewhat
\par whimsical idea of his. This was to this effect. In motion picture plays
\par (my friend insisted) kings were always much more kingly in appearance
\par and manner than any modern king would be likely to be. But (he declared)
\par it would be very difficult for a motion picture concern to get hold of
\par any actor to play the part who would look so much like an American
\par President as President Harding.
\par 
\par We stopped in to look at the east room, now again open. A character who
\par had evidently not been born in any of the capitols of Europe was
\par admiring the place vastly. He looked with especial approval at the
\par enormous chandeliers, those great showers, or regular storms, of glass.
\par "Pretty hard to beat," was his patriotic comment.
\par 
\par 
\par III
\par 
\par It's a big old building, dark inside, the Washington Post Office. He
\par looked like some sort of a guard about the premises who was too tired
\par to stand up and so did his guarding sitting in a chair. My friend had
\par got so accustomed to inquiring our way to the office of Secretary
\par Hughes, and of Secretary Weeks, and so on, that he asked where we would
\par find Secretary Hays.
\par 
\par The man looked at us very contemptuously. "The Postmaster General?" at
\par length he boomed. Well, he was on the fifth floor. As we stepped from
\par the car my friend remarked on the practice universal in Washington of
\par men removing their hats when in the presence of women in elevators.
\par 
\par Our appointment was for ten o'clock. We had got quite used, however, to
\par waiting an hour or so for the gentlemen we sought to see. Several other
\par callers were ahead of us here, and we sat down in the outer office when
\par we had presented our cards to a very kind and attentive young man who
\par appeared to be in charge.
\par 
\par Within a very few minutes, however, we were ushered round into a
\par secluded inner office. "The General," the young man said, "will be in in
\par a moment. He sees them in two different rooms at the same time." This
\par large room was entirely bare of painting or other decorations.
\par 
\par Speaking of decorations reminds me of the striking handsomeness of the
\par Cabinet officers we had so far been seeing. Beginning with the President
\par himself (prize winner of the lot in this respect) the spectacle of this
\par Administration had up to this moment been a regular beauty show.
\par 
\par The physiognomy of Mr. Hays, of course, strikes a somewhat different
\par note in the picture. Though he is not, I should say, as funny looking as
\par some of his pictures suggest.
\par 
\par He fairly leaped into the room. Spidery figure. Calls you by your last
\par name without the prefix of Mister. Very, very earnest in effect. No
\par questions necessary to get him started. He began at once to talk. Poured
\par forth a steady stream of rapid utterance. Denounced the idea of labor as
\par a "commodity." Said: "We have a big job here. Three hundred thousand
\par employees. Millions of customers. I think we can do it all right,
\par though. But our people in the department all over the country everywhere
\par must be made to feel that a human spirit is behind them. It's in the
\par heart that the battle's won. It's because of the spirit behind them
\par whether our men throw a letter on the floor before a door or put it
\par through the door." Made a gesture with his hands illustrating putting a
\par letter through a door. Looked very hard at the very clean top of his
\par desk much of the time as he talked. Now and then looked very straight
\par indeed at us. Gave us a generous amount of his time. At length arose
\par very briskly.
\par 
\par Routed us out around through some side way. Had a private elevator
\par concealed somewhere in a dark corner. Turned us over to the colored man
\par in charge of it with the request, "Won't you please take my friends
\par down?"
\par 
\par As we were crossing the street we ran into our old friend from New York
\par who edits a very flourishing women's magazine. Down here, he said, to
\par get an article from Mrs. Harding. Had found her altogether willing to
\par supply him with an article, but in so much of a flutter with her new
\par activities that she didn't see her way to finding time soon to write it.
\par What, we asked, was the article to be about? Well, Mrs. Harding's idea
\par was to revive all the old traditions of the White House. And what were
\par those traditions? Mrs. Harding hadn't said beyond the custom of Easter
\par egg-rolling.
\par 
\par We were on our way over to see Assistant Secretary of the Navy
\par Roosevelt. He is not in the State, Army and Navy building where Mr.
\par Denby is, but some ten minutes' walk away, in the long, rather fragile
\par looking Navy Department building constructed during the War.
\par 
\par Here numerous gold-braided officers continually come and go. The
\par building is filled with very beautiful models of fighting ships. At one
\par side of Roosevelt's door is a model of the _San Diego_, at the other
\par side a "sample U. S. Navy Patrol Boat."
\par 
\par As we gave him our cards a young man asked us if we knew "the Colonel."
\par An old Washington newspaper man had told us that morning, "He will go
\par far under his own hat." Several very large men, also waiting, were
\par smoking very large cigars while we waited. While all male visitors to
\par public offices in Washington appear to smoke continually, those in
\par government positions apparently do not smoke during office hours. And
\par government business hours there seem to be queer. The Senate goes into
\par session at just about lunch time. The President seems to be around in
\par his business office throughout the whole of the middle of the day. And
\par the office of the Secretary of State telephones you at six o'clock
\par Saturday night.
\par 
\par The young man showed us in. Mr. Roosevelt arose from his desk, shook
\par hands very cordially, said "How do you do?" sat down again and at the
\par moment said nothing further. It was up to us to swing the conversation.
\par So my friend launched out: We had nothing to do with affairs of state,
\par had no design to interview him as to naval matters, simply were curious
\par to see if we should find him eating an apple and wearing white sox, or
\par what. With hearty good nature, Mr. Roosevelt replied that he was not
\par eating an apple because he did not have one to eat, and that he had only
\par once worn white sox, woolen ones, when a boy at school.
\par 
\par He was very neatly dressed in a suit of quiet dark material, wore rich
\par dark red tie, with a stick pin to it. Curiously weather beaten looking
\par complexion. As he has just published a book we asked him if he intended
\par to carry on more or less of a literary career together with his public
\par life. He said, well, perhaps more or less. But he wouldn't have time for
\par much such work. He "practised" writing on Saturdays and Sundays, but
\par mainly for the purpose of attaining to clearness in expressing himself.
\par He insisted that the great bulk of his father's writing had been done
\par _before_ the full course of his political activities and _after_ he had
\par retired from them.
\par 
\par After we had arisen to go he walked up and down the room with us, with a
\par somewhat arm-in-arm effect. Declared we should know a friend of his up
\par in Boston, because we'd "like him." Said to look in on him again any
\par time when in Washington. Very affable young man.
\par 
\par We went out on S Street to see Wilson's new house. Handsome enough
\par structure, but, undetached from the building next door and fronting
\par directly on the sidewalk, we decided that it looked somewhat more like a
\par club than like a private residence. Were told later that the part of
\par that house to look at is the back of it, as there are wonderful gardens
\par there.
\par 
\par One cannot fail to note in the numerous art shops where pictures of
\par Harding, Roosevelt, Washington, Lincoln and Cleveland are displayed in
\par abundance the relative absence of pictures of Wilson.
\par 
\par Why do august statesmen in the lobby of the New Willard cross their legs
\par so that we can see that their shoes need to be half-soled? Why do so
\par many distinguished looking gentlemen in Washington wear their overcoats
\par as though they were sleeveless capes? What on earth do so many Oklahoma
\par looking characters do in Washington? Why is it that there the masses do
\par not, as in New York and Chicago and Los Angeles, stroll about at night?
\par 
\par We stopped in again at the executive office of the White House.
\par Remarkable number of doormen there got up somewhat like policemen, so
\par that you repeatedly have to explain yourself all over again. Man new to
\par us on today. Suspiciously asked our names. Then (though what just our
\par names could have meant to him I cannot see) shook hands with immense
\par friendliness, and told us his name.
\par 
\par Quite a throng waiting. Busy hum all about. Different crowd from usual.
\par Hardly any reporters. Old gentlemen. Stout red-faced fellows with large
\par black slouch hats. Several youngish women with very generous bosom
\par displays. Some sort of a delegation, apparently. We did not make out
\par just what. But the scene somewhat suggested a meeting of the Los Angeles
\par branch of the Ohio Society. At length the company lines up. We trail in
\par through with the rest.
\par 
\par The President, looming in the centre of his office, shakes hands with
\par each caller in turn, in a manner of paternal affection. Holds your hand
\par very gently within his for a considerable while. Rather odd position he
\par takes when shaking hands. Right shoulder lifted. Looks (though I felt
\par that he was unconscious of this effect) somewhat like a pose that a
\par painter might put his model into when about to paint him shaking hands.
\par 
\par He bent over us in a very fatherly fashion. Said, yes, yes, he had got
\par our letters while in the South. Which was quite a mistake, as we hadn't
\par written him any letters. But his kindly intention was quite
\par unmistakable.
\par 
\par 
\par IV
\par 
\par Senator New's secretary, in his room on the second floor of the Senate
\par Office building, was opening a wooden box that had come by mail. No; he
\par wasn't exactly opening this box, either. He was looking at it
\par suspiciously and cautiously tipping it from side to side. "Feels like it
\par was a snake," he said fearsomely. "Soft, live-like weight in there. I
\par don't believe I'll open it. You see," indicating the stamps, "it's from
\par India, too."
\par 
\par "But why would anybody be sending Senator New a snake?" inquired my
\par friend.
\par 
\par "Goodness gracious! We get lots of things just as queer as snakes,"
\par replied Mr. Winter. "I guess the Senator must be coming in pretty soon,"
\par he remarked, glancing about. "So many people coming in," he added, and
\par continued: "It's a remarkable thing. Visitors seem to have some sort of
\par psychic knowledge of when the Senator will be in. Same way out in
\par Indianapolis, we could always tell when Tom Taggart was likely to be
\par back soon from French Lick--so many people (who couldn't have heard from
\par him) looking for him at the Denizen House."
\par 
\par "Everybody," someone observed, "always comes to Washington at least once
\par a year." All United-Statesians, at any rate, one would say looking about
\par the city, probably do. And among visiting United-Statesians not
\par habitually seen in such profusion elsewhere one would certainly include,
\par Indians, Mormons, Porto-Ricans, Civil War veterans, pedagogues,
\par octogenarians, vegetarians, Virginians, Creoles, pastors, suffragettes,
\par honeymooners, aunts, portly ladies of peculiar outline, people of a very
\par simple past, and a remarkable number of gentlemen who still cling to
\par white "lawn" ties, hard boiled shirts and "Congress shoes."
\par 
\par Also, of course, that vast congregation of people who "want" something
\par in Washington. "What are you looking for around here?" a remark commonly
\par overheard in the hotel lobbies.
\par 
\par But there are other American cities to which "everybody" goes, too, now
\par or then, though the visitors are not perhaps so recognizable. Coming out
\par of the Capitol, passing through the grounds of the White House, what do
\par you frequently overhear? Frequently some such remark as this: "Haven't
\par you ever been in the subway? To the Bronx? When you go back you
\par certainly must go in it."
\par 
\par And out in Los Angeles they boastfully tell you that one way in which
\par Los Angeles "is like New York" is this: That whereas a man may or may
\par not happen to go to Richmond or to Detroit, sooner or later you are
\par bound to see him on the streets of Los Angeles. That, as I say, is what
\par they tell you out there.
\par 
\par But what are those aspects of Washington which are peculiar to that
\par city, and make it so unlike any other city in the United States? And
\par which in some cases make it an influence for the bad to many of its
\par visitors? And which in some cases it is so strange should be the aspect
\par of such a city?
\par 
\par For one thing, the first thing which must strike any stranger to the
\par city is the enormous extent of the souvenir business there. It is
\par perhaps natural enough that this should be so, and that souvenir shops
\par should range themselves in an almost unbroken stretch for miles. What is
\par not altogether so easy to answer is why nearly all of the souvenirs
\par should be the kind of souvenirs they are.
\par 
\par Printed portraits of the present President and of former Presidents, and
\par plaster busts of these personages, of course. That many of the articles
\par for "remembrance" should be touched with a patriotic design, of course,
\par too. But why today should so many millions of the "souvenir spoons"
\par (with the Capitol in relief on the bowl), the "hand painted" plates
\par (presenting a comic valentine likeness of George Washington), the
\par paper-weights (with a delirious lithograph of the Library of Congress
\par showing through), the "napkin rings," butter knives, and so on and so
\par on--why should such millions of these things be precisely in the style
\par of such articles proudly displayed in the home of my grandmother when I
\par was a boy in the Middle West?
\par 
\par Outside of Washington, as far as I know in the world, any considerable
\par exhibition of wares so reminiscent of the taste of the past can only be
\par found along the water fronts of a city where men of ships shop. And
\par there, along water fronts, you always find that same idea of ornament.
\par 
\par Another thing. Where in Washington are shops where real art is
\par sold--paintings of reputable character and rare specimens of antique
\par furniture? They may be there; I do not swear that they are not, but they
\par are remarkably difficult to find.
\par 
\par Painting reminds me. The Corcoran Gallery is, of course, a justly famous
\par museum of art. But a minor museum, containing no Old Masters, but an
\par excellent collection of American painting, particularly excellent in its
\par representation of the period immediately preceding the present, the
\par period of the men called our impressionist painters. Its best canvas, I
\par should say, is the painting by John H. Twachtman, called (I believe)
\par "The Waterfall." My point is, that visitors there certainly are seeing
\par what they are supposed to be seeing there--art.
\par 
\par What I am coming to (and I do not know why someone does not come to it
\par oftener) is this: That hordes of people who come to Washington will look
\par at with wonder as something fine anything which is shown to them. The
\par numerous beautiful works of architecture--to which is now added the very
\par noble Lincoln Memorial--they see, and probably derive something from.
\par But the cultural benefits of their visits to their Mecca of patriotic
\par interest must be weirdly distorted when they are led gaping through the
\par Capitol and are charged twenty-five cents apiece to be told by a guard
\par who knows as much about paintings as an ashman a quantity of imbecile
\par facts about prodigious canvases atrociously bad almost beyond belief.
\par 
\par The Embarkation of the Pilgrims and Washington Resigning his Commission,
\par and so forth, indisputably are historic moments for the American breast
\par to recall with solemn emotion. And the iniquity of these paintings here
\par to minds uninstructed in works of art is that by reason of their appeal
\par to sentiments of love of country these nightmares of ugliness are put
\par over on the visitor as standards of beauty.
\par 
\par Still speaking (after a fashion) of "art," another aspect of Washington
\par hits the eye. And that is the extremely moral note here. In Los Angeles
\par (that other nation's playground of holiday makers) perhaps even more
\par picture cards are displayed for sale. A very merry lot of pictures,
\par those out there--all of "California bathing girls" and very lightly
\par veiled figures, limbs rythmically flashing in "Greek dances." Such
\par picture cards of gaiety of course may be found in windows here and there
\par on some streets in New York and other cities. But after much window
\par gazing I fancy that anybody bent upon buying such things in Washington
\par would have to get them from a bootlegger or someone like that.
\par 
\par And whereas, as I recall, in other centres of urban life, and especially
\par on the Pacific Coast, the photographers' exhibits run very largely to
\par feminine beauty and fashion, in photographers' windows in Washington,
\par you will note, masculine greatness dominates the scene.
\par 
\par Speaking of photographers and such-like suggests another thing. Let us
\par come at the matter in this way. A good many women of culture and means,
\par I understand, choose to live in Washington; probably in large measure
\par because the city is beautifully laid out, because it is a pleasant size,
\par because there are no factories and subways there, and so on. We know
\par that numerous retired statesmen prefer to remain there. There is society
\par of the embassies. In consideration of all this, and in consideration
\par further of the comparatively large leisure there for an American city,
\par you would suppose that, behind the transient population, in Washington,
\par a highly civilized life went on. Very well.
\par 
\par True, they have the third greatest reference library in the world and
\par the numerous scholars associated with it. But where do the people _buy_
\par their books? One bookstore of fair size. Another good but quite small. A
\par third dealing mainly in second-hand volumes. Not one shop devoted to
\par sets in fine bindings, first editions, rare items and such things.
\par Though in Philadelphia, for instance, there is one of the finest (if not
\par the finest) bookshops dealing in rare books anywhere in the world. In
\par San Francisco numerous bookstores. Larger cities? Yes (as to that part
\par of it), of course.
\par 
\par But it does seem queer that not a single newspaper in Washington runs
\par book reviews or prints any degree at all of literary comment.
\par 
\par Alluding to San Francisco, that happy dale of the _bon-vivant_, how does
\par he who likes good living make out in Washington, unless he lives in a
\par club, an embassy, or at the White House? A grand public market, two
\par first-class hotel dining-rooms, and many fine homes. But an earnest
\par seeker after eating as a fine art could find tucked away none of those
\par chop-houses and restaurants to dine in which enlarge the soul of man.
\par 
\par But, of course, perhaps you can't have everything at once. From the
\par visitors' gallery the spectacle of the Senate in active session is a
\par game more national than baseball. "There he goes!" cries one ardent
\par spectator, pointing to a "home player," so to say, moving down the
\par aisle. "That's him! Gettin' along pretty good, ain't he?"
\par 
