\par CHAPTER XXVIII
\par 
\par FAME: A STORY OF AMERICAN LITERATURE
\par 
\par                           $10,000!
\par                 IN PRIZES FOR SHORT STORIES!
\par 
\par      _You_ have a story. We want to read it. Every human life has one
\par      great story in it. Every man, every woman, has at least one story
\par      to tell.
\par 
\par                       THIS MEANS YOU!
\par 
\par      From your experience, from your own heart history, you can draw a
\par      tale. You may not know that you can write. But you never know what
\par      you can do until you try. We believe there are thousands of
\par      unwritten little masterpieces, waiting only for the right
\par      encouragement to be produced. Here is our offer----
\par 
\par 
\par BENJAMIN KEYESER drew a long breath. "This means you"--there was no
\par doubt about that. These printed words had read his heart. He felt that
\par deep was answering unto deep.
\par 
\par A brief r\'e9sum\'e9 of his life passed through Keyes's mind. And he was
\par touched, as never before, by the romance of destiny. He had not
\par contrived to be called up to public charges or employments of dignity or
\par power in the world. When Ol' Necessity had tapped him on the shoulder he
\par had cut his scholastic pursuits short of college, and a family friend,
\par Dr. Nevens, had got him a fifth-rate job in a third-rate business
\par concern. Here it seemed extremely probable that he would spend a good
\par many of his days. By the continued exercise of steadiness of character,
\par diligence, and application, he might hope, as Dr. Nevens by way of
\par encouragement occasionally pointed out, to advance at the rate of a
\par couple of dollars or so every couple of years. Clerkdom hedged him about
\par as divinity doth a king.
\par 
\par The city directory rated him, "B. C. Keyes, Clerk." Should he be killed
\par in a railway accident, chosen as a juror, or arrested for homicide, the
\par newspapers would report that B. C. Keyes, a clerk, of 1120 Meredith
\par Street,--etc. There was, he felt when he looked at it fairly, no way
\par out. In the "Americans of Today" magazine articles, men rise from
\par bootblacks to multi-millionaires, but these legends, Keyes felt numbly,
\par had about as much relation to his own life as the hero tales of ancient
\par Greece. His lot was cast in the bottom of a well.
\par 
\par And yet,--Keyes had been considered a bright youngster at school; he
\par regarded himself as a rather bright young man now; and sometimes even
\par yet, in wayward, impractical moments, he saw in his mind a picture of
\par himself breaking away from the field (so to say) and coming rounding
\par into the home stretch to bear down on a grandstand wild with applause.
\par He bore about within him a subconscious premonition, as it were, which
\par apparently would not die, that something remarkable was to happen to him
\par sooner or later. An unpleasant circumstance was that it was getting
\par later now all the time. Still the estimate of his worth returned to him
\par by life did not rid him of the belief that he had been originally
\par intended by his Maker for higher things than he had found.
\par 
\par When, occasionally, the gloomy contrast of his life as it was with his
\par career as he conceived it had been meant to be depressed him too
\par untowardly, a young lady whom Keyes called Louise would administer
\par spiritual stimulants.
\par 
\par Louise was a very clever person, and she knew a superior young man when
\par she saw one. She did not care for your common men at all. She was
\par intellectual. She read everything, her friends said. She often told
\par Keyes that he ought to write. She knew, she declared, that he could
\par write better than most of the people who did write.
\par 
\par This idea of writing had, now and then, occurred to Keyes himself. He
\par was rather fond, in his odd hours, of reading periodical fiction, which
\par he liked to discuss with serious people like Louise. Sometimes with the
\par exhilaration occasioned by the reading of a particularly good story, a
\par romantic impulse to express himself welled up in him, and then
\par evaporated. Generally in these instances he wanted to write a kind of
\par story he had just read. He felt the glamour of the life of adventurous
\par tales. He thrilled in response to the note struck in that sort of
\par romance best exemplified, perhaps, in one of his favorites, "The Man Who
\par Would Be King." Or he longed to be like O. Henry, wise with the wisdom
\par of the Town. But there was one sort of story which always ignited in his
\par mind the thought that he really did know a story of his own. This he
\par sometimes positively yearned to tell. This the advertisement had put its
\par finger upon. "Every human life has one great story in it." It was even
\par so. "From your own heart history ..."--Benjamin Keyes felt that emotion
\par which is the conception of a work of art.
\par 
\par        *       *       *       *       *
\par 
\par He was pregnant with his idea. He rose from his bed betimes. He breathed
\par a strangely fragrant air. He looked at the beautiful world. He wrote. He
\par mentioned his little employment to no one: he felt rather ashamed of it,
\par in fact; but it infatuated him. He encountered some awful tough spots,
\par and at times he almost despaired--but he could not give up. Something
\par within him, which he himself was conscious he did not understand,
\par tortured him to go on. All day long, while at his business, his meals,
\par his shaving, his story turned and twisted and talked in the back of his
\par head. Despair alternated with exultation. At hours there came a gusto to
\par his work; words that he had heard or read, forgotten and never used,
\par came back to him from heaven knows where, and sprang to his pen at the
\par felicitous instance. He felt that his mind was more alert than he
\par remembered it to have ever been; he felt that his eyes were brighter;
\par his hands, his whole right arm, felt strong. He knew as he worked that
\par this was character, and this was sentiment, and this was humor. He was
\par shaken by the respiration of a heady drama. He felt that this--was
\par almost genius! And he was aghast that he had lived such a dull life
\par hitherto when this capacity had been in him.
\par 
\par He possessed little theoretic knowledge of writing; his story grew
\par naturally, like a tree: he was intelligent, and he had a story to tell
\par which must be told. In the matter of technical construction he followed
\par in a general way, intuitively, unconsciously for the most part, without
\par elaborate examination, the form of a short story as he was acquainted
\par with it through his reading of stories. He wandered alone at night,
\par oblivious of anything else, thinking, thinking his story over; and he
\par felt good in his brain and in his heart and in his stomach. He felt
\par virile, elated, full of power, and strangely happy. The joy of creating
\par a thing of art was upon him. Thrills ran down his spine and into his
\par legs; he would grin to himself in the dark streets; and sometimes he
\par laughed aloud. Everything else he neglected. He could not even read the
\par newspapers; he stayed at home two days from business; he worked early
\par and late, and walked up and down, throbbing, meantimes.
\par 
\par The story was almost finished. The story _was finished_. What would
\par Louise say? Would she think that he ought not to have written, ought not
\par to make public, so intimate a history? Then in the story he had carried
\par things further than they were in fact: the artistic instinct had
\par formally plighted the lovers' troth. He thought of submitting his
\par manuscript without showing it to Louise. Would it not be fine for her to
\par discover the story in print! But Keyes had to read that story to someone
\par or blow up.
\par 
\par        *       *       *       *       *
\par 
\par His evening with Louise began awkwardly. The pleasant interchange of
\par being did not, as usually so happily it did with Louise, flow naturally
\par along. Keyes was accustomed to feel that with Louise he talked better
\par than before anyone else. He now and then wished that certain other
\par people, upon whom he felt he had not made so favorable an impression as
\par he deserved, could overhear him sometime with Louise. Now, curiously,
\par with her he felt as he had with them: he could not somehow get his real
\par machinery started. Three or four times he determined to embark upon the
\par subject in his mind, and as many times the rising fulness in his chest
\par and the sudden quivering of his heart daunted him. As he looked now at
\par Louise, sitting there before him, the dignity of her as a young woman
\par struck him, and it occurred to him as extraordinary that he could have
\par been so intimate with her. He about concluded to put off his story until
\par another time, at which immediately he felt much relieved.
\par 
\par His gaze wandered about among the familiar objects of the little
\par parlor--the ordinary articles of the family furniture, the photographs
\par on the mantel, the hand-painted plate on the wall,--then rested upon the
\par framed Maxfield Parrish, which Keyes knew, with a glow of pride, to
\par express the superior refinement of Louise's own taste. Keyes shared
\par Louise's interest in art; he knew, and very much admired, the work of
\par Dulac, James Montgomery Flagg, N. C. Wyeth, Arthur Keller, and many
\par others; this was one of the fascinating bonds which united them, in
\par division from a frivolous, material, and unsympathetic world. He glanced
\par again now at the sumptuous Rackham book on the table, which it had been
\par such a delight to him to give her at Christmas; and the revived
\par discussion of \'e6sthetics led him fairly comfortably into the subject of
\par his own entrance into work in that field. His manuscript came out of
\par his pocket; and, straightening up on the edge of his chair, a little
\par nervous again in the still pause that ensued, he cleared his throat,
\par and, in a rather diffident voice, began to read. As he proceeded and
\par knew that his effort found favor, his want of confidence left him. He
\par fell into the swing and color of his work; and the heart of it he tasted
\par like fine wine as he read. In the more moving passages his voice shook a
\par trifle, and tears very nearly came into his eyes; it was all, he felt,
\par so beautiful. When he had concluded there was in Louise's eyes--as he
\par looked up, and saw her sitting, leaning forward with her chin on the
\par back of her hand, her elbow on her knee,--a strange light. It occurred
\par to Keyes that he did not remember ever to have seen a woman's face look
\par exactly that way before. Probably not. This was a light some men never
\par find on land or sea. It does not shine for any man more than once or
\par twice. They sat awhile, these two in the little parlor, and happiness
\par roared through their veins. Louise told Keyes that she had always known
\par that he "had it in him."
\par 
\par Then they arose, and they were near to each other, and their hearts
\par were filled, and beneath the chandelier he moved his arms about her. His
\par lips clasped hers. It was thus as it was in the story.
\par 
\par Keyes emerged from the brightly lighted doorway with Louise beaming
\par tenderly after him. In his blissful abstraction of mind he neglected, on
\par the dark porchway, to turn the corner of the house to the steps; but
\par walked instead, straight ahead, until the world gave way beneath him,
\par and he collapsed with a crash among the young vines.
\par 
\par The next week Louise, who held a position in the "Nickel's Weekly"
\par Circulation Branch office in the Middle West, neatly typed the
\par manuscript on one of the firm's machines. One evening they went together
\par to post the story.... The ancient, imperturbable moon observed this
\par momentous deed.
\par 
\par        *       *       *       *       *
\par 
\par When Keyes put that manuscript into the mail box, he _knew_ that it
\par would be accepted. He felt this in his bones. He felt it in the soles of
\par his feet and in the hair on his head.
\par 
\par For several days succeeding, a sensuous complacency pervaded young
\par Keyes. In a rich haze he saw himself acclaimed, famous, adored. His
\par nature was ardent, and he had always craved the warmth of approbation;
\par but he had not had it, except from Louise. Now there were moments when,
\par in a picture in his mind, he saw an attractive figure, which he
\par recognized as himself somewhat altered, come jauntily along, amiably
\par smiling, swinging a cane. He had always secretly desired very much to
\par carry a cane, but he had felt uncomfortably that the humbleness of his
\par position in life would make this ridiculous. In his moments of ambition
\par he had hoped, sometimes, that walking-sticks would not go out (to put it
\par so) before he came in. In the background of his mental picture Keyes
\par recognized among the doting multitude the faces of about all of his
\par acquaintances, some brought for the occasion from rather remote places.
\par 
\par Keyes felt a slight wrench of conscience in winking at this poetic
\par liberty taken with realistic probability. When a name occurred to him
\par the physiognomy of whose person was absent, Keyes's sense of probity was
\par smothered, with a slight twinge of pain, by the ardor of his
\par imagination; and place in the press was found for this person, very
\par kindly well up in front, where a good view could be had by him of the
\par celebrity--at this point the celebrity in the delectable vision was
\par observed gaily to light a cigarette. Discernible in the throng, too,
\par were some few whose mean and envious natures writhed, the psychologist
\par in Keyes perceived, at this handsome recognition of the worth of a young
\par man it had once been their wont to snub.
\par 
\par In this balmy temper of mind Keyes got down to business one morning a
\par little late. The humdrum of a business life had begun to be somewhat
\par more irksome than hitherto to Keyes's swelling spirit. He ruminated this
\par morning, as he stood before his tall stool at his ledger, on the curious
\par ill-adjustment of a universe so arranged that one of his capacity for
\par finer things could remain so unsuspected of the world about him, and the
\par rich value of his life to some unmeaning task-work be allowed to give. A
\par sudden electric buzzing beneath his high desk signalled him that his
\par presence was desired by his chief. "What now?" he thought, a little
\par tremulously and a little irritably, as he went: he had been caught up on
\par several slips lately. He paused respectfully in the private office
\par doorway. Mr. Winder, from his swivel-chair, flashed up his white
\par moustache very straight at Keyes. "Sit down," he directed. The suavity
\par which was his habit was quite absent. Keyes felt the presence in the air
\par of a good deal of masculine firmness.
\par 
\par "This," said Mr. Winder, his eye steadily on Keyes, "is a place of
\par business. It is not a gentleman's club. Now, I want you to take a brace.
\par That will do."
\par 
\par As Keyes took up his pen again and began to write, "By merchandise," his
\par breast was full with resentment: a sense of the real integrity of his
\par nature welled up in him. His mind rapidly generated the divers manly
\par replies he wished, with an intensity amounting to pain, he had thought
\par of a moment before. He saw himself, now exasperatingly too late, saying
\par with frank honesty to Mr. Winder:
\par 
\par "I realize that I have of late been a little delinquent. But (with some
\par eloquence) it has always been my intention to be, and I believe in the
\par main I have been, a faithful and conscientious employee. I shall not be
\par found wanting again."
\par 
\par But here he was a rebuked culprit. He felt the degradation of servitude.
\par He experienced sharply that violent yearning so familiar to all that
\par are employed everywhere, to be able to go in and tell Mr. Winder to go
\par to the devil. And though he felt at bottom the legitimacy, in the
\par business ethic, of Mr. Winder's attitude, he also felt forlornly the
\par coldness of the business relation, the brutal authority of worldly
\par power, and its conception of his insignificance. And he was stung at the
\par moral criminality, as he felt it to be, of a situation which placed such
\par a man as Mr. Winder over such a nature as his own; Mr. Winder he did not
\par suppose had read a book within the last ten years.
\par 
\par As, at that hour which sets the weary toiler free, in the gathering dusk
\par Keyes stood on the curb amid the hurrying throng homeward bound,--oh!
\par how he longed for that establishment in the eyes of men which the
\par success of his story would bring him. Oh, when would he hear! As he
\par bowled along in the crowded trolley the thought stole through him, until
\par it amounted almost to a conviction, that the great letter awaited him at
\par home now. He could hardly bear the tedium of the short journey.
\par Restlessly he turned his evening paper.
\par 
\par In him had developed of late a great interest in authors; he peered
\par between the pages, a little sheepishly, at the column, "Books and Their
\par Makers." He read that Mr. So and So, the author of "This and That," was
\par a young man thirty years of age. Instantly he reflected that he himself
\par was but twenty-seven. This was encouraging! He had formed a habit
\par recently of contrasting at once any writer's age with his own. If he
\par learned that Mr. Galsworthy, whose books were much advertised but which
\par he had not read, was forty-something, he wanted to know how old he had
\par been when he wrote his first book. Then he counted up the number of
\par books between that time--comparing his age at that time with his
\par own--and now. He was absorbed in the literary gossip of the day. That
\par Myra Kelly had been a schoolteacher, that Gertrude Atherton lived in
\par California, that Mr. Bennett had turned thirty before he published his
\par first book, that such a writer was in Rome, or that some other one was
\par engaged on a new work said to be about the Russian Jews,--he found very
\par interesting. He read in his newspaper the publishers' declaration that
\par Maurice Hewlett's new creation recalled Don Quixote, Cyrano, d'Artagnan,
\par Falstaff, Bombastes Furioso, Tartarin, Gil Blas. His notions concerning
\par the characters of this company were somewhat vague; but he was stirred
\par with an ambition to create some such character, too.
\par 
\par On leaving the car whom should he see but Dr. Nevens. They walked along
\par together. Dr. Nevens inquired about the business. A bad year, he
\par surmised, for trade. Trade! Keyes felt his heart thumping with the
\par temptation to confide the adventures of his literary life; which,
\par indeed, he had found exceedingly difficult to keep so much to himself.
\par But his position gave him clairvoyance: he divined that no sort of
\par ambition receives from people in general so little respect, by some
\par curious idiosyncrasy of the human mind, as literary aspiration. With
\par what coarse and withering scorn had an intimation--which had escaped
\par him--that he had sought to give some artistic articulation to his ideas
\par been met by Pimpkins the other day at the office!
\par 
\par The personality of Dr. Nevens, however, suggested a more sympathetic
\par attitude, by reason of the dentist's cultivation. Dr. Nevens was spoken
\par of as a "booklover." He had a "library"--it was, he implied, his
\par bachelor foible--the cornerstone of which was a set of the Thistle
\par edition of Stevenson that he had bought by subscription from an agent.
\par (Keyes had thought it odd one day that Dr. Nevens had not cut the
\par leaves.) And "the doctor" was fond of speaking familiarly of Dickens,
\par and gained much admiration by his often saying that he should like--had
\par he time--to read through "Esmond" once every year. Here, Keyes felt,
\par would be spiritual succor.
\par 
\par But Keyes quickly learned that he was quite in a different case from the
\par author of "Esmond." Dr. Nevens was kind, but pitying.
\par 
\par "Only one out of hundreds, thousands," he said, "ever comes to
\par anything."
\par 
\par It did not occur to him, Keyes thought, as within the range of remotest
\par possibility that he, Keyes, _might_ be one of these. Then came the
\par doctor's reason.
\par 
\par "You do not know anything," he said paternally, "anything at all."
\par 
\par Keyes realized, with some bitterness, that this world is not an
\par institution existing for the purpose of detecting and rewarding inner
\par worth. He had known enough to write his story, he guessed. With some
\par flare of rage, he felt that simply unsupported merit is rather frowned
\par upon, as tending by comparison to cast others possibly not possessing so
\par much of it somewhat into the shade. He had a savage thought that when
\par he was Dr. Nevens's age he would not be a country dentist. He saw the
\par intense egoism of mankind.
\par 
\par Dr. Nevens was determined to show a young man who had betrayed a
\par consciousness of superiority of grain, his place--economically and
\par socially. The selfish jealousy of the world!
\par 
\par        *       *       *       *       *
\par 
\par His letter had not come. There was only a package from Louise--a copy of
\par "Book Talk," containing a marked article on "Representative American
\par Story Tellers"; from this, after dinner, Keyes imbibed most of the
\par purported facts about Booth Tarkington. Then he went to bed to sleep
\par through the hours until the return of the postman.
\par 
\par The next evening still there was no letter. Keyes's spirit was troubled.
\par He sought the solace of solitude in the quiet, shadowed streets. A
\par reaction was succeeding his rosy complacency! Doubts pierced his
\par dissolving confidence. Was his story so good, after all? Somehow, as he
\par looked back at it now, it seemed much less strong than it had before. He
\par felt a sort of sinking in his stomach. A sickening suspicion came to
\par him that, perhaps, it was absurd. Maybe it was very silly. In a
\par disconnected way certain remarks and passages in it came back to him now
\par as quite questionable. Yes, they sounded pretty maudlin. He squirmed
\par within with mortification as a recollection of these passages passed
\par through his mind. He hoped his story would never get into print. A fear
\par that it might nauseated him. Then he was suffused with a sensation of
\par how little he amounted to. He felt, with a sense of great weakness, the
\par precariousness of his job. A horror came over him that he might lose it.
\par He wished he did not know Louise, who expected things of him. He felt
\par how awkward it was so to fail her. In the position he had got himself
\par into with her, how he had laid himself open to humiliating exposure! Oh,
\par why had he ever sought her? He wished he did not know anybody well. He
\par was an ass and he would never come to anything. He felt the futility of
\par his life. Why could he not slink away somewhere and live out his feeble
\par existence unobserved? As he got into bed he felt that very easily he
\par could cry.
\par 
