\par ... Keyes stood before a downtown news-stand. Hurrying pedestrians
\par bumped into him. An irascible character or two, thus impeded, glared
\par back at him--what was the matter with the fellow! Did he think there was
\par nobody but himself in the world?
\par 
\par B. C. Keyes walked home to the sound of a great orchestra reverberating
\par through him. He could not tolerate the thought of subduing himself to
\par the confinement of a car. He needed movement and air.
\par 
\par It had come, his great letter, a few weeks before. At his sitting down
\par to dinner his mother had given him the envelope. _The Favorite
\par Magazine_--these words had seemed to him to be printed in the upper
\par left-hand corner; it had struck him that perhaps the strain on his
\par nerves of late had so deranged his mind that he now saw, as in a
\par mirage, what was not. "Benjamin C. Keyes, Esq."--so ran the address.
\par Keyes in his dizziness noted this point: people had not customarily
\par addressed him as _esquire_. Then, for the first time in his life, he
\par held in his hand a substantial check payable to his own name--wealth!
\par Courteous and laudatory typewritten words danced before his burning
\par eyes.
\par 
\par He felt, though in a degree an hundred times intensified, as though he
\par had smoked so much tobacco, and drunk so much coffee, he could not
\par compose himself to eat, or read a paper, or go to bed, or stay where he
\par was; but must rush off somewhere else and talk hysterically. He got
\par through his meal blindly. He could not explain--just yet--to his mother:
\par he felt he could not control the patience necessary to begin at the
\par beginning and construct a coherent narrative.... He must go to Louise
\par who already understood the preliminary situation.
\par 
\par It had occurred to Keyes on his hurried, stumbling way thither that the
\par whole thing was unbelievable, and that he must be quite insane. After he
\par had pushed the bell, an interminable time seemed to elapse before his
\par ring was answered. As he stood there on the porch he felt his flesh
\par palpitating. A terrible fear came over him that Louise might not be at
\par home.... Louise said, when her frenzy had somewhat abated, that she had
\par always known that he "had it in him." She told him there was now "a
\par future" before him.... Keyes had determined to go on about his business
\par as though nothing unusual had occurred; then when the story appeared, to
\par accept congratulations with retiring modesty. Before noon the next day
\par he had told three people; by night, seven.
\par 
\par So, going over it all again, Keyes arrived at home, to learn that--"What
\par do you think?" His mother said "a reporter" had been at the house; an
\par occurrence--quite unprecedented in Mrs. Keyes's experience--which had
\par thrown her into considerable agitation. This public official she had
\par associated in her confusion with a policeman. He had, however, treated
\par her as a personage of great interest. He told her "there was nothing to
\par be ashamed of." He drew from her trembling lips some account of her
\par son's life, and requested a photograph.
\par 
\par Next day the dean of local newspapers, vigilant in patriotism, printed
\par an extended article on the "state's new writer." And in an editorial
\par entitled "The Modern Athens" (which referred to Keyes only by
\par implication) the paper affirmed again that Andiena was "by general
\par consent the present chief centre of letters in America." It
\par recapitulated the names of those of her sons and daughters whose works
\par were on the counters of every department store in the land. It concluded
\par by saying: "The hope of a people is in its writers, its chosen ones of
\par lofty thought, its poets and prophets, who shall dream and sing for it,
\par who shall gather up its tendencies and formulate its ideals and voice
\par its spirit, proclaiming its duties and awakening its enthusiasm." Keyes
\par read this, as he took it to be, moving and eloquent tribute to his prize
\par story with feelings akin to those experienced, very probably, by Isaiah.
\par 
\par Keyes received an ovation at "the office." The humility of Pimpkins's
\par admiration was abject. Keyes perceived the commanding quality of
\par ambition--when successful. Miss Wimble, the hollow-breasted cashieress,
\par regarded him with sheep's-eyes. Even Mr. Winder, in passing,
\par congratulated him upon his "stroke of luck."
\par 
\par Wonders once begun, it seemed, poured. Two letters awaited him that
\par evening. One from the editor of _The Monocle Magazine_. _The Monocle
\par Magazine_, as Louis said, "think of it!" The editor of this
\par distinguished institution spoke of his "pleasure" in reading Mr. Keyes's
\par "compelling" story; he begged to request the favor of the "offer" of
\par some of Keyes's "other work." By way of a fraternal insinuation he
\par mentioned that he was a native of Andiena, himself. "Most of us are,"
\par was his sportive comment. The "Consolidated Sunday Magazines, Inc.,"
\par wrote with much business directness to solicit "manuscript," at
\par "immediate payment on acceptance at your regular rates for fiction of
\par the first class."
\par 
\par        *       *       *       *       *
\par 
\par The extraordinary turn of events in Keyes's life brought him visitors as
\par well as letters. Dr. Nevens called, benignly smiling appreciation. His
\par impression appeared to be that he had not been mistaken in giving Keyes
\par his support. Of more constructive importance, however, was the turning
\par up of Mr. Tate, who had been Keyes's instructor in "English" at the
\par Longridge High School. A slender, pale, young man, with a bald, domed
\par forehead "rising in its white mass like a tower of mind," Mr. Tate was
\par understood to nourish a deep respect for literature. He had contributed
\par one or two very serious and painstaking "papers" on the English of
\par Chaucer (not very well understood by Keyes at the time), to "Poet-Lore";
\par and had edited, with notes, several "texts"--one of "The Lady of the
\par Lake," with an "introduction," for school use. He reverenced, he now
\par made evident, the "creative gift," as he designated it; which, he
\par realized, had been denied him. He had come to pay homage to a vessel of
\par this gift, his former pupil, now illustrious.
\par 
\par With the hand of destiny Mr. Tate touched a vital chord. Self-assertion;
\par to be no longer an unregarded atom in the mass of those born only to
\par labor for others; to find play for the mind and the passion which, by no
\par choice of his own, distinguished him from the time slave: this was now
\par Keyes's smouldering thought. Mr. Tate, from his conversancy with the
\par literary situation, reported that there never was in the history of the
\par world such a demand for fiction as now, and that "the publishers"
\par declared there was not an overproduction of good fiction. Editors, Mr.
\par Tate said, were eager to welcome new talent. He strongly encouraged
\par Keyes to adopt what he spoke of as the "literary life." In fact, he
\par seemed to consider that there was no alternative. And, indeed, already
\par in Keyes's own idea of his future he saw himself eventually settled
\par somewhere amid the Irvin-Cobbs, the Julian-Streets, the
\par Joseph-Hergesheimers, and other clever people whose society would be
\par congenial to him.
\par 
\par For the present he cultivated his ego, as became a literary light; and
\par now, with Mr. Tate's assistance, he began to devote the time at his
\par command to preparation for his life's work, to study. Mr. Tate was
\par ardent to be of service; he felt that he had here connected himself with
\par literary history in the making. The great need for Keyes, he felt, was
\par education. The creative genius, Mr. Tate said, could not be implanted;
\par but he felt that this other he could supply. He recommended the patient
\par study of men and books. He thought that what Keyes needed in especial
\par was "technical" knowledge; so he went at that strong. Maupassant, Mr.
\par Tate said, was the great master of the short story. Keyes began his
\par evening studies in English translations of Maupassant.
\par 
\par The galling yoke of his business life was becoming well-nigh unbearable.
\par His soul was in ferment. If only he did not have to get up to hurry
\par every morning down to that penitentiary, there to waste his days, he
\par could get something done. That sapped his vitals. And he was tortured by
\par a flame--to do, to read, study, create, grow, accomplish! He was
\par expanding against the walls of his environment. God! could he but burst
\par them asunder, and leap out!
\par 
\par Mr. Tate had a high idea of a thing which he spoke of as "style." In
\par elucidation of this theme he suggested perusal of essays and treatises
\par by DeQuincey, Walter Pater, and Professor Raleigh, He felt also that the
\par "art of fiction" should be mastered by his prot\'e9g\'e9. So Keyes pitched
\par into examinations of this recondite subject by Sir Walter Besant, Marion
\par Crawford, R. L. Stevenson, and Anthony Trollope. Keyes realized that he
\par had _not_ realized before what a lot there was _to_ writing. Mr. Tate
\par purchased out of his slender means as a present, "Success in
\par Literature," by G. H. Lewes. He unearthed a rich collection in titles of
\par books the consumption of which literature would be invaluable to one in
\par training for the literary profession. An admirable bibliography, this
\par list, of the genre which was Keyes's specialty:--"The Art of Short
\par Story Writing," "Practical Short Story Writing," "The Art of the Short
\par Story," "The Short Story," "Book of the Short Story," "How to Write a
\par Short Story," "Writing of the Short Story," "Short Story Writing,"
\par "Philosophy of the Short Story," "The Story-Teller's Art," "The Short
\par Story in English," "Selections from the World's Greatest Short Stories,"
\par "American Short Stories," "Great English Short-Story Writers." In the
\par reading room of the public library Keyes followed a series of articles
\par in "Book Talk" on the "Craftsmanship of Writing." He advanced in
\par literary culture, under Mr. Tate's zealous lead, to consideration of
\par "the novel," its history and development. And, too, to the drama, its
\par law and technique. His head was filled with the theory of d\'e9nouements,
\par "moments," rising actions, climaxes, suspended actions, and
\par catastrophes. At times he had an uneasy feeling that all these things
\par did not much help him to think up any new stories of his own. But Mr.
\par Tate said "that" would "come."
\par 
\par        *       *       *       *       *
\par 
\par And wealth and fame were even now at hand. The promoters of the great
\par prize contest advertising dodge had not been at fault in business
\par acumen; the winning story returned ample evidence of its popular appeal.
\par It was akin to the minds of the "peepul." _The Favorite Magazine_ was
\par sold during August by enterprising newsboys _on trolley cars_. That
\par great public whose literature is exclusively contemporaneous,--whose
\par world of letters is the current _Saturday Mail-Coach_, the _All-people's
\par Magazine_, the _Purple Book_, the _Nothing-But-Stories_, the _Modiste,
\par The Swift Set, Jones's--the Magazine that Entertains, Brisk Stories,
\par Popularity_, and the _Tip-Top_,--discussed the big features on front
\par porches. Keyes's story even attracted the interest of those _who seldom
\par read anything_. A number of letters from persons of that impulsive class
\par which communicates its inward feelings to authors personally unknown
\par were forwarded to Keyes from his publishers. A young lady resident in
\par St. Joe, Michigan, wrote to say that she thought the scene where the
\par boat upsets was the "_grandest thing_ ever written."
\par 
\par Imagine a man like Keyes sitting his days away on an office stool. His
\par mother, however, could not "see" his resigning his position. His
\par "father had always" ... and so forth. Keyes foamed within. What a
\par thing--woman's maddening narrowness! At the office Keyes's situation
\par grew, in subtle ways, more and more oppressive. His position appeared to
\par become equivocal. Mr. Winder seemed to make a point of increasing
\par exactness. Keyes felt a disposition in authority to put down any
\par subordinate uppishness of feeling possibly occasioned by doings outside
\par the line of business. And he became conscious, too, of a curious
\par estrangement from his associates there. They, on their side, Pimpkins in
\par especial, seemed to feel that he felt he was too good for them. And, in
\par truth, he did. The mundane aims of those around him got on his nerves.
\par Their commonplace thoughts irritated him. They were _common_ natures.
\par But, with fierce secret joy, Keyes knew that an event was approaching
\par which promised, would command, deliverance from it all.
\par 
\par Fall came. And the Favorite Publishing Company bound up the prize story
\par as a "gift book" for the holiday trade. Claud Clarence Chamberlain, the
\par well-known illustrator and creator of the famous "Picture-Hat Girl," was
\par commissioned to make the decorations. These were done with much dash in
\par highly colored crayon and popular sentiment. One was printed on the
\par paper jacket of the book, with the title in embossed letters. The
\par advertisement pronounced the work altogether "an exquisite piece of
\par book-making." It declared the production the "daintiest gift of the
\par season," and reminded "people of culture and refinement" that there was
\par "no present like a book."
\par 
\par Indeed a hero is not without fame in his own country. The
\par Stanton-Merritt bookstore on Capital Street arranged a window display of
\par about a ton of "Will Rockwell Makes Good," with one of Mr. Chamberlain's
\par original illustrations, framed, in the centre. A monster advertising
\par banner was flung across the front of the store above the entrance and
\par windows. Just inside, a pyramid breast-high was built of the books,
\par beneath an artistic piece of work--a hanging board upon which was burned
\par in old English letters: "'A good book is the precious life blood of a
\par Master Spirit'--Milton." A lady who informed the salesman that she
\par thought "books" were "just fine," bought twenty copies for holiday
\par distribution. She inquired if there was not a discount on that number
\par purchased.
\par 
\par Drugged with triumph, they returned together Saturday night from the
\par exhibition "down town"; and, in the now historic little parlor again,
\par Louise wept upon the shoulder of her affianced. Yes; they were formally
\par engaged. Keyes was not without a sensation that the situation was rather
\par chaotic. But destiny seemed to close in on him and bear him on.
\par 
\par The reviewers got on the job. And they were there with the goods.
\par Statements from a few typical press notices follow. "An absorbing
\par story," said the Topeka _Progressive_, "throbbing with optimism." "Mr.
\par Keyes strikes a new note in this unusual production; vivid,
\par dramatic,"--San Francisco _Lookout_. "A story of vivid and compelling
\par interest," one critic declared. "A delightful story, rich in heart
\par throbs," was one good one. One reviewer said, "Here we have a real love
\par story, a tale of love, tender and true, delightfully narrated. There are
\par so many fine, tender passages in the episode of these two, who live just
\par for each other, that reading the little book is like breathing strong,
\par refreshing air." "The creator of 'Will Rockwell," said one paper, "has
\par here written a new idyl of America." "An inspiring picture," said
\par another. One very fine critique said: "Once in awhile, possibly once in
\par a lifetime, there arises before us a writer of fiction whose genius is
\par undeniable the instant it greets us." When Keyes read this, quoted in
\par his publisher's latest newspaper advertisement, he knew that he had
\par found his work in the world. And reasoning from his experience, he saw
\par before him a calling that would be ever a noble intoxication of the
\par soul, a kind that would know naught of headaches or remorse.
\par 
\par But perhaps the best of all the critical dicta was this: "Written," it
\par declared, "with blood and tears and fire." Very impressive was the
\par number of times that were used such adjectives as "big," "vital,"
\par "absorbing," "compelling," "remarkable," "insistent," and "virile."
\par "Optimism," it developed too, was the supreme merit of fiction. One of
\par the arresting terms employed was "economy of means."
\par 
\par There were, it is true, a few dissenting voices from the chorus of
\par unrestrained praise, chiefly from certain notoriously dull,
\par conservative, killjoy journals. The New York _Evening Postman_ said:
\par "This somewhat amateurish little essay in fiction seems to be the
\par product of an untutored sincerity. In this, its sincerity, it is not
\par without a degree of vigor. We doubt, however, whether the author can
\par repeat the performance." And that irrepressibly ribald organ, the New
\par York _Beam_, could not forbear its customary jocular sport. Its smart
\par review of this little classic (as one bookseller already pronounced it)
\par began: "Hooray for 'Will'! Hooray also for 'Mabel'! They are the real
\par simegoozlia."
\par 
\par        *       *       *       *       *
\par 
\par "Don't you think you could write something now, dear?" inquired Mrs.
\par Keyes, who did not see how scholarship pure and simple was, so to say,
\par to move the boat.
\par 
\par This idea of writing something now had indeed occurred to Keyes; but
\par somehow he had not been able to think of anything in particular to
\par write. So he went on with his studies, at the same time keeping an eye
\par open for available material, characters, and plots.
\par 
\par "Surely you can write something, Ben, that we could get some money for,"
\par said Louise. A wife, after all, is only a woman, with a mind fitted to
\par petty things, such as groceries, family washings, clothing, and divers
\par household bills. It is irritating to a man of lofty mind who night and
\par day is racking his brain for an idea, to be prodded on in this fashion.
\par Keyes ground his teeth and bore it; he reflected that an author's life
\par is frequently a battle with mediocrity. Perhaps he was mistaken as to
\par where lay the mediocrity with which he battled.
\par 
\par He fretted and worried and at length sat himself down to write without
\par an inspiration. He bethought himself of Trollope's example to literary
\par aspirants, and tried to grind out two hundred and fifty words every
\par fifteen minutes for three hours a day. He couldn't write twenty. He kept
\par doggedly on. He could not make his characters act or talk--the talk was
\par the most hopeless thing of all. He couldn't, as once he had done, cry
\par over them. Sometimes, in the stillness of the night with his clock
\par ticking before him, he almost thought that he had regained for a moment
\par a tithe of the power he once had; but in the morning when he reviewed
\par his work he admitted that he had been sadly mistaken. Now doubts haunted
\par his soul; even as he wrote another consciousness within not thus
\par employed whispered of his impotency. Fact is, Keyes had not at all the
\par creative gift.
\par 
\par He struggled through a number of stories, some better and some worse.
\par When he mailed these it was with a faltering, doubting heart. Something
\par with a weak action away in his interior told him that they would not be
\par accepted.
\par 
\par Keyes got thinner in flesh, more distressed in spirit, and poorer in
\par this world's goods as time went on. Sometimes he felt like an imposter
\par and was ashamed to face his wife; then he reread his press notices and a
\par fever to do something shook him. But a man cannot support himself and
\par his wife on a fever to do something. Benjamin Cecil Keyes could not
\par understand the thing: if he had literary genius why couldn't he write?
\par If he had not, how then had he written? To sit in full view of one's
\par wife day after day pretending to be interested in a book when the
\par bill-collector calls; and to be tormented all the time by a desire to do
\par something and not to be able to do it, or know when, if ever, one will
\par be able; and to be ashamed and afraid to tell one's wife this; but to be
\par compelled to be there, or to run away, or to hang one's self--this is a
\par situation more than uncomfortable.
\par 
\par A thousand times Keyes decided to roll up his sleeves and do something
\par else--engage in any profitable employment; and a thousand times he
\par decided not to--just yet. A man often exists in this way until he gets
\par quite to the end of the string where the wolf is.
\par 
\par "That was an accident, Louise," said Keyes sadly one day. "I find I
\par can't write."
\par 
\par Keyes was mistaken again. No fine thing ever was made by accident. Keyes
\par managed to write that story because its theme was the most interesting
\par incident in his life; because it appealed to him more strongly than
\par anything else had in his whole experience; because he was thoroughly
\par familiar with the life and the people he featured in his story; because
\par he was absolutely sincere in his sympathies, appreciation, and emotions
\par here; he had no ideals set way beyond his power, no aping tendencies
\par after an effective style, no attention distracted by an ill-digested
\par knowledge of mechanical construction. The structure, and the style
\par simply came, probably because--and finally he managed to write that
\par story because--he was keyed up to it.
\par 
\par A domestic woman often has a wretchedly unworshipful view of art and
\par fame. Keyes's confession did not kill Louise. I suppose he expected her
\par to go back to her parents in high dudgeon as one who had been grossly
\par swindled.
\par 
\par "Do you care if you can't write?" she said, after a moment's silence.
\par "Just think how nice you are--how much nicer you were before you tried
\par to write! And how it has worried you!"
\par 
\par Keyes got a job as a collector for a mercantile house. "My health
\par demands outdoor employment," he told his acquaintances.
\par 
\par        *       *       *       *       *
\par 
\par Sometimes, alone with his lamp after the day's confounded drudgery,
\par Keyes got out the old magazine and reread his forgotten story.
