\par The Forethought
\par 
\par Herein lie buried many things which if read with patience may show the
\par strange meaning of being black here at the dawning of the Twentieth
\par Century.  This meaning is not without interest to you, Gentle Reader;
\par for the problem of the Twentieth Century is the problem of the color
\par line.  I pray you, then, receive my little book in all charity,
\par studying my words with me, forgiving mistake and foible for sake of the
\par faith and passion that is in me, and seeking the grain of truth hidden
\par there.
\par 
\par I have sought here to sketch, in vague, uncertain outline, the
\par spiritual world in which ten thousand thousand Americans live and
\par strive.  First, in two chapters I have tried to show what Emancipation
\par meant to them, and what was its aftermath.  In a third chapter I have
\par pointed out the slow rise of personal leadership, and criticized
\par candidly the leader who bears the chief burden of his race to-day.
\par Then, in two other chapters I have sketched in swift outline the two
\par worlds within and without the Veil, and thus have come to the central
\par problem of training men for life.  Venturing now into deeper detail, I
\par have in two chapters studied the struggles of the massed millions of
\par the black peasantry, and in another have sought to make clear the
\par present relations of the sons of master and man.  Leaving, then, the
\par white world, I have stepped within the Veil, raising it that you may
\par view faintly its deeper recesses,--the meaning of its religion, the
\par passion of its human sorrow, and the struggle of its greater souls.
\par All this I have ended with a tale twice told but seldom written, and a
\par chapter of song.
\par 
\par Some of these thoughts of mine have seen the light before in other
\par guise.  For kindly consenting to their republication here, in altered
\par and extended form, I must thank the publishers of the Atlantic Monthly,
\par The World's Work, the Dial, The New World, and the Annals of the
\par American Academy of Political and Social Science.  Before each chapter,
\par as now printed, stands a bar of the Sorrow Songs,--some echo of
\par haunting melody from the only American music which welled up from black
\par souls in the dark past.  And, finally, need I add that I who speak here
\par am bone of the bone and flesh of the flesh of them that live within the
\par Veil?
\par 
\par W.E.B Du B.
\par 
\par ATLANTA, GA., FEB. 1, 1903.
