\par I
\par 
\par Of Our Spiritual Strivings
\par 
\par   O water, voice of my heart, crying in the sand,
\par     All night long crying with a mournful cry,
\par   As I lie and listen, and cannot understand
\par       The voice of my heart in my side or the voice of the sea,
\par     O water, crying for rest, is it I, is it I?
\par       All night long the water is crying to me.
\par 
\par   Unresting water, there shall never be rest
\par     Till the last moon droop and the last tide fail,
\par   And the fire of the end begin to burn in the west;
\par       And the heart shall be weary and wonder and cry like the sea,
\par     All life long crying without avail,
\par       As the water all night long is crying to me.
\par 
\par   ARTHUR SYMONS.
\par 
\par 
\par Between me and the other world there is ever an unasked question:
\par unasked by some through feelings of delicacy; by others through the
\par difficulty of rightly framing it.  All, nevertheless, flutter round it.
\par They approach me in a half-hesitant sort of way, eye me curiously or
\par compassionately, and then, instead of saying directly, How does it feel
\par to be a problem?  they say, I know an excellent colored man in my town;
\par or, I fought at Mechanicsville; or, Do not these Southern outrages make
\par your blood boil?  At these I smile, or am interested, or reduce the
\par boiling to a simmer, as the occasion may require.  To the real
\par question, How does it feel to be a problem?  I answer seldom a word.
\par 
\par And yet, being a problem is a strange experience,--peculiar even for
\par one who has never been anything else, save perhaps in babyhood and in
\par Europe.  It is in the early days of rollicking boyhood that the
\par revelation first bursts upon one, all in a day, as it were.  I remember
\par well when the shadow swept across me. I was a little thing, away up in
\par the hills of New England, where the dark Housatonic winds between
\par Hoosac and Taghkanic to the sea.  In a wee wooden schoolhouse,
\par something put it into the boys' and girls' heads to buy gorgeous
\par visiting-cards--ten cents a package--and exchange.  The exchange was
\par merry, till one girl, a tall newcomer, refused my card,--refused it
\par peremptorily, with a glance.  Then it dawned upon me with a certain
\par suddenness that I was different from the others; or like, mayhap, in
\par heart and life and longing, but shut out from their world by a vast
\par veil.  I had thereafter no desire to tear down that veil, to creep
\par through; I held all beyond it in common contempt, and lived above it in
\par a region of blue sky and great wandering shadows.  That sky was bluest
\par when I could beat my mates at examination-time, or beat them at a
\par foot-race, or even beat their stringy heads.  Alas, with the years all
\par this fine contempt began to fade; for the words I longed for, and all
\par their dazzling opportunities, were theirs, not mine.  But they should
\par not keep these prizes, I said; some, all, I would wrest from them.
\par Just how I would do it I could never decide: by reading law, by healing
\par the sick, by telling the wonderful tales that swam in my head,--some
\par way.  With other black boys the strife was not so fiercely sunny: their
\par youth shrunk into tasteless sycophancy, or into silent hatred of the
\par pale world about them and mocking distrust of everything white; or
\par wasted itself in a bitter cry, Why did God make me an outcast and a
\par stranger in mine own house?  The shades of the prison-house closed
\par round about us all: walls strait and stubborn to the whitest, but
\par relentlessly narrow, tall, and unscalable to sons of night who must
\par plod darkly on in resignation, or beat unavailing palms against the
\par stone, or steadily, half hopelessly, watch the streak of blue above.
\par 
\par After the Egyptian and Indian, the Greek and Roman, the Teuton and
\par Mongolian, the Negro is a sort of seventh son, born with a veil, and
\par gifted with second-sight in this American world,--a world which yields
\par him no true self-consciousness, but only lets him see himself through
\par the revelation of the other world.  It is a peculiar sensation, this
\par double-consciousness, this sense of always looking at one's self
\par through the eyes of others, of measuring one's soul by the tape of a
\par world that looks on in amused contempt and pity.  One ever feels his
\par twoness,--an American, a Negro; two souls, two thoughts, two
\par unreconciled strivings; two warring ideals in one dark body, whose
\par dogged strength alone keeps it from being torn asunder.
\par 
\par The history of the American Negro is the history of this strife,--this
\par longing to attain self-conscious manhood, to merge his double self into
\par a better and truer self.  In this merging he wishes neither of the
\par older selves to be lost.  He would not Africanize America, for America
\par has too much to teach the world and Africa.  He would not bleach his
\par Negro soul in a flood of white Americanism, for he knows that Negro
\par blood has a message for the world.  He simply wishes to make it
\par possible for a man to be both a Negro and an American, without being
\par cursed and spit upon by his fellows, without having the doors of
\par Opportunity closed roughly in his face.
\par 
\par This, then, is the end of his striving: to be a co-worker in the
\par kingdom of culture, to escape both death and isolation, to husband and
\par use his best powers and his latent genius.  These powers of body and
\par mind have in the past been strangely wasted, dispersed, or forgotten.
\par The shadow of a mighty Negro past flits through the tale of Ethiopia
\par the Shadowy and of Egypt the Sphinx.  Through history, the powers of
\par single black men flash here and there like falling stars, and die
\par sometimes before the world has rightly gauged their brightness.  Here
\par in America, in the few days since Emancipation, the black man's turning
\par hither and thither in hesitant and doubtful striving has often made his
\par very strength to lose effectiveness, to seem like absence of power,
\par like weakness.  And yet it is not weakness,--it is the contradiction of
\par double aims.  The double-aimed struggle of the black artisan--on the
\par one hand to escape white contempt for a nation of  mere hewers of wood
\par and drawers of water, and on the other hand to plough and nail and dig
\par for a poverty-stricken horde--could only result in making him a poor
\par craftsman, for he had but half a heart in either cause.  By the poverty
\par and ignorance of his people, the Negro minister or doctor was tempted
\par toward quackery and demagogy; and by the criticism of the other world,
\par toward ideals that made him ashamed of his lowly tasks.  The would-be
\par black savant was confronted by the paradox that the knowledge his
\par people needed was a twice-told tale to his white neighbors, while the
\par knowledge which would teach the white world was Greek to his own flesh
\par and blood.  The innate love of harmony and beauty that set the ruder
\par souls of his people a-dancing and a-singing raised but confusion and
\par doubt in the soul of the black artist; for the beauty revealed to him
\par was the soul-beauty of a race which his larger audience despised, and
\par he could not articulate the message of another people.  This waste of
\par double aims, this seeking to satisfy two unreconciled ideals, has
\par wrought sad havoc with the courage and faith and deeds of ten thousand
\par thousand people,--has sent them often wooing false gods and invoking
\par false means of salvation, and at times has even seemed about to make
\par them ashamed of themselves.
\par 
\par Away back in the days of bondage they thought to see in one divine
\par event the end of all doubt and disappointment; few men ever worshipped
\par Freedom with half such unquestioning faith as did the American Negro
\par for two centuries.  To him, so far as he thought and dreamed, slavery
\par was indeed the sum of all villainies, the cause of all sorrow, the root
\par of all prejudice; Emancipation was the key to a promised land of
\par sweeter beauty than ever stretched before the eyes of wearied
\par Israelites.  In song and exhortation swelled one refrain--Liberty; in
\par his tears and curses the God he implored had Freedom in his right hand.
\par At last it came,--suddenly, fearfully, like a dream.  With one wild
\par carnival of blood and passion came the message in his own plaintive
\par cadences:--
\par 
\par   "Shout, O children!
\par   Shout, you're free!
\par   For God has bought your liberty!"
\par 
\par 
\par Years have passed away since then,--ten, twenty, forty; forty years of
\par national life, forty years of renewal and development, and yet the
\par swarthy spectre sits in its accustomed seat at the Nation's feast.  In
\par vain do we cry to this our vastest social problem:--
\par 
\par   "Take any shape but that, and my firm nerves
\par   Shall never tremble!"
\par 
\par 
\par The Nation has not yet found peace from its sins; the freedman has not
\par yet found in freedom his promised land.  Whatever of good may have come
\par in these years of change, the shadow of a deep disappointment rests
\par upon the Negro people,--a disappointment all the more bitter because
\par the unattained ideal was unbounded save by the simple ignorance of a
\par lowly people.
\par 
\par The first decade was merely a prolongation of the vain search for
\par freedom, the boon that seemed ever barely to elude their grasp,--like a
\par tantalizing will-o'-the-wisp, maddening and misleading the headless
\par host.  The holocaust of war, the terrors of the Ku-Klux Klan, the lies
\par of carpet-baggers, the disorganization of industry, and the
\par contradictory advice of friends and foes, left the bewildered serf with
\par no new watchword beyond the old cry for freedom.  As the time flew,
\par however, he began to grasp a new idea.  The ideal of liberty demanded
\par for its attainment powerful means, and these the Fifteenth Amendment
\par gave him.  The ballot, which before he had looked upon as a visible
\par sign of freedom, he now regarded as the chief means of gaining and
\par perfecting the liberty with which war had partially endowed him.  And
\par why not?  Had not votes made war and emancipated millions?  Had not
\par votes enfranchised the freedmen?  Was anything impossible to a power
\par that had done all this?  A million black men started with renewed zeal
\par to vote themselves into the kingdom.  So the decade flew away, the
\par revolution of 1876 came, and left the half-free serf weary, wondering,
\par but still inspired.  Slowly but steadily, in the following years, a new
\par vision began gradually to replace the dream of political power,--a
\par powerful movement, the rise of another ideal to guide the unguided,
\par another pillar of fire by night after a clouded day.  It was the ideal
\par of "book-learning"; the curiosity, born of compulsory ignorance, to
\par know and test the power of the cabalistic letters of the white man, the
\par longing to know.  Here at last seemed to have been discovered the
\par mountain path to Canaan; longer than the highway of Emancipation and
\par law, steep and rugged, but straight, leading to heights high enough to
\par overlook life.
\par 
\par Up the new path the advance guard toiled, slowly, heavily, doggedly;
\par only those who have watched and guided the faltering feet, the misty
\par minds, the dull understandings, of the dark pupils of these schools
\par know how faithfully, how piteously, this people strove to learn.  It
\par was weary work.  The cold statistician wrote down the inches of
\par progress here and there, noted also where here and there a foot had
\par slipped or some one had fallen.  To the tired climbers, the horizon was
\par ever dark, the mists were often cold, the Canaan was always dim and far
\par away.  If, however, the vistas disclosed as yet no goal, no
\par resting-place, little but flattery and criticism, the journey at least
\par gave leisure for reflection and self-examination; it changed the child
\par of Emancipation to the youth with dawning self-consciousness,
\par self-realization, self-respect.  In those sombre forests of his
\par striving his own soul rose before him, and he saw himself,--darkly as
\par through a veil; and yet he saw in himself some faint revelation of his
\par power, of his mission.  He began to have a dim feeling that, to attain
\par his place in the world, he must be himself, and not another.  For the
\par first time he sought to analyze the burden he bore upon his back, that
\par dead-weight of social degradation partially masked behind a half-named
\par Negro problem.  He felt his poverty; without a cent, without a home,
\par without land, tools, or savings, he had entered into competition with
\par rich, landed, skilled neighbors.  To be a poor man is hard, but to be a
\par poor race in a land of dollars is the very bottom of hardships.  He
\par felt the weight of his ignorance,--not simply of letters, but of life,
\par of business, of the humanities; the accumulated sloth and shirking and
\par awkwardness of decades and centuries shackled his hands and feet.  Nor
\par was his burden all poverty and ignorance.  The red stain of bastardy,
\par which two centuries of systematic legal defilement of Negro women had
\par stamped upon his race, meant not only the loss of ancient African
\par chastity, but also the hereditary weight of a mass of corruption from
\par white adulterers, threatening almost the obliteration of the Negro home.
\par 
\par A people thus handicapped ought not to be asked to race with the world,
\par but rather allowed to give all its time and thought to its own social
\par problems.  But alas! while sociologists gleefully count his bastards
\par and his prostitutes, the very soul of the toiling, sweating black man
\par is darkened by the shadow of a vast despair.  Men call the shadow
\par prejudice, and learnedly explain it as the natural defence of culture
\par against barbarism, learning against ignorance, purity against crime,
\par the "higher" against the "lower" races.  To which the Negro cries Amen!
\par and swears that to so much of this strange prejudice as is founded on
\par just homage to civilization, culture, righteousness, and progress, he
\par humbly bows and meekly does obeisance.  But before that nameless
\par prejudice that leaps beyond all this he stands helpless, dismayed, and
\par well-nigh speechless; before that personal disrespect and mockery, the
\par ridicule and systematic humiliation, the distortion of fact and wanton
\par license of fancy, the cynical ignoring of the better and the boisterous
\par welcoming of the worse, the all-pervading desire to inculcate disdain
\par for everything black, from Toussaint to the devil,--before this there
\par rises a sickening despair that would disarm and discourage any nation
\par save that black host to whom "discouragement" is an unwritten word.
\par 
\par But the facing of so vast a prejudice could not but bring the
\par inevitable self-questioning, self-disparagement, and lowering of ideals
\par which ever accompany repression and breed in an atmosphere of contempt
\par and hate.  Whisperings and portents came home upon the four winds: Lo!
\par we are diseased and dying, cried the dark hosts; we cannot write, our
\par voting is vain; what need of education, since we must always cook and
\par serve?  And the Nation echoed and enforced this self-criticism, saying:
\par Be content to be servants, and nothing more; what need of higher
\par culture for half-men?  Away with the black man's ballot, by force or
\par fraud,--and behold the suicide of a race!  Nevertheless, out of the
\par evil came something of good,--the more careful adjustment of education
\par to real life, the clearer perception of the Negroes' social
\par responsibilities, and the sobering realization of the meaning of
\par progress.
\par 
\par So dawned the time of Sturm und Drang: storm and stress to-day rocks
\par our little boat on the mad waters of the world-sea; there is within and
\par without the sound of conflict, the burning of body and rending of soul;
\par inspiration strives with doubt, and faith with vain questionings.  The
\par bright ideals of the past,--physical freedom, political power, the
\par training of brains and the training of hands,--all these in turn have
\par waxed and waned, until even the last grows dim and overcast.  Are they
\par all wrong,--all false?  No, not that, but each alone was over-simple
\par and incomplete,--the dreams of a credulous race-childhood, or the fond
\par imaginings of the other world which does not know and does not want to
\par know our power.  To be really true, all these ideals must be melted and
\par welded into one.  The training of the schools we need to-day more than
\par ever,--the training of deft hands, quick eyes and ears, and above all
\par the broader, deeper, higher culture of gifted minds and pure hearts.
\par The power of the ballot we need in sheer self-defence,--else what shall
\par save us from a second slavery?  Freedom, too, the long-sought, we still
\par seek,--the freedom of life and limb, the freedom to work and think, the
\par freedom to love and aspire.  Work, culture, liberty,--all these we
\par need, not singly but together, not successively but together, each
\par growing and aiding each, and all striving toward that vaster ideal that
\par swims before the Negro people, the ideal of human brotherhood, gained
\par through the unifying ideal of Race; the ideal of fostering and
\par developing the traits and talents of the Negro, not in opposition to or
\par contempt for other races, but rather in large conformity to the greater
\par ideals of the American Republic, in order that some day on American
\par soil two world-races may give each to each those characteristics both
\par so sadly lack.  We the darker ones come even now not altogether
\par empty-handed: there are to-day no truer exponents of the pure human
\par spirit of the Declaration of Independence than the American Negroes;
\par there is no true American music but the wild sweet melodies of the
\par Negro slave; the American fairy tales and folklore are Indian and
\par African; and, all in all, we black men seem the sole oasis of simple
\par faith and reverence in a dusty desert of dollars and smartness.  Will
\par America be poorer if she replace her brutal dyspeptic blundering with
\par light-hearted but determined Negro humility? or her coarse and cruel
\par wit with loving jovial good-humor? or her vulgar music with the soul of
\par the Sorrow Songs?
\par 
\par Merely a concrete test of the underlying principles of the great
\par republic is the Negro Problem, and the spiritual striving of the
\par freedmen's sons is the travail of souls whose burden is almost beyond
\par the measure of their strength, but who bear it in the name of an
\par historic race, in the name of this the land of their fathers' fathers,
\par and in the name of human opportunity.
\par 
\par 
\par And now what I have briefly sketched in large outline let me on coming
\par pages tell again in many ways, with loving emphasis and deeper detail,
\par that men may listen to the striving in the souls of black folk.
\par 
