\par 
\par II
\par 
\par Of the Dawn of Freedom
\par 
\par   Careless seems the great Avenger;
\par     History's lessons but record
\par   One death-grapple in the darkness
\par     'Twixt old systems and the Word;
\par   Truth forever on the scaffold,
\par     Wrong forever on the throne;
\par   Yet that scaffold sways the future,
\par     And behind the dim unknown
\par   Standeth God within the shadow
\par     Keeping watch above His own.
\par 
\par   LOWELL.
\par 
\par 
\par The problem of the twentieth century is the problem of the
\par color-line,--the relation of the darker to the lighter races of men in
\par Asia and Africa, in America and the islands of the sea.  It was a phase
\par of this problem that caused the Civil War; and however much they who
\par marched South and North in 1861 may have fixed on the technical points,
\par of union and local autonomy as a shibboleth, all nevertheless knew, as
\par we know, that the question of Negro slavery was the real cause of the
\par conflict.  Curious it was, too, how this deeper question ever forced
\par itself to the surface despite effort and disclaimer.  No sooner had
\par Northern armies touched Southern soil than this old question, newly
\par guised, sprang from the earth,--What shall be done with Negroes?
\par Peremptory military commands this way and that, could not answer the
\par query; the Emancipation Proclamation seemed but to broaden and
\par intensify the difficulties; and the War Amendments made the Negro
\par problems of to-day.
\par 
\par It is the aim of this essay to study the period of history from 1861 to
\par 1872 so far as it relates to the American Negro.  In effect, this tale
\par of the dawn of Freedom is an account of that government of men called
\par the Freedmen's Bureau,--one of the most singular and interesting of the
\par attempts made by a great nation to grapple with vast problems of race
\par and social condition.
\par 
\par The war has naught to do with slaves, cried Congress, the President,
\par and the Nation; and yet no sooner had the armies, East and West,
\par penetrated Virginia and Tennessee than fugitive slaves appeared within
\par their lines.  They came at night, when the flickering camp-fires shone
\par like vast unsteady stars along the black horizon: old men and thin,
\par with gray and tufted hair; women with frightened eyes, dragging
\par whimpering hungry children; men and girls, stalwart and gaunt,--a horde
\par of starving vagabonds, homeless, helpless, and pitiable, in their dark
\par distress.  Two methods of treating these newcomers seemed equally
\par logical to opposite sorts of minds.  Ben Butler, in Virginia, quickly
\par declared slave property contraband of war, and put the fugitives to
\par work; while Fremont, in Missouri, declared the slaves free under
\par martial law.  Butler's action was approved, but Fremont's was hastily
\par countermanded, and his successor, Halleck, saw things differently.
\par "Hereafter," he commanded, "no slaves should be allowed to come into
\par your lines at all; if any come without your knowledge, when owners call
\par for them deliver them."  Such a policy was difficult to enforce; some
\par of the black refugees declared themselves freemen, others showed that
\par their masters had deserted them, and still others were captured with
\par forts and plantations.  Evidently, too, slaves were a source of
\par strength to the Confederacy, and were being used as laborers and
\par producers.  "They constitute a military resource," wrote Secretary
\par Cameron, late in 1861; "and being such, that they should not be turned
\par over to the enemy is too plain to discuss."  So gradually the tone of
\par the army chiefs changed; Congress forbade the rendition of fugitives,
\par and Butler's "contrabands" were welcomed as military laborers.  This
\par complicated rather than solved the problem, for now the scattering
\par fugitives became a steady stream, which flowed faster as the armies
\par marched.
\par 
\par Then the long-headed man with care-chiselled face who sat in the White
\par House saw the inevitable, and emancipated the slaves of rebels on New
\par Year's, 1863.  A month later Congress called earnestly for the Negro
\par soldiers whom the act of July, 1862, had half grudgingly allowed to
\par enlist.  Thus the barriers were levelled and the deed was done.  The
\par stream of fugitives swelled to a flood, and anxious army officers kept
\par inquiring: "What must be done with slaves, arriving almost daily?  Are
\par we to find food and shelter for women and children?"
\par 
\par It was a Pierce of Boston who pointed out the way, and thus became in a
\par sense the founder of the Freedmen's Bureau.  He was a firm friend of
\par Secretary Chase; and when, in 1861, the care of slaves and abandoned
\par lands devolved upon the Treasury officials, Pierce was specially
\par detailed from the ranks to study the conditions.  First, he cared for
\par the refugees at Fortress Monroe; and then, after Sherman had captured
\par Hilton Head, Pierce was sent there to found his Port Royal experiment
\par of making free workingmen out of slaves.  Before his experiment was
\par barely started, however, the problem of the fugitives had assumed such
\par proportions that it was taken from the hands of the over-burdened
\par Treasury Department and given to the army officials.  Already centres
\par of massed freedmen were forming at Fortress Monroe, Washington, New
\par Orleans, Vicksburg and Corinth, Columbus, Ky., and Cairo, Ill., as well
\par as at Port Royal.  Army chaplains found here new and fruitful fields;
\par "superintendents of contrabands" multiplied, and some attempt at
\par systematic work was made by enlisting the able-bodied men and giving
\par work to the others.
\par 
\par Then came the Freedmen's Aid societies, born of the touching appeals
\par from Pierce and from these other centres of distress.  There was the
\par American Missionary Association, sprung from the Amistad, and now
\par full-grown for work; the various church organizations, the National
\par Freedmen's Relief Association, the American Freedmen's Union, the
\par Western Freedmen's Aid Commission,--in all fifty or more active
\par organizations, which sent clothes, money, school-books, and teachers
\par southward.  All they did was needed, for the destitution of the
\par freedmen was often reported as "too appalling for belief," and the
\par situation was daily growing worse rather than better.
\par 
\par And daily, too, it seemed more plain that this was no ordinary matter
\par of temporary relief, but a national crisis; for here loomed a labor
\par problem of vast dimensions.  Masses of Negroes stood idle, or, if they
\par worked spasmodically, were never sure of pay; and if perchance they
\par received pay, squandered the new thing thoughtlessly.  In these and
\par other ways were camp-life and the new liberty demoralizing the
\par freedmen.  The broader economic organization thus clearly demanded
\par sprang up here and there as accident and local conditions determined.
\par Here it was that Pierce's Port Royal plan of leased plantations and
\par guided workmen pointed out the rough way.  In Washington the military
\par governor, at the urgent appeal of the superintendent, opened
\par confiscated estates to the cultivation of the fugitives, and there in
\par the shadow of the dome gathered black farm villages.  General Dix gave
\par over estates to the freedmen of Fortress Monroe, and so on, South and
\par West.  The government and benevolent societies furnished the means of
\par cultivation, and the Negro turned again slowly to work.  The systems of
\par control, thus started, rapidly grew, here and there, into strange
\par little governments, like that of General Banks in Louisiana, with its
\par ninety thousand black subjects, its fifty thousand guided laborers, and
\par its annual budget of one hundred thousand dollars and more.  It made
\par out four thousand pay-rolls a year, registered all freedmen, inquired
\par into grievances and redressed them, laid and collected taxes, and
\par established a system of public schools.  So, too, Colonel Eaton, the
\par superintendent of Tennessee and Arkansas, ruled over one hundred
\par thousand freedmen, leased and cultivated seven thousand acres of cotton
\par land, and fed ten thousand paupers a year.  In South Carolina was
\par General Saxton, with his deep interest in black folk.  He succeeded
\par Pierce and the Treasury officials, and sold forfeited estates, leased
\par abandoned plantations, encouraged schools, and received from Sherman,
\par after that terribly picturesque march to the sea, thousands of the
\par wretched camp followers.
\par 
\par Three characteristic things one might have seen in Sherman's raid
\par through Georgia, which threw the new situation in shadowy relief: the
\par Conqueror, the Conquered, and the Negro.  Some see all significance in
\par the grim front of the destroyer, and some in the bitter sufferers of
\par the Lost Cause.  But to me neither soldier nor fugitive speaks with so
\par deep a meaning as that dark human cloud that clung like remorse on the
\par rear of those swift columns, swelling at times to half their size,
\par almost engulfing and choking them.  In vain were they ordered back, in
\par vain were bridges hewn from beneath their feet; on they trudged and
\par writhed and surged, until they rolled into Savannah, a starved and
\par naked horde of tens of thousands.  There too came the characteristic
\par military remedy: "The islands from Charleston south, the abandoned
\par rice-fields along the rivers for thirty miles back from the sea, and
\par the country bordering the St. John's River, Florida, are reserved and
\par set apart for the settlement of Negroes now made free by act of war."
\par So read the celebrated "Field-order Number Fifteen."
\par 
\par All these experiments, orders, and systems were bound to attract and
\par perplex the government and the nation.  Directly after the Emancipation
\par Proclamation, Representative Eliot had introduced a bill creating a
\par Bureau of Emancipation; but it was never reported.  The following June
\par a committee of inquiry, appointed by the Secretary of War, reported in
\par favor of a temporary bureau for the "improvement, protection, and
\par employment of refugee freedmen," on much the same lines as were
\par afterwards followed.  Petitions came in to President Lincoln from
\par distinguished citizens and organizations, strongly urging a
\par comprehensive and unified plan of dealing with the freedmen, under a
\par bureau which should be "charged with the study of plans and execution
\par of measures for easily guiding, and in every way judiciously and
\par humanely aiding, the passage of our emancipated and yet to be
\par emancipated blacks from the old condition of forced labor to their new
\par state of voluntary industry."
\par 
\par Some half-hearted steps were taken to accomplish this, in part, by
\par putting the whole matter again in charge of the special Treasury
\par agents.  Laws of 1863 and 1864 directed them to take charge of and
\par lease abandoned lands for periods not exceeding twelve months, and to
\par "provide in such leases, or otherwise, for the employment and general
\par welfare" of the freedmen.  Most of the army officers greeted this as a
\par welcome relief from perplexing "Negro affairs," and Secretary
\par Fessenden, July 29, 1864, issued an excellent system of regulations,
\par which were afterward closely followed by General Howard.  Under
\par Treasury agents, large quantities of land were leased in the
\par Mississippi Valley, and many Negroes were employed; but in August,
\par 1864, the new regulations were suspended for reasons of "public
\par policy," and the army was again in control.
\par 
\par Meanwhile Congress had turned its attention to the subject; and in
\par March the House passed a bill by a majority of two establishing a
\par Bureau for Freedmen in the War Department.  Charles Sumner, who had
\par charge of the bill in the Senate, argued that freedmen and abandoned
\par lands ought to be under the same department, and reported a substitute
\par for the House bill attaching the Bureau to the Treasury Department.
\par This bill passed, but too late for action by the House.  The debates
\par wandered over the whole policy of the administration and the general
\par question of slavery, without touching very closely the specific merits
\par of the measure in hand.  Then the national election took place; and the
\par administration, with a vote of renewed confidence from the country,
\par addressed itself to the matter more seriously.  A conference between
\par the two branches of Congress agreed upon a carefully drawn measure
\par which contained the chief provisions of Sumner's bill, but made the
\par proposed organization a department independent of both the War and the
\par Treasury officials.  The bill was conservative, giving the new
\par department "general superintendence of all freedmen."  Its purpose was
\par to "establish regulations" for them, protect them, lease them lands,
\par adjust their wages, and appear in civil and military courts as their
\par "next friend." There were many limitations attached to the powers thus
\par granted, and the organization was made permanent.  Nevertheless, the
\par Senate defeated the bill, and a new conference committee was appointed.
\par This committee reported a new bill, February 28, which was whirled
\par through just as the session closed, and became the act of 1865
\par establishing in the War Department a "Bureau of Refugees, Freedmen, and
\par Abandoned Lands."
\par 
\par This last compromise was a hasty bit of legislation, vague and
\par uncertain in outline.  A Bureau was created, "to continue during the
\par present War of Rebellion, and for one year thereafter," to which was
\par given "the supervision and management of all abandoned lands and the
\par control of all subjects relating to refugees and freedmen," under "such
\par rules and regulations as may be presented by the head of the Bureau and
\par approved by the President."  A Commissioner, appointed by the President
\par and Senate, was to control the Bureau, with an office force not
\par exceeding ten clerks.  The President might also appoint assistant
\par commissioners in the seceded States, and to all these offices military
\par officials might be detailed at regular pay.  The Secretary of War could
\par issue rations, clothing, and fuel to the destitute, and all abandoned
\par property was placed in the hands of the Bureau for eventual lease and
\par sale to ex-slaves in forty-acre parcels.
\par 
\par Thus did the United States government definitely assume charge of the
\par emancipated Negro as the ward of the nation.  It was a tremendous
\par undertaking.  Here at a stroke of the pen was erected a government of
\par millions of men,--and not ordinary men either, but black men
\par emasculated by a peculiarly complete system of slavery, centuries old;
\par and now, suddenly, violently, they come into a new birthright, at a
\par time of war and passion, in the midst of the stricken and embittered
\par population of their former masters.  Any man might well have hesitated
\par to assume charge of such a work, with vast responsibilities, indefinite
\par powers, and limited resources.  Probably no one but a soldier would
\par have answered such a call promptly; and, indeed, no one but a soldier
\par could be called, for Congress had appropriated no money for salaries
\par and expenses.
\par 
\par Less than a month after the weary Emancipator passed to his rest, his
\par successor assigned Major-Gen. Oliver O. Howard to duty as Commissioner
\par of the new Bureau.  He was a Maine man, then only thirty-five years of
\par age.  He had marched with Sherman to the sea, had fought well at
\par Gettysburg, and but the year before had been assigned to the command of
\par the Department of Tennessee.  An honest man, with too much faith in
\par human nature, little aptitude for business and intricate detail, he had
\par had large opportunity of becoming acquainted at first hand with much of
\par the work before him.  And of that work it has been truly said that "no
\par approximately correct history of civilization can ever be written which
\par does not throw out in bold relief, as one of the great landmarks of
\par political and social progress, the organization and administration of
\par the Freedmen's Bureau."
\par 
\par On May 12, 1865, Howard was appointed; and he assumed the duties of his
\par office promptly on the 15th, and began examining the field of work.  A
\par curious mess he looked upon: little despotisms, communistic
\par experiments, slavery, peonage, business speculations, organized
\par charity, unorganized almsgiving,--all reeling on under the guise of
\par helping the freedmen, and all enshrined in the smoke and blood of the
\par war and the cursing and silence of angry men.  On May 19 the new
\par government--for a government it really was--issued its constitution;
\par commissioners were to be appointed in each of the seceded states, who
\par were to take charge of "all subjects relating to refugees and
\par freedmen," and all relief and rations were to be given by their consent
\par alone.  The Bureau invited continued cooperation with benevolent
\par societies, and declared: "It will be the object of all commissioners to
\par introduce practicable systems of compensated labor," and to establish
\par schools.  Forthwith nine assistant commissioners were appointed.  They
\par were to hasten to their fields of work; seek gradually to close relief
\par establishments, and make the destitute self-supporting; act as courts
\par of law where there were no courts, or where Negroes were not recognized
\par in them as free; establish the institution of marriage among ex-slaves,
\par and keep records; see that freedmen were free to choose their
\par employers, and help in making fair contracts for them; and finally, the
\par circular said: "Simple good faith, for which we hope on all hands for
\par those concerned in the passing away of slavery, will especially relieve
\par the assistant commissioners in the discharge of their duties toward the
\par freedmen, as well as promote the general welfare."
\par 
\par No sooner was the work thus started, and the general system and local
\par organization in some measure begun, than two grave difficulties
\par appeared which changed largely the theory and outcome of Bureau work.
\par First, there were the abandoned lands of the South.  It had long been
\par the more or less definitely expressed theory of the North that all the
\par chief problems of Emancipation might be settled by establishing the
\par slaves on the forfeited lands of their masters,--a sort of poetic
\par justice, said some.  But this poetry done into solemn prose meant
\par either wholesale confiscation of private property in the South, or vast
\par appropriations.  Now Congress had not appropriated a cent, and no
\par sooner did the proclamations of general amnesty appear than the eight
\par hundred thousand acres of abandoned lands in the hands of the
\par Freedmen's Bureau melted quickly away.  The second difficulty lay in
\par perfecting the local organization of the Bureau throughout the wide
\par field of work.  Making a new machine and sending out officials of duly
\par ascertained fitness for a great work of social reform is no child's
\par task; but this task was even harder, for a new central organization had
\par to be fitted on a heterogeneous and confused but already existing
\par system of relief and control of ex-slaves; and the agents available for
\par this work must be sought for in an army still busy with war
\par operations,--men in the very nature of the case ill fitted for delicate
\par social work,--or among the questionable camp followers of an invading
\par host.  Thus, after a year's work, vigorously as it was pushed, the
\par problem looked even more difficult to grasp and solve than at the
\par beginning.  Nevertheless, three things that year's work did, well worth
\par the doing: it relieved a vast amount of physical suffering; it
\par transported seven thousand fugitives from congested centres back to the
\par farm; and, best of all, it inaugurated the crusade of the New England
\par schoolma'am.
\par 
\par The annals of this Ninth Crusade are yet to be written,--the tale of a
\par mission that seemed to our age far more quixotic than the quest of St.
\par Louis seemed to his.  Behind the mists of ruin and rapine waved the
\par calico dresses of women who dared, and after the hoarse mouthings of
\par the field guns rang the rhythm of the alphabet.  Rich and poor they
\par were, serious and curious.  Bereaved now of a father, now of a brother,
\par now of more than these, they came seeking a life work in planting New
\par England schoolhouses among the white and black of the South.  They did
\par their work well.  In that first year they taught one hundred thousand
\par souls, and more.
\par 
\par Evidently, Congress must soon legislate again on the hastily organized
\par Bureau, which had so quickly grown into wide significance and vast
\par possibilities.  An institution such as that was well-nigh as difficult
\par to end as to begin.  Early in 1866 Congress took up the matter, when
\par Senator Trumbull, of Illinois, introduced a bill to extend the Bureau
\par and enlarge its powers.  This measure received, at the hands of
\par Congress, far more thorough discussion and attention than its
\par predecessor.  The war cloud had thinned enough to allow a clearer
\par conception of the work of Emancipation.  The champions of the bill
\par argued that the strengthening of the Freedmen's Bureau was still a
\par military necessity; that it was needed for the proper carrying out of
\par the Thirteenth Amendment, and was a work of sheer justice to the
\par ex-slave, at a trifling cost to the government.  The opponents of the
\par measure declared that the war was over, and the necessity for war
\par measures past; that the Bureau, by reason of its extraordinary powers,
\par was clearly unconstitutional in time of peace, and was destined to
\par irritate the South and pauperize the freedmen, at a final cost of
\par possibly hundreds of millions.  These two arguments were unanswered,
\par and indeed unanswerable: the one that the extraordinary powers of the
\par Bureau threatened the civil rights of all citizens; and the other that
\par the government must have power to do what manifestly must be done, and
\par that present abandonment of the freedmen meant their practical
\par reenslavement.  The bill which finally passed enlarged and made
\par permanent the Freedmen's Bureau.  It was promptly vetoed by President
\par Johnson as "unconstitutional," "unnecessary," and "extrajudicial," and
\par failed of passage over the veto.  Meantime, however, the breach between
\par Congress and the President began to broaden, and a modified form of the
\par lost bill was finally passed over the President's second veto, July 16.
\par 
\par The act of 1866 gave the Freedmen's Bureau its final form,--the form by
\par which it will be known to posterity and judged of men.  It extended the
\par existence of the Bureau to July, 1868; it authorized additional
\par assistant commissioners, the retention of army officers mustered out of
\par regular service, the sale of certain forfeited lands to freedmen on
\par nominal terms, the sale of Confederate public property for Negro
\par schools, and a wider field of judicial interpretation and cognizance.
\par The government of the unreconstructed South was thus put very largely
\par in the hands of the Freedmen's Bureau, especially as in many cases the
\par departmental military commander was now made also assistant
\par commissioner.  It was thus that the Freedmen's Bureau became a
\par full-fledged government of men.  It made laws, executed them and
\par interpreted them; it laid and collected taxes, defined and punished
\par crime, maintained and used military force, and dictated such measures
\par as it thought necessary and proper for the accomplishment of its varied
\par ends.  Naturally, all these powers were not exercised continuously nor
\par to their fullest extent; and yet, as General Howard has said, "scarcely
\par any subject that has to be legislated upon in civil society failed, at
\par one time or another, to demand the action of this singular Bureau."
\par 
\par To understand and criticise intelligently so vast a work, one must not
\par forget an instant the drift of things in the later sixties.  Lee had
\par surrendered, Lincoln was dead, and Johnson and Congress were at
\par loggerheads; the Thirteenth Amendment was adopted, the Fourteenth
\par pending, and the Fifteenth declared in force in 1870.  Guerrilla
\par raiding, the ever-present flickering after-flame of war, was spending
\par its forces against the Negroes, and all the Southern land was awakening
\par as from some wild dream to poverty and social revolution.  In a time of
\par perfect calm, amid willing neighbors and streaming wealth, the social
\par uplifting of four million slaves to an assured and self-sustaining
\par place in the body politic and economic would have been a herculean
\par task; but when to the inherent difficulties of so delicate and nice a
\par social operation were added the spite and hate of conflict, the hell of
\par war; when suspicion and cruelty were rife, and gaunt Hunger wept beside
\par Bereavement,--in such a case, the work of any instrument of social
\par regeneration was in large part foredoomed to failure.  The very name of
\par the Bureau stood for a thing in the South which for two centuries and
\par better men had refused even to argue,--that life amid free Negroes was
\par simply unthinkable, the maddest of experiments.
\par 
\par The agents that the Bureau could command varied all the way from
\par unselfish philanthropists to narrow-minded busybodies and thieves; and
\par even though it be true that the average was far better than the worst,
\par it was the occasional fly that helped spoil the ointment.
\par 
\par Then amid all crouched the freed slave, bewildered between friend and
\par foe.  He had emerged from slavery,--not the worst slavery in the world,
\par not a slavery that made all life unbearable, rather a slavery that had
\par here and there something of kindliness, fidelity, and happiness,--but
\par withal slavery, which, so far as human aspiration and desert were
\par concerned, classed the black man and the ox together.  And the Negro
\par knew full well that, whatever their deeper convictions may have been,
\par Southern men had fought with desperate energy to perpetuate this
\par slavery under which the black masses, with half-articulate thought, had
\par writhed and shivered.  They welcomed freedom with a cry.  They shrank
\par from the master who still strove for their chains; they fled to the
\par friends that had freed them, even though those friends stood ready to
\par use them as a club for driving the recalcitrant South back into
\par loyalty.  So the cleft between the white and black South grew.  Idle to
\par say it never should have been; it was as inevitable as its results were
\par pitiable.  Curiously incongruous elements were left arrayed against
\par each other,--the North, the government, the carpet-bagger, and the
\par slave, here; and there, all the South that was white, whether gentleman
\par or vagabond, honest man or rascal, lawless murderer or martyr to duty.
\par 
\par Thus it is doubly difficult to write of this period calmly, so intense
\par was the feeling, so mighty the human passions that swayed and blinded
\par men.  Amid it all, two figures ever stand to typify that day to coming
\par ages,--the one, a gray-haired gentleman, whose fathers had quit
\par themselves like men, whose sons lay in nameless graves; who bowed to
\par the evil of slavery because its abolition threatened untold ill to all;
\par who stood at last, in the evening of life, a blighted, ruined form,
\par with hate in his eyes;--and the other, a form hovering dark and
\par mother-like, her awful face black with the mists of centuries, had
\par aforetime quailed at that white master's command, had bent in love over
\par the cradles of his sons and daughters, and closed in death the sunken
\par eyes of his wife,--aye, too, at his behest had laid herself low to his
\par lust, and borne a tawny man-child to the world, only to see her dark
\par boy's limbs scattered to the winds by midnight marauders riding after
\par "damned Niggers."  These were the saddest sights of that woful day; and
\par no man clasped the hands of these two passing figures of the
\par present-past; but, hating, they went to their long home, and, hating,
\par their children's children live today.
\par 
\par Here, then, was the field of work for the Freedmen's Bureau; and since,
\par with some hesitation, it was continued by the act of 1868 until 1869,
\par let us look upon four years of its work as a whole.  There were, in
\par 1868, nine hundred Bureau officials scattered from Washington to Texas,
\par ruling, directly and indirectly, many millions of men.  The deeds of
\par these rulers fall mainly under seven heads: the relief of physical
\par suffering, the overseeing of the beginnings of free labor, the buying
\par and selling of land, the establishment of schools, the paying of
\par bounties, the administration of justice, and the financiering of all
\par these activities.
\par 
\par Up to June, 1869, over half a million patients had been treated by
\par Bureau physicians and surgeons, and sixty hospitals and asylums had
\par been in operation.  In fifty months twenty-one million free rations
\par were distributed at a cost of over four million dollars.  Next came the
\par difficult question of labor.  First, thirty thousand black men were
\par transported from the refuges and relief stations back to the farms,
\par back to the critical trial of a new way of working.  Plain instructions
\par went out from Washington: the laborers must be free to choose their
\par employers, no fixed rate of wages was prescribed, and there was to be
\par no peonage or forced labor.  So far, so good; but where local agents
\par differed toto caelo in capacity and character, where the personnel was
\par continually changing, the outcome was necessarily varied.  The largest
\par element of success lay in the fact that the majority of the freedmen
\par were willing, even eager, to work.  So labor contracts were
\par written,--fifty thousand in a single State,--laborers advised, wages
\par guaranteed, and employers supplied.  In truth, the organization became
\par a vast labor bureau,--not perfect, indeed, notably defective here and
\par there, but on the whole successful beyond the dreams of thoughtful men.
\par The two great obstacles which confronted the officials were the tyrant
\par and the idler,--the slaveholder who was determined to perpetuate
\par slavery under another name; and, the freedman who regarded freedom as
\par perpetual rest,--the Devil and the Deep Sea.
\par 
\par In the work of establishing the Negroes as peasant proprietors, the
\par Bureau was from the first handicapped and at last absolutely checked.
\par Something was done, and larger things were planned; abandoned lands
\par were leased so long as they remained in the hands of the Bureau, and a
\par total revenue of nearly half a million dollars derived from black
\par tenants.  Some other lands to which the nation had gained title were
\par sold on easy terms, and public lands were opened for settlement to the
\par very few freedmen who had tools and capital.  But the vision of "forty
\par acres and a mule"--the righteous and reasonable ambition to become a
\par landholder, which the nation had all but categorically promised the
\par freedmen--was destined in most cases to bitter disappointment.  And
\par those men of marvellous hindsight who are today seeking to preach the
\par Negro back to the present peonage of the soil know well, or ought to
\par know, that the opportunity of binding the Negro peasant willingly to
\par the soil was lost on that day when the Commissioner of the Freedmen's
\par Bureau had to go to South Carolina and tell the weeping freedmen, after
\par their years of toil, that their land was not theirs, that there was a
\par mistake--somewhere.  If by 1874 the Georgia Negro alone owned three
\par hundred and fifty thousand acres of land, it was by grace of his thrift
\par rather than by bounty of the government.
\par 
\par The greatest success of the Freedmen's Bureau lay in the planting of
\par the free school among Negroes, and the idea of free elementary
\par education among all classes in the South.  It not only called the
\par school-mistresses through the benevolent agencies and built them
\par schoolhouses, but it helped discover and support such apostles of human
\par culture as Edmund Ware, Samuel Armstrong, and Erastus Cravath.  The
\par opposition to Negro education in the South was at first bitter, and
\par showed itself in ashes, insult, and blood; for the South believed an
\par educated Negro to be a dangerous Negro.  And the South was not wholly
\par wrong; for education among all kinds of men always has had, and always
\par will have, an element of danger and revolution, of dissatisfaction and
\par discontent.  Nevertheless, men strive to know.  Perhaps some inkling of
\par this paradox, even in the unquiet days of the Bureau, helped the
\par bayonets allay an opposition to human training which still to-day lies
\par smouldering in the South, but not flaming.  Fisk, Atlanta, Howard, and
\par Hampton were founded in these days, and six million dollars were
\par expended for educational work, seven hundred and fifty thousand dollars
\par of which the freedmen themselves gave of their poverty.
\par 
\par Such contributions, together with the buying of land and various other
\par enterprises, showed that the ex-slave was handling some free capital
\par already.  The chief initial source of this was labor in the army, and
\par his pay and bounty as a soldier.  Payments to Negro soldiers were at
\par first complicated by the ignorance of the recipients, and the fact that
\par the quotas of colored regiments from Northern States were largely
\par filled by recruits from the South, unknown to their fellow soldiers.
\par Consequently, payments were accompanied by such frauds that Congress,
\par by joint resolution in 1867, put the whole matter in the hands of the
\par Freedmen's Bureau.  In two years six million dollars was thus
\par distributed to five thousand claimants, and in the end the sum exceeded
\par eight million dollars.  Even in this system fraud was frequent; but
\par still the work put needed capital in the hands of practical paupers,
\par and some, at least, was well spent.
\par 
\par The most perplexing and least successful part of the Bureau's work lay
\par in the exercise of its judicial functions.  The regular Bureau court
\par consisted of one representative of the employer, one of the Negro, and
\par one of the Bureau.  If the Bureau could have maintained a perfectly
\par judicial attitude, this arrangement would have been ideal, and must in
\par time have gained confidence; but the nature of its other activities and
\par the character of its personnel prejudiced the Bureau in favor of the
\par black litigants, and led without doubt to much injustice and annoyance.
\par On the other hand, to leave the Negro in the hands of Southern courts
\par was impossible.  In a distracted land where slavery had hardly fallen,
\par to keep the strong from wanton abuse of the weak, and the weak from
\par gloating insolently over the half-shorn strength of the strong, was a
\par thankless, hopeless task.  The former masters of the land were
\par peremptorily ordered about, seized, and imprisoned, and punished over
\par and again, with scant courtesy from army officers.  The former slaves
\par were intimidated, beaten, raped, and butchered by angry and revengeful
\par men.  Bureau courts tended to become centres simply for punishing
\par whites, while the regular civil courts tended to become solely
\par institutions for perpetuating the slavery of blacks.  Almost every law
\par and method ingenuity could devise was employed by the legislatures to
\par reduce the Negroes to serfdom,--to make them the slaves of the State,
\par if not of individual owners; while the Bureau officials too often were
\par found striving to put the "bottom rail on top," and gave the freedmen a
\par power and independence which they could not yet use.  It is all well
\par enough for us of another generation to wax wise with advice to those
\par who bore the burden in the heat of the day.  It is full easy now to see
\par that the man who lost home, fortune, and family at a stroke, and saw
\par his land ruled by "mules and niggers," was really benefited by the
\par passing of slavery.  It is not difficult now to say to the young
\par freedman, cheated and cuffed about who has seen his father's head
\par beaten to a jelly and his own mother namelessly assaulted, that the
\par meek shall inherit the earth.  Above all, nothing is more convenient
\par than to heap on the Freedmen's Bureau all the evils of that evil day,
\par and damn it utterly for every mistake and blunder that was made.
\par 
\par All this is easy, but it is neither sensible nor just.  Someone had
\par blundered, but that was long before Oliver Howard was born; there was
\par criminal aggression and heedless neglect, but without some system of
\par control there would have been far more than there was.  Had that
\par control been from within, the Negro would have been re-enslaved, to all
\par intents and purposes.  Coming as the control did from without, perfect
\par men and methods would have bettered all things; and even with imperfect
\par agents and questionable methods, the work accomplished was not
\par undeserving of commendation.
\par 
\par  Such was the dawn of Freedom; such was the work of the
\par Freedmen's Bureau, which, summed up in brief, may be epitomized thus:
\par for some fifteen million dollars, beside the sums spent before 1865,
\par and the dole of benevolent societies, this Bureau set going a system of
\par free labor, established a beginning of peasant proprietorship, secured
\par the recognition of black freedmen before courts of law, and founded the
\par free common school in the South.  On the other hand, it failed to begin
\par the establishment of good-will between ex-masters and freedmen, to
\par guard its work wholly from paternalistic methods which discouraged
\par self-reliance, and to carry out to any considerable extent its implied
\par promises to furnish the freedmen with land.  Its successes were the
\par result of hard work, supplemented by the aid of philanthropists and the
\par eager striving of black men.  Its failures were the result of bad local
\par agents, the inherent difficulties of the work, and national neglect.
\par 
\par Such an institution, from its wide powers, great responsibilities,
\par large control of moneys, and generally conspicuous position, was
\par naturally open to repeated and bitter attack.  It sustained a searching
\par Congressional investigation at the instance of Fernando Wood in 1870.
\par Its archives and few remaining functions were with blunt discourtesy
\par transferred from Howard's control, in his absence, to the supervision
\par of Secretary of War Belknap in 1872, on the Secretary's recommendation.
\par Finally, in consequence of grave intimations of wrong-doing made by the
\par Secretary and his subordinates, General Howard was court-martialed in
\par 1874.  In both of these trials the Commissioner of the Freedmen's
\par Bureau was officially exonerated from any wilful misdoing, and his work
\par commended.  Nevertheless, many unpleasant things were brought to
\par light,--the methods of transacting the business of the Bureau were
\par faulty; several cases of defalcation were proved, and other frauds
\par strongly suspected; there were some business transactions which savored
\par of dangerous speculation, if not dishonesty; and around it all lay the
\par smirch of the Freedmen's Bank.
\par 
\par Morally and practically, the Freedmen's Bank was part of the Freedmen's
\par Bureau, although it had no legal connection with it.  With the prestige
\par of the government back of it, and a directing board of unusual
\par respectability and national reputation, this banking institution had
\par made a remarkable start in the development of that thrift among black
\par folk which slavery had kept them from knowing.  Then in one sad day
\par came the crash,--all the hard-earned dollars of the freedmen
\par disappeared; but that was the least of the loss,--all the faith in
\par saving went too, and much of the faith in men; and that was a loss that
\par a Nation which to-day sneers at Negro shiftlessness has never yet made
\par good.  Not even ten additional years of slavery could have done so much
\par to throttle the thrift of the freedmen as the mismanagement and
\par bankruptcy of the series of savings banks chartered by the Nation for
\par their especial aid.  Where all the blame should rest, it is hard to
\par say; whether the Bureau and the Bank died chiefly by reason of the
\par blows of its selfish friends or the dark machinations of its foes,
\par perhaps even time will never reveal, for here lies unwritten history.
\par 
\par Of the foes without the Bureau, the bitterest were those who attacked
\par not so much its conduct or policy under the law as the necessity for
\par any such institution at all.  Such attacks came primarily from the
\par Border States and the South; and they were summed up by Senator Davis,
\par of Kentucky, when he moved to entitle the act of 1866 a bill "to
\par promote strife and conflict between the white and black races . . . by
\par a grant of unconstitutional power."  The argument gathered tremendous
\par strength South and North; but its very strength was its weakness.  For,
\par argued the plain common-sense of the nation, if it is unconstitutional,
\par unpractical, and futile for the nation to stand guardian over its
\par helpless wards, then there is left but one alternative,--to make those
\par wards their own guardians by arming them with the ballot.  Moreover,
\par the path of the practical politician pointed the same way; for, argued
\par this opportunist, if we cannot peacefully reconstruct the South with
\par white votes, we certainly can with black votes.  So justice and force
\par joined hands.
\par 
\par The alternative thus offered the nation was not between full and
\par restricted Negro suffrage; else every sensible man, black and white,
\par would easily have chosen the latter.  It was rather a choice between
\par suffrage and slavery, after endless blood and gold had flowed to sweep
\par human bondage away.  Not a single Southern legislature stood ready to
\par admit a Negro, under any conditions, to the polls; not a single
\par Southern legislature believed free Negro labor was possible without a
\par system of restrictions that took all its freedom away; there was
\par scarcely a white man in the South who did not honestly regard
\par Emancipation as a crime, and its practical nullification as a duty.  In
\par such a situation, the granting of the ballot to the black man was a
\par necessity, the very least a guilty nation could grant a wronged race,
\par and the only method of compelling the South to accept the results of
\par the war.  Thus Negro suffrage ended a civil war by beginning a race
\par feud.  And some felt gratitude toward the race thus sacrificed in its
\par swaddling clothes on the altar of national integrity; and some felt and
\par feel only indifference and contempt.
\par 
\par Had political exigencies been less pressing, the opposition to
\par government guardianship of Negroes less bitter, and the attachment to
\par the slave system less strong, the social seer can well imagine a far
\par better policy,--a permanent Freedmen's Bureau, with a national system
\par of Negro schools; a carefully supervised employment and labor office; a
\par system of impartial protection before the regular courts; and such
\par institutions for social betterment as savings-banks, land and building
\par associations, and social settlements.  All this vast expenditure of
\par money and brains might have formed a great school of prospective
\par citizenship, and solved in a way we have not yet solved the most
\par perplexing and persistent of the Negro problems.
\par 
\par That such an institution was unthinkable in 1870 was due in part to
\par certain acts of the Freedmen's Bureau itself.  It came to regard its
\par work as merely temporary, and Negro suffrage as a final answer to all
\par present perplexities.  The political ambition of many of its agents and
\par proteges led it far afield into questionable activities, until the
\par South, nursing its own deep prejudices, came easily to ignore all the
\par good deeds of the Bureau and hate its very name with perfect hatred.
\par So the Freedmen's Bureau died, and its child was the Fifteenth
\par Amendment.
\par 
\par The passing of a great human institution before its work is done, like
\par the untimely passing of a single soul, but leaves a legacy of striving
\par for other men.  The legacy of the Freedmen's Bureau is the heavy
\par heritage of this generation.  To-day, when new and vaster problems are
\par destined to strain every fibre of the national mind and soul, would it
\par not be well to count this legacy honestly and carefully?  For this much
\par all men know: despite compromise, war, and struggle, the Negro is not
\par free.  In the backwoods of the Gulf States, for miles and miles, he may
\par not leave the plantation of his birth; in well-nigh the whole rural
\par South the black farmers are peons, bound by law and custom to an
\par economic slavery, from which the only escape is death or the
\par penitentiary.  In the most cultured sections and cities of the South
\par the Negroes are a segregated servile caste, with restricted rights and
\par privileges.  Before the courts, both in law and custom, they stand on a
\par different and peculiar basis.  Taxation without representation is the
\par rule of their political life.  And the result of all this is, and in
\par nature must have been, lawlessness and crime.  That is the large legacy
\par of the Freedmen's Bureau, the work it did not do because it could not.
\par 
\par 
\par I have seen a land right merry with the sun, where children sing, and
\par rolling hills lie like passioned women wanton with harvest.  And there
\par in the King's Highways sat and sits a figure veiled and bowed, by which
\par the traveller's footsteps hasten as they go.  On the tainted air broods
\par fear.  Three centuries' thought has been the raising and unveiling of
\par that bowed human heart, and now behold a century new for the duty and
\par the deed.  The problem of the Twentieth Century is the problem of the
\par color-line.
\par 
