\par III
\par 
\par Of Mr. Booker T. Washington and Others
\par 
\par   From birth till death enslaved; in word, in deed, unmanned!
\par   *     *     *     *     *     *     *     *     *
\par   Hereditary bondsmen!  Know ye not
\par   Who would be free themselves must strike the blow?
\par 
\par   BYRON.
\par 
\par Easily the most striking thing in the history of the American Negro
\par since 1876 is the ascendancy of Mr. Booker T. Washington.  It began at
\par the time when war memories and ideals were rapidly passing; a day of
\par astonishing commercial development was dawning; a sense of doubt and
\par hesitation overtook the freedmen's sons,--then it was that his leading
\par began.  Mr. Washington came, with a simple definite programme, at the
\par psychological moment when the nation was a little ashamed of having
\par bestowed so much sentiment on Negroes, and was concentrating its
\par energies on Dollars.  His programme of industrial education,
\par conciliation of the South, and submission and silence as to civil and
\par political rights, was not wholly original; the Free Negroes from 1830
\par up to war-time had striven to build industrial schools, and the
\par American Missionary Association had from the first taught various
\par trades; and Price and others had sought a way of honorable alliance
\par with the best of the Southerners.  But Mr. Washington first
\par indissolubly linked these things; he put enthusiasm, unlimited energy,
\par and perfect faith into his programme, and changed it from a by-path
\par into a veritable Way of Life.  And the tale of the methods by which he
\par did this is a fascinating study of human life.
\par 
\par It startled the nation to hear a Negro advocating such a programme
\par after many decades of bitter complaint; it startled and won the
\par applause of the South, it interested and won the admiration of the
\par North; and after a confused murmur of protest, it silenced if it did
\par not convert the Negroes themselves.
\par 
\par To gain the sympathy and cooperation of the various elements comprising
\par the white South was Mr. Washington's first task; and this, at the time
\par Tuskegee was founded, seemed, for a black man, well-nigh impossible.
\par And yet ten years later it was done in the word spoken at Atlanta: "In
\par all things purely social we can be as separate as the five fingers, and
\par yet one as the hand in all things essential to mutual progress."  This
\par "Atlanta Compromise" is by all odds the most notable thing in Mr.
\par Washington's career.  The South interpreted it in different ways: the
\par radicals received it as a complete surrender of the demand for civil
\par and political equality; the conservatives, as a generously conceived
\par working basis for mutual understanding.  So both approved it, and
\par to-day its author is certainly the most distinguished Southerner since
\par Jefferson Davis, and the one with the largest personal following.
\par 
\par Next to this achievement comes Mr. Washington's work in gaining place
\par and consideration in the North.  Others less shrewd and tactful had
\par formerly essayed to sit on these two stools and had fallen between
\par them; but as Mr. Washington knew the heart of the South from birth and
\par training, so by singular insight he intuitively grasped the spirit of
\par the age which was dominating the North.  And so thoroughly did he learn
\par the speech and thought of triumphant commercialism, and the ideals of
\par material prosperity, that the picture of a lone black boy poring over a
\par French grammar amid the weeds and dirt of a neglected home soon seemed
\par to him the acme of absurdities.  One wonders what Socrates and St.
\par Francis of Assisi would say to this.
\par 
\par And yet this very singleness of vision and thorough oneness with his
\par age is a mark of the successful man.  It is as though Nature must needs
\par make men narrow in order to give them force.  So Mr. Washington's cult
\par has gained unquestioning followers, his work has wonderfully prospered,
\par his friends are legion, and his enemies are confounded.  To-day he
\par stands as the one recognized spokesman of his ten million fellows, and
\par one of the most notable figures in a nation of seventy millions.  One
\par hesitates, therefore, to criticise a life which, beginning with so
\par little, has done so much.  And yet the time is come when one may speak
\par in all sincerity and utter courtesy of the mistakes and shortcomings of
\par Mr. Washington's career, as well as of his triumphs, without being
\par thought captious or envious, and without forgetting that it is easier
\par to do ill than well in the world.
\par 
\par The criticism that has hitherto met Mr. Washington has not always been
\par of this broad character.  In the South especially has he had to walk
\par warily to avoid the harshest judgments,--and naturally so, for he is
\par dealing with the one subject of deepest sensitiveness to that section.
\par Twice--once when at the Chicago celebration of the Spanish-American War
\par he alluded to the color-prejudice that is "eating away the vitals of
\par the South," and once when he dined with President Roosevelt--has the
\par resulting Southern criticism been violent enough to threaten seriously
\par his popularity.  In the North the feeling has several times forced
\par itself into words, that Mr. Washington's counsels of submission
\par overlooked certain elements of true manhood, and that his educational
\par programme was unnecessarily narrow.  Usually, however, such criticism
\par has not found open expression, although, too, the spiritual sons of the
\par Abolitionists have not been prepared to acknowledge that the schools
\par founded before Tuskegee, by men of broad ideals and self-sacrificing
\par spirit, were wholly failures or worthy of ridicule.  While, then,
\par criticism has not failed to follow Mr. Washington, yet the prevailing
\par public opinion of the land has been but too willing to deliver the
\par solution of a wearisome problem into his hands, and say, "If that is
\par all you and your race ask, take it."
\par 
\par Among his own people, however, Mr. Washington has encountered the
\par strongest and most lasting opposition, amounting at times to
\par bitterness, and even today continuing strong and insistent even though
\par largely silenced in outward expression by the public opinion of the
\par nation.  Some of this opposition is, of course, mere envy; the
\par disappointment of displaced demagogues and the spite of narrow minds.
\par But aside from this, there is among educated and thoughtful colored men
\par in all parts of the land a feeling of deep regret, sorrow, and
\par apprehension at the wide currency and ascendancy which some of Mr.
\par Washington's theories have gained.  These same men admire his sincerity
\par of purpose, and are willing to forgive much to honest endeavor which is
\par doing something worth the doing.  They cooperate with Mr. Washington as
\par far as they conscientiously can; and, indeed, it is no ordinary tribute
\par to this man's tact and power that, steering as he must between so many
\par diverse interests and opinions, he so largely retains the respect of
\par all.
\par 
\par But the hushing of the criticism of honest opponents is a dangerous
\par thing.  It leads some of the best of the critics to unfortunate silence
\par and paralysis of effort, and others to burst into speech so
\par passionately and intemperately as to lose listeners.  Honest and
\par earnest criticism from those whose interests are most nearly
\par touched,--criticism of writers by readers,--this is the soul of
\par democracy and the safeguard of modern society.  If the best of the
\par American Negroes receive by outer pressure a leader whom they had not
\par recognized before, manifestly there is here a certain palpable gain.
\par Yet there is also irreparable loss,--a loss of that peculiarly valuable
\par education which a group receives when by search and criticism it finds
\par and commissions its own leaders.  The way in which this is done is at
\par once the most elementary and the nicest problem of social growth.
\par History is but the record of such group-leadership; and yet how
\par infinitely changeful is its type and character!  And of all types and
\par kinds, what can be more instructive than the leadership of a group
\par within a group?--that curious double movement where real progress may
\par be negative and actual advance be relative retrogression.  All this is
\par the social student's inspiration and despair.
\par 
\par Now in the past the American Negro has had instructive experience in
\par the choosing of group leaders, founding thus a peculiar dynasty which
\par in the light of present conditions is worth while studying.  When
\par sticks and stones and beasts form the sole environment of a people,
\par their attitude is largely one of determined opposition to and conquest
\par of natural forces.  But when to earth and brute is added an environment
\par of men and ideas, then the attitude of the imprisoned group may take
\par three main forms,--a feeling of revolt and revenge; an attempt to
\par adjust all thought and action to the will of the greater group; or,
\par finally, a determined effort at self-realization and self-development
\par despite environing opinion.  The influence of all of these attitudes at
\par various times can be traced in the history of the American Negro, and
\par in the evolution of his successive leaders.
\par 
\par Before 1750, while the fire of African freedom still burned in the
\par veins of the slaves, there was in all leadership or attempted
\par leadership but the one motive of revolt and revenge,--typified in the
\par terrible Maroons, the Danish blacks, and Cato of Stono, and veiling all
\par the Americas in fear of insurrection.  The liberalizing tendencies of
\par the latter half of the eighteenth century brought, along with kindlier
\par relations between black and white, thoughts of ultimate adjustment and
\par assimilation.  Such aspiration was especially voiced in the earnest
\par songs of Phyllis, in the martyrdom of Attucks, the fighting of Salem
\par and Poor, the intellectual accomplishments of Banneker and Derham, and
\par the political demands of the Cuffes.
\par 
\par Stern financial and social stress after the war cooled much of the
\par previous humanitarian ardor.  The disappointment and impatience of the
\par Negroes at the persistence of slavery and serfdom voiced itself in two
\par movements.  The slaves in the South, aroused undoubtedly by vague
\par rumors of the Haytian revolt, made three fierce attempts at
\par insurrection,--in 1800 under Gabriel in Virginia, in 1822 under Vesey
\par in Carolina, and in 1831 again in Virginia under the terrible Nat
\par Turner.  In the Free States, on the other hand, a new and curious
\par attempt at self-development was made.  In Philadelphia and New York
\par color-prescription led to a withdrawal of Negro communicants from white
\par churches and the formation of a peculiar socio-religious institution
\par among the Negroes known as the African Church,--an organization still
\par living and controlling in its various branches over a million of men.
\par 
\par Walker's wild appeal against the trend of the times showed how the
\par world was changing after the coming of the cotton-gin.  By 1830 slavery
\par seemed hopelessly fastened on the South, and the slaves thoroughly
\par cowed into submission.  The free Negroes of the North, inspired by the
\par mulatto immigrants from the West Indies, began to change the basis of
\par their demands; they recognized the slavery of slaves, but insisted that
\par they themselves were freemen, and sought assimilation and amalgamation
\par with the nation on the same terms with other men.  Thus, Forten and
\par Purvis of Philadelphia, Shad of Wilmington, Du Bois of New Haven,
\par Barbadoes of Boston, and others, strove singly and together as men,
\par they said, not as slaves; as "people of color," not as "Negroes."  The
\par trend of the times, however, refused them recognition save in
\par individual and exceptional cases, considered them as one with all the
\par despised blacks, and they soon found themselves striving to keep even
\par the rights they formerly had of voting and working and moving as
\par freemen.  Schemes of migration and colonization arose among them; but
\par these they refused to entertain, and they eventually turned to the
\par Abolition movement as a final refuge.
\par 
\par Here, led by Remond, Nell, Wells-Brown, and Douglass, a new period of
\par self-assertion and self-development dawned.  To be sure, ultimate
\par freedom and assimilation was the ideal before the leaders, but the
\par assertion of the manhood rights of the Negro by himself was the main
\par reliance, and John Brown's raid was the extreme of its logic.  After
\par the war and emancipation, the great form of Frederick Douglass, the
\par greatest of American Negro leaders, still led the host.
\par Self-assertion, especially in political lines, was the main programme,
\par and behind Douglass came Elliot, Bruce, and Langston, and the
\par Reconstruction politicians, and, less conspicuous but of greater social
\par significance, Alexander Crummell and Bishop Daniel Payne.
\par 
\par Then came the Revolution of 1876, the suppression of the Negro votes,
\par the changing and shifting of ideals, and the seeking of new lights in
\par the great night.  Douglass, in his old age, still bravely stood for the
\par ideals of his early manhood,--ultimate assimilation through
\par self-assertion, and on no other terms.  For a time Price arose as a new
\par leader, destined, it seemed, not to give up, but to re-state the old
\par ideals in a form less repugnant to the white South.  But he passed away
\par in his prime.  Then came the new leader.  Nearly all the former ones
\par had become leaders by the silent suffrage of their fellows, had sought
\par to lead their own people alone, and were usually, save Douglass, little
\par known outside their race.  But Booker T. Washington arose as
\par essentially the leader not of one race but of two,--a compromiser
\par between the South, the North, and the Negro.  Naturally the Negroes
\par resented, at first bitterly, signs of compromise which surrendered
\par their civil and political rights, even though this was to be exchanged
\par for larger chances of economic development.  The rich and dominating
\par North, however, was not only weary of the race problem, but was
\par investing largely in Southern enterprises, and welcomed any method of
\par peaceful cooperation.  Thus, by national opinion, the Negroes began to
\par recognize Mr. Washington's leadership; and the voice of criticism was
\par hushed.
\par 
\par Mr. Washington represents in Negro thought the old attitude of
\par adjustment and submission; but adjustment at such a peculiar time as to
\par make his programme unique.  This is an age of unusual economic
\par development, and Mr. Washington's programme naturally takes an economic
\par cast, becoming a gospel of Work and Money to such an extent as
\par apparently almost completely to overshadow the higher aims of life.
\par Moreover, this is an age when the more advanced races are coming in
\par closer contact with the less developed races, and the race-feeling is
\par therefore intensified; and Mr. Washington's programme practically
\par accepts the alleged inferiority of the Negro races.  Again, in our own
\par land, the reaction from the sentiment of war time has given impetus to
\par race-prejudice against Negroes, and Mr. Washington withdraws many of
\par the high demands of Negroes as men and American citizens.  In other
\par periods of intensified prejudice all the Negro's tendency to
\par self-assertion has been called forth; at this period a policy of
\par submission is advocated.  In the history of nearly all other races and
\par peoples the doctrine preached at such crises has been that manly
\par self-respect is worth more than lands and houses, and that a people who
\par voluntarily surrender such respect, or cease striving for it, are not
\par worth civilizing.
\par 
\par In answer to this, it has been claimed that the Negro can survive only
\par through submission.  Mr. Washington distinctly asks that black people
\par give up, at least for the present, three things,--
\par 
\par First, political power,
\par 
\par Second, insistence on civil rights,
\par 
\par Third, higher education of Negro youth,--and concentrate all their
\par energies on industrial education, and accumulation of wealth, and the
\par conciliation of the South.  This policy has been courageously and
\par insistently advocated for over fifteen years, and has been triumphant
\par for perhaps ten years.  As a result of this tender of the palm-branch,
\par what has been the return?  In these years there have occurred:
\par 
\par 1.  The disfranchisement of the Negro.
\par 
\par 2.  The legal creation of a distinct status of civil inferiority for
\par the Negro.
\par 
\par 3.  The steady withdrawal of aid from institutions for the higher
\par training of the Negro.
\par 
\par These movements are not, to be sure, direct results of Mr. Washington's
\par teachings; but his propaganda has, without a shadow of doubt, helped
\par their speedier accomplishment.  The question then comes: Is it
\par possible, and probable, that nine millions of men can make effective
\par progress in economic lines if they are deprived of political rights,
\par made a servile caste, and allowed only the most meagre chance for
\par developing their exceptional men?  If history and reason give any
\par distinct answer to these questions, it is an emphatic NO.  And Mr.
\par Washington thus faces the triple paradox of his career:
\par 
\par 1.  He is striving nobly to make Negro artisans business men and
\par property-owners; but it is utterly impossible, under modern competitive
\par methods, for workingmen and property-owners to defend their rights and
\par exist without the right of suffrage.
\par 
\par 2.  He insists on thrift and self-respect, but at the same time
\par counsels a silent submission to civic inferiority such as is bound to
\par sap the manhood of any race in the long run.
\par 
\par 3.  He advocates common-school and industrial training, and depreciates
\par institutions of higher learning; but neither the Negro common-schools,
\par nor Tuskegee itself, could remain open a day were it not for teachers
\par trained in Negro colleges, or trained by their graduates.
\par 
\par This triple paradox in Mr. Washington's position is the object of
\par criticism by two classes of colored Americans.  One class is
\par spiritually descended from Toussaint the Savior, through Gabriel,
\par Vesey, and Turner, and they represent the attitude of revolt and
\par revenge; they hate the white South blindly and distrust the white race
\par generally, and so far as they agree on definite action, think that the
\par Negro's only hope lies in emigration beyond the borders of the United
\par States.  And yet, by the irony of fate, nothing has more effectually
\par made this programme seem hopeless than the recent course of the United
\par States toward weaker and darker peoples in the West Indies, Hawaii, and
\par the Philippines,--for where in the world may we go and be safe from
\par lying and brute force?
\par 
\par The other class of Negroes who cannot agree with Mr. Washington has
\par hitherto said little aloud.  They deprecate the sight of scattered
\par counsels, of internal disagreement; and especially they dislike making
\par their just criticism of a useful and earnest man an excuse for a
\par general discharge of venom from small-minded opponents.  Nevertheless,
\par the questions involved are so fundamental and serious that it is
\par difficult to see how men like the Grimkes, Kelly Miller, J. W. E.
\par Bowen, and other representatives of this group, can much longer be
\par silent.  Such men feel in conscience bound to ask of this nation three
\par things:
\par 
\par 1.  The right to vote.
\par 
\par 2.  Civic equality.
\par 
\par 3.  The education of youth according to ability.  They acknowledge Mr.
\par Washington's invaluable service in counselling patience and courtesy in
\par such demands; they do not ask that ignorant black men vote when
\par ignorant whites are debarred, or that any reasonable restrictions in
\par the suffrage should not be applied; they know that the low social level
\par of the mass of the race is responsible for much discrimination against
\par it, but they also know, and the nation knows, that relentless
\par color-prejudice is more often a cause than a result of the Negro's
\par degradation; they seek the abatement of this relic of barbarism, and
\par not its systematic encouragement and pampering by all agencies of
\par social power from the Associated Press to the Church of Christ.  They
\par advocate, with Mr. Washington, a broad system of Negro common schools
\par supplemented by thorough industrial training; but they are surprised
\par that a man of Mr. Washington's insight cannot see that no such
\par educational system ever has rested or can rest on any other basis than
\par that of the well-equipped college and university, and they insist that
\par there is a demand for a few such institutions throughout the South to
\par train the best of the Negro youth as teachers, professional men, and
\par leaders.
\par 
\par This group of men honor Mr. Washington for his attitude of conciliation
\par toward the white South; they accept the "Atlanta Compromise" in its
\par broadest interpretation; they recognize, with him, many signs of
\par promise, many men of high purpose and fair judgment, in this section;
\par they know that no easy task has been laid upon a region already
\par tottering under heavy burdens.  But, nevertheless, they insist that the
\par way to truth and right lies in straightforward honesty, not in
\par indiscriminate flattery; in praising those of the South who do well and
\par criticising uncompromisingly those who do ill; in taking advantage of
\par the opportunities at hand and urging their fellows to do the same, but
\par at the same time in remembering that only a firm adherence to their
\par higher ideals and aspirations will ever keep those ideals within the
\par realm of possibility.  They do not expect that the free right to vote,
\par to enjoy civic rights, and to be educated, will come in a moment; they
\par do not expect to see the bias and prejudices of years disappear at the
\par blast of a trumpet; but they are absolutely certain that the way for a
\par people to gain their reasonable rights is not by voluntarily throwing
\par them away and insisting that they do not want them; that the way for a
\par people to gain respect is not by continually belittling and ridiculing
\par themselves; that, on the contrary, Negroes must insist continually, in
\par season and out of season, that voting is necessary to modern manhood,
\par that color discrimination is barbarism, and that black boys need
\par education as well as white boys.
\par 
\par In failing thus to state plainly and unequivocally the legitimate
\par demands of their people, even at the cost of opposing an honored
\par leader, the thinking classes of American Negroes would shirk a heavy
\par responsibility,--a responsibility to themselves, a responsibility to
\par the struggling masses, a responsibility to the darker races of men
\par whose future depends so largely on this American experiment, but
\par especially a responsibility to this nation,--this common Fatherland.
\par It is wrong to encourage a man or a people in evil-doing; it is wrong
\par to aid and abet a national crime simply because it is unpopular not to
\par do so.  The growing spirit of kindliness and reconciliation between the
\par North and South after the frightful difference of a generation ago
\par ought to be a source of deep congratulation to all, and especially to
\par those whose mistreatment caused the war; but if that reconciliation is
\par to be marked by the industrial slavery and civic death of those same
\par black men, with permanent legislation into a position of inferiority,
\par then those black men, if they are really men, are called upon by every
\par consideration of patriotism and loyalty to oppose such a course by all
\par civilized methods, even though such opposition involves disagreement
\par with Mr. Booker T. Washington.  We have no right to sit silently by
\par while the inevitable seeds are sown for a harvest of disaster to our
\par children, black and white.
\par 
\par First, it is the duty of black men to judge the South discriminatingly.
\par The present generation of Southerners are not responsible for the past,
\par and they should not be blindly hated or blamed for it.  Furthermore, to
\par no class is the indiscriminate endorsement of the recent course of the
\par South toward Negroes more nauseating than to the best thought of the
\par South.  The South is not "solid"; it is a land in the ferment of social
\par change, wherein forces of all kinds are fighting for supremacy; and to
\par praise the ill the South is today perpetrating is just as wrong as to
\par condemn the good.  Discriminating and broad-minded criticism is what
\par the South needs,--needs it for the sake of her own white sons and
\par daughters, and for the insurance of robust, healthy mental and moral
\par development.
\par 
\par Today even the attitude of the Southern whites toward the blacks is
\par not, as so many assume, in all cases the same; the ignorant Southerner
\par hates the Negro, the workingmen fear his competition, the money-makers
\par wish to use him as a laborer, some of the educated see a menace in his
\par upward development, while others--usually the sons of the masters--wish
\par to help him to rise.  National opinion has enabled this last class to
\par maintain the Negro common schools, and to protect the Negro partially
\par in property, life, and limb.  Through the pressure of the money-makers,
\par the Negro is in danger of being reduced to semi-slavery, especially in
\par the country districts; the workingmen, and those of the educated who
\par fear the Negro, have united to disfranchise him, and some have urged
\par his deportation; while the passions of the ignorant are easily aroused
\par to lynch and abuse any black man.  To praise this intricate whirl of
\par thought and prejudice is nonsense; to inveigh indiscriminately against
\par "the South" is unjust; but to use the same breath in praising Governor
\par Aycock, exposing Senator Morgan, arguing with Mr. Thomas Nelson Page,
\par and denouncing Senator Ben Tillman, is not only sane, but the
\par imperative duty of thinking black men.
\par 
\par It would be unjust to Mr. Washington not to acknowledge that in several
\par instances he has opposed movements in the South which were unjust to
\par the Negro; he sent memorials to the Louisiana and Alabama
\par constitutional conventions, he has spoken against lynching, and in
\par other ways has openly or silently set his influence against sinister
\par schemes and unfortunate happenings.  Notwithstanding this, it is
\par equally true to assert that on the whole the distinct impression left
\par by Mr. Washington's propaganda is, first, that the South is justified
\par in its present attitude toward the Negro because of the Negro's
\par degradation; secondly, that the prime cause of the Negro's failure to
\par rise more quickly is his wrong education in the past; and, thirdly,
\par that his future rise depends primarily on his own efforts.  Each of
\par these propositions is a dangerous half-truth.  The supplementary truths
\par must never be lost sight of: first, slavery and race-prejudice are
\par potent if not sufficient causes of the Negro's position; second,
\par industrial and common-school training were necessarily slow in planting
\par because they had to await the black teachers trained by higher
\par institutions,--it being extremely doubtful if any essentially different
\par development was possible, and certainly a Tuskegee was unthinkable
\par before 1880; and, third, while it is a great truth to say that the
\par Negro must strive and strive mightily to help himself, it is equally
\par true that unless his striving be not simply seconded, but rather
\par aroused and encouraged, by the initiative of the richer and wiser
\par environing group, he cannot hope for great success.
\par 
\par In his failure to realize and impress this last point, Mr. Washington
\par is especially to be criticised.  His doctrine has tended to make the
\par whites, North and South, shift the burden of the Negro problem to the
\par Negro's shoulders and stand aside as critical and rather pessimistic
\par spectators; when in fact the burden belongs to the nation, and the
\par hands of none of us are clean if we bend not our energies to righting
\par these great wrongs.
\par 
\par The South ought to be led, by candid and honest criticism, to assert
\par her better self and do her full duty to the race she has cruelly
\par wronged and is still wronging.  The North--her co-partner in
\par guilt--cannot salve her conscience by plastering it with gold.  We
\par cannot settle this problem by diplomacy and suaveness, by "policy"
\par alone.  If worse come to worst, can the moral fibre of this country
\par survive the slow throttling and murder of nine millions of men?
\par 
\par The black men of America have a duty to perform, a duty stern and
\par delicate,--a forward movement to oppose a part of the work of their
\par greatest leader.  So far as Mr. Washington preaches Thrift, Patience,
\par and Industrial Training for the masses, we must hold up his hands and
\par strive with him, rejoicing in his honors and glorying in the strength
\par of this Joshua called of God and of man to lead the headless host.  But
\par so far as Mr. Washington apologizes for injustice, North or South, does
\par not rightly value the privilege and duty of voting, belittles the
\par emasculating effects of caste distinctions, and opposes the higher
\par training and ambition of our brighter minds,--so far as he, the South,
\par or the Nation, does this,--we must unceasingly and firmly oppose them.
\par By every civilized and peaceful method we must strive for the rights
\par which the world accords to men, clinging unwaveringly to those great
\par words which the sons of the Fathers would fain forget: "We hold these
\par truths to be self-evident: That all men are created equal; that they
\par are endowed by their Creator with certain unalienable rights; that
\par among these are life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness."
\par 
