\par   SCHILLER.
\par 
\par 
\par Once upon a time I taught school in the hills of Tennessee, where the
\par broad dark vale of the Mississippi begins to roll and crumple to greet
\par the Alleghanies.  I was a Fisk student then, and all Fisk men thought
\par that Tennessee--beyond the Veil--was theirs alone, and in vacation time
\par they sallied forth in lusty bands to meet the county
\par school-commissioners.  Young and happy, I too went, and I shall not
\par soon forget that summer, seventeen years ago.
\par 
\par First, there was a Teachers' Institute at the county-seat; and there
\par distinguished guests of the superintendent taught the teachers
\par fractions and spelling and other mysteries,--white teachers in the
\par morning, Negroes at night.  A picnic now and then, and a supper, and
\par the rough world was softened by laughter and song.  I remember how--
\par But I wander.
\par 
\par There came a day when all the teachers left the Institute and began the
\par hunt for schools.  I learn from hearsay (for my mother was mortally
\par afraid of firearms) that the hunting of ducks and bears and men is
\par wonderfully interesting, but I am sure that the man who has never
\par hunted a country school has something to learn of the pleasures of the
\par chase.  I see now the white, hot roads lazily rise and fall and wind
\par before me under the burning July sun; I feel the deep weariness of
\par heart and limb as ten, eight, six miles stretch relentlessly ahead; I
\par feel my heart sink heavily as I hear again and again, "Got a teacher?
\par Yes."  So I walked on and on--horses were too expensive--until I had
\par wandered beyond railways, beyond stage lines, to a land of "varmints"
\par and rattlesnakes, where the coming of a stranger was an event, and men
\par lived and died in the shadow of one blue hill.
\par 
\par Sprinkled over hill and dale lay cabins and farmhouses, shut out from
\par the world by the forests and the rolling hills toward the east.  There
\par I found at last a little school.  Josie told me of it; she was a thin,
\par homely girl of twenty, with a dark-brown face and thick, hard hair.  I
\par had crossed the stream at Watertown, and rested under the great
\par willows; then I had gone to the little cabin in the lot where Josie was
\par resting on her way to town.  The gaunt farmer made me welcome, and
\par Josie, hearing my errand, told me anxiously that they wanted a school
\par over the hill; that but once since the war had a teacher been there;
\par that she herself longed to learn,--and thus she ran on, talking fast
\par and loud, with much earnestness and energy.
\par 
\par Next morning I crossed the tall round hill, lingered to look at the
\par blue and yellow mountains stretching toward the Carolinas, then plunged
\par into the wood, and came out at Josie's home.  It was a dull frame
\par cottage with four rooms, perched just below the brow of the hill, amid
\par peach-trees.  The father was a quiet, simple soul, calmly ignorant,
\par with no touch of vulgarity.  The mother was different,--strong,
\par bustling, and energetic, with a quick, restless tongue, and an ambition
\par to live "like folks." There was a crowd of children.  Two boys had gone
\par away.  There remained two growing girls; a shy midget of eight; John,
\par tall, awkward, and eighteen; Jim, younger, quicker, and better looking;
\par and two babies of indefinite age.  Then there was Josie herself.  She
\par seemed to be the centre of the family: always busy at service, or at
\par home, or berry-picking; a little nervous and inclined to scold, like
\par her mother, yet faithful, too, like her father.  She had about her a
\par certain fineness, the shadow of an unconscious moral heroism that would
\par willingly give all of life to make life broader, deeper, and fuller for
\par her and hers.  I saw much of this family afterwards, and grew to love
\par them for their honest efforts to be decent and comfortable, and for
\par their knowledge of their own ignorance.  There was with them no
\par affectation.  The mother would scold the father for being so "easy";
\par Josie would roundly berate the boys for carelessness; and all knew that
\par it was a hard thing to dig a living out of a rocky side-hill.
\par 
\par I secured the school.  I remember the day I rode horseback out to the
\par commissioner's house with a pleasant young white fellow who wanted the
\par white school.  The road ran down the bed of a stream; the sun laughed
\par and the water jingled, and we rode on.  "Come in," said the
\par commissioner,--"come in.  Have a seat.  Yes, that certificate will do.
\par Stay to dinner.  What do you want a month?"  "Oh," thought I, "this is
\par lucky"; but even then fell the awful shadow of the Veil, for they ate
\par first, then I--alone.
\par 
\par The schoolhouse was a log hut, where Colonel Wheeler used to shelter
\par his corn.  It sat in a lot behind a rail fence and thorn bushes, near
\par the sweetest of springs.  There was an entrance where a door once was,
\par and within, a massive rickety fireplace; great chinks between the logs
\par served as windows.  Furniture was scarce.  A pale blackboard crouched
\par in the corner.  My desk was made of three boards, reinforced at
\par critical points, and my chair, borrowed from the landlady, had to be
\par returned every night.  Seats for the children--these puzzled me much.
\par I was haunted by a New England vision of neat little desks and chairs,
\par but, alas! the reality was rough plank benches without backs, and at
\par times without legs.  They had the one virtue of making naps
\par dangerous,--possibly fatal, for the floor was not to be trusted.
\par 
\par It was a hot morning late in July when the school opened.  I trembled
\par when I heard the patter of little feet down the dusty road, and saw the
\par growing row of dark solemn faces and bright eager eyes facing me.
\par First came Josie and her brothers and sisters.  The longing to know, to
\par be a student in the great school at Nashville, hovered like a star
\par above this child-woman amid her work and worry, and she studied
\par doggedly.  There were the Dowells from their farm over toward
\par Alexandria,--Fanny, with her smooth black face and wondering eyes;
\par Martha, brown and dull; the pretty girl-wife of a brother, and the
\par younger brood.
\par 
\par There were the Burkes,--two brown and yellow lads, and a tiny
\par haughty-eyed girl.  Fat Reuben's little chubby girl came, with golden
\par face and old-gold hair, faithful and solemn.  'Thenie was on hand
\par early,--a jolly, ugly, good-hearted girl, who slyly dipped snuff and
\par looked after her little bow-legged brother.  When her mother could
\par spare her, 'Tildy came,--a midnight beauty, with starry eyes and
\par tapering limbs; and her brother, correspondingly homely.  And then the
\par big boys,--the hulking Lawrences; the lazy Neills, unfathered sons of
\par mother and daughter; Hickman, with a stoop in his shoulders; and the
\par rest.
\par 
\par There they sat, nearly thirty of them, on the rough benches, their
\par faces shading from a pale cream to a deep brown, the little feet bare
\par and swinging, the eyes full of expectation, with here and there a
\par twinkle of mischief, and the hands grasping Webster's blue-black
\par spelling-book.  I loved my school, and the fine faith the children had
\par in the wisdom of their teacher was truly marvellous.  We read and
\par spelled together, wrote a little, picked flowers, sang, and listened to
\par stories of the world beyond the hill.  At times the school would
\par dwindle away, and I would start out.  I would visit Mun Eddings, who
\par lived in two very dirty rooms, and ask why little Lugene, whose flaming
\par face seemed ever ablaze with the dark-red hair uncombed, was absent all
\par last week, or why I missed so often the inimitable rags of Mack and Ed.
\par Then the father, who worked Colonel Wheeler's farm on shares, would
\par tell me how the crops needed the boys; and the thin, slovenly mother,
\par whose face was pretty when washed, assured me that Lugene must mind the
\par baby.  "But we'll start them again next week."  When the Lawrences
\par stopped, I knew that the doubts of the old folks about book-learning
\par had conquered again, and so, toiling up the hill, and getting as far
\par into the cabin as possible, I put Cicero "pro Archia Poeta" into the
\par simplest English with local applications, and usually convinced
\par them--for a week or so.
\par 
\par On Friday nights I often went home with some of the
\par children,--sometimes to Doc Burke's farm.  He was a great, loud, thin
\par Black, ever working, and trying to buy the seventy-five acres of hill
\par and dale where he lived; but people said that he would surely fail, and
\par the "white folks would get it all."  His wife was a magnificent Amazon,
\par with saffron face and shining hair, uncorseted and barefooted, and the
\par children were strong and beautiful.  They lived in a
\par one-and-a-half-room cabin in the hollow of the farm, near the spring.
\par The front room was full of great fat white beds, scrupulously neat; and
\par there were bad chromos on the walls, and a tired centre-table.  In the
\par tiny back kitchen I was often invited to "take out and help" myself to
\par fried chicken and wheat biscuit, "meat" and corn pone, string-beans and
\par berries.  At first I used to be a little alarmed at the approach of
\par bedtime in the one lone bedroom, but embarrassment was very deftly
\par avoided.  First, all the children nodded and slept, and were stowed
\par away in one great pile of goose feathers; next, the mother and the
\par father discreetly slipped away to the kitchen while I went to bed;
\par then, blowing out the dim light, they retired in the dark.  In the
\par morning all were up and away before I thought of awaking.  Across the
\par road, where fat Reuben lived, they all went outdoors while the teacher
\par retired, because they did not boast the luxury of a kitchen.
\par 
\par I liked to stay with the Dowells, for they had four rooms and plenty of
\par good country fare.  Uncle Bird had a small, rough farm, all woods and
\par hills, miles from the big road; but he was full of tales,--he preached
\par now and then,--and with his children, berries, horses, and wheat he was
\par happy and prosperous.  Often, to keep the peace, I must go where life
\par was less lovely; for instance, 'Tildy's mother was incorrigibly dirty,
\par Reuben's larder was limited seriously, and herds of untamed insects
\par wandered over the Eddingses' beds.  Best of all I loved to go to
\par Josie's, and sit on the porch, eating peaches, while the mother bustled
\par and talked: how Josie had bought the sewing-machine; how Josie worked
\par at service in winter, but that four dollars a month was "mighty little"
\par wages; how Josie longed to go away to school, but that it "looked like"
\par they never could get far enough ahead to let her; how the crops failed
\par and the well was yet unfinished; and, finally, how "mean" some of the
\par white folks were.
\par 
\par For two summers I lived in this little world; it was dull and humdrum.
\par The girls looked at the hill in wistful longing, and the boys fretted
\par and haunted Alexandria.  Alexandria was "town,"--a straggling, lazy
\par village of houses, churches, and shops, and an aristocracy of Toms,
\par Dicks, and Captains.  Cuddled on the hill to the north was the village
\par of the colored folks, who lived in three- or four-room unpainted
\par cottages, some neat and homelike, and some dirty.  The dwellings were
\par scattered rather aimlessly, but they centred about the twin temples of
\par the hamlet, the Methodist, and the Hard-Shell Baptist churches.  These,
\par in turn, leaned gingerly on a sad-colored schoolhouse.  Hither my
\par little world wended its crooked way on Sunday to meet other worlds, and
\par gossip, and wonder, and make the weekly sacrifice with frenzied priest
\par at the altar of the "old-time religion."  Then the soft melody and
\par mighty cadences of Negro song fluttered and thundered.
\par 
\par I have called my tiny community a world, and so its isolation made it;
\par and yet there was among us but a half-awakened common consciousness,
\par sprung from common joy and grief, at burial, birth, or wedding; from a
\par common hardship in poverty, poor land, and low wages; and, above all,
\par from the sight of the Veil that hung between us and Opportunity.  All
\par this caused us to think some thoughts together; but these, when ripe
\par for speech, were spoken in various languages.  Those whose eyes
\par twenty-five and more years before had seen "the glory of the coming of
\par the Lord," saw in every present hindrance or help a dark fatalism bound
\par to bring all things right in His own good time.  The mass of those to
\par whom slavery was a dim recollection of childhood found the world a
\par puzzling thing: it asked little of them, and they answered with little,
\par and yet it ridiculed their offering.  Such a paradox they could not
\par understand, and therefore sank into listless indifference, or
\par shiftlessness, or reckless bravado.  There were, however, some--such as
\par Josie, Jim, and Ben--to whom War, Hell, and Slavery were but childhood
\par tales, whose young appetites had been whetted to an edge by school and
\par story and half-awakened thought.  Ill could they be content, born
\par without and beyond the World.  And their weak wings beat against their
\par barriers,--barriers of caste, of youth, of life; at last, in dangerous
\par moments, against everything that opposed even a whim.
\par 
\par 
\par The ten years that follow youth, the years when first the realization
\par comes that life is leading somewhere,--these were the years that passed
\par after I left my little school.  When they were past, I came by chance
\par once more to the walls of Fisk University, to the halls of the chapel
\par of melody.  As I lingered there in the joy and pain of meeting old
\par school-friends, there swept over me a sudden longing to pass again
\par beyond the blue hill, and to see the homes and the school of other
\par days, and to learn how life had gone with my school-children; and I
\par went.
\par 
\par Josie was dead, and the gray-haired mother said simply, "We've had a
\par heap of trouble since you've been away."  I had feared for Jim.  With a
\par cultured parentage and a social caste to uphold him, he might have made
\par a venturesome merchant or a West Point cadet.  But here he was, angry
\par with life and reckless; and when Fanner Durham charged him with
\par stealing wheat, the old man had to ride fast to escape the stones which
\par the furious fool hurled after him.  They told Jim to run away; but he
\par would not run, and the constable came that afternoon.  It grieved
\par Josie, and great awkward John walked nine miles every day to see his
\par little brother through the bars of Lebanon jail.  At last the two came
\par back together in the dark night.  The mother cooked supper, and Josie
\par emptied her purse, and the boys stole away.  Josie grew thin and
\par silent, yet worked the more.  The hill became steep for the quiet old
\par father, and with the boys away there was little to do in the valley.
\par Josie helped them to sell the old farm, and they moved nearer town.
\par Brother Dennis, the carpenter, built a new house with six rooms; Josie
\par toiled a year in Nashville, and brought back ninety dollars to furnish
\par the house and change it to a home.
\par 
\par When the spring came, and the birds twittered, and the stream ran proud
\par and full, little sister Lizzie, bold and thoughtless, flushed with the
\par passion of youth, bestowed herself on the tempter, and brought home a
\par nameless child.  Josie shivered and worked on, with the vision of
\par schooldays all fled, with a face wan and tired,--worked until, on a
\par summer's day, some one married another; then Josie crept to her mother
\par like a hurt child, and slept--and sleeps.
\par 
\par I paused to scent the breeze as I entered the valley.  The Lawrences
\par have gone,--father and son forever,--and the other son lazily digs in
\par the earth to live.  A new young widow rents out their cabin to fat
\par Reuben.  Reuben is a Baptist preacher now, but I fear as lazy as ever,
\par though his cabin has three rooms; and little Ella has grown into a
\par bouncing woman, and is ploughing corn on the hot hillside.  There are
\par babies a-plenty, and one half-witted girl.  Across the valley is a
\par house I did not know before, and there I found, rocking one baby and
\par expecting another, one of my schoolgirls, a daughter of Uncle Bird
\par Dowell.  She looked somewhat worried with her new duties, but soon
\par bristled into pride over her neat cabin and the tale of her thrifty
\par husband, and the horse and cow, and the farm they were planning to buy.
\par 
\par My log schoolhouse was gone.  In its place stood Progress; and
\par Progress, I understand, is necessarily ugly.  The crazy foundation
\par stones still marked the former site of my poor little cabin, and not
\par far away, on six weary boulders, perched a jaunty board house, perhaps
\par twenty by thirty feet, with three windows and a door that locked.  Some
\par of the window-glass was broken, and part of an old iron stove lay
\par mournfully under the house.  I peeped through the window half
\par reverently, and found things that were more familiar.  The blackboard
\par had grown by about two feet, and the seats were still without backs.
\par The county owns the lot now, I hear, and every year there is a session
\par of school.  As I sat by the spring and looked on the Old and the New I
\par felt glad, very glad, and yet--
\par 
\par After two long drinks I started on.  There was the great double
\par log-house on the corner.  I remembered the broken, blighted family that
\par used to live there.  The strong, hard face of the mother, with its
\par wilderness of hair, rose before me.  She had driven her husband away,
\par and while I taught school a strange man lived there, big and jovial,
\par and people talked.  I felt sure that Ben and 'Tildy would come to
\par naught from such a home.  But this is an odd world; for Ben is a busy
\par farmer in Smith County, "doing well, too," they say, and he had cared
\par for little 'Tildy until last spring, when a lover married her.  A hard
\par life the lad had led, toiling for meat, and laughed at because he was
\par homely and crooked.  There was Sam Carlon, an impudent old skinflint,
\par who had definite notions about "niggers," and hired Ben a summer and
\par would not pay him.  Then the hungry boy gathered his sacks together,
\par and in broad daylight went into Carlon's corn; and when the hard-fisted
\par farmer set upon him, the angry boy flew at him like a beast.  Doc Burke
\par saved a murder and a lynching that day.
\par 
\par The story reminded me again of the Burkes, and an impatience seized me
\par to know who won in the battle, Doc or the seventy-five acres.  For it
\par is a hard thing to make a farm out of nothing, even in fifteen years.
\par So I hurried on, thinking of the Burkes.  They used to have a certain
\par magnificent barbarism about them that I liked.  They were never vulgar,
\par never immoral, but rather rough and primitive, with an
\par unconventionality that spent itself in loud guffaws, slaps on the back,
\par and naps in the corner.  I hurried by the cottage of the misborn Neill
\par boys.  It was empty, and they were grown into fat, lazy farm-hands.  I
\par saw the home of the Hickmans, but Albert, with his stooping shoulders,
\par had passed from the world.  Then I came to the Burkes' gate and peered
\par through; the enclosure looked rough and untrimmed, and yet there were
\par the same fences around the old farm save to the left, where lay
\par twenty-five other acres.  And lo! the cabin in the hollow had climbed
\par the hill and swollen to a half-finished six-room cottage.
\par 
\par The Burkes held a hundred acres, but they were still in debt.  Indeed,
\par the gaunt father who toiled night and day would scarcely be happy out
\par of debt, being so used to it.  Some day he must stop, for his massive
\par frame is showing decline.  The mother wore shoes, but the lion-like
\par physique of other days was broken.  The children had grown up.  Rob,
\par the image of his father, was loud and rough with laughter.  Birdie, my
\par school baby of six, had grown to a picture of maiden beauty, tall and
\par tawny.  "Edgar is gone," said the mother, with head half bowed,--"gone
\par to work in Nashville; he and his father couldn't agree."
\par 
\par Little Doc, the boy born since the time of my school, took me horseback
\par down the creek next morning toward Farmer Dowell's.  The road and the
\par stream were battling for mastery, and the stream had the better of it.
\par We splashed and waded, and the merry boy, perched behind me, chattered
\par and laughed.  He showed me where Simon Thompson had bought a bit of
\par ground and a home; but his daughter Lana, a plump, brown, slow girl,
\par was not there.  She had married a man and a farm twenty miles away.  We
\par wound on down the stream till we came to a gate that I did not
\par recognize, but the boy insisted that it was "Uncle Bird's."  The farm
\par was fat with the growing crop.  In that little valley was a strange
\par stillness as I rode up; for death and marriage had stolen youth and
\par left age and childhood there.  We sat and talked that night after the
\par chores were done.  Uncle Bird was grayer, and his eyes did not see so
\par well, but he was still jovial.  We talked of the acres bought,--one
\par hundred and twenty-five,--of the new guest-chamber added, of Martha's
\par marrying.  Then we talked of death: Fanny and Fred were gone; a shadow
\par hung over the other daughter, and when it lifted she was to go to
\par Nashville to school.  At last we spoke of the neighbors, and as night
\par fell, Uncle Bird told me how, on a night like that, 'Thenie came
\par wandering back to her home over yonder, to escape the blows of her
\par husband.  And next morning she died in the home that her little
\par bow-legged brother, working and saving, had bought for their widowed
\par mother.
\par 
\par My journey was done, and behind me lay hill and dale, and Life and
\par Death.  How shall man measure Progress there where the dark-faced Josie
\par lies?  How many heartfuls of sorrow shall balance a bushel of wheat?
\par How hard a thing is life to the lowly, and yet how human and real!  And
\par all this life and love and strife and failure,--is it the twilight of
\par nightfall or the flush of some faint-dawning day?
\par 
\par Thus sadly musing, I rode to Nashville in the Jim Crow car.
\par 
