\par V
\par 
\par Of the Wings of Atalanta
\par 
\par   O black boy of Atlanta!
\par     But half was spoken;
\par   The slave's chains and the master's
\par     Alike are broken;
\par   The one curse of the races
\par     Held both in tether;
\par   They are rising--all are rising--
\par     The black and white together.
\par 
\par   WHITTIER.
\par 
\par 
\par South of the North, yet north of the South, lies the City of a Hundred
\par Hills, peering out from the shadows of the past into the promise of the
\par future.  I have seen her in the morning, when the first flush of day
\par had half-roused her; she lay gray and still on the crimson soil of
\par Georgia; then the blue smoke began to curl from her chimneys, the
\par tinkle of bell and scream of whistle broke the silence, the rattle and
\par roar of busy life slowly gathered and swelled, until the seething whirl
\par of the city seemed a strange thing in a sleepy land.
\par 
\par Once, they say, even Atlanta slept dull and drowsy at the foot-hills of
\par the Alleghanies, until the iron baptism of war awakened her with its
\par sullen waters, aroused and maddened her, and left her listening to the
\par sea.  And the sea cried to the hills and the hills answered the sea,
\par till the city rose like a widow and cast away her weeds, and toiled for
\par her daily bread; toiled steadily, toiled cunningly,--perhaps with some
\par bitterness, with a touch, of reclame,--and yet with real earnestness,
\par and real sweat.
\par 
\par It is a hard thing to live haunted by the ghost of an untrue dream; to
\par see the wide vision of empire fade into real ashes and dirt; to feel
\par the pang of the conquered, and yet know that with all the Bad that fell
\par on one black day, something was vanquished that deserved to live,
\par something killed that in justice had not dared to die; to know that
\par with the Right that triumphed, triumphed something of Wrong, something
\par sordid and mean, something less than the broadest and best.  All this
\par is bitter hard; and many a man and city and people have found in it
\par excuse for sulking, and brooding, and listless waiting.
\par 
\par Such are not men of the sturdier make; they of Atlanta turned
\par resolutely toward the future; and that future held aloft vistas of
\par purple and gold:--Atlanta, Queen of the cotton kingdom; Atlanta,
\par Gateway to the Land of the Sun; Atlanta, the new Lachesis, spinner of
\par web and woof for the world.  So the city crowned her hundred hills with
\par factories, and stored her shops with cunning handiwork, and stretched
\par long iron ways to greet the busy Mercury in his coming.  And the Nation
\par talked of her striving.
\par 
\par 
\par Perhaps Atlanta was not christened for the winged maiden of dull
\par Boeotia; you know the tale,--how swarthy Atalanta, tall and wild, would
\par marry only him who out-raced her; and how the wily Hippomenes laid
\par three apples of gold in the way.  She fled like a shadow, paused,
\par startled over the first apple, but even as he stretched his hand, fled
\par again; hovered over the second, then, slipping from his hot grasp, flew
\par over river, vale, and hill; but as she lingered over the third, his
\par arms fell round her, and looking on each other, the blazing passion of
\par their love profaned the sanctuary of Love, and they were cursed.  If
\par Atlanta be not named for Atalanta, she ought to have been.
\par 
\par Atalanta is not the first or the last maiden whom greed of gold has led
\par to defile the temple of Love; and not maids alone, but men in the race
\par of life, sink from the high and generous ideals of youth to the
\par gambler's code of the Bourse; and in all our Nation's striving is not
\par the Gospel of Work befouled by the Gospel of Pay?  So common is this
\par that one-half think it normal; so unquestioned, that we almost fear to
\par question if the end of racing is not gold, if the aim of man is not
\par rightly to be rich.  And if this is the fault of America, how dire a
\par danger lies before a new land and a new city, lest Atlanta, stooping
\par for mere gold, shall find that gold accursed!
\par 
\par It was no maiden's idle whim that started this hard racing; a fearful
\par wilderness lay about the feet of that city after the War,--feudalism,
\par poverty, the rise of the Third Estate, serfdom, the re-birth of Law and
\par Order, and above and between all, the Veil of Race.  How heavy a
\par journey for weary feet!  what wings must Atalanta have to flit over all
\par this hollow and hill, through sour wood and sullen water, and by the
\par red waste of sun-baked clay!  How fleet must Atalanta be if she will
\par not be tempted by gold to profane the Sanctuary!
\par 
\par The Sanctuary of our fathers has, to be sure, few Gods,--some sneer,
\par "all too few."  There is the thrifty Mercury of New England, Pluto of
\par the North, and Ceres of the West; and there, too, is the half-forgotten
\par Apollo of the South, under whose aegis the maiden ran,--and as she ran
\par she forgot him, even as there in Boeotia Venus was forgot.  She forgot
\par the old ideal of the Southern gentleman,--that new-world heir of the
\par grace and courtliness of patrician, knight, and noble; forgot his honor
\par with his foibles, his kindliness with his carelessness, and stooped to
\par apples of gold,--to men busier and sharper, thriftier and more
\par unscrupulous.  Golden apples are beautiful--I remember the lawless days
\par of boyhood, when orchards in crimson and gold tempted me over fence and
\par field--and, too, the merchant who has dethroned the planter is no
\par despicable parvenu.  Work and wealth are the mighty levers to lift this
\par old new land; thrift and toil and saving are the highways to new hopes
\par and new possibilities; and yet the warning is needed lest the wily
\par Hippomenes tempt Atalanta to thinking that golden apples are the goal
\par of racing, and not mere incidents by the way.
\par 
\par Atlanta must not lead the South to dream of material prosperity as the
\par touchstone of all success; already the fatal might of this idea is
\par beginning to spread; it is replacing the finer type of Southerner with
\par vulgar money-getters; it is burying the sweeter beauties of Southern
\par life beneath pretence and ostentation.  For every social ill the
\par panacea of Wealth has been urged,--wealth to overthrow the remains of
\par the slave feudalism; wealth to raise the "cracker" Third Estate; wealth
\par to employ the black serfs, and the prospect of wealth to keep them
\par working; wealth as the end and aim of politics, and as the legal tender
\par for law and order; and, finally, instead of Truth, Beauty, and
\par Goodness, wealth as the ideal of the Public School.
\par 
\par Not only is this true in the world which Atlanta typifies, but it is
\par threatening to be true of a world beneath and beyond that world,--the
\par Black World beyond the Veil.  Today it makes little difference to
\par Atlanta, to the South, what the Negro thinks or dreams or wills.  In
\par the soul-life of the land he is to-day, and naturally will long remain,
\par unthought of, half forgotten; and yet when he does come to think and
\par will and do for himself,--and let no man dream that day will never
\par come,--then the part he plays will not be one of sudden learning, but
\par words and thoughts he has been taught to lisp in his race-childhood.
\par To-day the ferment of his striving toward self-realization is to the
\par strife of the white world like a wheel within a wheel: beyond the Veil
\par are smaller but like problems of ideals, of leaders and the led, of
\par serfdom, of poverty, of order and subordination, and, through all, the
\par Veil of Race.  Few know of these problems, few who know notice them;
\par and yet there they are, awaiting student, artist, and seer,--a field
\par for somebody sometime to discover.  Hither has the temptation of
\par Hippomenes penetrated; already in this smaller world, which now
\par indirectly and anon directly must influence the larger for good or ill,
\par the habit is forming of interpreting the world in dollars.  The old
\par leaders of Negro opinion, in the little groups where there is a Negro
\par social consciousness, are being replaced by new; neither the black
\par preacher nor the black teacher leads as he did two decades ago.  Into
\par their places are pushing the farmers and gardeners, the well-paid
\par porters and artisans, the business-men,--all those with property and
\par money.  And with all this change, so curiously parallel to that of the
\par Other-world, goes too the same inevitable change in ideals.  The South
\par laments to-day the slow, steady disappearance of a certain type of
\par Negro,--the faithful, courteous slave of other days, with his
\par incorruptible honesty and dignified humility.  He is passing away just
\par as surely as the old type of Southern gentleman is passing, and from
\par not dissimilar causes,--the sudden transformation of a fair far-off
\par ideal of Freedom into the hard reality of bread-winning and the
\par consequent deification of Bread.
\par 
\par In the Black World, the Preacher and Teacher embodied once the ideals
\par of this people--the strife for another and a juster world, the vague
\par dream of righteousness, the mystery of knowing; but to-day the danger
\par is that these ideals, with their simple beauty and weird inspiration,
\par will suddenly sink to a question of cash and a lust for gold.  Here
\par stands this black young Atalanta, girding herself for the race that
\par must be run; and if her eyes be still toward the hills and sky as in
\par the days of old, then we may look for noble running; but what if some
\par ruthless or wily or even thoughtless Hippomenes lay golden apples
\par before her?  What if the Negro people be wooed from a strife for
\par righteousness, from a love of knowing, to regard dollars as the be-all
\par and end-all of life?  What if to the Mammonism of America be added the
\par rising Mammonism of the re-born South, and the Mammonism of this South
\par be reinforced by the budding Mammonism of its half-wakened black
\par millions?  Whither, then, is the new-world quest of Goodness and Beauty
\par and Truth gone glimmering?  Must this, and that fair flower of Freedom
\par which, despite the jeers of latter-day striplings, sprung from our
\par fathers' blood, must that too degenerate into a dusty quest of
\par gold,--into lawless lust with Hippomenes?
\par 
\par 
\par The hundred hills of Atlanta are not all crowned with factories.  On
\par one, toward the west, the setting sun throws three buildings in bold
\par relief against the sky.  The beauty of the group lies in its simple
\par unity:--a broad lawn of green rising from the red street and mingled
\par roses and peaches; north and south, two plain and stately halls; and in
\par the midst, half hidden in ivy, a larger building, boldly graceful,
\par sparingly decorated, and with one low spire.  It is a restful group,
\par --one never looks for more; it is all here, all intelligible.  There I
\par live, and there I hear from day to day the low hum of restful life.  In
\par winter's twilight, when the red sun glows, I can see the dark figures
\par pass between the halls to the music of the night-bell.  In the morning,
\par when the sun is golden, the clang of the day-bell brings the hurry and
\par laughter of three hundred young hearts from hall and street, and from
\par the busy city below,--children all dark and heavy-haired,--to join
\par their clear young voices in the music of the morning sacrifice.  In a
\par half-dozen class-rooms they gather then,--here to follow the love-song
\par of Dido, here to listen to the tale of Troy divine; there to wander
\par among the stars, there to wander among men and nations,--and elsewhere
\par other well-worn ways of knowing this queer world.  Nothing new, no
\par time-saving devices,--simply old time-glorified methods of delving for
\par Truth, and searching out the hidden beauties of life, and learning the
\par good of living.  The riddle of existence is the college curriculum that
\par was laid before the Pharaohs, that was taught in the groves by Plato,
\par that formed the trivium and quadrivium, and is to-day laid before the
\par freedmen's sons by Atlanta University.  And this course of study will
\par not change; its methods will grow more deft and effectual, its content
\par richer by toil of scholar and sight of seer; but the true college will
\par ever have one goal,--not to earn meat, but to know the end and aim of
\par that life which meat nourishes.
\par 
\par The vision of life that rises before these dark eyes has in it nothing
\par mean or selfish.  Not at Oxford or at Leipsic, not at Yale or Columbia,
\par is there an air of higher resolve or more unfettered striving; the
\par determination to realize for men, both black and white, the broadest
\par possibilities of life, to seek the better and the best, to spread with
\par their own hands the Gospel of Sacrifice,--all this is the burden of
\par their talk and dream.  Here, amid a wide desert of caste and
\par proscription, amid the heart-hurting slights and jars and vagaries of a
\par deep race-dislike, lies this green oasis, where hot anger cools, and
\par the bitterness of disappointment is sweetened by the springs and
\par breezes of Parnassus; and here men may lie and listen, and learn of a
\par future fuller than the past, and hear the voice of Time:
\par 
\par   "Entbehren sollst du, sollst entbehren."
\par 
\par 
\par They made their mistakes, those who planted Fisk and Howard and Atlanta
\par before the smoke of battle had lifted; they made their mistakes, but
\par those mistakes were not the things at which we lately laughed somewhat
\par uproariously.  They were right when they sought to found a new
\par educational system upon the University: where, forsooth, shall we
\par ground knowledge save on the broadest and deepest knowledge?  The roots
\par of the tree, rather than the leaves, are the sources of its life; and
\par from the dawn of history, from Academus to Cambridge, the culture of
\par the University has been the broad foundation-stone on which is built
\par the kindergarten's A B C.
\par 
\par But these builders did make a mistake in minimizing the gravity of the
\par problem before them; in thinking it a matter of years and decades; in
\par therefore building quickly and laying their foundation carelessly, and
\par lowering the standard of knowing, until they had scattered haphazard
\par through the South some dozen poorly equipped high schools and miscalled
\par them universities.  They forgot, too, just as their successors are
\par forgetting, the rule of inequality:--that of the million black youth,
\par some were fitted to know and some to dig; that some had the talent and
\par capacity of university men, and some the talent and capacity of
\par blacksmiths; and that true training meant neither that all should be
\par college men nor all artisans, but that the one should be made a
\par missionary of culture to an untaught people, and the other a free
\par workman among serfs.  And to seek to make the blacksmith a scholar is
\par almost as silly as the more modern scheme of making the scholar a
\par blacksmith; almost, but not quite.
\par 
\par 
\par The function of the university is not simply to teach bread-winning, or
\par to furnish teachers for the public schools or to be a centre of polite
\par society; it is, above all, to be the organ of that fine adjustment
\par between real life and the growing knowledge of life, an adjustment
\par which forms the secret of civilization.  Such an institution the South
\par of to-day sorely needs.  She has religion, earnest, bigoted:--religion
\par that on both sides the Veil often omits the sixth, seventh, and eighth
\par commandments, but substitutes a dozen supplementary ones.  She has, as
\par Atlanta shows, growing thrift and love of toil; but she lacks that
\par broad knowledge of what the world knows and knew of human living and
\par doing, which she may apply to the thousand problems of real life to-day
\par confronting her.  The need of the South is knowledge and culture,--not
\par in dainty limited quantity, as before the war, but in broad busy
\par abundance in the world of work; and until she has this, not all the
\par Apples of Hesperides, be they golden and bejewelled, can save her from
\par the curse of the Boeotian lovers.
\par 
\par The Wings of Atalanta are the coming universities of the South.  They
\par alone can bear the maiden past the temptation of golden fruit.  They
\par will not guide her flying feet away from the cotton and gold; for--ah,
\par thoughtful Hippomenes!--do not the apples lie in the very Way of Life?
\par But they will guide her over and beyond them, and leave her kneeling in
\par the Sanctuary of Truth and Freedom and broad Humanity, virgin and
\par undefiled.  Sadly did the Old South err in human education, despising
\par the education of the masses, and niggardly in the support of colleges.
\par Her ancient university foundations dwindled and withered under the foul
\par breath of slavery; and even since the war they have fought a failing
\par fight for life in the tainted air of social unrest and commercial
\par selfishness, stunted by the death of criticism, and starving for lack
\par of broadly cultured men.  And if this is the white South's need and
\par danger, how much heavier the danger and need of the freedmen's sons!
\par how pressing here the need of broad ideals and true culture, the
\par conservation of soul from sordid aims and petty passions!  Let us build
\par the Southern university--William and Mary, Trinity, Georgia, Texas,
\par Tulane, Vanderbilt, and the others--fit to live; let us build, too, the
\par Negro universities:--Fisk, whose foundation was ever broad; Howard, at
\par the heart of the Nation; Atlanta at Atlanta, whose ideal of scholarship
\par has been held above the temptation of numbers.  Why not here, and
\par perhaps elsewhere, plant deeply and for all time centres of learning
\par and living, colleges that yearly would send into the life of the South
\par a few white men and a few black men of broad culture, catholic
\par tolerance, and trained ability, joining their hands to other hands, and
\par giving to this squabble of the Races a decent and dignified peace?
\par 
\par Patience, Humility, Manners, and Taste, common schools and
\par kindergartens, industrial and technical schools, literature and
\par tolerance,--all these spring from knowledge and culture, the children
\par of the university.  So must men and nations build, not otherwise, not
\par upside down.
\par 
\par Teach workers to work,--a wise saying; wise when applied to German boys
\par and American girls; wiser when said of Negro boys, for they have less
\par knowledge of working and none to teach them.  Teach thinkers to
\par think,--a needed knowledge in a day of loose and careless logic; and
\par they whose lot is gravest must have the carefulest training to think
\par aright.  If these things are so, how foolish to ask what is the best
\par education for one or seven or sixty million souls! shall we teach them
\par trades, or train them in liberal arts?  Neither and both: teach the
\par workers to work and the thinkers to think; make carpenters of
\par carpenters, and philosophers of philosophers, and fops of fools.  Nor
\par can we pause here.  We are training not isolated men but a living group
\par of men,--nay, a group within a group.  And the final product of our
\par training must be neither a psychologist nor a brickmason, but a man.
\par And to make men, we must have ideals, broad, pure, and inspiring ends
\par of living,--not sordid money-getting, not apples of gold.  The worker
\par must work for the glory of his handiwork, not simply for pay; the
\par thinker must think for truth, not for fame.  And all this is gained
\par only by human strife and longing; by ceaseless training and education;
\par by founding Right on righteousness and Truth on the unhampered search
\par for Truth; by founding the common school on the university, and the
\par industrial school on the common school; and weaving thus a system, not
\par a distortion, and bringing a birth, not an abortion.
\par 
\par 
\par When night falls on the City of a Hundred Hills, a wind gathers itself
\par from the seas and comes murmuring westward.  And at its bidding, the
\par smoke of the drowsy factories sweeps down upon the mighty city and
\par covers it like a pall, while yonder at the University the stars twinkle
\par above Stone Hall.  And they say that yon gray mist is the tunic of
\par Atalanta pausing over her golden apples.  Fly, my maiden, fly, for
\par yonder comes Hippomenes!
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par VI
\par 
\par Of the Training of Black Men
\par 
\par   Why, if the Soul can fling the Dust aside,
\par   And naked on the Air of Heaven ride,
\par     Were't not a Shame--were't not a Shame for him
\par   In this clay carcase crippled to abide?
\par 
\par   OMAR KHAYYAM (FITZGERALD).
\par 
\par 
\par From the shimmering swirl of waters where many, many thoughts ago the
\par slave-ship first saw the square tower of Jamestown, have flowed down to
\par our day three streams of thinking: one swollen from the larger world
\par here and overseas, saying, the multiplying of human wants in
\par culture-lands calls for the world-wide cooperation of men in satisfying
\par them.  Hence arises a new human unity, pulling the ends of earth
\par nearer, and all men, black, yellow, and white.  The larger humanity
\par strives to feel in this contact of living Nations and sleeping hordes a
\par thrill of new life in the world, crying, "If the contact of Life and
\par Sleep be Death, shame on such Life."  To be sure, behind this thought
\par lurks the afterthought of force and dominion,--the making of brown men
\par to delve when the temptation of beads and red calico cloys.
\par 
\par The second thought streaming from the death-ship and the curving river
\par is the thought of the older South,--the sincere and passionate belief
\par that somewhere between men and cattle, God created a tertium quid, and
\par called it a Negro,--a clownish, simple creature, at times even lovable
\par within its limitations, but straitly foreordained to walk within the
\par Veil.  To be sure, behind the thought lurks the afterthought,--some of
\par them with favoring chance might become men, but in sheer self-defence
\par we dare not let them, and we build about them walls so high, and hang
\par between them and the light a veil so thick, that they shall not even
\par think of breaking through.
\par 
\par And last of all there trickles down that third and darker thought,--the
\par thought of the things themselves, the confused, half-conscious mutter
\par of men who are black and whitened, crying "Liberty, Freedom,
\par Opportunity--vouchsafe to us, O boastful World, the chance of living
\par men!"  To be sure, behind the thought lurks the afterthought,--suppose,
\par after all, the World is right and we are less than men?  Suppose this
\par mad impulse within is all wrong, some mock mirage from the untrue?
\par 
\par So here we stand among thoughts of human unity, even through conquest
\par and slavery; the inferiority of black men, even if forced by fraud; a
\par shriek in the night for the freedom of men who themselves are not yet
\par sure of their right to demand it.  This is the tangle of thought and
\par afterthought wherein we are called to solve the problem of training men
\par for life.
\par 
\par Behind all its curiousness, so attractive alike to sage and dilettante,
\par lie its dim dangers, throwing across us shadows at once grotesque and
\par awful.  Plain it is to us that what the world seeks through desert and
\par wild we have within our threshold,--a stalwart laboring force, suited
\par to the semi-tropics; if, deaf to the voice of the Zeitgeist, we refuse
\par to use and develop these men, we risk poverty and loss.  If, on the
\par other hand, seized by the brutal afterthought, we debauch the race thus
\par caught in our talons, selfishly sucking their blood and brains in the
\par future as in the past, what shall save us from national decadence?
\par Only that saner selfishness, which Education teaches, can find the
\par rights of all in the whirl of work.
\par 
\par Again, we may decry the color-prejudice of the South, yet it remains a
\par heavy fact.  Such curious kinks of the human mind exist and must be
\par reckoned with soberly.  They cannot be laughed away, nor always
\par successfully stormed at, nor easily abolished by act of legislature.
\par And yet they must not be encouraged by being let alone.  They must be
\par recognized as facts, but unpleasant facts; things that stand in the way
\par of civilization and religion and common decency.  They can be met in
\par but one way,--by the breadth and broadening of human reason, by
\par catholicity of taste and culture.  And so, too, the native ambition and
\par aspiration of men, even though they be black, backward, and ungraceful,
\par must not lightly be dealt with.  To stimulate wildly weak and untrained
\par minds is to play with mighty fires; to flout their striving idly is to
\par welcome a harvest of brutish crime and shameless lethargy in our very
\par laps.  The guiding of thought and the deft coordination of deed is at
\par once the path of honor and humanity.
\par 
\par And so, in this great question of reconciling three vast and partially
\par contradictory streams of thought, the one panacea of Education leaps to
\par the lips of all:--such human training as will best use the labor of all
\par men without enslaving or brutalizing; such training as will give us
\par poise to encourage the prejudices that bulwark society, and to stamp
\par out those that in sheer barbarity deafen us to the wail of prisoned
\par souls within the Veil, and the mounting fury of shackled men.
\par 
\par But when we have vaguely said that Education will set this tangle
\par straight, what have we uttered but a truism?  Training for life teaches
\par living; but what training for the profitable living together of black
\par men and white?  A hundred and fifty years ago our task would have
\par seemed easier.  Then Dr. Johnson blandly assured us that education was
\par needful solely for the embellishments of life, and was useless for
\par ordinary vermin.  To-day we have climbed to heights where we would open
\par at least the outer courts of knowledge to all, display its treasures to
\par many, and select the few to whom its mystery of Truth is revealed, not
\par wholly by birth or the accidents of the stock market, but at least in
\par part according to deftness and aim, talent and character.  This
\par programme, however, we are sorely puzzled in carrying out through that
\par part of the land where the blight of slavery fell hardest, and where we
\par are dealing with two backward peoples.  To make here in human education
\par that ever necessary combination of the permanent and the contingent--of
\par the ideal and the practical in workable equilibrium--has been there, as
\par it ever must be in every age and place, a matter of infinite experiment
\par and frequent mistakes.
\par 
\par In rough approximation we may point out four varying decades of work in
\par Southern education since the Civil War.  From the close of the war
\par until 1876, was the period of uncertain groping and temporary relief.
\par There were army schools, mission schools, and schools of the Freedmen's
\par Bureau in chaotic disarrangement seeking system and co-operation.  Then
\par followed ten years of constructive definite effort toward the building
\par of complete school systems in the South.  Normal schools and colleges
\par were founded for the freedmen, and teachers trained there to man the
\par public schools.  There was the inevitable tendency of war to
\par underestimate the prejudices of the master and the ignorance of the
\par slave, and all seemed clear sailing out of the wreckage of the storm.
\par Meantime, starting in this decade yet especially developing from 1885
\par to 1895, began the industrial revolution of the South.  The land saw
\par glimpses of a new destiny and the stirring of new ideals.  The
\par educational system striving to complete itself saw new obstacles and a
\par field of work ever broader and deeper.  The Negro colleges, hurriedly
\par founded, were inadequately equipped, illogically distributed, and of
\par varying efficiency and grade; the normal and high schools were doing
\par little more than common-school work, and the common schools were
\par training but a third of the children who ought to be in them, and
\par training these too often poorly.  At the same time the white South, by
\par reason of its sudden conversion from the slavery ideal, by so much the
\par more became set and strengthened in its racial prejudice, and
\par crystallized it into harsh law and harsher custom; while the marvellous
\par pushing forward of the poor white daily threatened to take even bread
\par and butter from the mouths of the heavily handicapped sons of the
\par freedmen.  In the midst, then, of the larger problem of Negro education
\par sprang up the more practical question of work, the inevitable economic
\par quandary that faces a people in the transition from slavery to freedom,
\par and especially those who make that change amid hate and prejudice,
\par lawlessness and ruthless competition.
\par 
\par The industrial school springing to notice in this decade, but coming to
\par full recognition in the decade beginning with 1895, was the proffered
\par answer to this combined educational and economic crisis, and an answer
\par of singular wisdom and timeliness.  From the very first in nearly all
\par the schools some attention had been given to training in handiwork, but
\par now was this training first raised to a dignity that brought it in
\par direct touch with the South's magnificent industrial development, and
\par given an emphasis which reminded black folk that before the Temple of
\par Knowledge swing the Gates of Toil.
\par 
\par Yet after all they are but gates, and when turning our eyes from the
\par temporary and the contingent in the Negro problem to the broader
\par question of the permanent uplifting and civilization of black men in
\par America, we have a right to inquire, as this enthusiasm for material
\par advancement mounts to its height, if after all the industrial school is
\par the final and sufficient answer in the training of the Negro race; and
\par to ask gently, but in all sincerity, the ever-recurring query of the
\par ages, Is not life more than meat, and the body more than raiment?  And
\par men ask this to-day all the more eagerly because of sinister signs in
\par recent educational movements.  The tendency is here, born of slavery
\par and quickened to renewed life by the crazy imperialism of the day, to
\par regard human beings as among the material resources of a land to be
\par trained with an eye single to future dividends.  Race-prejudices, which
\par keep brown and black men in their "places," we are coming to regard as
\par useful allies with such a theory, no matter how much they may dull the
\par ambition and sicken the hearts of struggling human beings.  And above
\par all, we daily hear that an education that encourages aspiration, that
\par sets the loftiest of ideals and seeks as an end culture and character
\par rather than bread-winning, is the privilege of white men and the danger
\par and delusion of black.
\par 
\par Especially has criticism been directed against the former educational
\par efforts to aid the Negro.  In the four periods I have mentioned, we
\par find first, boundless, planless enthusiasm and sacrifice; then the
\par preparation of teachers for a vast public-school system; then the
\par launching and expansion of that school system amid increasing
\par difficulties; and finally the training of workmen for the new and
\par growing industries.  This development has been sharply ridiculed as a
\par logical anomaly and flat reversal of nature.  Soothly we have been told
\par that first industrial and manual training should have taught the Negro
\par to work, then simple schools should have taught him to read and write,
\par and finally, after years, high and normal schools could have completed
\par the system, as intelligence and wealth demanded.
\par 
\par That a system logically so complete was historically impossible, it
\par needs but a little thought to prove.  Progress in human affairs is more
\par often a pull than a push, a surging forward of the exceptional man, and
\par the lifting of his duller brethren slowly and painfully to his
\par vantage-ground.  Thus it was no accident that gave birth to
\par universities centuries before the common schools, that made fair
\par Harvard the first flower of our wilderness.  So in the South: the mass
\par of the freedmen at the end of the war lacked the intelligence so
\par necessary to modern workingmen.  They must first have the common school
\par to teach them to read, write, and cipher; and they must have higher
\par schools to teach teachers for the common schools.  The white teachers
\par who flocked South went to establish such a common-school system.  Few
\par held the idea of founding colleges; most of them at first would have
\par laughed at the idea.  But they faced, as all men since them have faced,
\par that central paradox of the South,--the social separation of the races.
\par At that time it was the sudden volcanic rupture of nearly all relations
\par between black and white, in work and government and family life.  Since
\par then a new adjustment of relations in economic and political affairs
\par has grown up,--an adjustment subtle and difficult to grasp, yet
\par singularly ingenious, which leaves still that frightful chasm at the
\par color-line across which men pass at their peril.  Thus, then and now,
\par there stand in the South two separate worlds; and separate not simply
\par in the higher realms of social intercourse, but also in church and
\par school, on railway and street-car, in hotels and theatres, in streets
\par and city sections, in books and newspapers, in asylums and jails, in
\par hospitals and graveyards.  There is still enough of contact for large
\par economic and group cooperation, but the separation is so thorough and
\par deep that it absolutely precludes for the present between the races
\par anything like that sympathetic and effective group-training and
\par leadership of the one by the other, such as the American Negro and all
\par backward peoples must have for effectual progress.
\par 
\par This the missionaries of '68 soon saw; and if effective industrial and
\par trade schools were impracticable before the establishment of a
\par common-school system, just as certainly no adequate common schools
\par could be founded until there were teachers to teach them.  Southern
\par whites would not teach them; Northern whites in sufficient numbers
\par could not be had.  If the Negro was to learn, he must teach himself,
\par and the most effective help that could be given him was the
\par establishment of schools to train Negro teachers.  This conclusion was
\par slowly but surely reached by every student of the situation until
\par simultaneously, in widely separated regions, without consultation or
\par systematic plan, there arose a series of institutions designed to
\par furnish teachers for the untaught.  Above the sneers of critics at the
\par obvious defects of this procedure must ever stand its one crushing
\par rejoinder: in a single generation they put thirty thousand black
\par teachers in the South; they wiped out the illiteracy of the majority of
\par the black people of the land, and they made Tuskegee possible.
\par 
\par Such higher training-schools tended naturally to deepen broader
\par development: at first they were common and grammar schools, then some
\par became high schools.  And finally, by 1900, some thirty-four had one
\par year or more of studies of college grade.  This development was reached
\par with different degrees of speed in different institutions: Hampton is
\par still a high school, while Fisk University started her college in 1871,
\par and Spelman Seminary about 1896.  In all cases the aim was
\par identical,--to maintain the standards of the lower training by giving
\par teachers and leaders the best practicable training; and above all, to
\par furnish the black world with adequate standards of human culture and
\par lofty ideals of life.  It was not enough that the teachers of teachers
\par should be trained in technical normal methods; they must also, so far
\par as possible, be broad-minded, cultured men and women, to scatter
\par civilization among a people whose ignorance was not simply of letters,
\par but of life itself.
\par 
\par It can thus be seen that the work of education in the South began with
\par higher institutions of training, which threw off as their foliage
\par common schools, and later industrial schools, and at the same time
\par strove to shoot their roots ever deeper toward college and university
\par training.  That this was an inevitable and necessary development,
\par sooner or later, goes without saying; but there has been, and still is,
\par a question in many minds if the natural growth was not forced, and if
\par the higher training was not either overdone or done with cheap and
\par unsound methods.  Among white Southerners this feeling is widespread
\par and positive.  A prominent Southern journal voiced this in a recent
\par editorial.
\par 
\par "The experiment that has been made to give the colored students
\par classical training has not been satisfactory.  Even though many were
\par able to pursue the course, most of them did so in a parrot-like way,
\par learning what was taught, but not seeming to appropriate the truth and
\par import of their instruction, and graduating without sensible aim or
\par valuable occupation for their future.  The whole scheme has proved a
\par waste of time, efforts, and the money of the state."
\par 
\par While most fair-minded men would recognize this as extreme and
\par overdrawn, still without doubt many are asking, Are there a sufficient
\par number of Negroes ready for college training to warrant the
\par undertaking?  Are not too many students prematurely forced into this
\par work?  Does it not have the effect of dissatisfying the young Negro
\par with his environment?  And do these graduates succeed in real life?
\par Such natural questions cannot be evaded, nor on the other hand must a
\par Nation naturally skeptical as to Negro ability assume an unfavorable
\par answer without careful inquiry and patient openness to conviction.  We
\par must not forget that most Americans answer all queries regarding the
\par Negro a priori, and that the least that human courtesy can do is to
\par listen to evidence.
\par 
\par The advocates of the higher education of the Negro would be the last to
\par deny the incompleteness and glaring defects of the present system: too
\par many institutions have attempted to do college work, the work in some
\par cases has not been thoroughly done, and quantity rather than quality
\par has sometimes been sought.  But all this can be said of higher
\par education throughout the land; it is the almost inevitable incident of
\par educational growth, and leaves the deeper question of the legitimate
\par demand for the higher training of Negroes untouched.  And this latter
\par question can be settled in but one way,--by a first-hand study of the
\par facts.  If we leave out of view all institutions which have not
\par actually graduated students from a course higher than that of a New
\par England high school, even though they be called colleges; if then we
\par take the thirty-four remaining institutions, we may clear up many
\par misapprehensions by asking searchingly, What kind of institutions are
\par they? what do they teach? and what sort of men do they graduate?
\par 
\par And first we may say that this type of college, including Atlanta,
\par Fisk, and Howard, Wilberforce and Claflin, Shaw, and the rest, is
\par peculiar, almost unique.  Through the shining trees that whisper before
\par me as I write, I catch glimpses of a boulder of New England granite,
\par covering a grave, which graduates of Atlanta University have placed
\par there,--
\par 
\par 
\par    "GRATEFUL MEMORY OF THEIR FORMER TEACHER
\par    AND FRIEND AND OF THE UNSELFISH LIFE HE LIVED,
\par    AND THE NOBLE WORK HE WROUGHT; THAT THEY,
\par    THEIR CHILDREN, AND THEIR CHILDREN'S CHILDREN
\par               MIGHT BE BLESSED."
\par 
\par 
\par This was the gift of New England to the freed Negro: not alms, but a
\par friend; not cash, but character.  It was not and is not money these
\par seething millions want, but love and sympathy, the pulse of hearts
\par beating with red blood;--a gift which to-day only their own kindred and
\par race can bring to the masses, but which once saintly souls brought to
\par their favored children in the crusade of the sixties, that finest thing
\par in American history, and one of the few things untainted by sordid
\par greed and cheap vainglory.  The teachers in these institutions came not
\par to keep the Negroes in their place, but to raise them out of the
\par defilement of the places where slavery had wallowed them.  The colleges
\par they founded were social settlements; homes where the best of the sons
\par of the freedmen came in close and sympathetic touch with the best
\par traditions of New England.  They lived and ate together, studied and
\par worked, hoped and harkened in the dawning light.  In actual formal
\par content their curriculum was doubtless old-fashioned, but in
\par educational power it was supreme, for it was the contact of living
\par souls.
\par 
\par From such schools about two thousand Negroes have gone forth with the
\par bachelor's degree.  The number in itself is enough to put at rest the
\par argument that too large a proportion of Negroes are receiving higher
\par training.  If the ratio to population of all Negro students throughout
\par the land, in both college and secondary training, be counted,
\par Commissioner Harris assures us "it must be increased to five times its
\par present average" to equal the average of the land.
\par 
\par Fifty years ago the ability of Negro students in any appreciable
\par numbers to master a modern college course would have been difficult to
\par prove.  To-day it is proved by the fact that four hundred Negroes, many
\par of whom have been reported as brilliant students, have received the
\par bachelor's degree from Harvard, Yale, Oberlin, and seventy other
\par leading colleges.  Here we have, then, nearly twenty-five hundred Negro
\par graduates, of whom the crucial query must be made, How far did their
\par training fit them for life?  It is of course extremely difficult to
\par collect satisfactory data on such a point,--difficult to reach the men,
\par to get trustworthy testimony, and to gauge that testimony by any
\par generally acceptable criterion of success.  In 1900, the Conference at
\par Atlanta University undertook to study these graduates, and published
\par the results.  First they sought to know what these graduates were
\par doing, and succeeded in getting answers from nearly two-thirds of the
\par living.  The direct testimony was in almost all cases corroborated by
\par the reports of the colleges where they graduated, so that in the main
\par the reports were worthy of credence.  Fifty-three per cent of these
\par graduates were teachers,--presidents of institutions, heads of normal
\par schools, principals of city school-systems, and the like.  Seventeen
\par per cent were clergymen; another seventeen per cent were in the
\par professions, chiefly as physicians.  Over six per cent were merchants,
\par farmers, and artisans, and four per cent were in the government
\par civil-service.  Granting even that a considerable proportion of the
\par third unheard from are unsuccessful, this is a record of usefulness.
\par Personally I know many hundreds of these graduates, and have
\par corresponded with more than a thousand; through others I have followed
\par carefully the life-work of scores; I have taught some of them and some
\par of the pupils whom they have taught, lived in homes which they have
\par builded, and looked at life through their eyes.  Comparing them as a
\par class with my fellow students in New England and in Europe, I cannot
\par hesitate in saying that nowhere have I met men and women with a broader
\par spirit of helpfulness, with deeper devotion to their life-work, or with
\par more consecrated determination to succeed in the face of bitter
\par difficulties than among Negro college-bred men.  They have, to be sure,
\par their proportion of ne'er-do-wells, their pedants and lettered fools,
\par but they have a surprisingly small proportion of them; they have not
\par that culture of manner which we instinctively associate with university
\par men, forgetting that in reality it is the heritage from cultured homes,
\par and that no people a generation removed from slavery can escape a
\par certain unpleasant rawness and gaucherie, despite the best of training.
\par 
\par With all their larger vision and deeper sensibility, these men have
\par usually been conservative, careful leaders.  They have seldom been
\par agitators, have withstood the temptation to head the mob, and have
\par worked steadily and faithfully in a thousand communities in the South.
\par As teachers, they have given the South a commendable system of city
\par schools and large numbers of private normal-schools and academies.
\par Colored college-bred men have worked side by side with white college
\par graduates at Hampton; almost from the beginning the backbone of
\par Tuskegee's teaching force has been formed of graduates from Fisk and
\par Atlanta.  And to-day the institute is filled with college graduates,
\par from the energetic wife of the principal down to the teacher of
\par agriculture, including nearly half of the executive council and a
\par majority of the heads of departments.  In the professions, college men
\par are slowly but surely leavening the Negro church, are healing and
\par preventing the devastations of disease, and beginning to furnish legal
\par protection for the liberty and property of the toiling masses.  All
\par this is needful work.  Who would do it if Negroes did not?  How could
\par Negroes do it if they were not trained carefully for it?  If white
\par people need colleges to furnish teachers, ministers, lawyers, and
\par doctors, do black people need nothing of the sort?
\par 
\par If it is true that there are an appreciable number of Negro youth in
\par the land capable by character and talent to receive that higher
\par training, the end of which is culture, and if the two and a half
\par thousand who have had something of this training in the past have in
\par the main proved themselves useful to their race and generation, the
\par question then comes, What place in the future development of the South
\par ought the Negro college and college-bred man to occupy?  That the
\par present social separation and acute race-sensitiveness must eventually
\par yield to the influences of culture, as the South grows civilized, is
\par clear.  But such transformation calls for singular wisdom and patience.
\par If, while the healing of this vast sore is progressing, the races are
\par to live for many years side by side, united in economic effort, obeying
\par a common government, sensitive to mutual thought and feeling, yet
\par subtly and silently separate in many matters of deeper human
\par intimacy,--if this unusual and dangerous development is to progress
\par amid peace and order, mutual respect and growing intelligence, it will
\par call for social surgery at once the delicatest and nicest in modern
\par history.  It will demand broad-minded, upright men, both white and
\par black, and in its final accomplishment American civilization will
\par triumph.  So far as white men are concerned, this fact is to-day being
\par recognized in the South, and a happy renaissance of university
\par education seems imminent.  But the very voices that cry hail to this
\par good work are, strange to relate, largely silent or antagonistic to the
\par higher education of the Negro.
\par 
\par Strange to relate! for this is certain, no secure civilization can be
\par built in the South with the Negro as an ignorant, turbulent
\par proletariat.  Suppose we seek to remedy this by making them laborers
\par and nothing more: they are not fools, they have tasted of the Tree of
\par Life, and they will not cease to think, will not cease attempting to
\par read the riddle of the world.  By taking away their best equipped
\par teachers and leaders, by slamming the door of opportunity in the faces
\par of their bolder and brighter minds, will you make them satisfied with
\par their lot? or will you not rather transfer their leading from the hands
\par of men taught to think to the hands of untrained demagogues?  We ought
\par not to forget that despite the pressure of poverty, and despite the
\par active discouragement and even ridicule of friends, the demand for
\par higher training steadily increases among Negro youth: there were, in
\par the years from 1875 to 1880, 22 Negro graduates from Northern colleges;
\par from 1885 to 1890 there were 43, and from 1895 to 1900, nearly 100
\par graduates.  From Southern Negro colleges there were, in the same three
\par periods, 143, 413, and over 500 graduates.  Here, then, is the plain
\par thirst for training; by refusing to give this Talented Tenth the key to
\par knowledge, can any sane man imagine that they will lightly lay aside
\par their yearning and contentedly become hewers of wood and drawers of
\par water?
\par 
\par No. The dangerously clear logic of the Negro's position will more and
\par more loudly assert itself in that day when increasing wealth and more
\par intricate social organization preclude the South from being, as it so
\par largely is, simply an armed camp for intimidating black folk.  Such
\par waste of energy cannot be spared if the South is to catch up with
\par civilization.  And as the black third of the land grows in thrift and
\par skill, unless skilfully guided in its larger philosophy, it must more
\par and more brood over the red past and the creeping, crooked present,
\par until it grasps a gospel of revolt and revenge and throws its new-found
\par energies athwart the current of advance.  Even to-day the masses of the
\par Negroes see all too clearly the anomalies of their position and the
\par moral crookedness of yours.  You may marshal strong indictments against
\par them, but their counter-cries, lacking though they be in formal logic,
\par have burning truths within them which you may not wholly ignore, O
\par Southern Gentlemen!  If you deplore their presence here, they ask, Who
\par brought us?  When you cry, Deliver us from the vision of intermarriage,
\par they answer that legal marriage is infinitely better than systematic
\par concubinage and prostitution.  And if in just fury you accuse their
\par vagabonds of violating women, they also in fury quite as just may
\par reply: The rape which your gentlemen have done against helpless black
\par women in defiance of your own laws is written on the foreheads of two
\par millions of mulattoes, and written in ineffaceable blood.  And finally,
\par when you fasten crime upon this race as its peculiar trait, they answer
\par that slavery was the arch-crime, and lynching and lawlessness its twin
\par abortions; that color and race are not crimes, and yet it is they which
\par in this land receive most unceasing condemnation, North, East, South,
\par and West.
\par 
\par I will not say such arguments are wholly justified,--I will not insist
\par that there is no other side to the shield; but I do say that of the
\par nine millions of Negroes in this nation, there is scarcely one out of
\par the cradle to whom these arguments do not daily present themselves in
\par the guise of terrible truth.  I insist that the question of the future
\par is how best to keep these millions from brooding over the wrongs of the
\par past and the difficulties of the present, so that all their energies
\par may be bent toward a cheerful striving and cooperation with their white
\par neighbors toward a larger, juster, and fuller future.  That one wise
\par method of doing this lies in the closer knitting of the Negro to the
\par great industrial possibilities of the South is a great truth.  And this
\par the common schools and the manual training and trade schools are
\par working to accomplish.  But these alone are not enough.  The
\par foundations of knowledge in this race, as in others, must be sunk deep
\par in the college and university if we would build a solid, permanent
\par structure.  Internal problems of social advance must inevitably come,
\par --problems of work and wages, of families and homes, of morals and the
\par true valuing of the things of life; and all these and other inevitable
\par problems of civilization the Negro must meet and solve largely for
\par himself, by reason of his isolation; and can there be any possible
\par solution other than by study and thought and an appeal to the rich
\par experience of the past?  Is there not, with such a group and in such a
\par crisis, infinitely more danger to be apprehended from half-trained
\par minds and shallow thinking than from over-education and
\par over-refinement?  Surely we have wit enough to found a Negro college so
\par manned and equipped as to steer successfully between the dilettante and
\par the fool.  We shall hardly induce black men to believe that if their
\par stomachs be full, it matters little about their brains.  They already
\par dimly perceive that the paths of peace winding between honest toil and
\par dignified manhood call for the guidance of skilled thinkers, the
\par loving, reverent comradeship between the black lowly and the black men
\par emancipated by training and culture.
\par 
\par The function of the Negro college, then, is clear: it must maintain the
\par standards of popular education, it must seek the social regeneration of
\par the Negro, and it must help in the solution of problems of race contact
\par and cooperation.  And finally, beyond all this, it must develop men.
\par Above our modern socialism, and out of the worship of the mass, must
\par persist and evolve that higher individualism which the centres of
\par culture protect; there must come a loftier respect for the sovereign
\par human soul that seeks to know itself and the world about it; that seeks
\par a freedom for expansion and self-development; that will love and hate
\par and labor in its own way, untrammeled alike by old and new.  Such souls
\par aforetime have inspired and guided worlds, and if we be not wholly
\par bewitched by our Rhinegold, they shall again.  Herein the longing of
\par black men must have respect: the rich and bitter depth of their
\par experience, the unknown treasures of their inner life, the strange
\par rendings of nature they have seen, may give the world new points of
\par view and make their loving, living, and doing precious to all human
\par hearts.  And to themselves in these the days that try their souls, the
\par chance to soar in the dim blue air above the smoke is to their finer
\par spirits boon and guerdon for what they lose on earth by being black.
\par 
\par I sit with Shakespeare and he winces not.  Across the color line I move
\par arm in arm with Balzac and Dumas, where smiling men and welcoming women
\par glide in gilded halls.  From out the caves of evening that swing
\par between the strong-limbed earth and the tracery of the stars, I summon
\par Aristotle and Aurelius and what soul I will, and they come all
\par graciously with no scorn nor condescension.  So, wed with Truth, I
\par dwell above the Veil.  Is this the life you grudge us, O knightly
\par America?  Is this the life you long to change into the dull red
\par hideousness of Georgia?  Are you so afraid lest peering from this high
\par Pisgah, between Philistine and Amalekite, we sight the Promised Land?
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par VII
\par 
\par Of the Black Belt
\par 
\par   I am black but comely, O ye daughters of Jerusalem,
\par   As the tents of Kedar, as the curtains of Solomon.
\par   Look not upon me, because I am black,
\par   Because the sun hath looked upon me:
\par   My mother's children were angry with me;
\par   They made me the keeper of the vineyards;
\par   But mine own vineyard have I not kept.
\par 
\par   THE SONG OF SOLOMON.
\par 
\par 
\par Out of the North the train thundered, and we woke to see the crimson
\par soil of Georgia stretching away bare and monotonous right and left.
\par Here and there lay straggling, unlovely villages, and lean men loafed
\par leisurely at the depots; then again came the stretch of pines and clay.
\par Yet we did not nod, nor weary of the scene; for this is historic
\par ground.  Right across our track, three hundred and sixty years ago,
\par wandered the cavalcade of Hernando de Soto, looking for gold and the
\par Great Sea; and he and his foot-sore captives disappeared yonder in the
\par grim forests to the west.  Here sits Atlanta, the city of a hundred
\par hills, with something Western, something Southern, and something quite
\par its own, in its busy life.  Just this side Atlanta is the land of the
\par Cherokees and to the southwest, not far from where Sam Hose was
\par crucified, you may stand on a spot which is to-day the centre of the
\par Negro problem,--the centre of those nine million men who are America's
\par dark heritage from slavery and the slave-trade.
\par 
\par Not only is Georgia thus the geographical focus of our Negro
\par population, but in many other respects, both now and yesterday, the
\par Negro problems have seemed to be centered in this State.  No other
\par State in the Union can count a million Negroes among its citizens,--a
\par population as large as the slave population of the whole Union in 1800;
\par no other State fought so long and strenuously to gather this host of
\par Africans.  Oglethorpe thought slavery against law and gospel; but the
\par circumstances which gave Georgia its first inhabitants were not
\par calculated to furnish citizens over-nice in their ideas about rum and
\par slaves.  Despite the prohibitions of the trustees, these Georgians,
\par like some of their descendants, proceeded to take the law into their
\par own hands; and so pliant were the judges, and so flagrant the
\par smuggling, and so earnest were the prayers of Whitefield, that by the
\par middle of the eighteenth century all restrictions were swept away, and
\par the slave-trade went merrily on for fifty years and more.
\par 
\par Down in Darien, where the Delegal riots took place some summers ago,
\par there used to come a strong protest against slavery from the Scotch
\par Highlanders; and the Moravians of Ebenezer did not like the system.
\par But not till the Haytian Terror of Toussaint was the trade in men even
\par checked; while the national statute of 1808 did not suffice to stop it.
\par How the Africans poured in!--fifty thousand between 1790 and 1810, and
\par then, from Virginia and from smugglers, two thousand a year for many
\par years more.  So the thirty thousand Negroes of Georgia in 1790 doubled
\par in a decade,--were over a hundred thousand in 1810, had reached two
\par hundred thousand in 1820, and half a million at the time of the war.
\par Thus like a snake the black population writhed upward.
\par 
\par But we must hasten on our journey.  This that we pass as we near
\par Atlanta is the ancient land of the Cherokees,--that brave Indian nation
\par which strove so long for its fatherland, until Fate and the United
\par States Government drove them beyond the Mississippi.  If you wish to
\par ride with me you must come into the "Jim Crow Car."  There will be no
\par objection,--already four other white men, and a little white girl with
\par her nurse, are in there.  Usually the races are mixed in there; but the
\par white coach is all white.  Of course this car is not so good as the
\par other, but it is fairly clean and comfortable.  The discomfort lies
\par chiefly in the hearts of those four black men yonder--and in mine.
\par 
\par We rumble south in quite a business-like way.  The bare red clay and
\par pines of Northern Georgia begin to disappear, and in their place
\par appears a rich rolling land, luxuriant, and here and there well tilled.
\par This is the land of the Creek Indians; and a hard time the Georgians
\par had to seize it.  The towns grow more frequent and more interesting,
\par and brand-new cotton mills rise on every side.  Below Macon the world
\par grows darker; for now we approach the Black Belt,--that strange land of
\par shadows, at which even slaves paled in the past, and whence come now
\par only faint and half-intelligible murmurs to the world beyond.  The "Jim
\par Crow Car" grows larger and a shade better; three rough field-hands and
\par two or three white loafers accompany us, and the newsboy still spreads
\par his wares at one end.  The sun is setting, but we can see the great
\par cotton country as we enter it,--the soil now dark and fertile, now thin
\par and gray, with fruit-trees and dilapidated buildings,--all the way to
\par Albany.
\par 
\par At Albany, in the heart of the Black Belt, we stop.  Two hundred miles
\par south of Atlanta, two hundred miles west of the Atlantic, and one
\par hundred miles north of the Great Gulf lies Dougherty County, with ten
\par thousand Negroes and two thousand whites.  The Flint River winds down
\par from Andersonville, and, turning suddenly at Albany, the county-seat,
\par hurries on to join the Chattahoochee and the sea.  Andrew Jackson knew
\par the Flint well, and marched across it once to avenge the Indian
\par Massacre at Fort Mims.  That was in 1814, not long before the battle of
\par New Orleans; and by the Creek treaty that followed this campaign, all
\par Dougherty County, and much other rich land, was ceded to Georgia.
\par Still, settlers fought shy of this land, for the Indians were all
\par about, and they were unpleasant neighbors in those days.  The panic of
\par 1837, which Jackson bequeathed to Van Buren, turned the planters from
\par the impoverished lands of Virginia, the Carolinas, and east Georgia,
\par toward the West.  The Indians were removed to Indian Territory, and
\par settlers poured into these coveted lands to retrieve their broken
\par fortunes.  For a radius of a hundred miles about Albany, stretched a
\par great fertile land, luxuriant with forests of pine, oak, ash, hickory,
\par and poplar; hot with the sun and damp with the rich black swamp-land;
\par and here the corner-stone of the Cotton Kingdom was laid.
\par 
\par Albany is to-day a wide-streeted, placid, Southern town, with a broad
\par sweep of stores and saloons, and flanking rows of homes,--whites
\par usually to the north, and blacks to the south.  Six days in the week
\par the town looks decidedly too small for itself, and takes frequent and
\par prolonged naps.  But on Saturday suddenly the whole county disgorges
\par itself upon the place, and a perfect flood of black peasantry pours
\par through the streets, fills the stores, blocks the sidewalks, chokes the
\par thoroughfares, and takes full possession of the town.  They are black,
\par sturdy, uncouth country folk, good-natured and simple, talkative to a
\par degree, and yet far more silent and brooding than the crowds of the
\par Rhine-pfalz, or Naples, or Cracow.  They drink considerable quantities
\par of whiskey, but do not get very drunk; they talk and laugh loudly at
\par times, but seldom quarrel or fight.  They walk up and down the streets,
\par meet and gossip with friends, stare at the shop windows, buy coffee,
\par cheap candy, and clothes, and at dusk drive home--happy? well no, not
\par exactly happy, but much happier than as though they had not come.
\par 
\par Thus Albany is a real capital,--a typical Southern county town, the
\par centre of the life of ten thousand souls; their point of contact with
\par the outer world, their centre of news and gossip, their market for
\par buying and selling, borrowing and lending, their fountain of justice
\par and law.  Once upon a time we knew country life so well and city life
\par so little, that we illustrated city life as that of a closely crowded
\par country district.  Now the world has well-nigh forgotten what the
\par country is, and we must imagine a little city of black people scattered
\par far and wide over three hundred lonesome square miles of land, without
\par train or trolley, in the midst of cotton and corn, and wide patches of
\par sand and gloomy soil.
\par 
\par It gets pretty hot in Southern Georgia in July,--a sort of dull,
\par determined heat that seems quite independent of the sun; so it took us
\par some days to muster courage enough to leave the porch and venture out
\par on the long country roads, that we might see this unknown world.
\par Finally we started.  It was about ten in the morning, bright with a
\par faint breeze, and we jogged leisurely southward in the valley of the
\par Flint.  We passed the scattered box-like cabins of the brickyard hands,
\par and the long tenement-row facetiously called "The Ark," and were soon
\par in the open country, and on the confines of the great plantations of
\par other days.  There is the "Joe Fields place"; a rough old fellow was
\par he, and had killed many a "nigger" in his day.  Twelve miles his
\par plantation used to run,--a regular barony.  It is nearly all gone now;
\par only straggling bits belong to the family, and the rest has passed to
\par Jews and Negroes.  Even the bits which are left are heavily mortgaged,
\par and, like the rest of the land, tilled by tenants.  Here is one of them
\par now,--a tall brown man, a hard worker and a hard drinker, illiterate,
\par but versed in farmlore, as his nodding crops declare.  This
\par distressingly new board house is his, and he has just moved out of
\par yonder moss-grown cabin with its one square room.
\par 
\par From the curtains in Benton's house, down the road, a dark comely face
\par is staring at the strangers; for passing carriages are not every-day
\par occurrences here.  Benton is an intelligent yellow man with a
\par good-sized family, and manages a plantation blasted by the war and now
\par the broken staff of the widow.  He might be well-to-do, they say; but
\par he carouses too much in Albany.  And the half-desolate spirit of
\par neglect born of the very soil seems to have settled on these acres.  In
\par times past there were cotton-gins and machinery here; but they have
\par rotted away.
\par 
\par The whole land seems forlorn and forsaken.  Here are the remnants of
\par the vast plantations of the Sheldons, the Pellots, and the Rensons; but
\par the souls of them are passed.  The houses lie in half ruin, or have
\par wholly disappeared; the fences have flown, and the families are
\par wandering in the world.  Strange vicissitudes have met these whilom
\par masters.  Yonder stretch the wide acres of Bildad Reasor; he died in
\par war-time, but the upstart overseer hastened to wed the widow.  Then he
\par went, and his neighbors too, and now only the black tenant remains; but
\par the shadow-hand of the master's grand-nephew or cousin or creditor
\par stretches out of the gray distance to collect the rack-rent
\par remorselessly, and so the land is uncared-for and poor.  Only black
\par tenants can stand such a system, and they only because they must.  Ten
\par miles we have ridden to-day and have seen no white face.
\par 
\par A resistless feeling of depression falls slowly upon us, despite the
\par gaudy sunshine and the green cottonfields.  This, then, is the Cotton
\par Kingdom,--the shadow of a marvellous dream.  And where is the King?
\par Perhaps this is he,--the sweating ploughman, tilling his eighty acres
\par with two lean mules, and fighting a hard battle with debt.  So we sit
\par musing, until, as we turn a corner on the sandy road, there comes a
\par fairer scene suddenly in view,--a neat cottage snugly ensconced by the
\par road, and near it a little store.  A tall bronzed man rises from the
\par porch as we hail him, and comes out to our carriage.  He is six feet in
\par height, with a sober face that smiles gravely.  He walks too straight
\par to be a tenant,--yes, he owns two hundred and forty acres.  "The land
\par is run down since the boom-days of eighteen hundred and fifty," he
\par explains, and cotton is low.  Three black tenants live on his place,
\par and in his little store he keeps a small stock of tobacco, snuff, soap,
\par and soda, for the neighborhood.  Here is his gin-house with new
\par machinery just installed.  Three hundred bales of cotton went through
\par it last year.  Two children he has sent away to school.  Yes, he says
\par sadly, he is getting on, but cotton is down to four cents; I know how
\par Debt sits staring at him.
\par 
\par Wherever the King may be, the parks and palaces of the Cotton Kingdom
\par have not wholly disappeared.  We plunge even now into great groves of
\par oak and towering pine, with an undergrowth of myrtle and shrubbery.
\par This was the "home-house" of the Thompsons,--slave-barons who drove
\par their coach and four in the merry past.  All is silence now, and ashes,
\par and tangled weeds.  The owner put his whole fortune into the rising
\par cotton industry of the fifties, and with the falling prices of the
\par eighties he packed up and stole away.  Yonder is another grove, with
\par unkempt lawn, great magnolias, and grass-grown paths.  The Big House
\par stands in half-ruin, its great front door staring blankly at the
\par street, and the back part grotesquely restored for its black tenant.  A
\par shabby, well-built Negro he is, unlucky and irresolute.  He digs hard
\par to pay rent to the white girl who owns the remnant of the place.  She
\par married a policeman, and lives in Savannah.
\par 
\par Now and again we come to churches.  Here is one now,--Shepherd's, they
\par call it,--a great whitewashed barn of a thing, perched on stilts of
\par stone, and looking for all the world as though it were just resting
\par here a moment and might be expected to waddle off down the road at
\par almost any time.  And yet it is the centre of a hundred cabin homes;
\par and sometimes, of a Sunday, five hundred persons from far and near
\par gather here and talk and eat and sing.  There is a schoolhouse near,--a
\par very airy, empty shed; but even this is an improvement, for usually the
\par school is held in the church.  The churches vary from log-huts to those
\par like Shepherd's, and the schools from nothing to this little house that
\par sits demurely on the county line.  It is a tiny plank-house, perhaps
\par ten by twenty, and has within a double row of rough unplaned benches,
\par resting mostly on legs, sometimes on boxes.  Opposite the door is a
\par square home-made desk.  In one corner are the ruins of a stove, and in
\par the other a dim blackboard.  It is the cheerfulest schoolhouse I have
\par seen in Dougherty, save in town.  Back of the schoolhouse is a
\par lodgehouse two stories high and not quite finished.  Societies meet
\par there,--societies "to care for the sick and bury the dead"; and these
\par societies grow and flourish.
\par 
\par We had come to the boundaries of Dougherty, and were about to turn west
\par along the county-line, when all these sights were pointed out to us by
\par a kindly old man, black, white-haired, and seventy.  Forty-five years
\par he had lived here, and now supports himself and his old wife by the
\par help of the steer tethered yonder and the charity of his black
\par neighbors.  He shows us the farm of the Hills just across the county
\par line in Baker,--a widow and two strapping sons, who raised ten bales
\par (one need not add "cotton" down here) last year.  There are fences and
\par pigs and cows, and the soft-voiced, velvet-skinned young Memnon, who
\par sauntered half-bashfully over to greet the strangers, is proud of his
\par home.  We turn now to the west along the county line.  Great dismantled
\par trunks of pines tower above the green cottonfields, cracking their
\par naked gnarled fingers toward the border of living forest beyond.  There
\par is little beauty in this region, only a sort of crude abandon that
\par suggests power,--a naked grandeur, as it were.  The houses are bare and
\par straight; there are no hammocks or easy-chairs, and few flowers.  So
\par when, as here at Rawdon's, one sees a vine clinging to a little porch,
\par and home-like windows peeping over the fences, one takes a long breath.
\par I think I never before quite realized the place of the Fence in
\par civilization.  This is the Land of the Unfenced, where crouch on either
\par hand scores of ugly one-room cabins, cheerless and dirty.  Here lies
\par the Negro problem in its naked dirt and penury.  And here are no
\par fences.  But now and then the crisscross rails or straight palings
\par break into view, and then we know a touch of culture is near.  Of
\par course Harrison Gohagen,--a quiet yellow man, young, smooth-faced, and
\par diligent,--of course he is lord of some hundred acres, and we expect to
\par see a vision of well-kept rooms and fat beds and laughing children.
\par For has he not fine fences?  And those over yonder, why should they
\par build fences on the rack-rented land?  It will only increase their rent.
\par 
\par On we wind, through sand and pines and glimpses of old plantations,
\par till there creeps into sight a cluster of buildings,--wood and brick,
\par mills and houses, and scattered cabins.  It seemed quite a village.  As
\par it came nearer and nearer, however, the aspect changed: the buildings
\par were rotten, the bricks were falling out, the mills were silent, and
\par the store was closed.  Only in the cabins appeared now and then a bit
\par of lazy life.  I could imagine the place under some weird spell, and
\par was half-minded to search out the princess.  An old ragged black man,
\par honest, simple, and improvident, told us the tale.  The Wizard of the
\par North--the Capitalist--had rushed down in the seventies to woo this coy
\par dark soil.  He bought a square mile or more, and for a time the
\par field-hands sang, the gins groaned, and the mills buzzed.  Then came a
\par change.  The agent's son embezzled the funds and ran off with them.
\par Then the agent himself disappeared.  Finally the new agent stole even
\par the books, and the company in wrath closed its business and its houses,
\par refused to sell, and let houses and furniture and machinery rust and
\par rot.  So the Waters-Loring plantation was stilled by the spell of
\par dishonesty, and stands like some gaunt rebuke to a scarred land.
\par 
\par Somehow that plantation ended our day's journey; for I could not shake
\par off the influence of that silent scene.  Back toward town we glided,
\par past the straight and thread-like pines, past a dark tree-dotted pond
\par where the air was heavy with a dead sweet perfume.  White
\par slender-legged curlews flitted by us, and the garnet blooms of the
\par cotton looked gay against the green and purple stalks.  A peasant girl
\par was hoeing in the field, white-turbaned and black-limbed.  All this we
\par saw, but the spell still lay upon us.
\par 
\par How curious a land is this,--how full of untold story, of tragedy and
\par laughter, and the rich legacy of human life; shadowed with a tragic
\par past, and big with future promise!  This is the Black Belt of Georgia.
\par Dougherty County is the west end of the Black Belt, and men once called
\par it the Egypt of the Confederacy.  It is full of historic interest.
\par First there is the Swamp, to the west, where the Chickasawhatchee flows
\par sullenly southward.  The shadow of an old plantation lies at its edge,
\par forlorn and dark.  Then comes the pool; pendent gray moss and brackish
\par waters appear, and forests filled with wildfowl.  In one place the wood
\par is on fire, smouldering in dull red anger; but nobody minds.  Then the
\par swamp grows beautiful; a raised road, built by chained Negro convicts,
\par dips down into it, and forms a way walled and almost covered in living
\par green.  Spreading trees spring from a prodigal luxuriance of
\par undergrowth; great dark green shadows fade into the black background,
\par until all is one mass of tangled semi-tropical foliage, marvellous in
\par its weird savage splendor.  Once we crossed a black silent stream,
\par where the sad trees and writhing creepers, all glinting fiery yellow
\par and green, seemed like some vast cathedral,--some green Milan builded
\par of wildwood.  And as I crossed, I seemed to see again that fierce
\par tragedy of seventy years ago.  Osceola, the Indian-Negro chieftain, had
\par risen in the swamps of Florida, vowing vengeance.  His war-cry reached
\par the red Creeks of Dougherty, and their war-cry rang from the
\par Chattahoochee to the sea.  Men and women and children fled and fell
\par before them as they swept into Dougherty.  In yonder shadows a dark and
\par hideously painted warrior glided stealthily on,--another and another,
\par until three hundred had crept into the treacherous swamp.  Then the
\par false slime closing about them called the white men from the east.
\par Waist-deep, they fought beneath the tall trees, until the war-cry was
\par hushed and the Indians glided back into the west.  Small wonder the
\par wood is red.
\par 
\par Then came the black slaves.  Day after day the clank of chained feet
\par marching from Virginia and Carolina to Georgia was heard in these rich
\par swamp lands.  Day after day the songs of the callous, the wail of the
\par motherless, and the muttered curses of the wretched echoed from the
\par Flint to the Chickasawhatchee, until by 1860 there had risen in West
\par Dougherty perhaps the richest slave kingdom the modern world ever knew.
\par A hundred and fifty barons commanded the labor of nearly six thousand
\par Negroes, held sway over farms with ninety thousand acres tilled land,
\par valued even in times of cheap soil at three millions of dollars.
\par Twenty thousand bales of ginned cotton went yearly to England, New and
\par Old; and men that came there bankrupt made money and grew rich.  In a
\par single decade the cotton output increased four-fold and the value of
\par lands was tripled.  It was the heyday of the nouveau riche, and a life
\par of careless extravagance among the masters.  Four and six bobtailed
\par thoroughbreds rolled their coaches to town; open hospitality and gay
\par entertainment were the rule.  Parks and groves were laid out, rich with
\par flower and vine, and in the midst stood the low wide-halled "big
\par house," with its porch and columns and great fireplaces.
\par 
\par And yet with all this there was something sordid, something forced,--a
\par certain feverish unrest and recklessness; for was not all this show and
\par tinsel built upon a groan?  "This land was a little Hell," said a
\par ragged, brown, and grave-faced man to me.  We were seated near a
\par roadside blacksmith shop, and behind was the bare ruin of some master's
\par home.  "I've seen niggers drop dead in the furrow, but they were kicked
\par aside, and the plough never stopped.  Down in the guard-house, there's
\par where the blood ran."
\par 
\par With such foundations a kingdom must in time sway and fall.  The
\par masters moved to Macon and Augusta, and left only the irresponsible
\par overseers on the land.  And the result is such ruin as this, the Lloyd
\par "home-place":--great waving oaks, a spread of lawn, myrtles and
\par chestnuts, all ragged and wild; a solitary gate-post standing where
\par once was a castle entrance; an old rusty anvil lying amid rotting
\par bellows and wood in the ruins of a blacksmith shop; a wide rambling old
\par mansion, brown and dingy, filled now with the grandchildren of the
\par slaves who once waited on its tables; while the family of the master
\par has dwindled to two lone women, who live in Macon and feed hungrily off
\par the remnants of an earldom.  So we ride on, past phantom gates and
\par falling homes,--past the once flourishing farms of the Smiths, the
\par Gandys, and the Lagores,--and find all dilapidated and half ruined,
\par even there where a solitary white woman, a relic of other days, sits
\par alone in state among miles of Negroes and rides to town in her ancient
\par coach each day.
\par 
\par This was indeed the Egypt of the Confederacy,--the rich granary whence
\par potatoes and corn and cotton poured out to the famished and ragged
\par Confederate troops as they battled for a cause lost long before 1861.
\par Sheltered and secure, it became the place of refuge for families,
\par wealth, and slaves.  Yet even then the hard ruthless rape of the land
\par began to tell.  The red-clay sub-soil already had begun to peer above
\par the loam.  The harder the slaves were driven the more careless and
\par fatal was their farming.  Then came the revolution of war and
\par Emancipation, the bewilderment of Reconstruction,--and now, what is the
\par Egypt of the Confederacy, and what meaning has it for the nation's weal
\par or woe?
\par 
\par It is a land of rapid contrasts and of curiously mingled hope and pain.
\par Here sits a pretty blue-eyed quadroon hiding her bare feet; she was
\par married only last week, and yonder in the field is her dark young
\par husband, hoeing to support her, at thirty cents a day without board.
\par Across the way is Gatesby, brown and tall, lord of two thousand acres
\par shrewdly won and held.  There is a store conducted by his black son, a
\par blacksmith shop, and a ginnery.  Five miles below here is a town owned
\par and controlled by one white New Englander.  He owns almost a Rhode
\par Island county, with thousands of acres and hundreds of black laborers.
\par Their cabins look better than most, and the farm, with machinery and
\par fertilizers, is much more business-like than any in the county,
\par although the manager drives hard bargains in wages.  When now we turn
\par and look five miles above, there on the edge of town are five houses of
\par prostitutes,--two of blacks and three of whites; and in one of the
\par houses of the whites a worthless black boy was harbored too openly two
\par years ago; so he was hanged for rape.  And here, too, is the high
\par whitewashed fence of the "stockade," as the county prison is called;
\par the white folks say it is ever full of black criminals,--the black
\par folks say that only colored boys are sent to jail, and they not because
\par they are guilty, but because the State needs criminals to eke out its
\par income by their forced labor.
\par 
\par Immigrants are heirs of the slave baron in Dougherty; and as we ride
\par westward, by wide stretching cornfields and stubby orchards of peach
\par and pear, we see on all sides within the circle of dark forest a Land
\par of Canaan.  Here and there are tales of projects for money-getting,
\par born in the swift days of Reconstruction,--"improvement" companies,
\par wine companies, mills and factories; most failed, and foreigners fell
\par heir.  It is a beautiful land, this Dougherty, west of the Flint.  The
\par forests are wonderful, the solemn pines have disappeared, and this is
\par the "Oakey Woods," with its wealth of hickories, beeches, oaks and
\par palmettos.  But a pall of debt hangs over the beautiful land; the
\par merchants are in debt to the wholesalers, the planters are in debt to
\par the merchants, the tenants owe the planters, and laborers bow and bend
\par beneath the burden of it all.  Here and there a man has raised his head
\par above these murky waters.  We passed one fenced stock-farm with grass
\par and grazing cattle, that looked very home-like after endless corn and
\par cotton.  Here and there are black free-holders: there is the gaunt
\par dull-black Jackson, with his hundred acres.  "I says, 'Look up!  If you
\par don't look up you can't get up,'" remarks Jackson, philosophically.
\par And he's gotten up.  Dark Carter's neat barns would do credit to New
\par England.  His master helped him to get a start, but when the black man
\par died last fall the master's sons immediately laid claim to the estate.
\par "And them white folks will get it, too," said my yellow gossip.
\par 
\par I turn from these well-tended acres with a comfortable feeling that the
\par Negro is rising.  Even then, however, the fields, as we proceed, begin
\par to redden and the trees disappear.  Rows of old cabins appear filled
\par with renters and laborers,--cheerless, bare, and dirty, for the most
\par part, although here and there the very age and decay makes the scene
\par picturesque.  A young black fellow greets us.  He is twenty-two, and
\par just married.  Until last year he had good luck renting; then cotton
\par fell, and the sheriff seized and sold all he had.  So he moved here,
\par where the rent is higher, the land poorer, and the owner inflexible; he
\par rents a forty-dollar mule for twenty dollars a year.  Poor lad!--a
\par slave at twenty-two.  This plantation, owned now by a foreigner, was a
\par part of the famous Bolton estate.  After the war it was for many years
\par worked by gangs of Negro convicts,--and black convicts then were even
\par more plentiful than now; it was a way of making Negroes work, and the
\par question of guilt was a minor one.  Hard tales of cruelty and
\par mistreatment of the chained freemen are told, but the county
\par authorities were deaf until the free-labor market was nearly ruined by
\par wholesale migration.  Then they took the convicts from the plantations,
\par but not until one of the fairest regions of the "Oakey Woods" had been
\par ruined and ravished into a red waste, out of which only a Yankee or an
\par immigrant could squeeze more blood from debt-cursed tenants.
\par 
\par No wonder that Luke Black, slow, dull, and discouraged, shuffles to our
\par carriage and talks hopelessly.  Why should he strive?  Every year finds
\par him deeper in debt.  How strange that Georgia, the world-heralded
\par refuge of poor debtors, should bind her own to sloth and misfortune as
\par ruthlessly as ever England did!  The poor land groans with its
\par birth-pains, and brings forth scarcely a hundred pounds of cotton to
\par the acre, where fifty years ago it yielded eight times as much.  Of his
\par meagre yield the tenant pays from a quarter to a third in rent, and
\par most of the rest in interest on food and supplies bought on credit.
\par Twenty years yonder sunken-cheeked, old black man has labored under
\par that system, and now, turned day-laborer, is supporting his wife and
\par boarding himself on his wages of a dollar and a half a week, received
\par only part of the year.
\par 
\par The Bolton convict farm formerly included the neighboring plantation.
\par Here it was that the convicts were lodged in the great log prison still
\par standing.  A dismal place it still remains, with rows of ugly huts
\par filled with surly ignorant tenants.  "What rent do you pay here?" I
\par inquired.  "I don't know,--what is it, Sam?"  "All we make," answered
\par Sam.  It is a depressing place,--bare, unshaded, with no charm of past
\par association, only a memory of forced human toil,--now, then, and before
\par the war.  They are not happy, these black men whom we meet throughout
\par this region.  There is little of the joyous abandon and playfulness
\par which we are wont to associate with the plantation Negro.  At best, the
\par natural good-nature is edged with complaint or has changed into
\par sullenness and gloom.  And now and then it blazes forth in veiled but
\par hot anger.  I remember one big red-eyed black whom we met by the
\par roadside.  Forty-five years he had labored on this farm, beginning with
\par nothing, and still having nothing.  To be sure, he had given four
\par children a common-school training, and perhaps if the new fence-law had
\par not allowed unfenced crops in West Dougherty he might have raised a
\par little stock and kept ahead.  As it is, he is hopelessly in debt,
\par disappointed, and embittered.  He stopped us to inquire after the black
\par boy in Albany, whom it was said a policeman had shot and killed for
\par loud talking on the sidewalk.  And then he said slowly: "Let a white
\par man touch me, and he dies; I don't boast this,--I don't say it around
\par loud, or before the children,--but I mean it.  I've seen them whip my
\par father and my old mother in them cotton-rows till the blood ran; by--"
\par and we passed on.
\par 
\par Now Sears, whom we met next lolling under the chubby oak-trees, was of
\par quite different fibre.  Happy?--Well, yes; he laughed and flipped
\par pebbles, and thought the world was as it was.  He had worked here
\par twelve years and has nothing but a mortgaged mule.  Children?  Yes,
\par seven; but they hadn't been to school this year,--couldn't afford books
\par and clothes, and couldn't spare their work.  There go part of them to
\par the fields now,--three big boys astride mules, and a strapping girl
\par with bare brown legs.  Careless ignorance and laziness here, fierce
\par hate and vindictiveness there;--these are the extremes of the Negro
\par problem which we met that day, and we scarce knew which we preferred.
\par 
\par Here and there we meet distinct characters quite out of the ordinary.
\par One came out of a piece of newly cleared ground, making a wide detour
\par to avoid the snakes.  He was an old, hollow-cheeked man, with a drawn
\par and characterful brown face.  He had a sort of self-contained
\par quaintness and rough humor impossible to describe; a certain cynical
\par earnestness that puzzled one.  "The niggers were jealous of me over on
\par the other place," he said, "and so me and the old woman begged this
\par piece of woods, and I cleared it up myself.  Made nothing for two
\par years, but I reckon I've got a crop now."  The cotton looked tall and
\par rich, and we praised it.  He curtsied low, and then bowed almost to the
\par ground, with an imperturbable gravity that seemed almost suspicious.
\par Then he continued, "My mule died last week,"--a calamity in this land
\par equal to a devastating fire in town,--"but a white man loaned me
\par another."  Then he added, eyeing us, "Oh, I gets along with white
\par folks."  We turned the conversation.  "Bears? deer?" he answered,
\par "well, I should say there were," and he let fly a string of brave
\par oaths, as he told hunting-tales of the swamp.  We left him standing
\par still in the middle of the road looking after us, and yet apparently
\par not noticing us.
\par 
\par The Whistle place, which includes his bit of land, was bought soon
\par after the war by an English syndicate, the "Dixie Cotton and Corn
\par Company."  A marvellous deal of style their factor put on, with his
\par servants and coach-and-six; so much so that the concern soon landed in
\par inextricable bankruptcy.  Nobody lives in the old house now, but a man
\par comes each winter out of the North and collects his high rents.  I know
\par not which are the more touching,--such old empty houses, or the homes
\par of the masters' sons.  Sad and bitter tales lie hidden back of those
\par white doors,--tales of poverty, of struggle, of disappointment.  A
\par revolution such as that of '63 is a terrible thing; they that rose rich
\par in the morning often slept in paupers' beds.  Beggars and vulgar
\par speculators rose to rule over them, and their children went astray.
\par See yonder sad-colored house, with its cabins and fences and glad
\par crops!  It is not glad within; last month the prodigal son of the
\par struggling father wrote home from the city for money.  Money!  Where
\par was it to come from?  And so the son rose in the night and killed his
\par baby, and killed his wife, and shot himself dead.  And the world passed
\par on.
\par 
\par I remember wheeling around a bend in the road beside a graceful bit of
\par forest and a singing brook.  A long low house faced us, with porch and
\par flying pillars, great oaken door, and a broad lawn shining in the
\par evening sun.  But the window-panes were gone, the pillars were
\par worm-eaten, and the moss-grown roof was falling in.  Half curiously I
\par peered through the unhinged door, and saw where, on the wall across the
\par hall, was written in once gay letters a faded "Welcome."
\par 
\par Quite a contrast to the southwestern part of Dougherty County is the
\par northwest.  Soberly timbered in oak and pine, it has none of that
\par half-tropical luxuriance of the southwest.  Then, too, there are fewer
\par signs of a romantic past, and more of systematic modern land-grabbing
\par and money-getting.  White people are more in evidence here, and farmer
\par and hired labor replace to some extent the absentee landlord and
\par rack-rented tenant.  The crops have neither the luxuriance of the
\par richer land nor the signs of neglect so often seen, and there were
\par fences and meadows here and there.  Most of this land was poor, and
\par beneath the notice of the slave-baron, before the war.  Since then his
\par poor relations and foreign immigrants have seized it.  The returns of
\par the farmer are too small to allow much for wages, and yet he will not
\par sell off small farms.  There is the Negro Sanford; he has worked
\par fourteen years as overseer on the Ladson place, and "paid out enough
\par for fertilizers to have bought a farm," but the owner will not sell off
\par a few acres.
\par 
\par Two children--a boy and a girl--are hoeing sturdily in the fields on
\par the farm where Corliss works.  He is smooth-faced and brown, and is
\par fencing up his pigs.  He used to run a successful cotton-gin, but the
\par Cotton Seed Oil Trust has forced the price of ginning so low that he
\par says it hardly pays him.  He points out a stately old house over the
\par way as the home of "Pa Willis."  We eagerly ride over, for "Pa Willis"
\par was the tall and powerful black Moses who led the Negroes for a
\par generation, and led them well.  He was a Baptist preacher, and when he
\par died, two thousand black people followed him to the grave; and now they
\par preach his funeral sermon each year.  His widow lives here,--a
\par weazened, sharp-featured little woman, who curtsied quaintly as we
\par greeted her.  Further on lives Jack Delson, the most prosperous Negro
\par farmer in the county.  It is a joy to meet him,--a great
\par broad-shouldered, handsome black man, intelligent and jovial.  Six
\par hundred and fifty acres he owns, and has eleven black tenants.  A neat
\par and tidy home nestled in a flower-garden, and a little store stands
\par beside it.
\par 
\par We pass the Munson place, where a plucky white widow is renting and
\par struggling; and the eleven hundred acres of the Sennet plantation, with
\par its Negro overseer.  Then the character of the farms begins to change.
\par Nearly all the lands belong to Russian Jews; the overseers are white,
\par and the cabins are bare board-houses scattered here and there.  The
\par rents are high, and day-laborers and "contract" hands abound.  It is a
\par keen, hard struggle for living here, and few have time to talk.  Tired
\par with the long ride, we gladly drive into Gillonsville.  It is a silent
\par cluster of farmhouses standing on the crossroads, with one of its
\par stores closed and the other kept by a Negro preacher.  They tell great
\par tales of busy times at Gillonsville before all the railroads came to
\par Albany; now it is chiefly a memory.  Riding down the street, we stop at
\par the preacher's and seat ourselves before the door.  It was one of those
\par scenes one cannot soon forget:--a wide, low, little house, whose
\par motherly roof reached over and sheltered a snug little porch.  There we
\par sat, after the long hot drive, drinking cool water,--the talkative
\par little storekeeper who is my daily companion; the silent old black
\par woman patching pantaloons and saying never a word; the ragged picture
\par of helpless misfortune who called in just to see the preacher; and
\par finally the neat matronly preacher's wife, plump, yellow, and
\par intelligent.  "Own land?" said the wife; "well, only this house."  Then
\par she added quietly.  "We did buy seven hundred acres across up yonder,
\par and paid for it; but they cheated us out of it.  Sells was the owner."
\par "Sells!" echoed the ragged misfortune, who was leaning against the
\par balustrade and listening, "he's a regular cheat.  I worked for him
\par thirty-seven days this spring, and he paid me in cardboard checks which
\par were to be cashed at the end of the month.  But he never cashed
\par them,--kept putting me off.  Then the sheriff came and took my mule and
\par corn and furniture--" "Furniture?  But furniture is exempt from seizure
\par by law."  "Well, he took it just the same," said the hard-faced man.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par VIII
\par 
\par Of the Quest of the Golden Fleece
\par 
\par   But the Brute said in his breast, "Till the mills I grind
\par           have ceased,
\par   The riches shall be dust of dust, dry ashes be the feast!
\par 
\par      "On the strong and cunning few
\par      Cynic favors I will strew;
\par   I will stuff their maw with overplus until their spirit dies;
\par   From the patient and the low
\par 
\par   I will take the joys they know;
\par       They shall hunger after vanities and still an-hungered go.
\par   Madness shall be on the people, ghastly jealousies arise;
\par   Brother's blood shall cry on brother up the dead and empty skies.
\par 
\par   WILLIAM VAUGHN MOODY.
\par 
\par 
\par Have you ever seen a cotton-field white with harvest,--its golden
\par fleece hovering above the black earth like a silvery cloud edged with
\par dark green, its bold white signals waving like the foam of billows from
\par Carolina to Texas across that Black and human Sea?  I have sometimes
\par half suspected that here the winged ram Chrysomallus left that Fleece
\par after which Jason and his Argonauts went vaguely wandering into the
\par shadowy East three thousand years ago; and certainly one might frame a
\par pretty and not far-fetched analogy of witchery and dragons' teeth, and
\par blood and armed men, between the ancient and the modern quest of the
\par Golden Fleece in the Black Sea.
\par 
\par And now the golden fleece is found; not only found, but, in its
\par birthplace, woven.  For the hum of the cotton-mills is the newest and
\par most significant thing in the New South to-day.  All through the
\par Carolinas and Georgia, away down to Mexico, rise these gaunt red
\par buildings, bare and homely, and yet so busy and noisy withal that they
\par scarce seem to belong to the slow and sleepy land.  Perhaps they sprang
\par from dragons' teeth.  So the Cotton Kingdom still lives; the world
\par still bows beneath her sceptre.  Even the markets that once defied the
\par parvenu have crept one by one across the seas, and then slowly and
\par reluctantly, but surely, have started toward the Black Belt.
\par 
\par To be sure, there are those who wag their heads knowingly and tell us
\par that the capital of the Cotton Kingdom has moved from the Black to the
\par White Belt,--that the Negro of to-day raises not more than half of the
\par cotton crop.  Such men forget that the cotton crop has doubled, and
\par more than doubled, since the era of slavery, and that, even granting
\par their contention, the Negro is still supreme in a Cotton Kingdom larger
\par than that on which the Confederacy builded its hopes.  So the Negro
\par forms to-day one of the chief figures in a great world-industry; and
\par this, for its own sake, and in the light of historic interest, makes
\par the field-hands of the cotton country worth studying.
\par 
\par We seldom study the condition of the Negro to-day honestly and
\par carefully.  It is so much easier to assume that we know it all.  Or
\par perhaps, having already reached conclusions in our own minds, we are
\par loth to have them disturbed by facts.  And yet how little we really
\par know of these millions,--of their daily lives and longings, of their
\par homely joys and sorrows, of their real shortcomings and the meaning of
\par their crimes!  All this we can only learn by intimate contact with the
\par masses, and not by wholesale arguments covering millions separate in
\par time and space, and differing widely in training and culture.  To-day,
\par then, my reader, let us turn our faces to the Black Belt of Georgia and
\par seek simply to know the condition of the black farm-laborers of one
\par county there.
\par 
\par Here in 1890 lived ten thousand Negroes and two thousand whites.  The
\par country is rich, yet the people are poor.  The keynote of the Black
\par Belt is debt; not commercial credit, but debt in the sense of continued
\par inability on the part of the mass of the population to make income
\par cover expense.  This is the direct heritage of the South from the
\par wasteful economies of the slave regime; but it was emphasized and
\par brought to a crisis by the Emancipation of the slaves.  In 1860,
\par Dougherty County had six thousand slaves, worth at least two and a half
\par millions of dollars; its farms were estimated at three
\par millions,--making five and a half millions of property, the value of
\par which depended largely on the slave system, and on the speculative
\par demand for land once marvellously rich but already partially
\par devitalized by careless and exhaustive culture.  The war then meant a
\par financial crash; in place of the five and a half millions of 1860,
\par there remained in 1870 only farms valued at less than two millions.
\par With this came increased competition in cotton culture from the rich
\par lands of Texas; a steady fall in the normal price of cotton followed,
\par from about fourteen cents a pound in 1860 until it reached four cents
\par in 1898.  Such a financial revolution was it that involved the owners
\par of the cotton-belt in debt.  And if things went ill with the master,
\par how fared it with the man?
\par 
\par The plantations of Dougherty County in slavery days were not as
\par imposing and aristocratic as those of Virginia.  The Big House was
\par smaller and usually one-storied, and sat very near the slave cabins.
\par Sometimes these cabins stretched off on either side like wings;
\par sometimes only on one side, forming a double row, or edging the road
\par that turned into the plantation from the main thoroughfare.  The form
\par and disposition of the laborers' cabins throughout the Black Belt is
\par to-day the same as in slavery days.  Some live in the self-same cabins,
\par others in cabins rebuilt on the sites of the old.  All are sprinkled in
\par little groups over the face of the land, centering about some
\par dilapidated Big House where the head-tenant or agent lives.  The
\par general character and arrangement of these dwellings remains on the
\par whole unaltered.  There were in the county, outside the corporate town
\par of Albany, about fifteen hundred Negro families in 1898.  Out of all
\par these, only a single family occupied a house with seven rooms; only
\par fourteen have five rooms or more.  The mass live in one- and two-room
\par homes.
\par 
\par The size and arrangements of a people's homes are no unfair index of
\par their condition.  If, then, we inquire more carefully into these Negro
\par homes, we find much that is unsatisfactory.  All over the face of the
\par land is the one-room cabin,--now standing in the shadow of the Big
\par House, now staring at the dusty road, now rising dark and sombre amid
\par the green of the cotton-fields.  It is nearly always old and bare,
\par built of rough boards, and neither plastered nor ceiled.  Light and
\par ventilation are supplied by the single door and by the square hole in
\par the wall with its wooden shutter.  There is no glass, porch, or
\par ornamentation without.  Within is a fireplace, black and smoky, and
\par usually unsteady with age.  A bed or two, a table, a wooden chest, and
\par a few chairs compose the furniture; while a stray show-bill or a
\par newspaper makes up the decorations for the walls.  Now and then one may
\par find such a cabin kept scrupulously neat, with merry steaming
\par fireplaces and hospitable door; but the majority are dirty and
\par dilapidated, smelling of eating and sleeping, poorly ventilated, and
\par anything but homes.
\par 
\par Above all, the cabins are crowded.  We have come to associate crowding
\par with homes in cities almost exclusively.  This is primarily because we
\par have so little accurate knowledge of country life.  Here in Dougherty
\par County one may find families of eight and ten occupying one or two
\par rooms, and for every ten rooms of house accommodation for the Negroes
\par there are twenty-five persons.  The worst tenement abominations of New
\par York do not have above twenty-two persons for every ten rooms.  Of
\par course, one small, close room in a city, without a yard, is in many
\par respects worse than the larger single country room.  In other respects
\par it is better; it has glass windows, a decent chimney, and a trustworthy
\par floor.  The single great advantage of the Negro peasant is that he may
\par spend most of his life outside his hovel, in the open fields.
\par 
\par There are four chief causes of these wretched homes: First, long custom
\par born of slavery has assigned such homes to Negroes; white laborers
\par would be offered better accommodations, and might, for that and similar
\par reasons, give better work.  Secondly, the Negroes, used to such
\par accommodations, do not as a rule demand better; they do not know what
\par better houses mean.  Thirdly, the landlords as a class have not yet
\par come to realize that it is a good business investment to raise the
\par standard of living among labor by slow and judicious methods; that a
\par Negro laborer who demands three rooms and fifty cents a day would give
\par more efficient work and leave a larger profit than a discouraged toiler
\par herding his family in one room and working for thirty cents.  Lastly,
\par among such conditions of life there are few incentives to make the
\par laborer become a better farmer.  If he is ambitious, he moves to town
\par or tries other labor; as a tenant-farmer his outlook is almost
\par hopeless, and following it as a makeshift, he takes the house that is
\par given him without protest.
\par 
\par In such homes, then, these Negro peasants live.  The families are both
\par small and large; there are many single tenants,--widows and bachelors,
\par and remnants of broken groups.  The system of labor and the size of the
\par houses both tend to the breaking up of family groups: the grown
\par children go away as contract hands or migrate to town, the sister goes
\par into service; and so one finds many families with hosts of babies, and
\par many newly married couples, but comparatively few families with
\par half-grown and grown sons and daughters.  The average size of Negro
\par families has undoubtedly decreased since the war, primarily from
\par economic stress.  In Russia over a third of the bridegrooms and over
\par half the brides are under twenty; the same was true of the antebellum
\par Negroes.  Today, however, very few of the boys and less than a fifth of
\par the Negro girls under twenty are married.  The young men marry between
\par the ages of twenty-five and thirty-five; the young women between twenty
\par and thirty.  Such postponement is due to the difficulty of earning
\par sufficient to rear and support a family; and it undoubtedly leads, in
\par the country districts, to sexual immorality.  The form of this
\par immorality, however, is very seldom that of prostitution, and less
\par frequently that of illegitimacy than one would imagine.  Rather, it
\par takes the form of separation and desertion after a family group has
\par been formed.  The number of separated persons is thirty-five to the
\par thousand,--a very large number.  It would of course be unfair to
\par compare this number with divorce statistics, for many of these
\par separated women are in reality widowed, were the truth known, and in
\par other cases the separation is not permanent.  Nevertheless, here lies
\par the seat of greatest moral danger.  There is little or no prostitution
\par among these Negroes, and over three-fourths of the families, as found
\par by house-to-house investigation, deserve to be classed as decent people
\par with considerable regard for female chastity.  To be sure, the ideas of
\par the mass would not suit New England, and there are many loose habits
\par and notions.  Yet the rate of illegitimacy is undoubtedly lower than in
\par Austria or Italy, and the women as a class are modest.  The plague-spot
\par in sexual relations is easy marriage and easy separation.  This is no
\par sudden development, nor the fruit of Emancipation.  It is the plain
\par heritage from slavery.  In those days Sam, with his master's consent,
\par "took up" with Mary.  No ceremony was necessary, and in the busy life
\par of the great plantations of the Black Belt it was usually dispensed
\par with.  If now the master needed Sam's work in another plantation or in
\par another part of the same plantation, or if he took a notion to sell the
\par slave, Sam's married life with Mary was usually unceremoniously broken,
\par and then it was clearly to the master's interest to have both of them
\par take new mates.  This widespread custom of two centuries has not been
\par eradicated in thirty years.  To-day Sam's grandson "takes up" with a
\par woman without license or ceremony; they live together decently and
\par honestly, and are, to all intents and purposes, man and wife.
\par Sometimes these unions are never broken until death; but in too many
\par cases family quarrels, a roving spirit, a rival suitor, or perhaps more
\par frequently the hopeless battle to support a family, lead to separation,
\par and a broken household is the result.  The Negro church has done much
\par to stop this practice, and now most marriage ceremonies are performed
\par by the pastors.  Nevertheless, the evil is still deep seated, and only
\par a general raising of the standard of living will finally cure it.
\par 
\par Looking now at the county black population as a whole, it is fair to
\par characterize it as poor and ignorant.  Perhaps ten per cent compose the
\par well-to-do and the best of the laborers, while at least nine per cent
\par are thoroughly lewd and vicious.  The rest, over eighty per cent, are
\par poor and ignorant, fairly honest and well meaning, plodding, and to a
\par degree shiftless, with some but not great sexual looseness.  Such class
\par lines are by no means fixed; they vary, one might almost say, with the
\par price of cotton.  The degree of ignorance cannot easily be expressed.
\par We may say, for instance, that nearly two-thirds of them cannot read or
\par write.  This but partially expresses the fact.  They are ignorant of
\par the world about them, of modern economic organization, of the function
\par of government, of individual worth and possibilities,--of nearly all
\par those things which slavery in self-defence had to keep them from
\par learning.  Much that the white boy imbibes from his earliest social
\par atmosphere forms the puzzling problems of the black boy's mature years.
\par America is not another word for Opportunity to all her sons.
\par 
\par It is easy for us to lose ourselves in details in endeavoring to grasp
\par and comprehend the real condition of a mass of human beings.  We often
\par forget that each unit in the mass is a throbbing human soul.  Ignorant
\par it may be, and poverty stricken, black and curious in limb and ways and
\par thought; and yet it loves and hates, it toils and tires, it laughs and
\par weeps its bitter tears, and looks in vague and awful longing at the
\par grim horizon of its life,--all this, even as you and I. These black
\par thousands are not in reality lazy; they are improvident and careless;
\par they insist on breaking the monotony of toil with a glimpse at the
\par great town-world on Saturday; they have their loafers and their
\par rascals; but the great mass of them work continuously and faithfully
\par for a return, and under circumstances that would call forth equal
\par voluntary effort from few if any other modern laboring class.  Over
\par eighty-eight per cent of them--men, women, and children--are farmers.
\par Indeed, this is almost the only industry.  Most of the children get
\par their schooling after the "crops are laid by," and very few there are
\par that stay in school after the spring work has begun.  Child-labor is to
\par be found here in some of its worst phases, as fostering ignorance and
\par stunting physical development.  With the grown men of the county there
\par is little variety in work: thirteen hundred are farmers, and two
\par hundred are laborers, teamsters, etc., including twenty-four artisans,
\par ten merchants, twenty-one preachers, and four teachers.  This
\par narrowness of life reaches its maximum among the women: thirteen
\par hundred and fifty of these are farm laborers, one hundred are servants
\par and washerwomen, leaving sixty-five housewives, eight teachers, and six
\par seamstresses.
\par 
\par Among this people there is no leisure class.  We often forget that in
\par the United States over half the youth and adults are not in the world
\par earning incomes, but are making homes, learning of the world, or
\par resting after the heat of the strife.  But here ninety-six per cent are
\par toiling; no one with leisure to turn the bare and cheerless cabin into
\par a home, no old folks to sit beside the fire and hand down traditions of
\par the past; little of careless happy childhood and dreaming youth.  The
\par dull monotony of daily toil is broken only by the gayety of the
\par thoughtless and the Saturday trip to town.  The toil, like all farm
\par toil, is monotonous, and here there are little machinery and few tools
\par to relieve its burdensome drudgery.  But with all this, it is work in
\par the pure open air, and this is something in a day when fresh air is
\par scarce.
\par 
\par The land on the whole is still fertile, despite long abuse.  For nine
\par or ten months in succession the crops will come if asked: garden
\par vegetables in April, grain in May, melons in June and July, hay in
\par August, sweet potatoes in September, and cotton from then to Christmas.
\par And yet on two-thirds of the land there is but one crop, and that
\par leaves the toilers in debt.  Why is this?
\par 
\par Away down the Baysan road, where the broad flat fields are flanked by
\par great oak forests, is a plantation; many thousands of acres it used to
\par run, here and there, and beyond the great wood.  Thirteen hundred human
\par beings here obeyed the call of one,--were his in body, and largely in
\par soul.  One of them lives there yet,--a short, stocky man, his
\par dull-brown face seamed and drawn, and his tightly curled hair
\par gray-white.  The crops?  Just tolerable, he said; just tolerable.
\par Getting on?  No--he wasn't getting on at all.  Smith of Albany
\par "furnishes" him, and his rent is eight hundred pounds of cotton.  Can't
\par make anything at that.  Why didn't he buy land!  Humph!  Takes money to
\par buy land.  And he turns away.  Free!  The most piteous thing amid all
\par the black ruin of war-time, amid the broken fortunes of the masters,
\par the blighted hopes of mothers and maidens, and the fall of an
\par empire,--the most piteous thing amid all this was the black freedman
\par who threw down his hoe because the world called him free.  What did
\par such a mockery of freedom mean?  Not a cent of money, not an inch of
\par land, not a mouthful of victuals,--not even ownership of the rags on
\par his back.  Free!  On Saturday, once or twice a month, the old master,
\par before the war, used to dole out bacon and meal to his Negroes.  And
\par after the first flush of freedom wore off, and his true helplessness
\par dawned on the freedman, he came back and picked up his hoe, and old
\par master still doled out his bacon and meal.  The legal form of service
\par was theoretically far different; in practice, task-work or "cropping"
\par was substituted for daily toil in gangs; and the slave gradually became
\par a metayer, or tenant on shares, in name, but a laborer with
\par indeterminate wages in fact.
\par 
\par Still the price of cotton fell, and gradually the landlords deserted
\par their plantations, and the reign of the merchant began.  The merchant
\par of the Black Belt is a curious institution,--part banker, part
\par landlord, part banker, and part despot.  His store, which used most
\par frequently to stand at the cross-roads and become the centre of a
\par weekly village, has now moved to town; and thither the Negro tenant
\par follows him.  The merchant keeps everything,--clothes and shoes, coffee
\par and sugar, pork and meal, canned and dried goods, wagons and ploughs,
\par seed and fertilizer,--and what he has not in stock he can give you an
\par order for at the store across the way.  Here, then, comes the tenant,
\par Sam Scott, after he has contracted with some absent landlord's agent
\par for hiring forty acres of land; he fingers his hat nervously until the
\par merchant finishes his morning chat with Colonel Saunders, and calls
\par out, "Well, Sam, what do you want?"  Sam wants him to "furnish"
\par him,--i.e., to advance him food and clothing for the year, and perhaps
\par seed and tools, until his crop is raised and sold.  If Sam seems a
\par favorable subject, he and the merchant go to a lawyer, and Sam executes
\par a chattel mortgage on his mule and wagon in return for seed and a
\par week's rations.  As soon as the green cotton-leaves appear above the
\par ground, another mortgage is given on the "crop."  Every Saturday, or at
\par longer intervals, Sam calls upon the merchant for his "rations"; a
\par family of five usually gets about thirty pounds of fat side-pork and a
\par couple of bushels of cornmeal a month.  Besides this, clothing and
\par shoes must be furnished; if Sam or his family is sick, there are orders
\par on the druggist and doctor; if the mule wants shoeing, an order on the
\par blacksmith, etc.  If Sam is a hard worker and crops promise well, he is
\par often encouraged to buy more,--sugar, extra clothes, perhaps a buggy.
\par But he is seldom encouraged to save.  When cotton rose to ten cents
\par last fall, the shrewd merchants of Dougherty County sold a thousand
\par buggies in one season, mostly to black men.
\par 
\par The security offered for such transactions--a crop and chattel
\par mortgage--may at first seem slight.  And, indeed, the merchants tell
\par many a true tale of shiftlessness and cheating; of cotton picked at
\par night, mules disappearing, and tenants absconding.  But on the whole
\par the merchant of the Black Belt is the most prosperous man in the
\par section.  So skilfully and so closely has he drawn the bonds of the law
\par about the tenant, that the black man has often simply to choose between
\par pauperism and crime; he "waives" all homestead exemptions in his
\par contract; he cannot touch his own mortgaged crop, which the laws put
\par almost in the full control of the land-owner and of the merchant.  When
\par the crop is growing the merchant watches it like a hawk; as soon as it
\par is ready for market he takes possession of it, sells it, pays the
\par landowner his rent, subtracts his bill for supplies, and if, as
\par sometimes happens, there is anything left, he hands it over to the
\par black serf for his Christmas celebration.
\par 
\par The direct result of this system is an all-cotton scheme of agriculture
\par and the continued bankruptcy of the tenant.  The currency of the Black
\par Belt is cotton.  It is a crop always salable for ready money, not
\par usually subject to great yearly fluctuations in price, and one which
\par the Negroes know how to raise.  The landlord therefore demands his rent
\par in cotton, and the merchant will accept mortgages on no other crop.
\par There is no use asking the black tenant, then, to diversify his
\par crops,--he cannot under this system.  Moreover, the system is bound to
\par bankrupt the tenant.  I remember once meeting a little one-mule wagon
\par on the River road.  A young black fellow sat in it driving listlessly,
\par his elbows on his knees.  His dark-faced wife sat beside him, stolid,
\par silent.
\par 
\par "Hello!" cried my driver,--he has a most imprudent way of addressing
\par these people, though they seem used to it,--"what have you got there?"
\par 
\par "Meat and meal," answered the man, stopping.  The meat lay uncovered in
\par the bottom of the wagon,--a great thin side of fat pork covered with
\par salt; the meal was in a white bushel bag.
\par 
\par "What did you pay for that meat?"
\par 
\par "Ten cents a pound."  It could have been bought for six or seven cents
\par cash.
\par 
\par "And the meal?"
\par 
\par "Two dollars."  One dollar and ten cents is the cash price in town.
\par Here was a man paying five dollars for goods which he could have bought
\par for three dollars cash, and raised for one dollar or one dollar and a
\par half.
\par 
\par Yet it is not wholly his fault.  The Negro farmer started
\par behind,--started in debt.  This was not his choosing, but the crime of
\par this happy-go-lucky nation which goes blundering along with its
\par Reconstruction tragedies, its Spanish war interludes and Philippine
\par matinees, just as though God really were dead.  Once in debt, it is no
\par easy matter for a whole race to emerge.
\par 
\par In the year of low-priced cotton, 1898, out of three hundred tenant
\par families one hundred and seventy-five ended their year's work in debt
\par to the extent of fourteen thousand dollars; fifty cleared nothing, and
\par the remaining seventy-five made a total profit of sixteen hundred
\par dollars.  The net indebtedness of the black tenant families of the
\par whole county must have been at least sixty thousand dollars.  In a more
\par prosperous year the situation is far better; but on the average the
\par majority of tenants end the year even, or in debt, which means that
\par they work for board and clothes.  Such an economic organization is
\par radically wrong.  Whose is the blame?
\par 
\par The underlying causes of this situation are complicated but
\par discernible.  And one of the chief, outside the carelessness of the
\par nation in letting the slave start with nothing, is the widespread
\par opinion among the merchants and employers of the Black Belt that only
\par by the slavery of debt can the Negro be kept at work.  Without doubt,
\par some pressure was necessary at the beginning of the free-labor system
\par to keep the listless and lazy at work; and even to-day the mass of the
\par Negro laborers need stricter guardianship than most Northern laborers.
\par Behind this honest and widespread opinion dishonesty and cheating of
\par the ignorant laborers have a good chance to take refuge.  And to all
\par this must be added the obvious fact that a slave ancestry and a system
\par of unrequited toil has not improved the efficiency or temper of the
\par mass of black laborers.  Nor is this peculiar to Sambo; it has in
\par history been just as true of John and Hans, of Jacques and Pat, of all
\par ground-down peasantries.  Such is the situation of the mass of the
\par Negroes in the Black Belt to-day; and they are thinking about it.
\par Crime, and a cheap and dangerous socialism, are the inevitable results
\par of this pondering.  I see now that ragged black man sitting on a log,
\par aimlessly whittling a stick.  He muttered to me with the murmur of many
\par ages, when he said: "White man sit down whole year; Nigger work day and
\par night and make crop; Nigger hardly gits bread and meat; white man
\par sittin' down gits all. It's wrong." And what do the better classes of
\par Negroes do to improve their situation?  One of two things: if any way
\par possible, they buy land; if not, they migrate to town.  Just as
\par centuries ago it was no easy thing for the serf to escape into the
\par freedom of town-life, even so to-day there are hindrances laid in the
\par way of county laborers.  In considerable parts of all the Gulf States,
\par and especially in Mississippi, Louisiana, and Arkansas, the Negroes on
\par the plantations in the back-country districts are still held at forced
\par labor practically without wages.  Especially is this true in districts
\par where the farmers are composed of the more ignorant class of poor
\par whites, and the Negroes are beyond the reach of schools and intercourse
\par with their advancing fellows.  If such a peon should run away, the
\par sheriff, elected by white suffrage, can usually be depended on to catch
\par the fugitive, return him, and ask no questions.  If he escape to
\par another county, a charge of petty thieving, easily true, can be
\par depended upon to secure his return.  Even if some unduly officious
\par person insist upon a trial, neighborly comity will probably make his
\par conviction sure, and then the labor due the county can easily be bought
\par by the master.  Such a system is impossible in the more civilized parts
\par of the South, or near the large towns and cities; but in those vast
\par stretches of land beyond the telegraph and the newspaper the spirit of
\par the Thirteenth Amendment is sadly broken.  This represents the lowest
\par economic depths of the black American peasant; and in a study of the
\par rise and condition of the Negro freeholder we must trace his economic
\par progress from the modern serfdom.
\par 
\par Even in the better-ordered country districts of the South the free
\par movement of agricultural laborers is hindered by the migration-agent
\par laws.  The "Associated Press" recently informed the world of the arrest
\par of a young white man in Southern Georgia who represented the "Atlantic
\par Naval Supplies Company," and who "was caught in the act of enticing
\par hands from the turpentine farm of Mr. John Greer."  The crime for which
\par this young man was arrested is taxed five hundred dollars for each
\par county in which the employment agent proposes to gather laborers for
\par work outside the State.  Thus the Negroes' ignorance of the
\par labor-market outside his own vicinity is increased rather than
\par diminished by the laws of nearly every Southern State.
\par 
\par Similar to such measures is the unwritten law of the back districts and
\par small towns of the South, that the character of all Negroes unknown to
\par the mass of the community must be vouched for by some white man.  This
\par is really a revival of the old Roman idea of the patron under whose
\par protection the new-made freedman was put.  In many instances this
\par system has been of great good to the Negro, and very often under the
\par protection and guidance of the former master's family, or other white
\par friends, the freedman progressed in wealth and morality.  But the same
\par system has in other cases resulted in the refusal of whole communities
\par to recognize the right of a Negro to change his habitation and to be
\par master of his own fortunes.  A black stranger in Baker County, Georgia,
\par for instance, is liable to be stopped anywhere on the public highway
\par and made to state his business to the satisfaction of any white
\par interrogator.  If he fails to give a suitable answer, or seems too
\par independent or "sassy," he may be arrested or summarily driven away.
\par 
\par Thus it is that in the country districts of the South, by written or
\par unwritten law, peonage, hindrances to the migration of labor, and a
\par system of white patronage exists over large areas.  Besides this, the
\par chance for lawless oppression and illegal exactions is vastly greater
\par in the country than in the city, and nearly all the more serious race
\par disturbances of the last decade have arisen from disputes in the count
\par between master and man,--as, for instance, the Sam Hose affair.  As a
\par result of such a situation, there arose, first, the Black Belt; and,
\par second, the Migration to Town.  The Black Belt was not, as many
\par assumed, a movement toward fields of labor under more genial climatic
\par conditions; it was primarily a huddling for self-protection,--a massing
\par of the black population for mutual defence in order to secure the peace
\par and tranquillity necessary to economic advance.  This movement took
\par place between Emancipation and 1880, and only partially accomplished
\par the desired results.  The rush to town since 1880 is the
\par counter-movement of men disappointed in the economic opportunities of
\par the Black Belt.
\par 
\par In Dougherty County, Georgia, one can see easily the results of this
\par experiment in huddling for protection.  Only ten per cent of the adult
\par population was born in the county, and yet the blacks outnumber the
\par whites four or five to one.  There is undoubtedly a security to the
\par blacks in their very numbers,--a personal freedom from arbitrary
\par treatment, which makes hundreds of laborers cling to Dougherty in spite
\par of low wages and economic distress.  But a change is coming, and slowly
\par but surely even here the agricultural laborers are drifting to town and
\par leaving the broad acres behind.  Why is this?  Why do not the Negroes
\par become land-owners, and build up the black landed peasantry, which has
\par for a generation and more been the dream of philanthropist and
\par statesman?
\par 
\par To the car-window sociologist, to the man who seeks to understand and
\par know the South by devoting the few leisure hours of a holiday trip to
\par unravelling the snarl of centuries,--to such men very often the whole
\par trouble with the black field-hand may be summed up by Aunt Ophelia's
\par word, "Shiftless!"  They have noted repeatedly scenes like one I saw
\par last summer.  We were riding along the highroad to town at the close of
\par a long hot day.  A couple of young black fellows passed us in a
\par muleteam, with several bushels of loose corn in the ear.  One was
\par driving, listlessly bent forward, his elbows on his knees,--a
\par happy-go-lucky, careless picture of irresponsibility.  The other was
\par fast asleep in the bottom of the wagon.  As we passed we noticed an ear
\par of corn fall from the wagon.  They never saw it,--not they.  A rod
\par farther on we noted another ear on the ground; and between that
\par creeping mule and town we counted twenty-six ears of corn.  Shiftless?
\par Yes, the personification of shiftlessness.  And yet follow those boys:
\par they are not lazy; to-morrow morning they'll be up with the sun; they
\par work hard when they do work, and they work willingly.  They have no
\par sordid, selfish, money-getting ways, but rather a fine disdain for mere
\par cash.  They'll loaf before your face and work behind your back with
\par good-natured honesty.  They'll steal a watermelon, and hand you back
\par your lost purse intact.  Their great defect as laborers lies in their
\par lack of incentive beyond the mere pleasure of physical exertion.  They
\par are careless because they have not found that it pays to be careful;
\par they are improvident because the improvident ones of their acquaintance
\par get on about as well as the provident.  Above all, they cannot see why
\par they should take unusual pains to make the white man's land better, or
\par to fatten his mule, or save his corn.  On the other hand, the white
\par land-owner argues that any attempt to improve these laborers by
\par increased responsibility, or higher wages, or better homes, or land of
\par their own, would be sure to result in failure.  He shows his Northern
\par visitor the scarred and wretched land; the ruined mansions, the
\par worn-out soil and mortgaged acres, and says, This is Negro freedom!
\par 
\par Now it happens that both master and man have just enough argument on
\par their respective sides to make it difficult for them to understand each
\par other.  The Negro dimly personifies in the white man all his ills and
\par misfortunes; if he is poor, it is because the white man seizes the
\par fruit of his toil; if he is ignorant, it is because the white man gives
\par him neither time nor facilities to learn; and, indeed, if any
\par misfortune happens to him, it is because of some hidden machinations of
\par "white folks."  On the other hand, the masters and the masters' sons
\par have never been able to see why the Negro, instead of settling down to
\par be day-laborers for bread and clothes, are infected with a silly desire
\par to rise in the world, and why they are sulky, dissatisfied, and
\par careless, where their fathers were happy and dumb and faithful.  "Why,
\par you niggers have an easier time than I do," said a puzzled Albany
\par merchant to his black customer.  "Yes," he replied, "and so does yo'
\par hogs."
\par 
\par Taking, then, the dissatisfied and shiftless field-hand as a
\par starting-point, let us inquire how the black thousands of Dougherty
\par have struggled from him up toward their ideal, and what that ideal is.
\par All social struggle is evidenced by the rise, first of economic, then
\par of social classes, among a homogeneous population.  To-day the
\par following economic classes are plainly differentiated among these
\par Negroes.
\par 
\par A "submerged tenth" of croppers, with a few paupers; forty per cent who
\par are metayers and thirty-nine per cent of semi-metayers and
\par wage-laborers.  There are left five per cent of money-renters and six
\par per cent of freeholders,--the "Upper Ten" of the land.  The croppers
\par are entirely without capital, even in the limited sense of food or
\par money to keep them from seed-time to harvest.  All they furnish is
\par their labor; the land-owner furnishes land, stock, tools, seed, and
\par house; and at the end of the year the laborer gets from a third to a
\par half of the crop.  Out of his share, however, comes pay and interest
\par for food and clothing advanced him during the year.  Thus we have a
\par laborer without capital and without wages, and an employer whose
\par capital is largely his employees' wages.  It is an unsatisfactory
\par arrangement, both for hirer and hired, and is usually in vogue on poor
\par land with hard-pressed owners.
\par 
\par Above the croppers come the great mass of the black population who work
\par the land on their own responsibility, paying rent in cotton and
\par supported by the crop-mortgage system.  After the war this system was
\par attractive to the freedmen on account of its larger freedom and its
\par possibility for making a surplus.  But with the carrying out of the
\par crop-lien system, the deterioration of the land, and the slavery of
\par debt, the position of the metayers has sunk to a dead level of
\par practically unrewarded toil.  Formerly all tenants had some capital,
\par and often considerable; but absentee landlordism, rising rack-rent, and
\par failing cotton have stripped them well-nigh of all, and probably not
\par over half of them to-day own their mules.  The change from cropper to
\par tenant was accomplished by fixing the rent.  If, now, the rent fixed
\par was reasonable, this was an incentive to the tenant to strive.  On the
\par other hand, if the rent was too high, or if the land deteriorated, the
\par result was to discourage and check the efforts of the black peasantry.
\par There is no doubt that the latter case is true; that in Dougherty
\par County every economic advantage of the price of cotton in market and of
\par the strivings of the tenant has been taken advantage of by the
\par landlords and merchants, and swallowed up in rent and interest.  If
\par cotton rose in price, the rent rose even higher; if cotton fell, the
\par rent remained or followed reluctantly.  If the tenant worked hard and
\par raised a large crop, his rent was raised the next year; if that year
\par the crop failed, his corn was confiscated and his mule sold for debt.
\par There were, of course, exceptions to this,--cases of personal kindness
\par and forbearance; but in the vast majority of cases the rule was to
\par extract the uttermost farthing from the mass of the black farm laborers.
\par 
\par The average metayer pays from twenty to thirty per cent of his crop in
\par rent.  The result of such rack-rent can only be evil,--abuse and
\par neglect of the soil, deterioration in the character of the laborers,
\par and a widespread sense of injustice.  "Wherever the country is poor,"
\par cried Arthur Young, "it is in the hands of metayers," and "their
\par condition is more wretched than that of day-laborers."  He was talking
\par of Italy a century ago; but he might have been talking of Dougherty
\par County to-day.  And especially is that true to-day which he declares
\par was true in France before the Revolution: "The metayers are considered
\par as little better than menial servants, removable at pleasure, and
\par obliged to conform in all things to the will of the landlords."  On
\par this low plane half the black population of Dougherty County--perhaps
\par more than half the black millions of this land--are to-day struggling.
\par 
\par A degree above these we may place those laborers who receive money
\par wages for their work.  Some receive a house with perhaps a garden-spot;
\par then supplies of food and clothing are advanced, and certain fixed
\par wages are given at the end of the year, varying from thirty to sixty
\par dollars, out of which the supplies must be paid for, with interest.
\par About eighteen per cent of the population belong to this class of
\par semi-metayers, while twenty-two per cent are laborers paid by the month
\par or year, and are either "furnished" by their own savings or perhaps
\par more usually by some merchant who takes his chances of payment.  Such
\par laborers receive from thirty-five to fifty cents a day during the
\par working season.  They are usually young unmarried persons, some being
\par women; and when they marry they sink to the class of metayers, or, more
\par seldom, become renters.
\par 
\par The renters for fixed money rentals are the first of the emerging
\par classes, and form five per cent of the families.  The sole advantage of
\par this small class is their freedom to choose their crops, and the
\par increased responsibility which comes through having money transactions.
\par While some of the renters differ little in condition from the metayers,
\par yet on the whole they are more intelligent and responsible persons, and
\par are the ones who eventually become land-owners.  Their better character
\par and greater shrewdness enable them to gain, perhaps to demand, better
\par terms in rents; rented farms, varying from forty to a hundred acres,
\par bear an average rental of about fifty-four dollars a year.  The men who
\par conduct such farms do not long remain renters; either they sink to
\par metayers, or with a successful series of harvests rise to be
\par land-owners.
\par 
\par In 1870 the tax-books of Dougherty report no Negroes as landholders.
\par If there were any such at that time,--and there may have been a
\par few,--their land was probably held in the name of some white patron,--a
\par method not uncommon during slavery.  In 1875 ownership of land had
\par begun with seven hundred and fifty acres; ten years later this had
\par increased to over sixty-five hundred acres, to nine thousand acres in
\par 1890 and ten thousand in 1900.  The total assessed property has in this
\par same period risen from eighty thousand dollars in 1875 to two hundred
\par and forty thousand dollars in 1900.
\par 
\par Two circumstances complicate this development and make it in some
\par respects difficult to be sure of the real tendencies; they are the
\par panic of 1893, and the low price of cotton in 1898.  Besides this, the
\par system of assessing property in the country districts of Georgia is
\par somewhat antiquated and of uncertain statistical value; there are no
\par assessors, and each man makes a sworn return to a tax-receiver.  Thus
\par public opinion plays a large part, and the returns vary strangely from
\par year to year.  Certainly these figures show the small amount of
\par accumulated capital among the Negroes, and the consequent large
\par dependence of their property on temporary prosperity.  They have little
\par to tide over a few years of economic depression, and are at the mercy
\par of the cotton-market far more than the whites.  And thus the
\par land-owners, despite their marvellous efforts, are really a transient
\par class, continually being depleted by those who fall back into the class
\par of renters or metayers, and augmented by newcomers from the masses.  Of
\par one hundred land-owners in 1898, half had bought their land since 1893,
\par a fourth between 1890 and 1893, a fifth between 1884 and 1890, and the
\par rest between 1870 and 1884.  In all, one hundred and eighty-five
\par Negroes have owned land in this county since 1875.
\par 
\par If all the black land-owners who had ever held land here had kept it or
\par left it in the hands of black men, the Negroes would have owned nearer
\par thirty thousand acres than the fifteen thousand they now hold.  And yet
\par these fifteen thousand acres are a creditable showing,--a proof of no
\par little weight of the worth and ability of the Negro people.  If they
\par had been given an economic start at Emancipation, if they had been in
\par an enlightened and rich community which really desired their best good,
\par then we might perhaps call such a result small or even insignificant.
\par But for a few thousand poor ignorant field-hands, in the face of
\par poverty, a falling market, and social stress, to save and capitalize
\par two hundred thousand dollars in a generation has meant a tremendous
\par effort.  The rise of a nation, the pressing forward of a social class,
\par means a bitter struggle, a hard and soul-sickening battle with the
\par world such as few of the more favored classes know or appreciate.
\par 
\par Out of the hard economic conditions of this portion of the Black Belt,
\par only six per cent of the population have succeeded in emerging into
\par peasant proprietorship; and these are not all firmly fixed, but grow
\par and shrink in number with the wavering of the cotton-market.  Fully
\par ninety-four per cent have struggled for land and failed, and half of
\par them sit in hopeless serfdom.  For these there is one other avenue of
\par escape toward which they have turned in increasing numbers, namely,
\par migration to town.  A glance at the distribution of land among the
\par black owners curiously reveals this fact.  In 1898 the holdings were as
\par follows: Under forty acres, forty-nine families; forty to two hundred
\par and fifty acres, seventeen families; two hundred and fifty to one
\par thousand acres, thirteen families; one thousand or more acres, two
\par families.  Now in 1890 there were forty-four holdings, but only nine of
\par these were under forty acres.  The great increase of holdings, then,
\par has come in the buying of small homesteads near town, where their
\par owners really share in the town life; this is a part of the rush to
\par town.  And for every land-owner who has thus hurried away from the
\par narrow and hard conditions of country life, how many field-hands, how
\par many tenants, how many ruined renters, have joined that long
\par procession?  Is it not strange compensation?  The sin of the country
\par districts is visited on the town, and the social sores of city life
\par to-day may, here in Dougherty County, and perhaps in many places near
\par and far, look for their final healing without the city walls.
\par 
