\par IX
\par 
\par Of the Sons of Master and Man
\par 
\par   Life treads on life, and heart on heart;
\par   We press too close in church and mart
\par   To keep a dream or grave apart.
\par 
\par   MRS. BROWNING.
\par 
\par 
\par The world-old phenomenon of the contact of diverse races of men is to
\par have new exemplification during the new century.  Indeed, the
\par characteristic of our age is the contact of European civilization with
\par the world's undeveloped peoples.  Whatever we may say of the results of
\par such contact in the past, it certainly forms a chapter in human action
\par not pleasant to look back upon.  War, murder, slavery, extermination,
\par and debauchery,--this has again and again been the result of carrying
\par civilization and the blessed gospel to the isles of the sea and the
\par heathen without the law.  Nor does it altogether satisfy the conscience
\par of the modern world to be told complacently that all this has been
\par right and proper, the fated triumph of strength over weakness, of
\par righteousness over evil, of superiors over inferiors.  It would
\par certainly be soothing if one could readily believe all this; and yet
\par there are too many ugly facts for everything to be thus easily
\par explained away.  We feel and know that there are many delicate
\par differences in race psychology, numberless changes that our crude
\par social measurements are not yet able to follow minutely, which explain
\par much of history and social development.  At the same time, too, we know
\par that these considerations have never adequately explained or excused
\par the triumph of brute force and cunning over weakness and innocence.
\par 
\par It is, then, the strife of all honorable men of the twentieth century
\par to see that in the future competition of races the survival of the
\par fittest shall mean the triumph of the good, the beautiful, and the
\par true; that we may be able to preserve for future civilization all that
\par is really fine and noble and strong, and not continue to put a premium
\par on greed and impudence and cruelty.  To bring this hope to fruition, we
\par are compelled daily to turn more and more to a conscientious study of
\par the phenomena of race-contact,--to a study frank and fair, and not
\par falsified and colored by our wishes or our fears.  And we have in the
\par South as fine a field for such a study as the world affords,--a field,
\par to be sure, which the average American scientist deems somewhat beneath
\par his dignity, and which the average man who is not a scientist knows all
\par about, but nevertheless a line of study which by reason of the enormous
\par race complications with which God seems about to punish this nation
\par must increasingly claim our sober attention, study, and thought, we
\par must ask, what are the actual relations of whites and blacks in the
\par South? and we must be answered, not by apology or fault-finding, but by
\par a plain, unvarnished tale.
\par 
\par In the civilized life of to-day the contact of men and their relations
\par to each other fall in a few main lines of action and communication:
\par there is, first, the physical proximity of home and dwelling-places,
\par the way in which neighborhoods group themselves, and the contiguity of
\par neighborhoods.  Secondly, and in our age chiefest, there are the
\par economic relations,--the methods by which individuals cooperate for
\par earning a living, for the mutual satisfaction of wants, for the
\par production of wealth.  Next, there are the political relations, the
\par cooperation in social control, in group government, in laying and
\par paying the burden of taxation.  In the fourth place there are the less
\par tangible but highly important forms of intellectual contact and
\par commerce, the interchange of ideas through conversation and conference,
\par through periodicals and libraries; and, above all, the gradual
\par formation for each community of that curious tertium quid which we call
\par public opinion.  Closely allied with this come the various forms of
\par social contact in everyday life, in travel, in theatres, in house
\par gatherings, in marrying and giving in marriage.  Finally, there are the
\par varying forms of religious enterprise, of moral teaching and benevolent
\par endeavor.  These are the principal ways in which men living in the same
\par communities are brought into contact with each other.  It is my present
\par task, therefore, to indicate, from my point of view, how the black race
\par in the South meet and mingle with the whites in these matters of
\par everyday life.
\par 
\par First, as to physical dwelling.  It is usually possible to draw in
\par nearly every Southern community a physical color-line on the map, on
\par the one side of which whites dwell and on the other Negroes.  The
\par winding and intricacy of the geographical color-line varies, of course,
\par in different communities.  I know some towns where a straight line
\par drawn through the middle of the main street separates nine-tenths of
\par the whites from nine-tenths of the blacks.  In other towns the older
\par settlement of whites has been encircled by a broad band of blacks; in
\par still other cases little settlements or nuclei of blacks have sprung up
\par amid surrounding whites.  Usually in cities each street has its
\par distinctive color, and only now and then do the colors meet in close
\par proximity.  Even in the country something of this segregation is
\par manifest in the smaller areas, and of course in the larger phenomena of
\par the Black Belt.
\par 
\par All this segregation by color is largely independent of that natural
\par clustering by social grades common to all communities.  A Negro slum
\par may be in dangerous proximity to a white residence quarter, while it is
\par quite common to find a white slum planted in the heart of a respectable
\par Negro district.  One thing, however, seldom occurs: the best of the
\par whites and the best of the Negroes almost never live in anything like
\par close proximity.  It thus happens that in nearly every Southern town
\par and city, both whites and blacks see commonly the worst of each other.
\par This is a vast change from the situation in the past, when, through the
\par close contact of master and house-servant in the patriarchal big house,
\par one found the best of both races in close contact and sympathy, while
\par at the same time the squalor and dull round of toil among the
\par field-hands was removed from the sight and hearing of the family.  One
\par can easily see how a person who saw slavery thus from his father's
\par parlors, and sees freedom on the streets of a great city, fails to
\par grasp or comprehend the whole of the new picture.  On the other hand,
\par the settled belief of the mass of the Negroes that the Southern white
\par people do not have the black man's best interests at heart has been
\par intensified in later years by this continual daily contact of the
\par better class of blacks with the worst representatives of the white race.
\par 
\par Coming now to the economic relations of the races, we are on ground
\par made familiar by study, much discussion, and no little philanthropic
\par effort.  And yet with all this there are many essential elements in the
\par cooperation of Negroes and whites for work and wealth that are too
\par readily overlooked or not thoroughly understood.  The average American
\par can easily conceive of a rich land awaiting development and filled with
\par black laborers.  To him the Southern problem is simply that of making
\par efficient workingmen out of this material, by giving them the requisite
\par technical skill and the help of invested capital.  The problem,
\par however, is by no means as simple as this, from the obvious fact that
\par these workingmen have been trained for centuries as slaves.  They
\par exhibit, therefore, all the advantages and defects of such training;
\par they are willing and good-natured, but not self-reliant, provident, or
\par careful.  If now the economic development of the South is to be pushed
\par to the verge of exploitation, as seems probable, then we have a mass of
\par workingmen thrown into relentless competition with the workingmen of
\par the world, but handicapped by a training the very opposite to that of
\par the modern self-reliant democratic laborer.  What the black laborer
\par needs is careful personal guidance, group leadership of men with hearts
\par in their bosoms, to train them to foresight, carefulness, and honesty.
\par Nor does it require any fine-spun theories of racial differences to
\par prove the necessity of such group training after the brains of the race
\par have been knocked out by two hundred and fifty years of assiduous
\par education in submission, carelessness, and stealing.  After
\par Emancipation, it was the plain duty of some one to assume this group
\par leadership and training of the Negro laborer.  I will not stop here to
\par inquire whose duty it was--whether that of the white ex-master who had
\par profited by unpaid toil, or the Northern philanthropist whose
\par persistence brought on the crisis, or the National Government whose
\par edict freed the bondmen; I will not stop to ask whose duty it was, but
\par I insist it was the duty of some one to see that these workingmen were
\par not left alone and unguided, without capital, without land, without
\par skill, without economic organization, without even the bald protection
\par of law, order, and decency,--left in a great land, not to settle down
\par to slow and careful internal development, but destined to be thrown
\par almost immediately into relentless and sharp competition with the best
\par of modern workingmen under an economic system where every participant
\par is fighting for himself, and too often utterly regardless of the rights
\par or welfare of his neighbor.
\par 
\par For we must never forget that the economic system of the South to-day
\par which has succeeded the old regime is not the same system as that of
\par the old industrial North, of England, or of France, with their
\par trade-unions, their restrictive laws, their written and unwritten
\par commercial customs, and their long experience.  It is, rather, a copy
\par of that England of the early nineteenth century, before the factory
\par acts,--the England that wrung pity from thinkers and fired the wrath of
\par Carlyle.  The rod of empire that passed from the hands of Southern
\par gentlemen in 1865, partly by force, partly by their own petulance, has
\par never returned to them.  Rather it has passed to those men who have
\par come to take charge of the industrial exploitation of the New
\par South,--the sons of poor whites fired with a new thirst for wealth and
\par power, thrifty and avaricious Yankees, and unscrupulous immigrants.
\par Into the hands of these men the Southern laborers, white and black,
\par have fallen; and this to their sorrow.  For the laborers as such, there
\par is in these new captains of industry neither love nor hate, neither
\par sympathy nor romance; it is a cold question of dollars and dividends.
\par Under such a system all labor is bound to suffer.  Even the white
\par laborers are not yet intelligent, thrifty, and well trained enough to
\par maintain themselves against the powerful inroads of organized capital.
\par The results among them, even, are long hours of toil, low wages, child
\par labor, and lack of protection against usury and cheating.  But among
\par the black laborers all this is aggravated, first, by a race prejudice
\par which varies from a doubt and distrust among the best element of whites
\par to a frenzied hatred among the worst; and, secondly, it is aggravated,
\par as I have said before, by the wretched economic heritage of the
\par freedmen from slavery.  With this training it is difficult for the
\par freedman to learn to grasp the opportunities already opened to him, and
\par the new opportunities are seldom given him, but go by favor to the
\par whites.
\par 
\par Left by the best elements of the South with little protection or
\par oversight, he has been made in law and custom the victim of the worst
\par and most unscrupulous men in each community.  The crop-lien system
\par which is depopulating the fields of the South is not simply the result
\par of shiftlessness on the part of Negroes, but is also the result of
\par cunningly devised laws as to mortgages, liens, and misdemeanors, which
\par can be made by conscienceless men to entrap and snare the unwary until
\par escape is impossible, further toil a farce, and protest a crime.  I
\par have seen, in the Black Belt of Georgia, an ignorant, honest Negro buy
\par and pay for a farm in installments three separate times, and then in
\par the face of law and decency the enterprising American who sold it to
\par him pocketed the money and deed and left the black man landless, to
\par labor on his own land at thirty cents a day.  I have seen a black
\par farmer fall in debt to a white storekeeper, and that storekeeper go to
\par his farm and strip it of every single marketable article,--mules,
\par ploughs, stored crops, tools, furniture, bedding, clocks,
\par looking-glass,--and all this without a sheriff or officer, in the face
\par of the law for homestead exemptions, and without rendering to a single
\par responsible person any account or reckoning.  And such proceedings can
\par happen, and will happen, in any community where a class of ignorant
\par toilers are placed by custom and race-prejudice beyond the pale of
\par sympathy and race-brotherhood.  So long as the best elements of a
\par community do not feel in duty bound to protect and train and care for
\par the weaker members of their group, they leave them to be preyed upon by
\par these swindlers and rascals.
\par 
\par This unfortunate economic situation does not mean the hindrance of all
\par advance in the black South, or the absence of a class of black
\par landlords and mechanics who, in spite of disadvantages, are
\par accumulating property and making good citizens.  But it does mean that
\par this class is not nearly so large as a fairer economic system might
\par easily make it, that those who survive in the competition are
\par handicapped so as to accomplish much less than they deserve to, and
\par that, above all, the personnel of the successful class is left to
\par chance and accident, and not to any intelligent culling or reasonable
\par methods of selection.  As a remedy for this, there is but one possible
\par procedure.  We must accept some of the race prejudice in the South as a
\par fact,--deplorable in its intensity, unfortunate in results, and
\par dangerous for the future, but nevertheless a hard fact which only time
\par can efface.  We cannot hope, then, in this generation, or for several
\par generations, that the mass of the whites can be brought to assume that
\par close sympathetic and self-sacrificing leadership of the blacks which
\par their present situation so eloquently demands.  Such leadership, such
\par social teaching and example, must come from the blacks themselves.  For
\par some time men doubted as to whether the Negro could develop such
\par leaders; but to-day no one seriously disputes the capability of
\par individual Negroes to assimilate the culture and common sense of modern
\par civilization, and to pass it on, to some extent at least, to their
\par fellows.  If this is true, then here is the path out of the economic
\par situation, and here is the imperative demand for trained Negro leaders
\par of character and intelligence,--men of skill, men of light and leading,
\par college-bred men, black captains of industry, and missionaries of
\par culture; men who thoroughly comprehend and know modern civilization,
\par and can take hold of Negro communities and raise and train them by
\par force of precept and example, deep sympathy, and the inspiration of
\par common blood and ideals.  But if such men are to be effective they must
\par have some power,--they must be backed by the best public opinion of
\par these communities, and able to wield for their objects and aims such
\par weapons as the experience of the world has taught are indispensable to
\par human progress.
\par 
\par Of such weapons the greatest, perhaps, in the modern world is the power
\par of the ballot; and this brings me to a consideration of the third form
\par of contact between whites and blacks in the South,--political activity.
\par 
\par In the attitude of the American mind toward Negro suffrage can be
\par traced with unusual accuracy the prevalent conceptions of government.
\par In the fifties we were near enough the echoes of the French Revolution
\par to believe pretty thoroughly in universal suffrage.  We argued, as we
\par thought then rather logically, that no social class was so good, so
\par true, and so disinterested as to be trusted wholly with the political
\par destiny of its neighbors; that in every state the best arbiters of
\par their own welfare are the persons directly affected; consequently that
\par it is only by arming every hand with a ballot,--with the right to have
\par a voice in the policy of the state,--that the greatest good to the
\par greatest number could be attained.  To be sure, there were objections
\par to these arguments, but we thought we had answered them tersely and
\par convincingly; if some one complained of the ignorance of voters, we
\par answered, "Educate them."  If another complained of their venality, we
\par replied, "Disfranchise them or put them in jail."  And, finally, to the
\par men who feared demagogues and the natural perversity of some human
\par beings we insisted that time and bitter experience would teach the most
\par hardheaded.  It was at this time that the question of Negro suffrage in
\par the South was raised.  Here was a defenceless people suddenly made
\par free.  How were they to be protected from those who did not believe in
\par their freedom and were determined to thwart it?  Not by force, said the
\par North; not by government guardianship, said the South; then by the
\par ballot, the sole and legitimate defence of a free people, said the
\par Common Sense of the Nation.  No one thought, at the time, that the
\par ex-slaves could use the ballot intelligently or very effectively; but
\par they did think that the possession of so great power by a great class
\par in the nation would compel their fellows to educate this class to its
\par intelligent use.
\par 
\par Meantime, new thoughts came to the nation: the inevitable period of
\par moral retrogression and political trickery that ever follows in the
\par wake of war overtook us.  So flagrant became the political scandals
\par that reputable men began to leave politics alone, and politics
\par consequently became disreputable.  Men began to pride themselves on
\par having nothing to do with their own government, and to agree tacitly
\par with those who regarded public office as a private perquisite.  In this
\par state of mind it became easy to wink at the suppression of the Negro
\par vote in the South, and to advise self-respecting Negroes to leave
\par politics entirely alone.  The decent and reputable citizens of the
\par North who neglected their own civic duties grew hilarious over the
\par exaggerated importance with which the Negro regarded the franchise.
\par Thus it easily happened that more and more the better class of Negroes
\par followed the advice from abroad and the pressure from home, and took no
\par further interest in politics, leaving to the careless and the venal of
\par their race the exercise of their rights as voters.  The black vote that
\par still remained was not trained and educated, but further debauched by
\par open and unblushing bribery, or force and fraud; until the Negro voter
\par was thoroughly inoculated with the idea that politics was a method of
\par private gain by disreputable means.
\par 
\par And finally, now, to-day, when we are awakening to the fact that the
\par perpetuity of republican institutions on this continent depends on the
\par purification of the ballot, the civic training of voters, and the
\par raising of voting to the plane of a solemn duty which a patriotic
\par citizen neglects to his peril and to the peril of his children's
\par children,--in this day, when we are striving for a renaissance of civic
\par virtue, what are we going to say to the black voter of the South?  Are
\par we going to tell him still that politics is a disreputable and useless
\par form of human activity?  Are we going to induce the best class of
\par Negroes to take less and less interest in government, and to give up
\par their right to take such an interest, without a protest?  I am not
\par saying a word against all legitimate efforts to purge the ballot of
\par ignorance, pauperism, and crime.  But few have pretended that the
\par present movement for disfranchisement in the South is for such a
\par purpose; it has been plainly and frankly declared in nearly every case
\par that the object of the disfranchising laws is the elimination of the
\par black man from politics.
\par 
\par Now, is this a minor matter which has no influence on the main question
\par of the industrial and intellectual development of the Negro?  Can we
\par establish a mass of black laborers and artisans and landholders in the
\par South who, by law and public opinion, have absolutely no voice in
\par shaping the laws under which they live and work?  Can the modern
\par organization of industry, assuming as it does free democratic
\par government and the power and ability of the laboring classes to compel
\par respect for their welfare,--can this system be carried out in the South
\par when half its laboring force is voiceless in the public councils and
\par powerless in its own defence?  To-day the black man of the South has
\par almost nothing to say as to how much he shall be taxed, or how those
\par taxes shall be expended; as to who shall execute the laws, and how they
\par shall do it; as to who shall make the laws, and how they shall be made.
\par It is pitiable that frantic efforts must be made at critical times to
\par get law-makers in some States even to listen to the respectful
\par presentation of the black man's side of a current controversy.  Daily
\par the Negro is coming more and more to look upon law and justice, not as
\par protecting safeguards, but as sources of humiliation and oppression.
\par The laws are made by men who have little interest in him; they are
\par executed by men who have absolutely no motive for treating the black
\par people with courtesy or consideration; and, finally, the accused
\par law-breaker is tried, not by his peers, but too often by men who would
\par rather punish ten innocent Negroes than let one guilty one escape.
\par 
\par I should be the last one to deny the patent weaknesses and shortcomings
\par of the Negro people; I should be the last to withhold sympathy from the
\par white South in its efforts to solve its intricate social problems.  I
\par freely acknowledged that it is possible, and sometimes best, that a
\par partially undeveloped people should be ruled by the best of their
\par stronger and better neighbors for their own good, until such time as
\par they can start and fight the world's battles alone.  I have already
\par pointed out how sorely in need of such economic and spiritual guidance
\par the emancipated Negro was, and I am quite willing to admit that if the
\par representatives of the best white Southern public opinion were the
\par ruling and guiding powers in the South to-day the conditions indicated
\par would be fairly well fulfilled.  But the point I have insisted upon and
\par now emphasize again, is that the best opinion of the South to-day is
\par not the ruling opinion.  That to leave the Negro helpless and without a
\par ballot to-day is to leave him not to the guidance of the best, but
\par rather to the exploitation and debauchment of the worst; that this is
\par no truer of the South than of the North,--of the North than of Europe:
\par in any land, in any country under modern free competition, to lay any
\par class of weak and despised people, be they white, black, or blue, at
\par the political mercy of their stronger, richer, and more resourceful
\par fellows, is a temptation which human nature seldom has withstood and
\par seldom will withstand.
\par 
\par Moreover, the political status of the Negro in the South is closely
\par connected with the question of Negro crime.  There can be no doubt that
\par crime among Negroes has sensibly increased in the last thirty years,
\par and that there has appeared in the slums of great cities a distinct
\par criminal class among the blacks.  In explaining this unfortunate
\par development, we must note two things: (1) that the inevitable result of
\par Emancipation was to increase crime and criminals, and (2) that the
\par police system of the South was primarily designed to control slaves.
\par As to the first point, we must not forget that under a strict slave
\par system there can scarcely be such a thing as crime.  But when these
\par variously constituted human particles are suddenly thrown broadcast on
\par the sea of life, some swim, some sink, and some hang suspended, to be
\par forced up or down by the chance currents of a busy hurrying world.  So
\par great an economic and social revolution as swept the South in '63 meant
\par a weeding out among the Negroes of the incompetents and vicious, the
\par beginning of a differentiation of social grades.  Now a rising group of
\par people are not lifted bodily from the ground like an inert solid mass,
\par but rather stretch upward like a living plant with its roots still
\par clinging in the mould.  The appearance, therefore, of the Negro
\par criminal was a phenomenon to be awaited; and while it causes anxiety,
\par it should not occasion surprise.
\par 
\par Here again the hope for the future depended peculiarly on careful and
\par delicate dealing with these criminals.  Their offences at first were
\par those of laziness, carelessness, and impulse, rather than of malignity
\par or ungoverned viciousness.  Such misdemeanors needed discriminating
\par treatment, firm but reformatory, with no hint of injustice, and full
\par proof of guilt.  For such dealing with criminals, white or black, the
\par South had no machinery, no adequate jails or reformatories; its police
\par system was arranged to deal with blacks alone, and tacitly assumed that
\par every white man was ipso facto a member of that police.  Thus grew up a
\par double system of justice, which erred on the white side by undue
\par leniency and the practical immunity of red-handed criminals, and erred
\par on the black side by undue severity, injustice, and lack of
\par discrimination.  For, as I have said, the police system of the South
\par was originally designed to keep track of all Negroes, not simply of
\par criminals; and when the Negroes were freed and the whole South was
\par convinced of the impossibility of free Negro labor, the first and
\par almost universal device was to use the courts as a means of reenslaving
\par the blacks.  It was not then a question of crime, but rather one of
\par color, that settled a man's conviction on almost any charge.  Thus
\par Negroes came to look upon courts as instruments of injustice and
\par oppression, and upon those convicted in them as martyrs and victims.
\par 
\par When, now, the real Negro criminal appeared, and instead of petty
\par stealing and vagrancy we began to have highway robbery, burglary,
\par murder, and rape, there was a curious effect on both sides the
\par color-line: the Negroes refused to believe the evidence of white
\par witnesses or the fairness of white juries, so that the greatest
\par deterrent to crime, the public opinion of one's own social caste, was
\par lost, and the criminal was looked upon as crucified rather than hanged.
\par On the other hand, the whites, used to being careless as to the guilt
\par or innocence of accused Negroes, were swept in moments of passion
\par beyond law, reason, and decency.  Such a situation is bound to increase
\par crime, and has increased it.  To natural viciousness and vagrancy are
\par being daily added motives of revolt and revenge which stir up all the
\par latent savagery of both races and make peaceful attention to economic
\par development often impossible.
\par 
\par But the chief problem in any community cursed with crime is not the
\par punishment of the criminals, but the preventing of the young from being
\par trained to crime.  And here again the peculiar conditions of the South
\par have prevented proper precautions.  I have seen twelve-year-old boys
\par working in chains on the public streets of Atlanta, directly in front
\par of the schools, in company with old and hardened criminals; and this
\par indiscriminate mingling of men and women and children makes the
\par chain-gangs perfect schools of crime and debauchery.  The struggle for
\par reformatories, which has gone on in Virginia, Georgia, and other
\par States, is the one encouraging sign of the awakening of some
\par communities to the suicidal results of this policy.
\par 
\par It is the public schools, however, which can be made, outside the
\par homes, the greatest means of training decent self-respecting citizens.
\par We have been so hotly engaged recently in discussing trade-schools and
\par the higher education that the pitiable plight of the public-school
\par system in the South has almost dropped from view.  Of every five
\par dollars spent for public education in the State of Georgia, the white
\par schools get four dollars and the Negro one dollar; and even then the
\par white public-school system, save in the cities, is bad and cries for
\par reform.  If this is true of the whites, what of the blacks?  I am
\par becoming more and more convinced, as I look upon the system of
\par common-school training in the South, that the national government must
\par soon step in and aid popular education in some way.  To-day it has been
\par only by the most strenuous efforts on the part of the thinking men of
\par the South that the Negro's share of the school fund has not been cut
\par down to a pittance in some half-dozen States; and that movement not
\par only is not dead, but in many communities is gaining strength.  What in
\par the name of reason does this nation expect of a people, poorly trained
\par and hard pressed in severe economic competition, without political
\par rights, and with ludicrously inadequate common-school facilities?  What
\par can it expect but crime and listlessness, offset here and there by the
\par dogged struggles of the fortunate and more determined who are
\par themselves buoyed by the hope that in due time the country will come to
\par its senses?
\par 
\par I have thus far sought to make clear the physical, economic, and
\par political relations of the Negroes and whites in the South, as I have
\par conceived them, including, for the reasons set forth, crime and
\par education.  But after all that has been said on these more tangible
\par matters of human contact, there still remains a part essential to a
\par proper description of the South which it is difficult to describe or
\par fix in terms easily understood by strangers.  It is, in fine, the
\par atmosphere of the land, the thought and feeling, the thousand and one
\par little actions which go to make up life.  In any community or nation it
\par is these little things which are most elusive to the grasp and yet most
\par essential to any clear conception of the group life taken as a whole.
\par What is thus true of all communities is peculiarly true of the South,
\par where, outside of written history and outside of printed law, there has
\par been going on for a generation as deep a storm and stress of human
\par souls, as intense a ferment of feeling, as intricate a writhing of
\par spirit, as ever a people experienced.  Within and without the sombre
\par veil of color vast social forces have been at work,--efforts for human
\par betterment, movements toward disintegration and despair, tragedies and
\par comedies in social and economic life, and a swaying and lifting and
\par sinking of human hearts which have made this land a land of mingled
\par sorrow and joy, of change and excitement and unrest.
\par 
\par The centre of this spiritual turmoil has ever been the millions of
\par black freedmen and their sons, whose destiny is so fatefully bound up
\par with that of the nation.  And yet the casual observer visiting the
\par South sees at first little of this.  He notes the growing frequency of
\par dark faces as he rides along,--but otherwise the days slip lazily on,
\par the sun shines, and this little world seems as happy and contented as
\par other worlds he has visited.  Indeed, on the question of questions--the
\par Negro problem--he hears so little that there almost seems to be a
\par conspiracy of silence; the morning papers seldom mention it, and then
\par usually in a far-fetched academic way, and indeed almost every one
\par seems to forget and ignore the darker half of the land, until the
\par astonished visitor is inclined to ask if after all there IS any problem
\par here.  But if he lingers long enough there comes the awakening: perhaps
\par in a sudden whirl of passion which leaves him gasping at its bitter
\par intensity; more likely in a gradually dawning sense of things he had
\par not at first noticed.  Slowly but surely his eyes begin to catch the
\par shadows of the color-line: here he meets crowds of Negroes and whites;
\par then he is suddenly aware that he cannot discover a single dark face;
\par or again at the close of a day's wandering he may find himself in some
\par strange assembly, where all faces are tinged brown or black, and where
\par he has the vague, uncomfortable feeling of the stranger.  He realizes
\par at last that silently, resistlessly, the world about flows by him in
\par two great streams: they ripple on in the same sunshine, they approach
\par and mingle their waters in seeming carelessness,--then they divide and
\par flow wide apart.  It is done quietly; no mistakes are made, or if one
\par occurs, the swift arm of the law and of public opinion swings down for
\par a moment, as when the other day a black man and a white woman were
\par arrested for talking together on Whitehall Street in Atlanta.
\par 
\par Now if one notices carefully one will see that between these two
\par worlds, despite much physical contact and daily intermingling, there is
\par almost no community of intellectual life or point of transference where
\par the thoughts and feelings of one race can come into direct contact and
\par sympathy with the thoughts and feelings of the other.  Before and
\par directly after the war, when all the best of the Negroes were domestic
\par servants in the best of the white families, there were bonds of
\par intimacy, affection, and sometimes blood relationship, between the
\par races.  They lived in the same home, shared in the family life, often
\par attended the same church, and talked and conversed with each other.
\par But the increasing civilization of the Negro since then has naturally
\par meant the development of higher classes: there are increasing numbers
\par of ministers, teachers, physicians, merchants, mechanics, and
\par independent farmers, who by nature and training are the aristocracy and
\par leaders of the blacks.  Between them, however, and the best element of
\par the whites, there is little or no intellectual commerce.  They go to
\par separate churches, they live in separate sections, they are strictly
\par separated in all public gatherings, they travel separately, and they
\par are beginning to read different papers and books.  To most libraries,
\par lectures, concerts, and museums, Negroes are either not admitted at
\par all, or on terms peculiarly galling to the pride of the very classes
\par who might otherwise be attracted.  The daily paper chronicles the
\par doings of the black world from afar with no great regard for accuracy;
\par and so on, throughout the category of means for intellectual
\par communication,--schools, conferences, efforts for social betterment,
\par and the like,--it is usually true that the very representatives of the
\par two races, who for mutual benefit and the welfare of the land ought to
\par be in complete understanding and sympathy, are so far strangers that
\par one side thinks all whites are narrow and prejudiced, and the other
\par thinks educated Negroes dangerous and insolent.  Moreover, in a land
\par where the tyranny of public opinion and the intolerance of criticism is
\par for obvious historical reasons so strong as in the South, such a
\par situation is extremely difficult to correct.  The white man, as well as
\par the Negro, is bound and barred by the color-line, and many a scheme of
\par friendliness and philanthropy, of broad-minded sympathy and generous
\par fellowship between the two has dropped still-born because some busybody
\par has forced the color-question to the front and brought the tremendous
\par force of unwritten law against the innovators.
\par 
\par It is hardly necessary for me to add very much in regard to the social
\par contact between the races.  Nothing has come to replace that finer
\par sympathy and love between some masters and house servants which the
\par radical and more uncompromising drawing of the color-line in recent
\par years has caused almost completely to disappear.  In a world where it
\par means so much to take a man by the hand and sit beside him, to look
\par frankly into his eyes and feel his heart beating with red blood; in a
\par world where a social cigar or a cup of tea together means more than
\par legislative halls and magazine articles and speeches,--one can imagine
\par the consequences of the almost utter absence of such social amenities
\par between estranged races, whose separation extends even to parks and
\par streetcars.
\par 
\par Here there can be none of that social going down to the people,--the
\par opening of heart and hand of the best to the worst, in generous
\par acknowledgment of a common humanity and a common destiny.  On the other
\par hand, in matters of simple almsgiving, where there can be no question
\par of social contact, and in the succor of the aged and sick, the South,
\par as if stirred by a feeling of its unfortunate limitations, is generous
\par to a fault.  The black beggar is never turned away without a good deal
\par more than a crust, and a call for help for the unfortunate meets quick
\par response.  I remember, one cold winter, in Atlanta, when I refrained
\par from contributing to a public relief fund lest Negroes should be
\par discriminated against, I afterward inquired of a friend: "Were any
\par black people receiving aid?"  "Why," said he, "they were all black."
\par 
\par And yet this does not touch the kernel of the problem.  Human
\par advancement is not a mere question of almsgiving, but rather of
\par sympathy and cooperation among classes who would scorn charity.  And
\par here is a land where, in the higher walks of life, in all the higher
\par striving for the good and noble and true, the color-line comes to
\par separate natural friends and coworkers; while at the bottom of the
\par social group, in the saloon, the gambling-hell, and the brothel, that
\par same line wavers and disappears.
\par 
\par I have sought to paint an average picture of real relations between the
\par sons of master and man in the South.  I have not glossed over matters
\par for policy's sake, for I fear we have already gone too far in that sort
\par of thing.  On the other hand, I have sincerely sought to let no unfair
\par exaggerations creep in.  I do not doubt that in some Southern
\par communities conditions are better than those I have indicated; while I
\par am no less certain that in other communities they are far worse.
\par 
\par Nor does the paradox and danger of this situation fail to interest and
\par perplex the best conscience of the South.  Deeply religious and
\par intensely democratic as are the mass of the whites, they feel acutely
\par the false position in which the Negro problems place them.  Such an
\par essentially honest-hearted and generous people cannot cite the
\par caste-levelling precepts of Christianity, or believe in equality of
\par opportunity for all men, without coming to feel more and more with each
\par generation that the present drawing of the color-line is a flat
\par contradiction to their beliefs and professions.  But just as often as
\par they come to this point, the present social condition of the Negro
\par stands as a menace and a portent before even the most open-minded: if
\par there were nothing to charge against the Negro but his blackness or
\par other physical peculiarities, they argue, the problem would be
\par comparatively simple; but what can we say to his ignorance,
\par shiftlessness, poverty, and crime?  can a self-respecting group hold
\par anything but the least possible fellowship with such persons and
\par survive? and shall we let a mawkish sentiment sweep away the culture of
\par our fathers or the hope of our children?  The argument so put is of
\par great strength, but it is not a whit stronger than the argument of
\par thinking Negroes: granted, they reply, that the condition of our masses
\par is bad; there is certainly on the one hand adequate historical cause
\par for this, and unmistakable evidence that no small number have, in spite
\par of tremendous disadvantages, risen to the level of American
\par civilization.  And when, by proscription and prejudice, these same
\par Negroes are classed with and treated like the lowest of their people,
\par simply because they are Negroes, such a policy not only discourages
\par thrift and intelligence among black men, but puts a direct premium on
\par the very things you complain of,--inefficiency and crime.  Draw lines
\par of crime, of incompetency, of vice, as tightly and uncompromisingly as
\par you will, for these things must be proscribed; but a color-line not
\par only does not accomplish this purpose, but thwarts it.
\par 
\par In the face of two such arguments, the future of the South depends on
\par the ability of the representatives of these opposing views to see and
\par appreciate and sympathize with each other's position,--for the Negro to
\par realize more deeply than he does at present the need of uplifting the
\par masses of his people, for the white people to realize more vividly than
\par they have yet done the deadening and disastrous effect of a
\par color-prejudice that classes Phillis Wheatley and Sam Hose in the same
\par despised class.
\par 
\par It is not enough for the Negroes to declare that color-prejudice is the
\par sole cause of their social condition, nor for the white South to reply
\par that their social condition is the main cause of prejudice.  They both
\par act as reciprocal cause and effect, and a change in neither alone will
\par bring the desired effect.  Both must change, or neither can improve to
\par any great extent.  The Negro cannot stand the present reactionary
\par tendencies and unreasoning drawing of the color-line indefinitely
\par without discouragement and retrogression.  And the condition of the
\par Negro is ever the excuse for further discrimination.  Only by a union
\par of intelligence and sympathy across the color-line in this critical
\par period of the Republic shall justice and right triumph,
\par 
\par   "That mind and soul according well,
\par   May make one music as before,
\par             But vaster."
\par 
