\par X
\par 
\par Of the Faith of the Fathers
\par 
\par   Dim face of Beauty haunting all the world,
\par     Fair face of Beauty all too fair to see,
\par   Where the lost stars adown the heavens are hurled,--
\par 
\par     There, there alone for thee
\par 
\par     May white peace be.
\par 
\par   Beauty, sad face of Beauty, Mystery, Wonder,
\par     What are these dreams to foolish babbling men
\par   Who cry with little noises 'neath the thunder
\par 
\par     Of Ages ground to sand,
\par 
\par     To a little sand.
\par 
\par   FIONA MACLEOD.
\par 
\par 
\par It was out in the country, far from home, far from my foster home, on a
\par dark Sunday night.  The road wandered from our rambling log-house up
\par the stony bed of a creek, past wheat and corn, until we could hear
\par dimly across the fields a rhythmic cadence of song,--soft, thrilling,
\par powerful, that swelled and died sorrowfully in our ears.  I was a
\par country schoolteacher then, fresh from the East, and had never seen a
\par Southern Negro revival.  To be sure, we in Berkshire were not perhaps
\par as stiff and formal as they in Suffolk of olden time; yet we were very
\par quiet and subdued, and I know not what would have happened those clear
\par Sabbath mornings had some one punctuated the sermon with a wild scream,
\par or interrupted the long prayer with a loud Amen!  And so most striking
\par to me, as I approached the village and the little plain church perched
\par aloft, was the air of intense excitement that possessed that mass of
\par black folk.  A sort of suppressed terror hung in the air and seemed to
\par seize us,--a pythian madness, a demoniac possession, that lent terrible
\par reality to song and word.  The black and massive form of the preacher
\par swayed and quivered as the words crowded to his lips and flew at us in
\par singular eloquence.  The people moaned and fluttered, and then the
\par gaunt-cheeked brown woman beside me suddenly leaped straight into the
\par air and shrieked like a lost soul, while round about came wail and
\par groan and outcry, and a scene of human passion such as I had never
\par conceived before.
\par 
\par Those who have not thus witnessed the frenzy of a Negro revival in the
\par untouched backwoods of the South can but dimly realize the religious
\par feeling of the slave; as described, such scenes appear grotesque and
\par funny, but as seen they are awful.  Three things characterized this
\par religion of the slave,--the Preacher, the Music, and the Frenzy.  The
\par Preacher is the most unique personality developed by the Negro on
\par American soil.  A leader, a politician, an orator, a "boss," an
\par intriguer, an idealist,--all these he is, and ever, too, the centre of
\par a group of men, now twenty, now a thousand in number.  The combination
\par of a certain adroitness with deep-seated earnestness, of tact with
\par consummate ability, gave him his preeminence, and helps him maintain
\par it.  The type, of course, varies according to time and place, from the
\par West Indies in the sixteenth century to New England in the nineteenth,
\par and from the Mississippi bottoms to cities like New Orleans or New York.
\par 
\par The Music of Negro religion is that plaintive rhythmic melody, with its
\par touching minor cadences, which, despite caricature and defilement,
\par still remains the most original and beautiful expression of human life
\par and longing yet born on American soil.  Sprung from the African
\par forests, where its counterpart can still be heard, it was adapted,
\par changed, and intensified by the tragic soul-life of the slave, until,
\par under the stress of law and whip, it became the one true expression of
\par a people's sorrow, despair, and hope.
\par 
\par Finally the Frenzy of "Shouting," when the Spirit of the Lord passed
\par by, and, seizing the devotee, made him mad with supernatural joy, was
\par the last essential of Negro religion and the one more devoutly believed
\par in than all the rest.  It varied in expression from the silent rapt
\par countenance or the low murmur and moan to the mad abandon of physical
\par fervor,--the stamping, shrieking, and shouting, the rushing to and fro
\par and wild waving of arms, the weeping and laughing, the vision and the
\par trance.  All this is nothing new in the world, but old as religion, as
\par Delphi and Endor.  And so firm a hold did it have on the Negro, that
\par many generations firmly believed that without this visible
\par manifestation of the God there could be no true communion with the
\par Invisible.
\par 
\par These were the characteristics of Negro religious life as developed up
\par to the time of Emancipation.  Since under the peculiar circumstances of
\par the black man's environment they were the one expression of his higher
\par life, they are of deep interest to the student of his development, both
\par socially and psychologically.  Numerous are the attractive lines of
\par inquiry that here group themselves.  What did slavery mean to the
\par African savage?  What was his attitude toward the World and Life?  What
\par seemed to him good and evil,--God and Devil?  Whither went his longings
\par and strivings, and wherefore were his heart-burnings and
\par disappointments?  Answers to such questions can come only from a study
\par of Negro religion as a development, through its gradual changes from
\par the heathenism of the Gold Coast to the institutional Negro church of
\par Chicago.
\par 
\par Moreover, the religious growth of millions of men, even though they be
\par slaves, cannot be without potent influence upon their contemporaries.
\par The Methodists and Baptists of America owe much of their condition to
\par the silent but potent influence of their millions of Negro converts.
\par Especially is this noticeable in the South, where theology and
\par religious philosophy are on this account a long way behind the North,
\par and where the religion of the poor whites is a plain copy of Negro
\par thought and methods.  The mass of "gospel" hymns which has swept
\par through American churches and well-nigh ruined our sense of song
\par consists largely of debased imitations of Negro melodies made by ears
\par that caught the jingle but not the music, the body but not the soul, of
\par the Jubilee songs.  It is thus clear that the study of Negro religion
\par is not only a vital part of the history of the Negro in America, but no
\par uninteresting part of American history.
\par 
\par The Negro church of to-day is the social centre of Negro life in the
\par United States, and the most characteristic expression of African
\par character.  Take a typical church in a small Virginia town: it is the
\par "First Baptist"--a roomy brick edifice seating five hundred or more
\par persons, tastefully finished in Georgia pine, with a carpet, a small
\par organ, and stained-glass windows.  Underneath is a large assembly room
\par with benches.  This building is the central club-house of a community
\par of a thousand or more Negroes.  Various organizations meet here,--the
\par church proper, the Sunday-school, two or three insurance societies,
\par women's societies, secret societies, and mass meetings of various
\par kinds.  Entertainments, suppers, and lectures are held beside the five
\par or six regular weekly religious services.  Considerable sums of money
\par are collected and expended here, employment is found for the idle,
\par strangers are introduced, news is disseminated and charity distributed.
\par At the same time this social, intellectual, and economic centre is a
\par religious centre of great power.  Depravity, Sin, Redemption, Heaven,
\par Hell, and Damnation are preached twice a Sunday after the crops are
\par laid by; and few indeed of the community have the hardihood to
\par withstand conversion.  Back of this more formal religion, the Church
\par often stands as a real conserver of morals, a strengthener of family
\par life, and the final authority on what is Good and Right.
\par 
\par Thus one can see in the Negro church to-day, reproduced in microcosm,
\par all the great world from which the Negro is cut off by color-prejudice
\par and social condition.  In the great city churches the same tendency is
\par noticeable and in many respects emphasized.  A great church like the
\par Bethel of Philadelphia has over eleven hundred members, an edifice
\par seating fifteen hundred persons and valued at one hundred thousand
\par dollars, an annual budget of five thousand dollars, and a government
\par consisting of a pastor with several assisting local preachers, an
\par executive and legislative board, financial boards and tax collectors;
\par general church meetings for making laws; sub-divided groups led by
\par class leaders, a company of militia, and twenty-four auxiliary
\par societies.  The activity of a church like this is immense and
\par far-reaching, and the bishops who preside over these organizations
\par throughout the land are among the most powerful Negro rulers in the
\par world.
\par 
\par Such churches are really governments of men, and consequently a little
\par investigation reveals the curious fact that, in the South, at least,
\par practically every American Negro is a church member.  Some, to be sure,
\par are not regularly enrolled, and a few do not habitually attend
\par services; but, practically, a proscribed people must have a social
\par centre, and that centre for this people is the Negro church.  The
\par census of 1890 showed nearly twenty-four thousand Negro churches in the
\par country, with a total enrolled membership of over two and a half
\par millions, or ten actual church members to every twenty-eight persons,
\par and in some Southern States one in every two persons.  Besides these
\par there is the large number who, while not enrolled as members, attend
\par and take part in many of the activities of the church.  There is an
\par organized Negro church for every sixty black families in the nation,
\par and in some States for every forty families, owning, on an average, a
\par thousand dollars' worth of property each, or nearly twenty-six million
\par dollars in all.
\par 
\par Such, then, is the large development of the Negro church since
\par Emancipation.  The question now is, What have been the successive steps
\par of this social history and what are the present tendencies?  First, we
\par must realize that no such institution as the Negro church could rear
\par itself without definite historical foundations.  These foundations we
\par can find if we remember that the social history of the Negro did not
\par start in America.  He was brought from a definite social
\par environment,--the polygamous clan life under the headship of the chief
\par and the potent influence of the priest.  His religion was
\par nature-worship, with profound belief in invisible surrounding
\par influences, good and bad, and his worship was through incantation and
\par sacrifice.  The first rude change in this life was the slave ship and
\par the West Indian sugar-fields.  The plantation organization replaced the
\par clan and tribe, and the white master replaced the chief with far
\par greater and more despotic powers.  Forced and long-continued toil
\par became the rule of life, the old ties of blood relationship and kinship
\par disappeared, and instead of the family appeared a new polygamy and
\par polyandry, which, in some cases, almost reached promiscuity.  It was a
\par terrific social revolution, and yet some traces were retained of the
\par former group life, and the chief remaining institution was the Priest
\par or Medicine-man.  He early appeared on the plantation and found his
\par function as the healer of the sick, the interpreter of the Unknown, the
\par comforter of the sorrowing, the supernatural avenger of wrong, and the
\par one who rudely but picturesquely expressed the longing, disappointment,
\par and resentment of a stolen and oppressed people.  Thus, as bard,
\par physician, judge, and priest, within the narrow limits allowed by the
\par slave system, rose the Negro preacher, and under him the first church
\par was not at first by any means Christian nor definitely organized;
\par rather it was an adaptation and mingling of heathen rites among the
\par members of each plantation, and roughly designated as Voodooism.
\par Association with the masters, missionary effort and motives of
\par expediency gave these rites an early veneer of Christianity, and after
\par the lapse of many generations the Negro church became Christian.
\par 
\par Two characteristic things must be noticed in regard to the church.
\par First, it became almost entirely Baptist and Methodist in faith;
\par secondly, as a social institution it antedated by many decades the
\par monogamic Negro home.  From the very circumstances of its beginning,
\par the church was confined to the plantation, and consisted primarily of a
\par series of disconnected units; although, later on, some freedom of
\par movement was allowed, still this geographical limitation was always
\par important and was one cause of the spread of the decentralized and
\par democratic Baptist faith among the slaves.  At the same time, the
\par visible rite of baptism appealed strongly to their mystic temperament.
\par To-day the Baptist Church is still largest in membership among Negroes,
\par and has a million and a half communicants.  Next in popularity came the
\par churches organized in connection with the white neighboring churches,
\par chiefly Baptist and Methodist, with a few Episcopalian and others.  The
\par Methodists still form the second greatest denomination, with nearly a
\par million members.  The faith of these two leading denominations was more
\par suited to the slave church from the prominence they gave to religious
\par feeling and fervor.  The Negro membership in other denominations has
\par always been small and relatively unimportant, although the
\par Episcopalians and Presbyterians are gaining among the more intelligent
\par classes to-day, and the Catholic Church is making headway in certain
\par sections.  After Emancipation, and still earlier in the North, the
\par Negro churches largely severed such affiliations as they had had with
\par the white churches, either by choice or by compulsion.  The Baptist
\par churches became independent, but the Methodists were compelled early to
\par unite for purposes of episcopal government.  This gave rise to the
\par great African Methodist Church, the greatest Negro organization in the
\par world, to the Zion Church and the Colored Methodist, and to the black
\par conferences and churches in this and other denominations.
\par 
\par The second fact noted, namely, that the Negro church antedates the
\par Negro home, leads to an explanation of much that is paradoxical in this
\par communistic institution and in the morals of its members.  But
\par especially it leads us to regard this institution as peculiarly the
\par expression of the inner ethical life of a people in a sense seldom true
\par elsewhere.  Let us turn, then, from the outer physical development of
\par the church to the more important inner ethical life of the people who
\par compose it.  The Negro has already been pointed out many times as a
\par religious animal,--a being of that deep emotional nature which turns
\par instinctively toward the supernatural.  Endowed with a rich tropical
\par imagination and a keen, delicate appreciation of Nature, the
\par transplanted African lived in a world animate with gods and devils,
\par elves and witches; full of strange influences,--of Good to be implored,
\par of Evil to be propitiated.  Slavery, then, was to him the dark triumph
\par of Evil over him.  All the hateful powers of the Under-world were
\par striving against him, and a spirit of revolt and revenge filled his
\par heart.  He called up all the resources of heathenism to aid,--exorcism
\par and witch-craft, the mysterious Obi worship with its barbarious rites,
\par spells, and blood-sacrifice even, now and then, of human victims.
\par Weird midnight orgies and mystic conjurations were invoked, the
\par witch-woman and the voodoo-priest became the centre of Negro group
\par life, and that vein of vague superstition which characterizes the
\par unlettered Negro even to-day was deepened and strengthened.
\par 
\par In spite, however, of such success as that of the fierce Maroons, the
\par Danish blacks, and others, the spirit of revolt gradually died away
\par under the untiring energy and superior strength of the slave masters.
\par By the middle of the eighteenth century the black slave had sunk, with
\par hushed murmurs, to his place at the bottom of a new economic system,
\par and was unconsciously ripe for a new philosophy of life.  Nothing
\par suited his condition then better than the doctrines of passive
\par submission embodied in the newly learned Christianity.  Slave masters
\par early realized this, and cheerfully aided religious propaganda within
\par certain bounds.  The long system of repression and degradation of the
\par Negro tended to emphasize the elements of his character which made him
\par a valuable chattel: courtesy became humility, moral strength
\par degenerated into submission, and the exquisite native appreciation of
\par the beautiful became an infinite capacity for dumb suffering.  The
\par Negro, losing the joy of this world, eagerly seized upon the offered
\par conceptions of the next; the avenging Spirit of the Lord enjoining
\par patience in this world, under sorrow and tribulation until the Great
\par Day when He should lead His dark children home,--this became his
\par comforting dream.  His preacher repeated the prophecy, and his bards
\par sang,--
\par 
\par   "Children, we all shall be free
\par   When the Lord shall appear!"
\par 
\par 
\par This deep religious fatalism, painted so beautifully in "Uncle Tom,"
\par came soon to breed, as all fatalistic faiths will, the sensualist side
\par by side with the martyr.  Under the lax moral life of the plantation,
\par where marriage was a farce, laziness a virtue, and property a theft, a
\par religion of resignation and submission degenerated easily, in less
\par strenuous minds, into a philosophy of indulgence and crime.  Many of
\par the worst characteristics of the Negro masses of to-day had their seed
\par in this period of the slave's ethical growth.  Here it was that the
\par Home was ruined under the very shadow of the Church, white and black;
\par here habits of shiftlessness took root, and sullen hopelessness
\par replaced hopeful strife.
\par 
\par With the beginning of the abolition movement and the gradual growth of
\par a class of free Negroes came a change.  We often neglect the influence
\par of the freedman before the war, because of the paucity of his numbers
\par and the small weight he had in the history of the nation.  But we must
\par not forget that his chief influence was internal,--was exerted on the
\par black world; and that there he was the ethical and social leader.
\par Huddled as he was in a few centres like Philadelphia, New York, and New
\par Orleans, the masses of the freedmen sank into poverty and listlessness;
\par but not all of them.  The free Negro leader early arose and his chief
\par characteristic was intense earnestness and deep feeling on the slavery
\par question.  Freedom became to him a real thing and not a dream.  His
\par religion became darker and more intense, and into his ethics crept a
\par note of revenge, into his songs a day of reckoning close at hand.  The
\par "Coming of the Lord" swept this side of Death, and came to be a thing
\par to be hoped for in this day.  Through fugitive slaves and irrepressible
\par discussion this desire for freedom seized the black millions still in
\par bondage, and became their one ideal of life.  The black bards caught
\par new notes, and sometimes even dared to sing,--
\par 
\par   "O Freedom, O Freedom, O Freedom over me!
\par   Before I'll be a slave
\par   I'll be buried in my grave,
\par   And go home to my Lord
\par   And be free."
\par 
\par 
\par For fifty years Negro religion thus transformed itself and identified
\par itself with the dream of Abolition, until that which was a radical fad
\par in the white North and an anarchistic plot in the white South had
\par become a religion to the black world.  Thus, when Emancipation finally
\par came, it seemed to the freedman a literal Coming of the Lord.  His
\par fervid imagination was stirred as never before, by the tramp of armies,
\par the blood and dust of battle, and the wail and whirl of social
\par upheaval.  He stood dumb and motionless before the whirlwind: what had
\par he to do with it?  Was it not the Lord's doing, and marvellous in his
\par eyes?  Joyed and bewildered with what came, he stood awaiting new
\par wonders till the inevitable Age of Reaction swept over the nation and
\par brought the crisis of to-day.
\par 
\par It is difficult to explain clearly the present critical stage of Negro
\par religion.  First, we must remember that living as the blacks do in
\par close contact with a great modern nation, and sharing, although
\par imperfectly, the soul-life of that nation, they must necessarily be
\par affected more or less directly by all the religious and ethical forces
\par that are to-day moving the United States.  These questions and
\par movements are, however, overshadowed and dwarfed by the (to them)
\par all-important question of their civil, political, and economic status.
\par They must perpetually discuss the "Negro Problem,"--must live, move,
\par and have their being in it, and interpret all else in its light or
\par darkness.  With this come, too, peculiar problems of their inner
\par life,--of the status of women, the maintenance of Home, the training of
\par children, the accumulation of wealth, and the prevention of crime.  All
\par this must mean a time of intense ethical ferment, of religious
\par heart-searching and intellectual unrest.  From the double life every
\par American Negro must live, as a Negro and as an American, as swept on by
\par the current of the nineteenth while yet struggling in the eddies of the
\par fifteenth century,--from this must arise a painful self-consciousness,
\par an almost morbid sense of personality and a moral hesitancy which is
\par fatal to self-confidence.  The worlds within and without the Veil of
\par Color are changing, and changing rapidly, but not at the same rate, not
\par in the same way; and this must produce a peculiar wrenching of the
\par soul, a peculiar sense of doubt and bewilderment.  Such a double life,
\par with double thoughts, double duties, and double social classes, must
\par give rise to double words and double ideals, and tempt the mind to
\par pretence or revolt, to hypocrisy or radicalism.
\par 
\par In some such doubtful words and phrases can one perhaps most clearly
\par picture the peculiar ethical paradox that faces the Negro of to-day and
\par is tingeing and changing his religious life.  Feeling that his rights
\par and his dearest ideals are being trampled upon, that the public
\par conscience is ever more deaf to his righteous appeal, and that all the
\par reactionary forces of prejudice, greed, and revenge are daily gaining
\par new strength and fresh allies, the Negro faces no enviable dilemma.
\par Conscious of his impotence, and pessimistic, he often becomes bitter
\par and vindictive; and his religion, instead of a worship, is a complaint
\par and a curse, a wail rather than a hope, a sneer rather than a faith.
\par On the other hand, another type of mind, shrewder and keener and more
\par tortuous too, sees in the very strength of the anti-Negro movement its
\par patent weaknesses, and with Jesuitic casuistry is deterred by no
\par ethical considerations in the endeavor to turn this weakness to the
\par black man's strength.  Thus we have two great and hardly reconcilable
\par streams of thought and ethical strivings; the danger of the one lies in
\par anarchy, that of the other in hypocrisy.  The one type of Negro stands
\par almost ready to curse God and die, and the other is too often found a
\par traitor to right and a coward before force; the one is wedded to ideals
\par remote, whimsical, perhaps impossible of realization; the other forgets
\par that life is more than meat and the body more than raiment.  But, after
\par all, is not this simply the writhing of the age translated into
\par black,--the triumph of the Lie which today, with its false culture,
\par faces the hideousness of the anarchist assassin?
\par 
\par To-day the two groups of Negroes, the one in the North, the other in
\par the South, represent these divergent ethical tendencies, the first
\par tending toward radicalism, the other toward hypocritical compromise.
\par It is no idle regret with which the white South mourns the loss of the
\par old-time Negro,--the frank, honest, simple old servant who stood for
\par the earlier religious age of submission and humility.  With all his
\par laziness and lack of many elements of true manhood, he was at least
\par open-hearted, faithful, and sincere.  To-day he is gone, but who is to
\par blame for his going?  Is it not those very persons who mourn for him?
\par Is it not the tendency, born of Reconstruction and Reaction, to found a
\par society on lawlessness and deception, to tamper with the moral fibre of
\par a naturally honest and straightforward people until the whites threaten
\par to become ungovernable tyrants and the blacks criminals and hypocrites?
\par Deception is the natural defence of the weak against the strong, and
\par the South used it for many years against its conquerors; to-day it must
\par be prepared to see its black proletariat turn that same two-edged
\par weapon against itself.  And how natural this is!  The death of Denmark
\par Vesey and Nat Turner proved long since to the Negro the present
\par hopelessness of physical defence.  Political defence is becoming less
\par and less available, and economic defence is still only partially
\par effective.  But there is a patent defence at hand,--the defence of
\par deception and flattery, of cajoling and lying.  It is the same defence
\par which peasants of the Middle Age used and which left its stamp on their
\par character for centuries.  To-day the young Negro of the South who would
\par succeed cannot be frank and outspoken, honest and self-assertive, but
\par rather he is daily tempted to be silent and wary, politic and sly; he
\par must flatter and be pleasant, endure petty insults with a smile, shut
\par his eyes to wrong; in too many cases he sees positive personal
\par advantage in deception and lying.  His real thoughts, his real
\par aspirations, must be guarded in whispers; he must not criticise, he
\par must not complain.  Patience, humility, and adroitness must, in these
\par growing black youth, replace impulse, manliness, and courage.  With
\par this sacrifice there is an economic opening, and perhaps peace and some
\par prosperity.  Without this there is riot, migration, or crime.  Nor is
\par this situation peculiar to the Southern United States, is it not rather
\par the only method by which undeveloped races have gained the right to
\par share modern culture?  The price of culture is a Lie.
\par 
\par On the other hand, in the North the tendency is to emphasize the
\par radicalism of the Negro.  Driven from his birthright in the South by a
\par situation at which every fibre of his more outspoken and assertive
\par nature revolts, he finds himself in a land where he can scarcely earn a
\par decent living amid the harsh competition and the color discrimination.
\par At the same time, through schools and periodicals, discussions and
\par lectures, he is intellectually quickened and awakened.  The soul, long
\par pent up and dwarfed, suddenly expands in new-found freedom.  What
\par wonder that every tendency is to excess,--radical complaint, radical
\par remedies, bitter denunciation or angry silence.  Some sink, some rise.
\par The criminal and the sensualist leave the church for the gambling-hell
\par and the brothel, and fill the slums of Chicago and Baltimore; the
\par better classes segregate themselves from the group-life of both white
\par and black, and form an aristocracy, cultured but pessimistic, whose
\par bitter criticism stings while it points out no way of escape.  They
\par despise the submission and subserviency of the Southern Negroes, but
\par offer no other means by which a poor and oppressed minority can exist
\par side by side with its masters.  Feeling deeply and keenly the
\par tendencies and opportunities of the age in which they live, their souls
\par are bitter at the fate which drops the Veil between; and the very fact
\par that this bitterness is natural and justifiable only serves to
\par intensify it and make it more maddening.
\par 
\par Between the two extreme types of ethical attitude which I have thus
\par sought to make clear wavers the mass of the millions of Negroes, North
\par and South; and their religious life and activity partake of this social
\par conflict within their ranks.  Their churches are differentiating,--now
\par into groups of cold, fashionable devotees, in no way distinguishable
\par from similar white groups save in color of skin; now into large social
\par and business institutions catering to the desire for information and
\par amusement of their members, warily avoiding unpleasant questions both
\par within and without the black world, and preaching in effect if not in
\par word: Dum vivimus, vivamus.
\par 
\par But back of this still broods silently the deep religious feeling of
\par the real Negro heart, the stirring, unguided might of powerful human
\par souls who have lost the guiding star of the past and seek in the great
\par night a new religious ideal.  Some day the Awakening will come, when
\par the pent-up vigor of ten million souls shall sweep irresistibly toward
\par the Goal, out of the Valley of the Shadow of Death, where all that
\par makes life worth living--Liberty, Justice, and Right--is marked "For
\par White People Only."
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par XI
\par 
\par Of the Passing of the First-Born
\par 
\par   O sister, sister, thy first-begotten,
\par   The hands that cling and the feet that follow,
\par   The voice of the child's blood crying yet,
\par   WHO HATH REMEMBERED ME?  WHO HATH FORGOTTEN?
\par   Thou hast forgotten, O summer swallow,
\par   But the world shall end when I forget.
\par 
\par   SWINBURNE.
\par 
\par 
\par "Unto you a child is born," sang the bit of yellow paper that fluttered
\par into my room one brown October morning.  Then the fear of fatherhood
\par mingled wildly with the joy of creation; I wondered how it looked and
\par how it felt--what were its eyes, and how its hair curled and crumpled
\par itself.  And I thought in awe of her,--she who had slept with Death to
\par tear a man-child from underneath her heart, while I was unconsciously
\par wandering.  I fled to my wife and child, repeating the while to myself
\par half wonderingly, "Wife and child?  Wife and child?"--fled fast and
\par faster than boat and steam-car, and yet must ever impatiently await
\par them; away from the hard-voiced city, away from the flickering sea into
\par my own Berkshire Hills that sit all sadly guarding the gates of
\par Massachusetts.
\par 
\par Up the stairs I ran to the wan mother and whimpering babe, to the
\par sanctuary on whose altar a life at my bidding had offered itself to win
\par a life, and won.  What is this tiny formless thing, this newborn wail
\par from an unknown world,--all head and voice?  I handle it curiously, and
\par watch perplexed its winking, breathing, and sneezing.  I did not love
\par it then; it seemed a ludicrous thing to love; but her I loved, my
\par girl-mother, she whom now I saw unfolding like the glory of the
\par morning--the transfigured woman.  Through her I came to love the wee
\par thing, as it grew strong; as its little soul unfolded itself in twitter
\par and cry and half-formed word, and as its eyes caught the gleam and
\par flash of life.  How beautiful he was, with his olive-tinted flesh and
\par dark gold ringlets, his eyes of mingled blue and brown, his perfect
\par little limbs, and the soft voluptuous roll which the blood of Africa
\par had moulded into his features!  I held him in my arms, after we had
\par sped far away from our Southern home,--held him, and glanced at the hot
\par red soil of Georgia and the breathless city of a hundred hills, and
\par felt a vague unrest.  Why was his hair tinted with gold?  An evil omen
\par was golden hair in my life.  Why had not the brown of his eyes crushed
\par out and killed the blue?--for brown were his father's eyes, and his
\par father's father's.  And thus in the Land of the Color-line I saw, as it
\par fell across my baby, the shadow of the Veil.
\par 
\par Within the Veil was he born, said I; and there within shall he live,--a
\par Negro and a Negro's son.  Holding in that little head--ah,
\par bitterly!--he unbowed pride of a hunted race, clinging with that tiny
\par dimpled hand--ah, wearily!--to a hope not hopeless but unhopeful, and
\par seeing with those bright wondering eyes that peer into my soul a land
\par whose freedom is to us a mockery and whose liberty a lie.  I saw the
\par shadow of the Veil as it passed over my baby, I saw the cold city
\par towering above the blood-red land.  I held my face beside his little
\par cheek, showed him the star-children and the twinkling lights as they
\par began to flash, and stilled with an even-song the unvoiced terror of my
\par life.
\par 
\par So sturdy and masterful he grew, so filled with bubbling life, so
\par tremulous with the unspoken wisdom of a life but eighteen months
\par distant from the All-life,--we were not far from worshipping this
\par revelation of the divine, my wife and I. Her own life builded and
\par moulded itself upon the child; he tinged her every dream and idealized
\par her every effort.  No hands but hers must touch and garnish those
\par little limbs; no dress or frill must touch them that had not wearied
\par her fingers; no voice but hers could coax him off to Dreamland, and she
\par and he together spoke some soft and unknown tongue and in it held
\par communion.  I too mused above his little white bed; saw the strength of
\par my own arm stretched onward through the ages through the newer strength
\par of his; saw the dream of my black fathers stagger a step onward in the
\par wild phantasm of the world; heard in his baby voice the voice of the
\par Prophet that was to rise within the Veil.
\par 
\par And so we dreamed and loved and planned by fall and winter, and the
\par full flush of the long Southern spring, till the hot winds rolled from
\par the fetid Gulf, till the roses shivered and the still stern sun
\par quivered its awful light over the hills of Atlanta.  And then one night
\par the little feet pattered wearily to the wee white bed, and the tiny
\par hands trembled; and a warm flushed face tossed on the pillow, and we
\par knew baby was sick.  Ten days he lay there,--a swift week and three
\par endless days, wasting, wasting away.  Cheerily the mother nursed him
\par the first days, and laughed into the little eyes that smiled again.
\par Tenderly then she hovered round him, till the smile fled away and Fear
\par crouched beside the little bed.
\par 
\par Then the day ended not, and night was a dreamless terror, and joy and
\par sleep slipped away.  I hear now that Voice at midnight calling me from
\par dull and dreamless trance,--crying, "The Shadow of Death!  The Shadow
\par of Death!"  Out into the starlight I crept, to rouse the gray
\par physician,--the Shadow of Death, the Shadow of Death.  The hours
\par trembled on; the night listened; the ghastly dawn glided like a tired
\par thing across the lamplight.  Then we two alone looked upon the child as
\par he turned toward us with great eyes, and stretched his stringlike
\par hands,--the Shadow of Death!  And we spoke no word, and turned away.
\par 
\par He died at eventide, when the sun lay like a brooding sorrow above the
\par western hills, veiling its face; when the winds spoke not, and the
\par trees, the great green trees he loved, stood motionless.  I saw his
\par breath beat quicker and quicker, pause, and then his little soul leapt
\par like a star that travels in the night and left a world of darkness in
\par its train.  The day changed not; the same tall trees peeped in at the
\par windows, the same green grass glinted in the setting sun.  Only in the
\par chamber of death writhed the world's most piteous thing--a childless
\par mother.
\par 
\par I shirk not.  I long for work.  I pant for a life full of striving.  I
\par am no coward, to shrink before the rugged rush of the storm, nor even
\par quail before the awful shadow of the Veil.  But hearken, O Death!  Is
\par not this my life hard enough,--is not that dull land that stretches its
\par sneering web about me cold enough,--is not all the world beyond these
\par four little walls pitiless enough, but that thou must needs enter
\par here,--thou, O Death?  About my head the thundering storm beat like a
\par heartless voice, and the crazy forest pulsed with the curses of the
\par weak; but what cared I, within my home beside my wife and baby boy?
\par Wast thou so jealous of one little coign of happiness that thou must
\par needs enter there,--thou, O Death?
\par 
\par A perfect life was his, all joy and love, with tears to make it
\par brighter,--sweet as a summer's day beside the Housatonic.  The world
\par loved him; the women kissed his curls, the men looked gravely into his
\par wonderful eyes, and the children hovered and fluttered about him.  I
\par can see him now, changing like the sky from sparkling laughter to
\par darkening frowns, and then to wondering thoughtfulness as he watched
\par the world.  He knew no color-line, poor dear--and the Veil, though it
\par shadowed him, had not yet darkened half his sun.  He loved the white
\par matron, he loved his black nurse; and in his little world walked souls
\par alone, uncolored and unclothed.  I--yea, all men--are larger and purer
\par by the infinite breadth of that one little life.  She who in simple
\par clearness of vision sees beyond the stars said when he had flown, "He
\par will be happy There; he ever loved beautiful things."  And I, far more
\par ignorant, and blind by the web of mine own weaving, sit alone winding
\par words and muttering, "If still he be, and he be There, and there be a
\par There, let him be happy, O Fate!"
\par 
\par Blithe was the morning of his burial, with bird and song and
\par sweet-smelling flowers.  The trees whispered to the grass, but the
\par children sat with hushed faces.  And yet it seemed a ghostly unreal
\par day,--the wraith of Life.  We seemed to rumble down an unknown street
\par behind a little white bundle of posies, with the shadow of a song in
\par our ears.  The busy city dinned about us; they did not say much, those
\par pale-faced hurrying men and women; they did not say much,--they only
\par glanced and said, "Niggers!"
\par 
\par We could not lay him in the ground there in Georgia, for the earth
\par there is strangely red; so we bore him away to the northward, with his
\par flowers and his little folded hands.  In vain, in vain!--for where, O
\par God!  beneath thy broad blue sky shall my dark baby rest in
\par peace,--where Reverence dwells, and Goodness, and a Freedom that is
\par free?
\par 
\par All that day and all that night there sat an awful gladness in my
\par heart,--nay, blame me not if I see the world thus darkly through the
\par Veil,--and my soul whispers ever to me saying, "Not dead, not dead, but
\par escaped; not bond, but free."  No bitter meanness now shall sicken his
\par baby heart till it die a living death, no taunt shall madden his happy
\par boyhood.  Fool that I was to think or wish that this little soul should
\par grow choked and deformed within the Veil!  I might have known that
\par yonder deep unworldly look that ever and anon floated past his eyes was
\par peering far beyond this narrow Now.  In the poise of his little
\par curl-crowned head did there not sit all that wild pride of being which
\par his father had hardly crushed in his own heart?  For what, forsooth,
\par shall a Negro want with pride amid the studied humiliations of fifty
\par million fellows?  Well sped, my boy, before the world had dubbed your
\par ambition insolence, had held your ideals unattainable, and taught you
\par to cringe and bow.  Better far this nameless void that stops my life
\par than a sea of sorrow for you.
\par 
\par Idle words; he might have borne his burden more bravely than we,--aye,
\par and found it lighter too, some day; for surely, surely this is not the
\par end.  Surely there shall yet dawn some mighty morning to lift the Veil
\par and set the prisoned free.  Not for me,--I shall die in my bonds,--but
\par for fresh young souls who have not known the night and waken to the
\par morning; a morning when men ask of the workman, not "Is he white?" but
\par "Can he work?"  When men ask artists, not "Are they black?" but "Do
\par they know?"  Some morning this may be, long, long years to come.  But
\par now there wails, on that dark shore within the Veil, the same deep
\par voice, THOU SHALT FOREGO!  And all have I foregone at that command, and
\par with small complaint,--all save that fair young form that lies so
\par coldly wed with death in the nest I had builded.
\par 
\par If one must have gone, why not I?  Why may I not rest me from this
\par restlessness and sleep from this wide waking?  Was not the world's
\par alembic, Time, in his young hands, and is not my time waning?  Are
\par there so many workers in the vineyard that the fair promise of this
\par little body could lightly be tossed away?  The wretched of my race that
\par line the alleys of the nation sit fatherless and unmothered; but Love
\par sat beside his cradle, and in his ear Wisdom waited to speak.  Perhaps
\par now he knows the All-love, and needs not to be wise.  Sleep, then,
\par child,--sleep till I sleep and waken to a baby voice and the ceaseless
\par patter of little feet--above the Veil.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par XII
\par 
\par Of Alexander Crummell
\par 
\par   Then from the Dawn it seemed there came, but faint
\par   As from beyond the limit of the world,
\par   Like the last echo born of a great cry,
\par   Sounds, as if some fair city were one voice
\par   Around a king returning from his wars.
\par 
\par   TENNYSON.
\par 
\par 
\par This is the story of a human heart,--the tale of a black boy who many
\par long years ago began to struggle with life that he might know the world
\par and know himself.  Three temptations he met on those dark dunes that
\par lay gray and dismal before the wonder-eyes of the child: the temptation
\par of Hate, that stood out against the red dawn; the temptation of
\par Despair, that darkened noonday; and the temptation of Doubt, that ever
\par steals along with twilight.  Above all, you must hear of the vales he
\par crossed,--the Valley of Humiliation and the Valley of the Shadow of
\par Death.
\par 
\par I saw Alexander Crummell first at a Wilberforce commencement season,
\par amid its bustle and crush.  Tall, frail, and black he stood, with
\par simple dignity and an unmistakable air of good breeding.  I talked with
\par him apart, where the storming of the lusty young orators could not harm
\par us.  I spoke to him politely, then curiously, then eagerly, as I began
\par to feel the fineness of his character,--his calm courtesy, the
\par sweetness of his strength, and his fair blending of the hope and truth
\par of life.  Instinctively I bowed before this man, as one bows before the
\par prophets of the world.  Some seer he seemed, that came not from the
\par crimson Past or the gray To-come, but from the pulsing Now,--that
\par mocking world which seemed to me at once so light and dark, so splendid
\par and sordid.  Fourscore years had he wandered in this same world of
\par mine, within the Veil.
\par 
\par He was born with the Missouri Compromise and lay a-dying amid the
\par echoes of Manila and El Caney: stirring times for living, times dark to
\par look back upon, darker to look forward to. The black-faced lad that
\par paused over his mud and marbles seventy years ago saw puzzling vistas
\par as he looked down the world.  The slave-ship still groaned across the
\par Atlantic, faint cries burdened the Southern breeze, and the great black
\par father whispered mad tales of cruelty into those young ears.  From the
\par low doorway the mother silently watched her boy at play, and at
\par nightfall sought him eagerly lest the shadows bear him away to the land
\par of slaves.
\par 
\par So his young mind worked and winced and shaped curiously a vision of
\par Life; and in the midst of that vision ever stood one dark figure
\par alone,--ever with the hard, thick countenance of that bitter father,
\par and a form that fell in vast and shapeless folds.  Thus the temptation
\par of Hate grew and shadowed the growing child,--gliding stealthily into
\par his laughter, fading into his play, and seizing his dreams by day and
\par night with rough, rude turbulence.  So the black boy asked of sky and
\par sun and flower the never-answered Why? and loved, as he grew, neither
\par the world nor the world's rough ways.
\par 
\par Strange temptation for a child, you may think; and yet in this wide
\par land to-day a thousand thousand dark children brood before this same
\par temptation, and feel its cold and shuddering arms.  For them, perhaps,
\par some one will some day lift the Veil,--will come tenderly and cheerily
\par into those sad little lives and brush the brooding hate away, just as
\par Beriah Green strode in upon the life of Alexander Crummell.  And before
\par the bluff, kind-hearted man the shadow seemed less dark.  Beriah Green
\par had a school in Oneida County, New York, with a score of mischievous
\par boys.  "I'm going to bring a black boy here to educate," said Beriah
\par Green, as only a crank and an abolitionist would have dared to say.
\par "Oho!" laughed the boys.  "Ye-es," said his wife; and Alexander came.
\par Once before, the black boy had sought a school, had travelled, cold and
\par hungry, four hundred miles up into free New Hampshire, to Canaan.  But
\par the godly farmers hitched ninety yoke of oxen to the abolition
\par schoolhouse and dragged it into the middle of the swamp.  The black boy
\par trudged away.
\par 
\par The nineteenth was the first century of human sympathy,--the age when
\par half wonderingly we began to descry in others that transfigured spark
\par of divinity which we call Myself; when clodhoppers and peasants, and
\par tramps and thieves, and millionaires and--sometimes--Negroes, became
\par throbbing souls whose warm pulsing life touched us so nearly that we
\par half gasped with surprise, crying, "Thou too!  Hast Thou seen Sorrow
\par and the dull waters of Hopelessness?  Hast Thou known Life?"  And then
\par all helplessly we peered into those Other-worlds, and wailed, "O World
\par of Worlds, how shall man make you one?"
\par 
\par So in that little Oneida school there came to those schoolboys a
\par revelation of thought and longing beneath one black skin, of which they
\par had not dreamed before.  And to the lonely boy came a new dawn of
\par sympathy and inspiration.  The shadowy, formless thing--the temptation
\par of Hate, that hovered between him and the world--grew fainter and less
\par sinister.  It did not wholly fade away, but diffused itself and
\par lingered thick at the edges.  Through it the child now first saw the
\par blue and gold of life,--the sun-swept road that ran 'twixt heaven and
\par earth until in one far-off wan wavering line they met and kissed.  A
\par vision of life came to the growing boy,--mystic, wonderful.  He raised
\par his head, stretched himself, breathed deep of the fresh new air.
\par Yonder, behind the forests, he heard strange sounds; then glinting
\par through the trees he saw, far, far away, the bronzed hosts of a nation
\par calling,--calling faintly, calling loudly.  He heard the hateful clank
\par of their chains; he felt them cringe and grovel, and there rose within
\par him a protest and a prophecy.  And he girded himself to walk down the
\par world.
\par 
\par A voice and vision called him to be a priest,--a seer to lead the
\par uncalled out of the house of bondage.  He saw the headless host turn
\par toward him like the whirling of mad waters,--he stretched forth his
\par hands eagerly, and then, even as he stretched them, suddenly there
\par swept across the vision the temptation of Despair.
\par 
\par They were not wicked men,--the problem of life is not the problem of
\par the wicked,--they were calm, good men, Bishops of the Apostolic Church
\par of God, and strove toward righteousness.  They said slowly, "It is all
\par very natural--it is even commendable; but the General Theological
\par Seminary of the Episcopal Church cannot admit a Negro."  And when that
\par thin, half-grotesque figure still haunted their doors, they put their
\par hands kindly, half sorrowfully, on his shoulders, and said, "Now,--of
\par course, we--we know how YOU feel about it; but you see it is
\par impossible,--that is--well--it is premature.  Sometime, we
\par trust--sincerely trust--all such distinctions will fade away; but now
\par the world is as it is."
\par 
\par This was the temptation of Despair; and the young man fought it
\par doggedly.  Like some grave shadow he flitted by those halls, pleading,
\par arguing, half angrily demanding admittance, until there came the final
\par NO: until men hustled the disturber away, marked him as foolish,
\par unreasonable, and injudicious, a vain rebel against God's law.  And
\par then from that Vision Splendid all the glory faded slowly away, and
\par left an earth gray and stern rolling on beneath a dark despair.  Even
\par the kind hands that stretched themselves toward him from out the depths
\par of that dull morning seemed but parts of the purple shadows.  He saw
\par them coldly, and asked, "Why should I strive by special grace when the
\par way of the world is closed to me?"  All gently yet, the hands urged him
\par on,--the hands of young John Jay, that daring father's daring son; the
\par hands of the good folk of Boston, that free city.  And yet, with a way
\par to the priesthood of the Church open at last before him, the cloud
\par lingered there; and even when in old St. Paul's the venerable Bishop
\par raised his white arms above the Negro deacon--even then the burden had
\par not lifted from that heart, for there had passed a glory from the earth.
\par 
\par And yet the fire through which Alexander Crummell went did not burn in
\par vain.  Slowly and more soberly he took up again his plan of life.  More
\par critically he studied the situation.  Deep down below the slavery and
\par servitude of the Negro people he saw their fatal weaknesses, which long
\par years of mistreatment had emphasized.  The dearth of strong moral
\par character, of unbending righteousness, he felt, was their great
\par shortcoming, and here he would begin.  He would gather the best of his
\par people into some little Episcopal chapel and there lead, teach, and
\par inspire them, till the leaven spread, till the children grew, till the
\par world hearkened, till--till--and then across his dream gleamed some
\par faint after-glow of that first fair vision of youth--only an
\par after-glow, for there had passed a glory from the earth.
\par 
\par One day--it was in 1842, and the springtide was struggling merrily with
\par the May winds of New England--he stood at last in his own chapel in
\par Providence, a priest of the Church.  The days sped by, and the dark
\par young clergyman labored; he wrote his sermons carefully; he intoned his
\par prayers with a soft, earnest voice; he haunted the streets and accosted
\par the wayfarers; he visited the sick, and knelt beside the dying.  He
\par worked and toiled, week by week, day by day, month by month.  And yet
\par month by month the congregation dwindled, week by week the hollow walls
\par echoed more sharply, day by day the calls came fewer and fewer, and day
\par by day the third temptation sat clearer and still more clearly within
\par the Veil; a temptation, as it were, bland and smiling, with just a
\par shade of mockery in its smooth tones.  First it came casually, in the
\par cadence of a voice: "Oh, colored folks?  Yes."  Or perhaps more
\par definitely: "What do you EXPECT?"  In voice and gesture lay the
\par doubt--the temptation of Doubt.  How he hated it, and stormed at it
\par furiously!  "Of course they are capable," he cried; "of course they can
\par learn and strive and achieve--" and "Of course," added the temptation
\par softly, "they do nothing of the sort."  Of all the three temptations,
\par this one struck the deepest.  Hate?  He had outgrown so childish a
\par thing.  Despair?  He had steeled his right arm against it, and fought
\par it with the vigor of determination.  But to doubt the worth of his
\par life-work,--to doubt the destiny and capability of the race his soul
\par loved because it was his; to find listless squalor instead of eager
\par endeavor; to hear his own lips whispering, "They do not care; they
\par cannot know; they are dumb driven cattle,--why cast your pearls before
\par swine?"--this, this seemed more than man could bear; and he closed the
\par door, and sank upon the steps of the chancel, and cast his robe upon
\par the floor and writhed.
\par 
\par The evening sunbeams had set the dust to dancing in the gloomy chapel
\par when he arose.  He folded his vestments, put away the hymn-books, and
\par closed the great Bible.  He stepped out into the twilight, looked back
\par upon the narrow little pulpit with a weary smile, and locked the door.
\par Then he walked briskly to the Bishop, and told the Bishop what the
\par Bishop already knew.  "I have failed," he said simply.  And gaining
\par courage by the confession, he added: "What I need is a larger
\par constituency.  There are comparatively few Negroes here, and perhaps
\par they are not of the best.  I must go where the field is wider, and try
\par again."  So the Bishop sent him to Philadelphia, with a letter to
\par Bishop Onderdonk.
\par 
\par Bishop Onderdonk lived at the head of six white steps,--corpulent,
\par red-faced, and the author of several thrilling tracts on Apostolic
\par Succession.  It was after dinner, and the Bishop had settled himself
\par for a pleasant season of contemplation, when the bell must needs ring,
\par and there must burst in upon the Bishop a letter and a thin, ungainly
\par Negro.  Bishop Onderdonk read the letter hastily and frowned.
\par Fortunately, his mind was already clear on this point; and he cleared
\par his brow and looked at Crummell.  Then he said, slowly and
\par impressively: "I will receive you into this diocese on one condition:
\par no Negro priest can sit in my church convention, and no Negro church
\par must ask for representation there."
\par 
\par I sometimes fancy I can see that tableau: the frail black figure,
\par nervously twitching his hat before the massive abdomen of Bishop
\par Onderdonk; his threadbare coat thrown against the dark woodwork of the
\par bookcases, where Fox's "Lives of the Martyrs" nestled happily beside
\par "The Whole Duty of Man."  I seem to see the wide eyes of the Negro
\par wander past the Bishop's broadcloth to where the swinging glass doors
\par of the cabinet glow in the sunlight.  A little blue fly is trying to
\par cross the yawning keyhole.  He marches briskly up to it, peers into the
\par chasm in a surprised sort of way, and rubs his feelers reflectively;
\par then he essays its depths, and, finding it bottomless, draws back
\par again.  The dark-faced priest finds himself wondering if the fly too
\par has faced its Valley of Humiliation, and if it will plunge into
\par it,--when lo! it spreads its tiny wings and buzzes merrily across,
\par leaving the watcher wingless and alone.
\par 
\par Then the full weight of his burden fell upon him.  The rich walls
\par wheeled away, and before him lay the cold rough moor winding on through
\par life, cut in twain by one thick granite ridge,--here, the Valley of
\par Humiliation; yonder, the Valley of the Shadow of Death.  And I know not
\par which be darker,--no, not I. But this I know: in yonder Vale of the
\par Humble stand to-day a million swarthy men, who willingly would
\par 
\par   ". . . bear the whips and scorns of time,
\par   The oppressor's wrong, the proud man's contumely,
\par   The pangs of despised love, the law's delay,
\par   The insolence of office, and the spurns
\par   That patient merit of the unworthy takes,"--
\par 
\par all this and more would they bear did they but know that this were
\par sacrifice and not a meaner thing.  So surged the thought within that
\par lone black breast.  The Bishop cleared his throat suggestively; then,
\par recollecting that there was really nothing to say, considerately said
\par nothing, only sat tapping his foot impatiently.  But Alexander Crummell
\par said, slowly and heavily: "I will never enter your diocese on such
\par terms."  And saying this, he turned and passed into the Valley of the
\par Shadow of Death.  You might have noted only the physical dying, the
\par shattered frame and hacking cough; but in that soul lay deeper death
\par than that.  He found a chapel in New York,--the church of his father;
\par he labored for it in poverty and starvation, scorned by his fellow
\par priests.  Half in despair, he wandered across the sea, a beggar with
\par outstretched hands.  Englishmen clasped them,--Wilberforce and Stanley,
\par Thirwell and Ingles, and even Froude and Macaulay; Sir Benjamin Brodie
\par bade him rest awhile at Queen's College in Cambridge, and there he
\par lingered, struggling for health of body and mind, until he took his
\par degree in '53.  Restless still, and unsatisfied, he turned toward
\par Africa, and for long years, amid the spawn of the slave-smugglers,
\par sought a new heaven and a new earth.
\par 
\par So the man groped for light; all this was not Life,--it was the
\par world-wandering of a soul in search of itself, the striving of one who
\par vainly sought his place in the world, ever haunted by the shadow of a
\par death that is more than death,--the passing of a soul that has missed
\par its duty.  Twenty years he wandered,--twenty years and more; and yet
\par the hard rasping question kept gnawing within him, "What, in God's
\par name, am I on earth for?"  In the narrow New York parish his soul
\par seemed cramped and smothered.  In the fine old air of the English
\par University he heard the millions wailing over the sea.  In the wild
\par fever-cursed swamps of West Africa he stood helpless and alone.
\par 
\par You will not wonder at his weird pilgrimage,--you who in the swift
\par whirl of living, amid its cold paradox and marvellous vision, have
\par fronted life and asked its riddle face to face.  And if you find that
\par riddle hard to read, remember that yonder black boy finds it just a
\par little harder; if it is difficult for you to find and face your duty,
\par it is a shade more difficult for him; if your heart sickens in the
\par blood and dust of battle, remember that to him the dust is thicker and
\par the battle fiercer.  No wonder the wanderers fall!  No wonder we point
\par to thief and murderer, and haunting prostitute, and the never-ending
\par throng of unhearsed dead!  The Valley of the Shadow of Death gives few
\par of its pilgrims back to the world.
\par 
\par But Alexander Crummell it gave back.  Out of the temptation of Hate,
\par and burned by the fire of Despair, triumphant over Doubt, and steeled
\par by Sacrifice against Humiliation, he turned at last home across the
\par waters, humble and strong, gentle and determined.  He bent to all the
\par gibes and prejudices, to all hatred and discrimination, with that rare
\par courtesy which is the armor of pure souls.  He fought among his own,
\par the low, the grasping, and the wicked, with that unbending
\par righteousness which is the sword of the just.  He never faltered, he
\par seldom complained; he simply worked, inspiring the young, rebuking the
\par old, helping the weak, guiding the strong.
\par 
\par So he grew, and brought within his wide influence all that was best of
\par those who walk within the Veil.  They who live without knew not nor
\par dreamed of that full power within, that mighty inspiration which the
\par dull gauze of caste decreed that most men should not know.  And now
\par that he is gone, I sweep the Veil away and cry, Lo! the soul to whose
\par dear memory I bring this little tribute.  I can see his face still,
\par dark and heavy-lined beneath his snowy hair; lighting and shading, now
\par with inspiration for the future, now in innocent pain at some human
\par wickedness, now with sorrow at some hard memory from the past.  The
\par more I met Alexander Crummell, the more I felt how much that world was
\par losing which knew so little of him.  In another age he might have sat
\par among the elders of the land in purple-bordered toga; in another
\par country mothers might have sung him to the cradles.
\par 
\par He did his work,--he did it nobly and well; and yet I sorrow that here
\par he worked alone, with so little human sympathy.  His name to-day, in
\par this broad land, means little, and comes to fifty million ears laden
\par with no incense of memory or emulation.  And herein lies the tragedy of
\par the age: not that men are poor,--all men know something of poverty; not
\par that men are wicked,--who is good? not that men are ignorant,--what is
\par Truth?  Nay, but that men know so little of men.
\par 
\par 
\par He sat one morning gazing toward the sea.  He smiled and said, "The
\par gate is rusty on the hinges."  That night at starrise a wind came
\par moaning out of the west to blow the gate ajar, and then the soul I
\par loved fled like a flame across the Seas, and in its seat sat Death.
\par 
\par I wonder where he is to-day?  I wonder if in that dim world beyond, as
\par he came gliding in, there rose on some wan throne a King,--a dark and
\par pierced Jew, who knows the writhings of the earthly damned, saying, as
\par he laid those heart-wrung talents down, "Well done!" while round about
\par the morning stars sat singing.
\par 
