\par XIII
\par 
\par Of the Coming of John
\par 
\par   What bring they 'neath the midnight,
\par     Beside the River-sea?
\par   They bring the human heart wherein
\par     No nightly calm can be;
\par   That droppeth never with the wind,
\par     Nor drieth with the dew;
\par   O calm it, God; thy calm is broad
\par     To cover spirits too.
\par 
\par    The river floweth on.
\par 
\par   MRS. BROWNING.
\par 
\par 
\par Carlisle Street runs westward from the centre of Johnstown, across a
\par great black bridge, down a hill and up again, by little shops and
\par meat-markets, past single-storied homes, until suddenly it stops
\par against a wide green lawn.  It is a broad, restful place, with two
\par large buildings outlined against the west.  When at evening the winds
\par come swelling from the east, and the great pall of the city's smoke
\par hangs wearily above the valley, then the red west glows like a
\par dreamland down Carlisle Street, and, at the tolling of the supper-bell,
\par throws the passing forms of students in dark silhouette against the
\par sky.  Tall and black, they move slowly by, and seem in the sinister
\par light to flit before the city like dim warning ghosts.  Perhaps they
\par are; for this is Wells Institute, and these black students have few
\par dealings with the white city below.
\par 
\par And if you will notice, night after night, there is one dark form that
\par ever hurries last and late toward the twinkling lights of Swain
\par Hall,--for Jones is never on time.  A long, straggling fellow he is,
\par brown and hard-haired, who seems to be growing straight out of his
\par clothes, and walks with a half-apologetic roll.  He used perpetually to
\par set the quiet dining-room into waves of merriment, as he stole to his
\par place after the bell had tapped for prayers; he seemed so perfectly
\par awkward.  And yet one glance at his face made one forgive him
\par much,--that broad, good-natured smile in which lay no bit of art or
\par artifice, but seemed just bubbling good-nature and genuine satisfaction
\par with the world.
\par 
\par He came to us from Altamaha, away down there beneath the gnarled oaks
\par of Southeastern Georgia, where the sea croons to the sands and the
\par sands listen till they sink half drowned beneath the waters, rising
\par only here and there in long, low islands.  The white folk of Altamaha
\par voted John a good boy,--fine plough-hand, good in the rice-fields,
\par handy everywhere, and always good-natured and respectful.  But they
\par shook their heads when his mother wanted to send him off to school.
\par "It'll spoil him,--ruin him," they said; and they talked as though they
\par knew.  But full half the black folk followed him proudly to the
\par station, and carried his queer little trunk and many bundles.  And
\par there they shook and shook hands, and the girls kissed him shyly and
\par the boys clapped him on the back.  So the train came, and he pinched
\par his little sister lovingly, and put his great arms about his mother's
\par neck, and then was away with a puff and a roar into the great yellow
\par world that flamed and flared about the doubtful pilgrim.  Up the coast
\par they hurried, past the squares and palmettos of Savannah, through the
\par cotton-fields and through the weary night, to Millville, and came with
\par the morning to the noise and bustle of Johnstown.
\par 
\par And they that stood behind, that morning in Altamaha, and watched the
\par train as it noisily bore playmate and brother and son away to the
\par world, had thereafter one ever-recurring word,--"When John comes." Then
\par what parties were to be, and what speakings in the churches; what new
\par furniture in the front room,--perhaps even a new front room; and there
\par would be a new schoolhouse, with John as teacher; and then perhaps a
\par big wedding; all this and more--when John comes.  But the white people
\par shook their heads.
\par 
\par At first he was coming at Christmas-time,--but the vacation proved too
\par short; and then, the next summer,--but times were hard and schooling
\par costly, and so, instead, he worked in Johnstown.  And so it drifted to
\par the next summer, and the next,--till playmates scattered, and mother
\par grew gray, and sister went up to the Judge's kitchen to work.  And
\par still the legend lingered,--"When John comes."
\par 
\par Up at the Judge's they rather liked this refrain; for they too had a
\par John--a fair-haired, smooth-faced boy, who had played many a long
\par summer's day to its close with his darker namesake.  "Yes, sir!  John
\par is at Princeton, sir," said the broad-shouldered gray-haired Judge
\par every morning as he marched down to the post-office.  "Showing the
\par Yankees what a Southern gentleman can do," he added; and strode home
\par again with his letters and papers.  Up at the great pillared house they
\par lingered long over the Princeton letter,--the Judge and his frail wife,
\par his sister and growing daughters.  "It'll make a man of him," said the
\par Judge, "college is the place."  And then he asked the shy little
\par waitress, "Well, Jennie, how's your John?" and added reflectively, "Too
\par bad, too bad your mother sent him off--it will spoil him."  And the
\par waitress wondered.
\par 
\par Thus in the far-away Southern village the world lay waiting, half
\par consciously, the coming of two young men, and dreamed in an
\par inarticulate way of new things that would be done and new thoughts that
\par all would think.  And yet it was singular that few thought of two
\par Johns,--for the black folk thought of one John, and he was black; and
\par the white folk thought of another John, and he was white.  And neither
\par world thought the other world's thought, save with a vague unrest.
\par 
\par Up in Johnstown, at the Institute, we were long puzzled at the case of
\par John Jones.  For a long time the clay seemed unfit for any sort of
\par moulding.  He was loud and boisterous, always laughing and singing, and
\par never able to work consecutively at anything.  He did not know how to
\par study; he had no idea of thoroughness; and with his tardiness,
\par carelessness, and appalling good-humor, we were sore perplexed.  One
\par night we sat in faculty-meeting, worried and serious; for Jones was in
\par trouble again.  This last escapade was too much, and so we solemnly
\par voted "that Jones, on account of repeated disorder and inattention to
\par work, be suspended for the rest of the term."
\par 
\par It seemed to us that the first time life ever struck Jones as a really
\par serious thing was when the Dean told him he must leave school.  He
\par stared at the gray-haired man blankly, with great eyes.  "Why,--why,"
\par he faltered, "but--I haven't graduated!"  Then the Dean slowly and
\par clearly explained, reminding him of the tardiness and the carelessness,
\par of the poor lessons and neglected work, of the noise and disorder,
\par until the fellow hung his head in confusion.  Then he said quickly,
\par "But you won't tell mammy and sister,--you won't write mammy, now will
\par you?  For if you won't I'll go out into the city and work, and come
\par back next term and show you something."  So the Dean promised
\par faithfully, and John shouldered his little trunk, giving neither word
\par nor look to the giggling boys, and walked down Carlisle Street to the
\par great city, with sober eyes and a set and serious face.
\par 
\par Perhaps we imagined it, but someway it seemed to us that the serious
\par look that crept over his boyish face that afternoon never left it
\par again.  When he came back to us he went to work with all his rugged
\par strength.  It was a hard struggle, for things did not come easily to
\par him,--few crowding memories of early life and teaching came to help him
\par on his new way; but all the world toward which he strove was of his own
\par building, and he builded slow and hard.  As the light dawned
\par lingeringly on his new creations, he sat rapt and silent before the
\par vision, or wandered alone over the green campus peering through and
\par beyond the world of men into a world of thought.  And the thoughts at
\par times puzzled him sorely; he could not see just why the circle was not
\par square, and carried it out fifty-six decimal places one
\par midnight,--would have gone further, indeed, had not the matron rapped
\par for lights out.  He caught terrible colds lying on his back in the
\par meadows of nights, trying to think out the solar system; he had grave
\par doubts as to the ethics of the Fall of Rome, and strongly suspected the
\par Germans of being thieves and rascals, despite his textbooks; he
\par pondered long over every new Greek word, and wondered why this meant
\par that and why it couldn't mean something else, and how it must have felt
\par to think all things in Greek.  So he thought and puzzled along for
\par himself,--pausing perplexed where others skipped merrily, and walking
\par steadily through the difficulties where the rest stopped and
\par surrendered.
\par 
\par Thus he grew in body and soul, and with him his clothes seemed to grow
\par and arrange themselves; coat sleeves got longer, cuffs appeared, and
\par collars got less soiled.  Now and then his boots shone, and a new
\par dignity crept into his walk.  And we who saw daily a new thoughtfulness
\par growing in his eyes began to expect something of this plodding boy.
\par Thus he passed out of the preparatory school into college, and we who
\par watched him felt four more years of change, which almost transformed
\par the tall, grave man who bowed to us commencement morning.  He had left
\par his queer thought-world and come back to a world of motion and of men.
\par He looked now for the first time sharply about him, and wondered he had
\par seen so little before.  He grew slowly to feel almost for the first
\par time the Veil that lay between him and the white world; he first
\par noticed now the oppression that had not seemed oppression before,
\par differences that erstwhile seemed natural, restraints and slights that
\par in his boyhood days had gone unnoticed or been greeted with a laugh.
\par He felt angry now when men did not call him "Mister," he clenched his
\par hands at the "Jim Crow" cars, and chafed at the color-line that hemmed
\par in him and his.  A tinge of sarcasm crept into his speech, and a vague
\par bitterness into his life; and he sat long hours wondering and planning
\par a way around these crooked things.  Daily he found himself shrinking
\par from the choked and narrow life of his native town.  And yet he always
\par planned to go back to Altamaha,--always planned to work there.  Still,
\par more and more as the day approached he hesitated with a nameless dread;
\par and even the day after graduation he seized with eagerness the offer of
\par the Dean to send him North with the quartette during the summer
\par vacation, to sing for the Institute.  A breath of air before the
\par plunge, he said to himself in half apology.
\par 
\par It was a bright September afternoon, and the streets of New York were
\par brilliant with moving men.  They reminded John of the sea, as he sat in
\par the square and watched them, so changelessly changing, so bright and
\par dark, so grave and gay.  He scanned their rich and faultless clothes,
\par the way they carried their hands, the shape of their hats; he peered
\par into the hurrying carriages.  Then, leaning back with a sigh, he said,
\par "This is the World."  The notion suddenly seized him to see where the
\par world was going; since many of the richer and brighter seemed hurrying
\par all one way.  So when a tall, light-haired young man and a little
\par talkative lady came by, he rose half hesitatingly and followed them.
\par Up the street they went, past stores and gay shops, across a broad
\par square, until with a hundred others they entered the high portal of a
\par great building.
\par 
\par He was pushed toward the ticket-office with the others, and felt in his
\par pocket for the new five-dollar bill he had hoarded.  There seemed
\par really no time for hesitation, so he drew it bravely out, passed it to
\par the busy clerk, and received simply a ticket but no change.  When at
\par last he realized that he had paid five dollars to enter he knew not
\par what, he stood stockstill amazed.  "Be careful," said a low voice
\par behind him; "you must not lynch the colored gentleman simply because
\par he's in your way," and a girl looked up roguishly into the eyes of her
\par fair-haired escort.  A shade of annoyance passed over the escort's
\par face.  "You WILL not understand us at the South," he said half
\par impatiently, as if continuing an argument.  "With all your professions,
\par one never sees in the North so cordial and intimate relations between
\par white and black as are everyday occurrences with us.  Why, I remember
\par my closest playfellow in boyhood was a little Negro named after me, and
\par surely no two,--WELL!" The man stopped short and flushed to the roots
\par of his hair, for there directly beside his reserved orchestra chairs
\par sat the Negro he had stumbled over in the hallway.  He hesitated and
\par grew pale with anger, called the usher and gave him his card, with a
\par few peremptory words, and slowly sat down.  The lady deftly changed the
\par subject.
\par 
\par All this John did not see, for he sat in a half-daze minding the scene
\par about him; the delicate beauty of the hall, the faint perfume, the
\par moving myriad of men, the rich clothing and low hum of talking seemed
\par all a part of a world so different from his, so strangely more
\par beautiful than anything he had known, that he sat in dreamland, and
\par started when, after a hush, rose high and clear the music of
\par Lohengrin's swan.  The infinite beauty of the wail lingered and swept
\par through every muscle of his frame, and put it all a-tune.  He closed
\par his eyes and grasped the elbows of the chair, touching unwittingly the
\par lady's arm.  And the lady drew away.  A deep longing swelled in all his
\par heart to rise with that clear music out of the dirt and dust of that
\par low life that held him prisoned and befouled.  If he could only live up
\par in the free air where birds sang and setting suns had no touch of
\par blood!  Who had called him to be the slave and butt of all?  And if he
\par had called, what right had he to call when a world like this lay open
\par before men?
\par 
\par Then the movement changed, and fuller, mightier harmony swelled away.
\par He looked thoughtfully across the hall, and wondered why the beautiful
\par gray-haired woman looked so listless, and what the little man could be
\par whispering about.  He would not like to be listless and idle, he
\par thought, for he felt with the music the movement of power within him.
\par If he but had some master-work, some life-service, hard,--aye, bitter
\par hard, but without the cringing and sickening servility, without the
\par cruel hurt that hardened his heart and soul.  When at last a soft
\par sorrow crept across the violins, there came to him the vision of a
\par far-off home, the great eyes of his sister, and the dark drawn face of
\par his mother.  And his heart sank below the waters, even as the sea-sand
\par sinks by the shores of Altamaha, only to be lifted aloft again with
\par that last ethereal wail of the swan that quivered and faded away into
\par the sky.
\par 
\par It left John sitting so silent and rapt that he did not for some time
\par notice the usher tapping him lightly on the shoulder and saying
\par politely, "Will you step this way, please, sir?"  A little surprised,
\par he arose quickly at the last tap, and, turning to leave his seat,
\par looked full into the face of the fair-haired young man.  For the first
\par time the young man recognized his dark boyhood playmate, and John knew
\par that it was the Judge's son.  The White John started, lifted his hand,
\par and then froze into his chair; the black John smiled lightly, then
\par grimly, and followed the usher down the aisle.  The manager was sorry,
\par very, very sorry,--but he explained that some mistake had been made in
\par selling the gentleman a seat already disposed of; he would refund the
\par money, of course,--and indeed felt the matter keenly, and so forth,
\par and--before he had finished John was gone, walking hurriedly across the
\par square and down the broad streets, and as he passed the park he
\par buttoned his coat and said, "John Jones, you're a natural-born fool."
\par Then he went to his lodgings and wrote a letter, and tore it up; he
\par wrote another, and threw it in the fire.  Then he seized a scrap of
\par paper and wrote: "Dear Mother and Sister--I am coming--John."
\par 
\par "Perhaps," said John, as he settled himself on the train, "perhaps I am
\par to blame myself in struggling against my manifest destiny simply
\par because it looks hard and unpleasant.  Here is my duty to Altamaha
\par plain before me; perhaps they'll let me help settle the Negro problems
\par there,--perhaps they won't.  'I will go in to the King, which is not
\par according to the law; and if I perish, I perish.'" And then he mused
\par and dreamed, and planned a life-work; and the train flew south.
\par 
\par Down in Altamaha, after seven long years, all the world knew John was
\par coming.  The homes were scrubbed and scoured,--above all, one; the
\par gardens and yards had an unwonted trimness, and Jennie bought a new
\par gingham.  With some finesse and negotiation, all the dark Methodists
\par and Presbyterians were induced to join in a monster welcome at the
\par Baptist Church; and as the day drew near, warm discussions arose on
\par every corner as to the exact extent and nature of John's
\par accomplishments.  It was noontide on a gray and cloudy day when he
\par came.  The black town flocked to the depot, with a little of the white
\par at the edges,--a happy throng, with "Good-mawnings" and "Howdys" and
\par laughing and joking and jostling.  Mother sat yonder in the window
\par watching; but sister Jennie stood on the platform, nervously fingering
\par her dress, tall and lithe, with soft brown skin and loving eyes peering
\par from out a tangled wilderness of hair.  John rose gloomily as the train
\par stopped, for he was thinking of the "Jim Crow" car; he stepped to the
\par platform, and paused: a little dingy station, a black crowd gaudy and
\par dirty, a half-mile of dilapidated shanties along a straggling ditch of
\par mud.  An overwhelming sense of the sordidness and narrowness of it all
\par seized him; he looked in vain for his mother, kissed coldly the tall,
\par strange girl who called him brother, spoke a short, dry word here and
\par there; then, lingering neither for handshaking nor gossip, started
\par silently up the street, raising his hat merely to the last eager old
\par aunty, to her open-mouthed astonishment.  The people were distinctly
\par bewildered.  This silent, cold man,--was this John?  Where was his
\par smile and hearty hand-grasp?  "'Peared kind o' down in the mouf," said
\par the Methodist preacher thoughtfully.  "Seemed monstus stuck up,"
\par complained a Baptist sister.  But the white postmaster from the edge of
\par the crowd expressed the opinion of his folks plainly.  "That damn
\par Nigger," said he, as he shouldered the mail and arranged his tobacco,
\par "has gone North and got plum full o' fool notions; but they won't work
\par in Altamaha."  And the crowd melted away.
\par 
\par The meeting of welcome at the Baptist Church was a failure.  Rain
\par spoiled the barbecue, and thunder turned the milk in the ice-cream.
\par When the speaking came at night, the house was crowded to overflowing.
\par The three preachers had especially prepared themselves, but somehow
\par John's manner seemed to throw a blanket over everything,--he seemed so
\par cold and preoccupied, and had so strange an air of restraint that the
\par Methodist brother could not warm up to his theme and elicited not a
\par single "Amen"; the Presbyterian prayer was but feebly responded to, and
\par even the Baptist preacher, though he wakened faint enthusiasm, got so
\par mixed up in his favorite sentence that he had to close it by stopping
\par fully fifteen minutes sooner than he meant.  The people moved uneasily
\par in their seats as John rose to reply.  He spoke slowly and
\par methodically.  The age, he said, demanded new ideas; we were far
\par different from those men of the seventeenth and eighteenth
\par centuries,--with broader ideas of human brotherhood and destiny.  Then
\par he spoke of the rise of charity and popular education, and particularly
\par of the spread of wealth and work.  The question was, then, he added
\par reflectively, looking at the low discolored ceiling, what part the
\par Negroes of this land would take in the striving of the new century.  He
\par sketched in vague outline the new Industrial School that might rise
\par among these pines, he spoke in detail of the charitable and
\par philanthropic work that might be organized, of money that might be
\par saved for banks and business.  Finally he urged unity, and deprecated
\par especially religious and denominational bickering.  "To-day," he said,
\par with a smile, "the world cares little whether a man be Baptist or
\par Methodist, or indeed a churchman at all, so long as he is good and
\par true.  What difference does it make whether a man be baptized in river
\par or washbowl, or not at all?  Let's leave all that littleness, and look
\par higher."  Then, thinking of nothing else, he slowly sat down.  A
\par painful hush seized that crowded mass.  Little had they understood of
\par what he said, for he spoke an unknown tongue, save the last word about
\par baptism; that they knew, and they sat very still while the clock
\par ticked.  Then at last a low suppressed snarl came from the Amen corner,
\par and an old bent man arose, walked over the seats, and climbed straight
\par up into the pulpit.  He was wrinkled and black, with scant gray and
\par tufted hair; his voice and hands shook as with palsy; but on his face
\par lay the intense rapt look of the religious fanatic.  He seized the
\par Bible with his rough, huge hands; twice he raised it inarticulate, and
\par then fairly burst into words, with rude and awful eloquence.  He
\par quivered, swayed, and bent; then rose aloft in perfect majesty, till
\par the people moaned and wept, wailed and shouted, and a wild shrieking
\par arose from the corners where all the pent-up feeling of the hour
\par gathered itself and rushed into the air.  John never knew clearly what
\par the old man said; he only felt himself held up to scorn and scathing
\par denunciation for trampling on the true Religion, and he realized with
\par amazement that all unknowingly he had put rough, rude hands on
\par something this little world held sacred.  He arose silently, and passed
\par out into the night.  Down toward the sea he went, in the fitful
\par starlight, half conscious of the girl who followed timidly after him.
\par When at last he stood upon the bluff, he turned to his little sister
\par and looked upon her sorrowfully, remembering with sudden pain how
\par little thought he had given her.  He put his arm about her and let her
\par passion of tears spend itself on his shoulder.
\par 
\par Long they stood together, peering over the gray unresting water.
\par 
\par "John," she said, "does it make every one--unhappy when they study and
\par learn lots of things?"
\par 
\par He paused and smiled.  "I am afraid it does," he said.
\par 
\par "And, John, are you glad you studied?"
\par 
\par "Yes," came the answer, slowly but positively.
\par 
\par She watched the flickering lights upon the sea, and said thoughtfully,
\par "I wish I was unhappy,--and--and," putting both arms about his neck, "I
\par think I am, a little, John."
\par 
\par It was several days later that John walked up to the Judge's house to
\par ask for the privilege of teaching the Negro school.  The Judge himself
\par met him at the front door, stared a little hard at him, and said
\par brusquely, "Go 'round to the kitchen door, John, and wait."  Sitting on
\par the kitchen steps, John stared at the corn, thoroughly perplexed.  What
\par on earth had come over him?  Every step he made offended some one.  He
\par had come to save his people, and before he left the depot he had hurt
\par them.  He sought to teach them at the church, and had outraged their
\par deepest feelings.  He had schooled himself to be respectful to the
\par Judge, and then blundered into his front door.  And all the time he had
\par meant right,--and yet, and yet, somehow he found it so hard and strange
\par to fit his old surroundings again, to find his place in the world about
\par him.  He could not remember that he used to have any difficulty in the
\par past, when life was glad and gay.  The world seemed smooth and easy
\par then.  Perhaps,--but his sister came to the kitchen door just then and
\par said the Judge awaited him.
\par 
\par The Judge sat in the dining-room amid his morning's mail, and he did
\par not ask John to sit down.  He plunged squarely into the business.
\par "You've come for the school, I suppose.  Well John, I want to speak to
\par you plainly.  You know I'm a friend to your people.  I've helped you
\par and your family, and would have done more if you hadn't got the notion
\par of going off.  Now I like the colored people, and sympathize with all
\par their reasonable aspirations; but you and I both know, John, that in
\par this country the Negro must remain subordinate, and can never expect to
\par be the equal of white men.  In their place, your people can be honest
\par and respectful; and God knows, I'll do what I can to help them.  But
\par when they want to reverse nature, and rule white men, and marry white
\par women, and sit in my parlor, then, by God! we'll hold them under if we
\par have to lynch every Nigger in the land.  Now, John, the question is,
\par are you, with your education and Northern notions, going to accept the
\par situation and teach the darkies to be faithful servants and laborers as
\par your fathers were,--I knew your father, John, he belonged to my
\par brother, and he was a good Nigger.  Well--well, are you going to be
\par like him, or are you going to try to put fool ideas of rising and
\par equality into these folks' heads, and make them discontented and
\par unhappy?"
\par 
\par "I am going to accept the situation, Judge Henderson," answered John,
\par with a brevity that did not escape the keen old man.  He hesitated a
\par moment, and then said shortly, "Very well,--we'll try you awhile.
\par Good-morning."
\par 
\par It was a full month after the opening of the Negro school that the
\par other John came home, tall, gay, and headstrong.  The mother wept, the
\par sisters sang.  The whole white town was glad.  A proud man was the
\par Judge, and it was a goodly sight to see the two swinging down Main
\par Street together.  And yet all did not go smoothly between them, for the
\par younger man could not and did not veil his contempt for the little
\par town, and plainly had his heart set on New York.  Now the one cherished
\par ambition of the Judge was to see his son mayor of Altamaha,
\par representative to the legislature, and--who could say?--governor of
\par Georgia.  So the argument often waxed hot between them.  "Good heavens,
\par father," the younger man would say after dinner, as he lighted a cigar
\par and stood by the fireplace, "you surely don't expect a young fellow
\par like me to settle down permanently in this--this God-forgotten town
\par with nothing but mud and Negroes?"  "I did," the Judge would answer
\par laconically; and on this particular day it seemed from the gathering
\par scowl that he was about to add something more emphatic, but neighbors
\par had already begun to drop in to admire his son, and the conversation
\par drifted.
\par 
\par "Heah that John is livenin' things up at the darky school," volunteered
\par the postmaster, after a pause.
\par 
\par "What now?" asked the Judge, sharply.
\par 
\par "Oh, nothin' in particulah,--just his almighty air and uppish ways.
\par B'lieve I did heah somethin' about his givin' talks on the French
\par Revolution, equality, and such like.  He's what I call a dangerous
\par Nigger."
\par 
\par "Have you heard him say anything out of the way?"
\par 
\par "Why, no,--but Sally, our girl, told my wife a lot of rot.  Then, too,
\par I don't need to heah: a Nigger what won't say 'sir' to a white man,
\par or--"
\par 
\par "Who is this John?" interrupted the son.
\par 
\par "Why, it's little black John, Peggy's son,--your old playfellow."
\par 
\par The young man's face flushed angrily, and then he laughed.
\par 
\par "Oh," said he, "it's the darky that tried to force himself into a seat
\par beside the lady I was escorting--"
\par 
\par But Judge Henderson waited to hear no more.  He had been nettled all
\par day, and now at this he rose with a half-smothered oath, took his hat
\par and cane, and walked straight to the schoolhouse.
\par 
\par For John, it had been a long, hard pull to get things started in the
\par rickety old shanty that sheltered his school.  The Negroes were rent
\par into factions for and against him, the parents were careless, the
\par children irregular and dirty, and books, pencils, and slates largely
\par missing.  Nevertheless, he struggled hopefully on, and seemed to see at
\par last some glimmering of dawn.  The attendance was larger and the
\par children were a shade cleaner this week.  Even the booby class in
\par reading showed a little comforting progress.  So John settled himself
\par with renewed patience this afternoon.
\par 
\par "Now, Mandy," he said cheerfully, "that's better; but you mustn't chop
\par your words up so: 'If--the-man--goes.' Why, your little brother even
\par wouldn't tell a story that way, now would he?"
\par 
\par "Naw, suh, he cain't talk."
\par 
\par "All right; now let's try again: 'If the man--'
\par 
\par "John!"
\par 
\par The whole school started in surprise, and the teacher half arose, as
\par the red, angry face of the Judge appeared in the open doorway.
\par 
\par "John, this school is closed.  You children can go home and get to
\par work.  The white people of Altamaha are not spending their money on
\par black folks to have their heads crammed with impudence and lies.  Clear
\par out!  I'll lock the door myself."
\par 
\par Up at the great pillared house the tall young son wandered aimlessly
\par about after his father's abrupt departure.  In the house there was
\par little to interest him; the books were old and stale, the local
\par newspaper flat, and the women had retired with headaches and sewing.
\par He tried a nap, but it was too warm.  So he sauntered out into the
\par fields, complaining disconsolately, "Good Lord! how long will this
\par imprisonment last!"  He was not a bad fellow,--just a little spoiled
\par and self-indulgent, and as headstrong as his proud father.  He seemed a
\par young man pleasant to look upon, as he sat on the great black stump at
\par the edge of the pines idly swinging his legs and smoking.  "Why, there
\par isn't even a girl worth getting up a respectable flirtation with," he
\par growled.  Just then his eye caught a tall, willowy figure hurrying
\par toward him on the narrow path.  He looked with interest at first, and
\par then burst into a laugh as he said, "Well, I declare, if it isn't
\par Jennie, the little brown kitchen-maid!  Why, I never noticed before
\par what a trim little body she is.  Hello, Jennie!  Why, you haven't
\par kissed me since I came home," he said gaily.  The young girl stared at
\par him in surprise and confusion,--faltered something inarticulate, and
\par attempted to pass.  But a wilful mood had seized the young idler, and
\par he caught at her arm.  Frightened, she slipped by; and half
\par mischievously he turned and ran after her through the tall pines.
\par 
\par Yonder, toward the sea, at the end of the path, came John slowly, with
\par his head down.  He had turned wearily homeward from the schoolhouse;
\par then, thinking to shield his mother from the blow, started to meet his
\par sister as she came from work and break the news of his dismissal to
\par her.  "I'll go away," he said slowly; "I'll go away and find work, and
\par send for them.  I cannot live here longer."  And then the fierce,
\par buried anger surged up into his throat.  He waved his arms and hurried
\par wildly up the path.
\par 
\par The great brown sea lay silent.  The air scarce breathed.  The dying
\par day bathed the twisted oaks and mighty pines in black and gold.  There
\par came from the wind no warning, not a whisper from the cloudless sky.
\par There was only a black man hurrying on with an ache in his heart,
\par seeing neither sun nor sea, but starting as from a dream at the
\par frightened cry that woke the pines, to see his dark sister struggling
\par in the arms of a tall and fair-haired man.
\par 
\par He said not a word, but, seizing a fallen limb, struck him with all the
\par pent-up hatred of his great black arm, and the body lay white and still
\par beneath the pines, all bathed in sunshine and in blood.  John looked at
\par it dreamily, then walked back to the house briskly, and said in a soft
\par voice, "Mammy, I'm going away--I'm going to be free."
\par 
\par She gazed at him dimly and faltered, "No'th, honey, is yo' gwine No'th
\par agin?"
\par 
\par He looked out where the North Star glistened pale above the waters, and
\par said, "Yes, mammy, I'm going--North."
\par 
\par Then, without another word, he went out into the narrow lane, up by the
\par straight pines, to the same winding path, and seated himself on the
\par great black stump, looking at the blood where the body had lain.
\par Yonder in the gray past he had played with that dead boy, romping
\par together under the solemn trees.  The night deepened; he thought of the
\par boys at Johnstown.  He wondered how Brown had turned out, and Carey?
\par And Jones,--Jones?  Why, he was Jones, and he wondered what they would
\par all say when they knew, when they knew, in that great long dining-room
\par with its hundreds of merry eyes.  Then as the sheen of the starlight
\par stole over him, he thought of the gilded ceiling of that vast concert
\par hall, heard stealing toward him the faint sweet music of the swan.
\par Hark! was it music, or the hurry and shouting of men?  Yes, surely!
\par Clear and high the faint sweet melody rose and fluttered like a living
\par thing, so that the very earth trembled as with the tramp of horses and
\par murmur of angry men.
\par 
\par He leaned back and smiled toward the sea, whence rose the strange
\par melody, away from the dark shadows where lay the noise of horses
\par galloping, galloping on.  With an effort he roused himself, bent
\par forward, and looked steadily down the pathway, softly humming the "Song
\par of the Bride,"--
\par 
\par   "Freudig gefuhrt, ziehet dahin."
\par 
\par Amid the trees in the dim morning twilight he watched their shadows
\par dancing and heard their horses thundering toward him, until at last
\par they came sweeping like a storm, and he saw in front that haggard
\par white-haired man, whose eyes flashed red with fury.  Oh, how he pitied
\par him,--pitied him,--and wondered if he had the coiling twisted rope.
\par Then, as the storm burst round him, he rose slowly to his feet and
\par turned his closed eyes toward the Sea.
\par 
\par And the world whistled in his ears.
\par 
