\par XIV
\par 
\par Of the Sorrow Songs
\par 
\par   I walk through the churchyard
\par       To lay this body down;
\par   I know moon-rise, I know star-rise;
\par   I walk in the moonlight, I walk in the starlight;
\par   I'll lie in the grave and stretch out my arms,
\par   I'll go to judgment in the evening of the day,
\par   And my soul and thy soul shall meet that day,
\par       When I lay this body down.
\par 
\par   NEGRO SONG.
\par 
\par 
\par They that walked in darkness sang songs in the olden days--Sorrow
\par Songs--for they were weary at heart.  And so before each thought that I
\par have written in this book I have set a phrase, a haunting echo of these
\par weird old songs in which the soul of the black slave spoke to men.
\par Ever since I was a child these songs have stirred me strangely.  They
\par came out of the South unknown to me, one by one, and yet at once I knew
\par them as of me and of mine.  Then in after years when I came to
\par Nashville I saw the great temple builded of these songs towering over
\par the pale city.  To me Jubilee Hall seemed ever made of the songs
\par themselves, and its bricks were red with the blood and dust of toil.
\par Out of them rose for me morning, noon, and night, bursts of wonderful
\par melody, full of the voices of my brothers and sisters, full of the
\par voices of the past.
\par 
\par Little of beauty has America given the world save the rude grandeur God
\par himself stamped on her bosom; the human spirit in this new world has
\par expressed itself in vigor and ingenuity rather than in beauty.  And so
\par by fateful chance the Negro folk-song--the rhythmic cry of the
\par slave--stands to-day not simply as the sole American music, but as the
\par most beautiful expression of human experience born this side the seas.
\par It has been neglected, it has been, and is, half despised, and above
\par all it has been persistently mistaken and misunderstood; but
\par notwithstanding, it still remains as the singular spiritual heritage of
\par the nation and the greatest gift of the Negro people.
\par 
\par Away back in the thirties the melody of these slave songs stirred the
\par nation, but the songs were soon half forgotten.  Some, like "Near the
\par lake where drooped the willow," passed into current airs and their
\par source was forgotten; others were caricatured on the "minstrel" stage
\par and their memory died away.  Then in war-time came the singular Port
\par Royal experiment after the capture of Hilton Head, and perhaps for the
\par first time the North met the Southern slave face to face and heart to
\par heart with no third witness.  The Sea Islands of the Carolinas, where
\par they met, were filled with a black folk of primitive type, touched and
\par moulded less by the world about them than any others outside the Black
\par Belt.  Their appearance was uncouth, their language funny, but their
\par hearts were human and their singing stirred men with a mighty power.
\par Thomas Wentworth Higginson hastened to tell of these songs, and Miss
\par McKim and others urged upon the world their rare beauty.  But the world
\par listened only half credulously until the Fisk Jubilee Singers sang the
\par slave songs so deeply into the world's heart that it can never wholly
\par forget them again.
\par 
\par There was once a blacksmith's son born at Cadiz, New York, who in the
\par changes of time taught school in Ohio and helped defend Cincinnati from
\par Kirby Smith.  Then he fought at Chancellorsville and Gettysburg and
\par finally served in the Freedmen's Bureau at Nashville.  Here he formed a
\par Sunday-school class of black children in 1866, and sang with them and
\par taught them to sing.  And then they taught him to sing, and when once
\par the glory of the Jubilee songs passed into the soul of George L. White,
\par he knew his life-work was to let those Negroes sing to the world as
\par they had sung to him.  So in 1871 the pilgrimage of the Fisk Jubilee
\par Singers began.  North to Cincinnati they rode,--four half-clothed black
\par boys and five girl-women,--led by a man with a cause and a purpose.
\par They stopped at Wilberforce, the oldest of Negro schools, where a black
\par bishop blessed them.  Then they went, fighting cold and starvation,
\par shut out of hotels, and cheerfully sneered at, ever northward; and ever
\par the magic of their song kept thrilling hearts, until a burst of
\par applause in the Congregational Council at Oberlin revealed them to the
\par world.  They came to New York and Henry Ward Beecher dared to welcome
\par them, even though the metropolitan dailies sneered at his "Nigger
\par Minstrels."  So their songs conquered till they sang across the land
\par and across the sea, before Queen and Kaiser, in Scotland and Ireland,
\par Holland and Switzerland.  Seven years they sang, and brought back a
\par hundred and fifty thousand dollars to found Fisk University.
\par 
\par Since their day they have been imitated--sometimes well, by the singers
\par of Hampton and Atlanta, sometimes ill, by straggling quartettes.
\par Caricature has sought again to spoil the quaint beauty of the music,
\par and has filled the air with many debased melodies which vulgar ears
\par scarce know from the real.  But the true Negro folk-song still lives in
\par the hearts of those who have heard them truly sung and in the hearts of
\par the Negro people.
\par 
\par What are these songs, and what do they mean?  I know little of music
\par and can say nothing in technical phrase, but I know something of men,
\par and knowing them, I know that these songs are the articulate message of
\par the slave to the world.  They tell us in these eager days that life was
\par joyous to the black slave, careless and happy.  I can easily believe
\par this of some, of many.  But not all the past South, though it rose from
\par the dead, can gainsay the heart-touching witness of these songs.  They
\par are the music of an unhappy people, of the children of disappointment;
\par they tell of death and suffering and unvoiced longing toward a truer
\par world, of misty wanderings and hidden ways.
\par 
\par The songs are indeed the siftings of centuries; the music is far more
\par ancient than the words, and in it we can trace here and there signs of
\par development.  My grandfather's grandmother was seized by an evil Dutch
\par trader two centuries ago; and coming to the valleys of the Hudson and
\par Housatonic, black, little, and lithe, she shivered and shrank in the
\par harsh north winds, looked longingly at the hills, and often crooned a
\par heathen melody to the child between her knees, thus:
\par 
\par   Do ba-na co-ba, ge-ne me, ge-ne me!
\par   Do ba-na co-ba, ge-ne me, ge-ne me!
\par   Ben d' nu-li, nu-li, nu-li, ben d' le.
\par 
\par 
\par The child sang it to his children and they to their children's
\par children, and so two hundred years it has travelled down to us and we
\par sing it to our children, knowing as little as our fathers what its
\par words may mean, but knowing well the meaning of its music.
\par 
\par This was primitive African music; it may be seen in larger form in the
\par strange chant which heralds "The Coming of John":
\par 
\par   "You may bury me in the East,
\par    You may bury me in the West,
\par    But I'll hear the trumpet sound in that morning,"
\par 
\par --the voice of exile.
\par 
\par Ten master songs, more or less, one may pluck from the forest of
\par melody-songs of undoubted Negro origin and wide popular currency, and
\par songs peculiarly characteristic of the slave.  One of these I have just
\par mentioned.  Another whose strains begin this book is "Nobody knows the
\par trouble I've seen."  When, struck with a sudden poverty, the United
\par States refused to fulfill its promises of land to the freedmen, a
\par brigadier-general went down to the Sea Islands to carry the news.  An
\par old woman on the outskirts of the throng began singing this song; all
\par the mass joined with her, swaying.  And the soldier wept.
\par 
\par The third song is the cradle-song of death which all men know,-"Swing
\par low, sweet chariot,"--whose bars begin the life story of "Alexander
\par Crummell."  Then there is the song of many waters, "Roll, Jordan,
\par roll," a mighty chorus with minor cadences.  There were many songs of
\par the fugitive like that which opens "The Wings of Atalanta," and the
\par more familiar "Been a-listening."  The seventh is the song of the End
\par and the Beginning--"My Lord, what a mourning! when the stars begin to
\par fall"; a strain of this is placed before "The Dawn of Freedom."  The
\par song of groping--"My way's cloudy"--begins "The Meaning of Progress";
\par the ninth is the song of this chapter--"Wrestlin' Jacob, the day is
\par a-breaking,"--a paean of hopeful strife.  The last master song is the
\par song of songs--"Steal away,"--sprung from "The Faith of the Fathers."
\par 
\par There are many others of the Negro folk-songs as striking and
\par characteristic as these, as, for instance, the three strains in the
\par third, eighth, and ninth chapters; and others I am sure could easily
\par make a selection on more scientific principles.  There are, too, songs
\par that seem to be a step removed from the more primitive types: there is
\par the maze-like medley, "Bright sparkles," one phrase of which heads "The
\par Black Belt"; the Easter carol, "Dust, dust and ashes"; the dirge, "My
\par mother's took her flight and gone home"; and that burst of melody
\par hovering over "The Passing of the First-Born"--"I hope my mother will
\par be there in that beautiful world on high."
\par 
\par These represent a third step in the development of the slave song, of
\par which "You may bury me in the East" is the first, and songs like "March
\par on" (chapter six) and "Steal away" are the second.  The first is
\par African music, the second Afro-American, while the third is a blending
\par of Negro music with the music heard in the foster land.  The result is
\par still distinctively Negro and the method of blending original, but the
\par elements are both Negro and Caucasian.  One might go further and find a
\par fourth step in this development, where the songs of white America have
\par been distinctively influenced by the slave songs or have incorporated
\par whole phrases of Negro melody, as "Swanee River" and "Old Black Joe."
\par Side by side, too, with the growth has gone the debasements and
\par imitations--the Negro "minstrel" songs, many of the "gospel" hymns, and
\par some of the contemporary "coon" songs,--a mass of music in which the
\par novice may easily lose himself and never find the real Negro melodies.
\par 
\par In these songs, I have said, the slave spoke to the world.  Such a
\par message is naturally veiled and half articulate.  Words and music have
\par lost each other and new and cant phrases of a dimly understood theology
\par have displaced the older sentiment.  Once in a while we catch a strange
\par word of an unknown tongue, as the "Mighty Myo," which figures as a
\par river of death; more often slight words or mere doggerel are joined to
\par music of singular sweetness.  Purely secular songs are few in number,
\par partly because many of them were turned into hymns by a change of
\par words, partly because the frolics were seldom heard by the stranger,
\par and the music less often caught.  Of nearly all the songs, however, the
\par music is distinctly sorrowful.  The ten master songs I have mentioned
\par tell in word and music of trouble and exile, of strife and hiding; they
\par grope toward some unseen power and sigh for rest in the End.
\par 
\par The words that are left to us are not without interest, and, cleared of
\par evident dross, they conceal much of real poetry and meaning beneath
\par conventional theology and unmeaning rhapsody.  Like all primitive folk,
\par the slave stood near to Nature's heart.  Life was a "rough and rolling
\par sea" like the brown Atlantic of the Sea Islands; the "Wilderness" was
\par the home of God, and the "lonesome valley" led to the way of life.
\par "Winter'll soon be over," was the picture of life and death to a
\par tropical imagination.  The sudden wild thunderstorms of the South awed
\par and impressed the Negroes,--at times the rumbling seemed to them
\par "mournful," at times imperious:
\par 
\par   "My Lord calls me,
\par   He calls me by the thunder,
\par   The trumpet sounds it in my soul."
\par 
\par 
\par The monotonous toil and exposure is painted in many words.  One sees
\par the ploughmen in the hot, moist furrow, singing:
\par 
\par   "Dere's no rain to wet you,
\par    Dere's no sun to burn you,
\par    Oh, push along, believer,
\par    I want to go home."
\par 
\par 
\par The bowed and bent old man cries, with thrice-repeated wail:
\par 
\par   "O Lord, keep me from sinking down,"
\par 
\par and he rebukes the devil of doubt who can whisper:
\par 
\par   "Jesus is dead and God's gone away."
\par 
\par 
\par Yet the soul-hunger is there, the restlessness of the savage, the wail
\par of the wanderer, and the plaint is put in one little phrase:
\par 
\par   My soul wants something that's new, that's new
\par 
\par 
\par Over the inner thoughts of the slaves and their relations one with
\par another the shadow of fear ever hung, so that we get but glimpses here
\par and there, and also with them, eloquent omissions and silences.  Mother
\par and child are sung, but seldom father; fugitive and weary wanderer call
\par for pity and affection, but there is little of wooing and wedding; the
\par rocks and the mountains are well known, but home is unknown.  Strange
\par blending of love and helplessness sings through the refrain:
\par 
\par   "Yonder's my ole mudder,
\par    Been waggin' at de hill so long;
\par   'Bout time she cross over,
\par    Git home bime-by."
\par 
\par Elsewhere comes the cry of the "motherless" and the "Farewell,
\par farewell, my only child."
\par 
\par Love-songs are scarce and fall into two categories--the frivolous and
\par light, and the sad.  Of deep successful love there is ominous silence,
\par and in one of the oldest of these songs there is a depth of history and
\par meaning:
\par 
\par   Poor Ro-sy, poor gal; Poor Ro-sy,
\par   poor gal; Ro-sy break my poor heart,
\par   Heav'n shall-a-be my home.
\par 
\par 
\par A black woman said of the song, "It can't be sung without a full heart
\par and a troubled sperrit."  The same voice sings here that sings in the
\par German folk-song:
\par 
\par     "Jetz Geh i' an's brunele, trink' aber net."
\par 
\par 
\par Of death the Negro showed little fear, but talked of it familiarly and
\par even fondly as simply a crossing of the waters, perhaps--who
\par knows?--back to his ancient forests again.  Later days transfigured his
\par fatalism, and amid the dust and dirt the toiler sang:
\par 
\par   "Dust, dust and ashes, fly over my grave,
\par    But the Lord shall bear my spirit home."
\par 
\par 
\par The things evidently borrowed from the surrounding world undergo
\par characteristic change when they enter the mouth of the slave.
\par Especially is this true of Bible phrases.  "Weep, O captive daughter of
\par Zion," is quaintly turned into "Zion, weep-a-low," and the wheels of
\par Ezekiel are turned every way in the mystic dreaming of the slave, till
\par he says:
\par 
\par  "There's a little wheel a-turnin' in-a-my heart."
\par 
\par 
\par As in olden time, the words of these hymns were improvised by some
\par leading minstrel of the religious band.  The circumstances of the
\par gathering, however, the rhythm of the songs, and the limitations of
\par allowable thought, confined the poetry for the most part to single or
\par double lines, and they seldom were expanded to quatrains or longer
\par tales, although there are some few examples of sustained efforts,
\par chiefly paraphrases of the Bible.  Three short series of verses have
\par always attracted me,--the one that heads this chapter, of one line of
\par which Thomas Wentworth Higginson has fittingly said, "Never, it seems
\par to me, since man first lived and suffered was his infinite longing for
\par peace uttered more plaintively."  The second and third are descriptions
\par of the Last Judgment,--the one a late improvisation, with some traces
\par of outside influence:
\par 
\par 
\par   "Oh, the stars in the elements are falling,
\par    And the moon drips away into blood,
\par    And the ransomed of the Lord are returning unto God,
\par    Blessed be the name of the Lord."
\par 
\par And the other earlier and homelier picture from the low coast lands:
\par 
\par   "Michael, haul the boat ashore,
\par    Then you'll hear the horn they blow,
\par    Then you'll hear the trumpet sound,
\par    Trumpet sound the world around,
\par    Trumpet sound for rich and poor,
\par    Trumpet sound the Jubilee,
\par    Trumpet sound for you and me."
\par 
\par 
\par Through all the sorrow of the Sorrow Songs there breathes a hope--a
\par faith in the ultimate justice of things.  The minor cadences of despair
\par change often to triumph and calm confidence.  Sometimes it is faith in
\par life, sometimes a faith in death, sometimes assurance of boundless
\par justice in some fair world beyond.  But whichever it is, the meaning is
\par always clear: that sometime, somewhere, men will judge men by their
\par souls and not by their skins.  Is such a hope justified?  Do the Sorrow
\par Songs sing true?
\par 
\par The silently growing assumption of this age is that the probation of
\par races is past, and that the backward races of to-day are of proven
\par inefficiency and not worth the saving.  Such an assumption is the
\par arrogance of peoples irreverent toward Time and ignorant of the deeds
\par of men.  A thousand years ago such an assumption, easily possible,
\par would have made it difficult for the Teuton to prove his right to life.
\par Two thousand years ago such dogmatism, readily welcome, would have
\par scouted the idea of blond races ever leading civilization.  So wofully
\par unorganized is sociological knowledge that the meaning of progress, the
\par meaning of "swift" and "slow" in human doing, and the limits of human
\par perfectability, are veiled, unanswered sphinxes on the shores of
\par science.  Why should AEschylus have sung two thousand years before
\par Shakespeare was born?  Why has civilization flourished in Europe, and
\par flickered, flamed, and died in Africa?  So long as the world stands
\par meekly dumb before such questions, shall this nation proclaim its
\par ignorance and unhallowed prejudices by denying freedom of opportunity
\par to those who brought the Sorrow Songs to the Seats of the Mighty?
\par 
\par Your country?  How came it yours?  Before the Pilgrims landed we were
\par here.  Here we have brought our three gifts and mingled them with
\par yours: a gift of story and song--soft, stirring melody in an
\par ill-harmonized and unmelodious land; the gift of sweat and brawn to
\par beat back the wilderness, conquer the soil, and lay the foundations of
\par this vast economic empire two hundred years earlier than your weak
\par hands could have done it; the third, a gift of the Spirit.  Around us
\par the history of the land has centred for thrice a hundred years; out of
\par the nation's heart we have called all that was best to throttle and
\par subdue all that was worst; fire and blood, prayer and sacrifice, have
\par billowed over this people, and they have found peace only in the altars
\par of the God of Right.  Nor has our gift of the Spirit been merely
\par passive.  Actively we have woven ourselves with the very warp and woof
\par of this nation,--we fought their battles, shared their sorrow, mingled
\par our blood with theirs, and generation after generation have pleaded
\par with a headstrong, careless people to despise not Justice, Mercy, and
\par Truth, lest the nation be smitten with a curse.  Our song, our toil,
\par our cheer, and warning have been given to this nation in
\par blood-brotherhood.  Are not these gifts worth the giving?  Is not this
\par work and striving?  Would America have been America without her Negro
\par people?
\par 
\par Even so is the hope that sang in the songs of my fathers well sung.  If
\par somewhere in this whirl and chaos of things there dwells Eternal Good,
\par pitiful yet masterful, then anon in His good time America shall rend
\par the Veil and the prisoned shall go free.  Free, free as the sunshine
\par trickling down the morning into these high windows of mine, free as
\par yonder fresh young voices welling up to me from the caverns of brick
\par and mortar below--swelling with song, instinct with life, tremulous
\par treble and darkening bass.  My children, my little children, are
\par singing to the sunshine, and thus they sing:
\par 
\par   Let us cheer the wea-ry trav-el-ler,
\par   Cheer the wea-ry trav-el-ler, Let us
\par   cheer the wea-ry trav-el-ler
\par   A-long the heav-en-ly way.
\par 
\par And the traveller girds himself, and sets his face toward the Morning,
\par and goes his way.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par The Afterthought
\par 
